INSERT INTO `assignments` VALUES (1,'Homework 1','<p>i. (Due: 2/8 midnight) Do an analysis using the framework you are assigned. </p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Choose a segment of video from one of the videos of the class &quot;doing long division&quot;. The segment you select should be roughly one minute in length. In the text of your post include a link to the video you are using and include the times (minutes and seconds) that the segment begins and ends. </li>\r\n	<li>Write a roughly 500 word analysis of the segment of video you chose to analyze from the perspective of the framework you were assigned to use. Where it makes it easier to follow your text include transcriptions of conversation or snapshots of the video. Make the best argument you can for why you think this frame of analysis is significant and revealing; choosing the right segment of video will make this task easier.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>ii. (Due: 2/22 midnight) Write commentaries on the analyses of at least two of your teammates; every member of the team should get at least two commentaries. Com- mentaries should be 250 words. Also write short thoughtful responses to the com- mentariesxx you receive on your work. This part of the data will be much more interesting if you engage in thoughtful conversations with one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iii. (Due: 2/29 midnight) Do a second analysis of the segment of video you used in part i of this assignment; it must be the same video segment. Use a di erent frame of analysis than the one you were initially assigned. Include references to the analyses of your teammates and a paragraph that compares the two analyses and reflects on what you learned from going through parts i-iii of this homework. This should also be roughly 500 words.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>iv. (Due 3/4 midnight) You will be assigned the analyses of four students in the class who worked on di erent teams than yours. Rank the analyses in the order of persua- siveness: the most persuasive has a rank of 1.</p>\r\n','2016-02-09 04:59:00','2016-03-05 04:59:00','2016-02-01 22:30:19','2016-03-03 20:12:21'),(2,'Homework 2','<p>Homework 2: Communication and Problem Solving In this homework you will do some analysis of the data we collected from the TPS java coding exercises. You will use the platform developed by Michelle Sisti and Nishan Acharya again with some minor modifications to do this assignment. You will work in teams of three or four. Each member of your team will be assigned a different segment of transcript to analyze. 1. (Due: 3/8 11 PM) Do a draft of an analysis. Once you post a draft you can start collaborating with other students and writing the comments that are required for this assignment. a. Post a copy of the transcript you are given to analyze at the top of your draft. Use headings to clearly mark each part of your draft. Be sure to provide concrete details by referring to specific elements of the transcript and quoting the relevant chat. Your goal is to get as close as you can to the the underlying phenomena that are being represented in the transcript. b. Analyze the chat in your transcript in terms of grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; copresence. c. Do an analysis of your transcript in terms of the access framework (four access characteristics) described in Perkins paper Person-plus: a distributed view of thinking and learning. Is there a distribution of executive function? Explain. d. Do one of the following two analyses (your choice). i. Do an analysis of the transcript where the participants are doing some problem-solving. Is there a joint problem space? What work is done to maintain the infrastructure as the students work together, creating and sharing knowledge. To quote Roschelle &amp; Teasley (1995, p 76): &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration. Explain how that quote is relevant to your transcript. Be specific in your analysis of the chat. (Note, you have already done some of this analysis in part b. Nevertheless, make sure your answer to this part is self-contained.) ii. Explain your transcript from the perspective of situated activity. What is the the context and arena while the participants did the java exercise? Does the transcript provide an example of the dialectic relation between context and setting? Are there elements of the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing? 2. (Due: 3/11 11 PM) Write commentaries on the analyses of at least two of your teammates; every member of the team should get at least two commentaries. Commentaries should be 100 words. Also write short thoughtful responses to the commentaries you receive on your work. This part of the data will be much more interesting if you engage in thoughtful conversations with one another. 3. (Due: 3/14 11 PM) Do a second draft of the analysis you did in part 1 of this assignment. Reflect on the impact of part 2 of this assignment on your revisions to the first draft of the assignment. What did you learn by reviewing the analysis work of other members of your team? Did it change your level of confidence in your own work? et cetera 4. (Due 3/17 11 PM) You will be assigned the analyses of four students in the class who worked on different teams than yours. Rank the analyses in the order of persuasiveness and clarity: the most persuasive and clear has a rank of 1.</p>\r\n','2016-03-09 04:00:00','2016-03-15 03:00:00','2016-02-29 21:57:20','2016-03-17 15:11:38'),(3,'Homework 3','<p><strong>Homework 3: Collaborative Learning</strong><br />\r\nIn this homework you will do some analysis of the data we collected earlier in the semester from<br />\r\nthe homework platform you are using this semester. You will continue to work in teams of three<br />\r\nor four. Each member of your team will be assigned a different segment of transcript to analyze.<br />\r\n1. (Due: 3/22 11 PM) Do a draft of an analysis. Once you post a draft you can start collaborating<br />\r\nwith other students and writing the comments that are required for this assignment.<br />\r\na. Is there evidence that the students are working in a joint problem space? What work is<br />\r\ndone to maintain the infrastructure as the students work together, creating and sharing<br />\r\nknowledge. To quote Roschelle &amp; Teasley (1995, p 76): &ldquo;collaborators must have ways<br />\r\nof: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for<br />\r\nevidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the<br />\r\ncollaboration. Explain how that quote is relevant to your transcript. Find a few relevant<br />\r\nand interesting examples to illustrate your comments.<br />\r\nb. How do Merril&rsquo;s first five principles of instruction design apply to the homework platform?<br />\r\nSequence through each of the principles and their corollaries; create subheading for every<br />\r\nprinciple. Find a few relevant and interesting examples to illustrate your comments. If<br />\r\nyou don&rsquo;t think a principle or corollary applies provide a brief explanation of why.<br />\r\nc. Do an analysis from the perspective of the Dillenbourg paper on the collaborative learning<br />\r\nsupported by the platform. Provide evidence from the transcripts that supports your<br />\r\nanalysis. What are the scales of the collaboration? Enumerate the significant features of<br />\r\nthe setup to the online collaboration. Do you see elements of the collaboration which are<br />\r\nenhanced by the assignment of roles or the use of scaffolding? What opportunities exist for<br />\r\nKen (Head of the lab) to monitor student work and progress? Is there symmetry? Can the<br />\r\nparticipants perform the same actions? Are there common goals? Do the students work<br />\r\ntogether? Can you find evidence of negotiation and misunderstanding that is productive<br />\r\nfor learning?<br />\r\n2. (Due: 3/25 11 PM) Write commentaries on the analyses of at least two of your teammates;<br />\r\nevery member of the team should get at least two commentaries. Commentaries should be 100<br />\r\nwords. Also write short thoughtful responses to the commentaries you receive on your work.<br />\r\nThis part of the data will be much more interesting if you engage in thoughtful conversations<br />\r\nwith one another.<br />\r\n3. (Due: 3/28 11 PM) Do a second draft of the analysis you did in part 1 of this assignment.<br />\r\nReflect on the impact of part 2 of this assignment on your revisions to the first draft of the<br />\r\nassignment. What did you learn by reviewing the analysis work of other members of your<br />\r\nteam? Did it change your level of confidence in your own work? et cetera<br />\r\n4. (Due 3/31 11 PM) You will be assigned the analyses of four students in the class who worked<br />\r\non different teams than yours. Rank the analyses in the order of persuasiveness and clarity:<br />\r\nthe most persuasive and clear has a rank of 1.</p>\r\n','2016-03-23 03:00:00','2016-03-29 03:00:00','2016-03-18 13:29:01','2016-03-18 13:29:01');
