INSERT INTO `comments` VALUES (1,'Hello! Firstly, I would like to say that you did a great job on your first draft. Because you chose to select a segment that was in the middle of the video, I think you were thoughtful in providing a descriptive summary of the beginning of the video that led up to the segment you picked so that your team could have a good understanding of the interaction that took place without us having to watch the whole thing.\r\n\r\nYou\'re analysis as the interactive position was very thorough. You were able to point out that the interaction was \"informal, cooperative, and verbal problem-solving process\" which I agree with. I think you could have added some additional analysis about whether the interaction was scripted/unscripted and egalitarian/autocratic because it is part of a joint activities dimensions of variation. In my opinion, the interaction was egalitarian because each person had an equal chance and opportunity to participate and contribute in the problem solving. Additionally, I think the interaction was unscripted because it was an in class assignment that two students had to collaborate on without prior experience working with each other (I believe) and the turn-taking was not planned.\r\n\r\nIt was a good idea on your part to incorporate the quotes of what the person said when you did your analysis as well as including the precise time in which to find it. It was helpful for me to follow. It could have been even better if you added in some comments about the turn-allocations techniques such as when it was self-selection and when it was current selects next. Also, it is good to mention the idea of grounding in terms of an interactive position. Overall, nice job!',9,14,'2016-02-09 03:03:47','2016-02-09 03:03:47'),(2,'Hello! I think that your decision to separate your analysis into three specific examples was a nice decision and it was easy to follow. Your third external constraint is what I immediately think of when I hear external framework. It\'s important to note that this idea of reducing the cognitive load and using paper and pencil in this particular case is the term called complementary strategy. A few things I wanted to give notes about was that you didn\'t provide an exact range of time where you wanted to focus on. The beginning you mention around 1:15 and then in the middle of your explanation, you mention around :30 and :45. I think you should mention a specific time frame. Another point you could discuss is the idea of memory and how it plays into saving processing time. there is an instance in the segment of the video where they recount a previous number they wrote down and it would be really good to mention. You\'re first constraint was really interesting. I never thought about it like that. It was a little confusing to me so maybe a little more explanation of how it is an external idea would be helpful to include. Overall, good job! Side note: you should include the link to the video you selected.',9,15,'2016-02-09 05:04:31','2016-02-09 05:04:31'),(3,'Your post gives a good summary of what external cognition is. You give good background on the subject and the utility of using external representations in this situation. Relying on the world to reduce cognitive load is a good strategy for completing complicated tasks. Something else to consider in your analysis is how the external representation specifically serves to reduce the cognitive load. You touch on the fact that writing down the problem, in and of itself, reduces the cognitive load by preventing Chloe from having to remember the numbers. How does the way the problem is written on the page also reduce the cognitive workload? Certain people write these problems differently. How do you think the way the problem is written on the page works to make things easier on the person doing the calculation?  Lining up the numbers in a certain way helps to remind them where they are in the problem. Writing the result of the multiplication under the number she is going to subtract from could potentially make the subtraction easier. It\'s interesting that Chloe even writes the subtraction substeps on the side. How does that factor into the cognitive workload? Even in the substeps, the external representation of the multiplication problems help to reduce the cognitive workload. ',19,22,'2016-02-10 02:24:54','2016-02-10 02:24:54'),(4,'You present an interesting viewpoint through your analysis. I urge you to consider the difference between interactive and competitive in your analysis. For a cognitive process to display aspects of interaction, it is not necessary for it to be competitive. There is not a prerequisite for an opponent. The idea is that there is a goal for the group of people and they work together and interact to make progress toward that goal. In football, the goal may be to play as a team in such a way that they score more than they allow the opponent to score and ultimately this leads to them winning the game. In the example of the long division problem, the goal is to successfully complete the problem at hand; that is, the goal is to arrive at the correct answer when dividing the two numbers. The conversation between them is definitely interactive but what are some markers of the interaction? What are the markers that signify that the interaction has led to progress toward the goal? When they realize they have made a mistake, what occurs in their interaction to indicate that they need to backtrack in order to eventually make more progress toward their goal?',19,19,'2016-02-10 03:51:34','2016-02-10 03:51:34'),(5,'Very interesting analysis! There is a lot going on in those first 15 seconds after 1:24 in the video and I would like to dig a little deeper into the turn-taking of Ken and Rick Ken drove the locally managed turn taking, because he was doing the math. \r\n\r\n At 1:28 there is an awkward, unclear transitional relevance place. Ken had asked \"Do I add a zero?.... I think I add a zero\". It sounds like Ken might have been asking for Ricks help, self-selecting for the turn to change. However, Rick either thought it was a rhetorical question or intentionally left Ken to solve the question himself. Either way, the initial empty response to his question left him confused so he affirms his guess with little confidence. At this moment, Rick steps in, \"No you just pull the one down\" 1:31. The confidence in Ricks voice easily changes Ken\'s mind and he listens. \"Pull the one down. Alright, alright. I have not done this since 4th grade\" 1:32. Although Ken might have been slightly embarrassed, in analyzing this interaction we can see him re-learning long division. In other words, through this brief interaction, we can analyze how through cooperation in turn-taking, Rick helped Ken grow his zone of proximal development and continue with the long division problem.\r\n',23,11,'2016-02-16 19:51:53','2016-02-16 19:51:53'),(6,'This is a tough clip to find much evidence for a cultural historic analysis. It would be interesting to expand on your last idea about the internal operation Chenxi was performing. The external operation she was performing was driven by a cultural understanding of how to to long division. She must have grown up in a different culture than you did and as a result was taught long division differently. In this analysis, we can see that the long division is a socially mediated activity. At some point in her life she was taught long division in a social setting. In this video she is drawing off the previous knowledge she built from her childhood. That knowledge was passed down to her teacher from generations before in a similar manner.\r\n\r\nThis is a good example of a double world in which Chenxi is externalizing the previous knowledge she had about long division. If there wasn\'t someone teach her long division as a child, she wouldn\'t have been able to start the problem. \r\n\r\nYou can also see her intellectual development expand as she performs the problem. She vocalizes to herself and her partner and previous knowledge comes back to her. Speech and practical activity converge here in a culturally mediated social interaction. \r\n\r\nIn analyzing the internal operation of Chenxi further, you can dig deeper into the cultural historic aspects of her problem solving.',23,23,'2016-02-17 18:32:14','2016-02-17 18:32:14'),(7,'This is a tough clip to find much evidence for a cultural historic analysis. It would be interesting to expand on your last idea about the internal operation Chenxi was performing. The external operation she was performing was driven by a cultural understanding of how to to long division. She must have grown up in a different culture than you did and as a result was taught long division differently. In this analysis, we can see that the long division is a socially mediated activity. At some point in her life she was taught long division in a social setting. In this video she is drawing off the previous knowledge she built from her childhood. That knowledge was passed down to her teacher from generations before in a similar manner.\r\n\r\nThis is a good example of a double world in which Chenxi is externalizing the previous knowledge she had about long division. If there wasn\'t someone teach her long division as a child, she wouldn\'t have been able to start the problem. \r\n\r\nYou can also see her intellectual development expand as she performs the problem. She vocalizes to herself and her partner and previous knowledge comes back to her. Speech and practical activity converge here in a culturally mediated social interaction. \r\n\r\nIn analyzing the internal operation of Chenxi further, you can dig deeper into the cultural historic aspects of her problem solving.',23,23,'2016-02-17 18:32:36','2016-02-17 18:32:36'),(8,'I thought your analysis was a great use of some instances of the meditational triangle presented in the cultural historical approach to cognition paper.  Indeed the subject, Will, can use the tools of a pen and paper or a calculator to solve the long-division problem.  I thought it was a great observation that the tool of a pen and paper could be use in a different way to solve the problem depending on where the subject learned long division (the subjects cultural upbringing).  \r\n\r\nI agree that there was much communication between Kathy and Will, and that communication allowed Kathy to let Will know that he had made a mistake in the long division procedure, which Will was able to realize with Kathy\'s prompt.  After this prompt Will changes the external representation of the problem.  You write, \"In doing so, Kathy has passed along knowledge to Will and he has internalized that knowledge. In the future, he will have this knowledge and will be able to use that knowledge to complete the problem individually.\"  I would urge you to elaborate exactly on what this knowledge that Kathy passed to Will is in a general sense.  If you can present an argument that this knowledge is something that can be used to help Will solve long-division problems in a more efficient or better manner in the future, then this knowledge Will have indeed contributed to Will\'s long-division knowledgbase.  However, the error that Kathy found was a small computation error on Will\'s part and it is not clear to me if a realization of this error to Will will make Will better at long-division in the future.',7,6,'2016-02-18 17:16:08','2016-02-18 17:16:08'),(9,'I thought that it was great how you pulled instances of external elements that could be used to reduce cognitive loads from Chloe and Joe\'s video.  You\'re absolutely right by stating that a long division problem without the use of external elements such as a pencil and paper would put an overload on cognitive loads such as working memory.  Clearly things like scratch papers and pencils can be used to reduce this working memory load when solving a cognitive tasks like long division.  Thus, your example of using a paper and pencil in addition to your mental function as a technique to solve the problem is an complementary strategy.  In Kirch\'s paper, Kirch describes how subjects use various complementary strategies for reducing the cognitive workload for a variety of mental functions such as memory, attention, and perception.  I would encourage you to hypothesize the different mental functions (IE memory) of the cognitive workload that are being lessened when Chloe is using various external elements like a paper and pencil to solve the long division problem.',7,22,'2016-02-18 21:57:15','2016-02-18 21:57:15'),(10,'The video segment that you chose is a very good resource to analyze concepts related to cultural historic. And I think you did a good job in choosing which aspect to analyze, when you comparing how Abby and Benedickt did the long division problem with how Saad and Mojir did. I could infer that Abby and Mojir probably had different cultural historical backgrounds due to the evidence that they had different writing style during their calculating process. But my inference is more based on my own knowledge and understanding of cultural historic than from reading the analysis in your article. The connection between cultural historic concepts and the evidence that Abby and Mojir has different writing style is not very obvious, so it would be better to have more analysis about how you get from one to the other. I think including some ideas and concept definitions in the reading material might help with that. Also, I agree with you that the tools Abby used to mediate her long division problem were a pencil and paper, but it would be better if you can analyze how these tools really help the solving process, and what might be different if she chose to use another tool. I am also a little bit confused about the analysis of inter to intra psychological change, since I do not understand why the interaction between Abby and Benedickt showed a change from inter to intra.',17,20,'2016-02-19 00:20:15','2016-02-19 00:20:15'),(11,'I really like your analysis in your article. Your ideas are well expressed, analyzed, and highly related to the concepts of cultural historic. I think there are two main ideas in your article. The first idea is that people know how to do long division because teachers or parents have taught them, and later they teach themselves. This argument shows a transition of externalization to internalization, but does not completely show that the method of doing long division is cultural historic. Cultural historic might be explained more thoroughly if you argue that teachers and parents also learned the method of doing long division from their elders, and the elders learned this from their ancestors as well and so on. The second idea is that every one has his special cultural historical background, which is different from that of others. I think you did a good job in illustrate this idea through analyzing different video clips, and I really love the examples you gave. I would just suggest you to add more specific details in your example. By so far your examples are not very detailed, since I do not know where to refer the examples you gave. Another tiny suggestion is that using some topic sentences to summarize your main ideas might make your arguments look clearer. ',17,24,'2016-02-19 02:49:38','2016-02-19 02:49:38'),(12,'First of all, excellent analysis on Bradâ€™s long division which helped me to go through the post easily. Brad started to solve the problem in a different way (of course) which I cannot say an unorthodox way by setting up that table at the beginning which he thought/knew could be useful later on. I would call that table thing setting up a calculator which gives the output for the calculation by looking into that. This could be a great way to solve the problem easily not putting much pressure on brain but I find this useful for solving only one long division with enough time. If there were multiple long division problems to solve of different types, setting up tables for all of those might take a lot of time than solving the problem in other ways. Brad discovered other better way to solve the problem in the middle which led him to skew a bit from using the table (maybe). Also Brad got rid of extra parts of the problem by erasing those completely which I think (also the analyst thought that too I guess) helped him to focus on one part which heâ€™s currently on. If I was doing that, I would scratch the extra/unnecessary parts and those visible ones wouldnâ€™t let me think ahead and thatâ€™s why I think Brads way of getting rid of unnecessary parts/numbers and being focused on one part is pretty cool. According to the analysis, Brad uses internal dialogues to solve the problem and just narrated the actions, which I think another great way of being focused. I think over time, as he kept on moving, his confidence grew which is pretty obvious and turned him less dependent on the other helping tools (such as using table).\r\nGreat analysis, far better than mine of course, also itâ€™d be helpful if the analyst added the video link and the time at the top but anyways, the video link is already available to everyone. ',14,7,'2016-02-19 07:16:10','2016-02-19 07:16:10'),(13,'I like that you focused on one, very short, and specific part of the transcript. I\'m a bit confused on why you added that first part of your response, claiming that this interaction does not necessarily follow the rules of a conversation as defined by Sacks, Schegloff, and Jefferson, and yet still analyze the situation as if it did fit said definition.\r\nIn a way, actually, I think Katherine\'s prompt to Ariel can be seen as part of turn-taking, and negates the issue of participants not having full control. Because Katherine is asking Ariel for her thoughts, I would think that it counts as Katherine allocating the next turn to Ariel, using a question-answer adjacency pair.\r\nI also think it would be interesting for you to get into the relationship between Ariel\'s writing and Katherine\'s understanding. Ariel is externalizing her thoughts when she writes things down, but she is also interacting with Katherine in a way, showing her what it is Ariel is thinking. Even though Katherine mis-interprets the signals, such as when she thought Ariel was unsure of the next step rather than continuing to work on the current one.\r\nAdditionally, I think Katherine\'s repetition (\"but you take the next one down, right?\"), rather than showing a paradox of understanding, is actually an indication of the situation not truely being grounded. And Katherine\'s \"Oh\" is a self-imposed fix to the misunderstanding, at which point she asks Ariel for confirmation in order to ground her new understanding of the situation.',21,13,'2016-02-19 07:38:57','2016-02-19 07:38:57'),(14,'Perhaps it would be helpful to also discuss the externalized parts of Maria\'s memory that are not actually written down? For example, when she points at things with her pencil while working, which is an important action to help her keep her place and reduce her memory load.\r\nAdditionally, it may be useful to discuss why actions showing externalized cognition are helpful to Maria and Zak. On one hand, they are helping Maria, and without the cues she would have a number of troubles. With writing all over the page, she has to keep track of exactly what goes with what, where she is going next in the problem, and what she has already done. On the other hand, the writing is providing information for Zak on where Maria is currently, and is acting as external memory for him while following along with Maria\'s calculations. This way he does not have to write down his own calculations in order to check hers, he can see the whole process she is going through to do the math, step by step, and can check her incrementally that way.\r\nI think it would also be good to get further into the reasoning behind Maria crossing out numbers while subtracting (around 1:18). So for example, by making the zero a ten, she is not simply making marks to help her remember, but also making the subtraction itself easier. Because she doesn\'t have to consider two different digit places, only one place in the number, and can deal with the higher digits later.',21,12,'2016-02-19 08:18:40','2016-02-19 08:18:40'),(15,'	First of all, this is clearly a well thought out analysis, and itâ€™s impressive you managed to get all this from such a short video clip, which I think is exactly what Professor Alterman wanted.  Your initial sentence and the subsequent arguments substantiating its claims gives the response a clear and solid framework, which helps avoid the common pitfall of meandering, one which I have seen much of in other first drafts of academic writings (be they in this class or others). Adding the transcription of the video at the start of your response made it easy to know what you were referring to in your evidence, negating the need to constantly watch the video to ensure your claims are well-founded.\r\n	There are some minor criticisms I have, but truthfully none are content-related.  First, there are a few grammatical errors â€“ I donâ€™t know if Professor Alterman will be grading us on those, but if so, check your spelling of â€œdivisorâ€ in your first paragraph, along with a few strange lapses of syntax in sentences such as â€œFurthermore, there are three grounding knowledgeâ€¦â€  If we are told grammar is a non-issue, feel free to disregard these suggestions.\r\n	The main suggestion I would make that I think will greatly enhance the readability of this response is to break up the paragraphs a bit more.  As it is right now, you have two very long paragraphs (full of great content).  If you split them up more, readers (and graders) will be more inclined and able to pay close attention to your well-thought out analysis, and the urge to skip sentences or skim for main ideas will hopefully be eradicated. \r\n',12,17,'2016-02-21 22:45:35','2016-02-21 22:45:35'),(16,'61 words for a quote from a paper we read is quite long, especially considering your response is on the shorter side (492 words, which is OK as along as all of them are helping to develop a tight argument). As it stands now, a 61 word quote is a little over 12% of your response, and, since we can operate under the assumption we have all read the same materials, I would recommend you trim it down or remove it entirely, so that you can focus your words on the meat of your response, and limit exposition.  \r\n	The second quote you use, from the video, is also quite lengthy â€“ 94 words, coming in at almost 20% of your response.  This combined with the previous quote means around a third of your response is all quotes â€“ once again, Iâ€™d recommend trimming them down (but definitely keep the relevant parts of Willâ€™s quote, as it helps orient the reader and ready them for your analysis of it).  \r\n	Minor grammar / spelling issues â€“ for instance, check â€œcognitive.â€  Iâ€™d recommend pasting the whole thing into Microsoft Word and see where any red / green lines appear.  \r\n	Your third paragraph (talking about Kirsh and his coin experiment) seems fairly divorced from the rest of your response. Consider either cutting it out or tying it into your analysis more clearly.\r\n	Overall Iâ€™d say youâ€™re onto a solid analysis.  As with cooking a good steak, the trick is to keep the meat nice and juicy (have good content, keep it interesting and well-flowing), grill it well (build your ideas to conclusions, substantiate claims) and trim the fat (cut unnecessary quotes and segments).\r\n',12,21,'2016-02-21 22:56:40','2016-02-21 22:56:40'),(17,'Oops! Forgot to put a video link. Here it is: https://youtu.be/196RavNMjGU. \r\nI also found it interesting to watch Brad\'s confidence grow as he did the problem. I imagine that he became more confident with his procedural knowledge with practice and was able to perform the calculation with increasing speed. I wonder if the table he set up helped him recall his previous knowledge of long division. If so, even though it took him a minute to set it up, it would have increased his calculation speed later on in the problem. In that case, it probably wouldn\'t matter if he tried multiple long division problems of different types, with the table he would still perform the problem faster.',23,7,'2016-02-21 23:06:59','2016-02-21 23:06:59'),(18,'First and foremost, I think you good job with the post. I think your article covered all major aspects of internal framework and provided pertinent examples to help explain it. In addition, you define the terms before using them to explain the video, which makes it easier for the reader to follow and understand your analysis. When you say \"the script is an example of procedural knowledge that is represented in the video\", you leave it for the viewer to figure out what parts of the video comprises procedural knowledge, and analyze what is part of a script and what is not. While you distinguish very clearly between procedural knowledge and plan later in the post, you could have been more specific here too. Maybe stating what actions form a large part of the script (in terms of actions in the video) before explaining it would have been a better idea. In the second paragraph, you provide a very specific, good, and relevant example of why he was able to do the explained part of calculation, and explained it by stating that \"was able to reference a script of how to set up a long division problem from previous knowledge\". I think this was also a good chance to include how he attained this procedural knowledge; for example, by making a claim that he probably learned long division in middle school. I think it is important to mention this without going into detail because you frequently refer to his prior knowledge â€“correctlyâ€“ to explain his actions. Furthermore, you mention how Will hesitated to choose 2 as the correct number because he is doing mental math, however, isn\'t this also procedural knowledge? I think he knows from his previous experience that he has to make a calculated guess about the number he should choose. You manage to capture all major aspects of internal framework by mentioning locus of control although you don\'t explain it in detail. Overall, I found your post to be interesting and well-written.',10,2,'2016-02-22 03:00:33','2016-02-22 03:00:33'),(19,'I think your post is very well-organized in that you separate different aspects into different paragraphs and don\'t deviate from it. In the first paragraph, I was expecting that you would transition into how Ethan and Talie use the resources available to them to solve the problem. I also found it a little hard to understand when you mentioned \"primed Ethan and Talie in a myriad of ways, many of them subconsciously inbuilt into the situation\". In addition, I agree with the previous commenter in saying that it is important that you mention the purpose of using a paper and pencil, the resources, to solve the long division problem. This is a crucial information for explaining the role the externalization of problem-solving plays in completing any activity, in this case, calculating the quotient for the given long division problem. Your explanation of how the externalization of problem solving would have been different for people from different places was very good. You could have frequently referred to specific parts of the video throughout the post so that it would be more clear to the reader what part of the video you were using to explain, and for them to form their own opinion about it. I think your argument in the third paragraph was very important for the explanation of external cognition. In general, your post gave me a good idea about external cognition.',10,15,'2016-02-22 03:01:54','2016-02-22 03:01:54'),(20,'<p>I agree that it would be useful to describe how the externalization helps Zak as well. The first commenter makes many good points about the benefits Zak got from Maria&#39;s externalization and how that facilitated their collaboration. I especially like that you specifically pointed out that this helped Zak follow her thought process and make sure she was doing the arithmetic correctly. These are two very important actions, and it is especially good that you separated them. However, given the word limit of the analysis, I think the original author did a good job of describing the way Maria benefited from the externalization. The author did a good job of explaining the precise actions Maria took and how each one helped. I would argue that they did acknowledge the non-written external cues to some extent, and that helped further the point. They described the use of the pencil to mark the subproblems and draw arrows. While these are written down, they function in a similar way to pointing in that they reduce the memory load and don&#39;t directly contribute to the arithmetic. That could have been expanded in a longer response, but I think this one did a good job of going deep into a few actions rather than trying to squeeze a bunch into just 500 words.</p>\r\n',4,12,'2016-02-22 03:57:02','2016-02-23 03:37:59'),(21,'This analysis seems to veer towards the external framework towards the middle. For example, you identify the steps that Ariel takes to subtract the numbers and then describe how the notations at the top aid her memory, which is more external than cultural. One spot in this segment that seems to demonstrate cultural differences is at 2:57 when Katherine says \"see, I would be doing math... like writing down the multiplication.\" Ariel is attempting to perform mental math to figure out the number of times the current number fits into the divisor, whereas Katherine suggests writing it down instead. Both methods can be used to solve the problem, but each partner has a preferred method which probably stems from how she learned to perform long division. Ariel continues performing the calculation in her head, by estimating the number will go in 7 times \"because three times seven is twenty-one.\" Katherine\'s method of writing the numbers down will produce a more accurate answer, but take more time. There are pros and cons to each method, and both are indicative of the respective ways in which each partner learned long division.',4,10,'2016-02-22 04:29:51','2016-02-22 04:29:51'),(22,'I appreciate the very meticulous word and percentage count. The paper quoted was actually not a paper which the class read. While we are on the critical train, its better to begin your comment with something positive then continue to criticize the piece, and not the other way around for your few kind suggestions aren\'t cared about at that point. ',15,21,'2016-02-22 21:34:13','2016-02-22 21:34:13'),(23,'I like the fact that you chose the introductory segment of the video. As you said, this segment of the video contains many information about internal framework and allowed you to have a through and detailed analysis on the subject.\r\n\r\nYou mentioned that at the beginning of the long division process, Will directly placed a 2 above the fourth digit.  I think you did a very good job describing the process in detailed. However, it might be a good idea to have more analysis on the process.  Because even though it all happened in several seconds and it seems Will did nothing but placing a single number, the process required many mental activities.  At 0:15 second,  you mentioned the words Will said in the video.  I think the words you picked out was very helpful and explained itself in some way.\r\nIn the second  part, you talked about as the long division process went on, Will found it was getting more difficult to solve the problem.  I liked that you paid much attention on what Will said in the video and the efforts you spent on relating the information provided in what Will said to the concept we learnt in class.  However, readers might want to know how the internal locus of control work more specifically. \r\nOverall, itâ€™s an organized and well-written analysis with great attention on detail. ',28,2,'2016-02-22 23:40:59','2016-02-22 23:40:59'),(24,'The first paragraph clearly demonstrates the main discussion of this post, which is the internal procedural knowledge that Ariel masters for solving long division. It also clearly sets the scope of discussion, which is the fragment of the first 60 to 90 seconds in the video. It could be better if you paste the link to the video somewhere in the beginning of the post so that the reader can easily go to the video and watch it. The first part of the analysis showing how setting up a long division is internally embodied in Ariel is pretty good. It is an excellent evidence for proving that solving a long division is a procedural knowledge which Ariel has already achieved. However this fragment appears from the beginning of the video to about 0:25. It is not in the scope of your discussion. Also I really like the script part in the post. The script shows not only how solving a long division is driven by procedural knowledge, but also what each procedure exactly is. One problem is that, when applying the script to the situation, the analysis spreads through the full video, as you said at the very end of the post. ',13,5,'2016-02-22 23:48:34','2016-02-22 23:48:34'),(25,'You did a fantastic job on this analysis, especially in convincing the reader of the Internal framework\'s applicability to the selected video clip. What I found really interesting at the start of the clip is Brad\'s multiples chart, and how he goes about creating it. You noted that â€œInstead of attempting to visualize how many times 3,437 goes into 9,705 as most everyone else does, Brad decides to write out all the multiples of 3,437 on the side of the paper.â€ I figured that Brad prefers to fully externally represent his arithmetic problems, rather than making internal estimates. I then noticed that rather than writing out each successive multiple problem (including the numbers he is carrying over, etc), he relies mostly on mental math and â€œthinking aloud,â€ only marking down his final answers. Then later on, once solving the long division problem,  he fully wrote out each calculation instead of using the strict mental math from the multiples chart creation. This balance between using internal and external solving strategies was something I had yet to see, and found very interesting. \r\n\r\nAdditionally, we can really tell that Brad has solid procedural knowledge of solving long division problems, and that he can easily recall and exercise his own tried and true methods. It would be interesting to know if the use of a multiples chart was something that he initially learned when he first learned how to do long division, or if this was a trick he later thought of himself to solve the problem more efficiently.',8,7,'2016-02-23 00:01:22','2016-02-23 00:01:22'),(26,'I second the previous commenters remarks. Your analysis was fantastic. You touch upon each aspect of Talie and Ethan\'s interaction and truly highlight all that we have been discussing in class. I agree with the suggestion to break down your paragraphs for it would help the reader father understand and appreciate your train of though (but don\'t worry about the grammar). The quality and elaborations which you provided were exceptional. You showed a true understanding of the literature which we have read and discussed in class. Do you think that the conversation between Talie & Ethan could have been more direct?  I wish that you would have elaborated on the point that Talie didnâ€™t make strong enough evidences for Ethan to know that she had accepted Ethan\'s remarks prior. Elaborating on how did you know this and that section would enable you to answer my question about their interaction being more direct.',15,17,'2016-02-23 00:14:11','2016-02-23 00:14:11'),(27,'I really like that you pulled out Chloeâ€™s statement from 0:38 (â€œSo, Iâ€™m guessing [the divisor] goes in [the dividend] twice, it might go in there a third timeâ€), and I think a lot of focus can be put on how she comes to that conclusion and what she does with that guess: even though she states that she assumes the divisor should be multiplied by two, she quickly multiplies it by three to ensure that she is making the correct choice.  As you mentioned, she has the procedural knowledge of how to perform long division, but when she became unsure which number (two or three) to multiply with, she paused her action to explore other possibilities and altered her plan based off of the results of these explorations.\r\n\r\nLater you state that Chloe was likely able to continue with the division because she â€œhas presumably carried out the process enough times in her life.â€  Why do you think that she would express doubt that she knows how to divide such â€œbig numbersâ€ as the one in this problem?  The procedure she used throughout her life can be used on numbers of any size, but Chloe appears to be uncertain in her abilities.  There could have been an issue in her confidence to apply her long unused procedural knowledge to create a plan for this specific number, though she obviously gets past this issue and solves the problem successfully.',6,16,'2016-02-23 00:20:34','2016-02-23 00:20:34'),(28,'Itâ€™s very interesting that you argued that the division problem was written backwards from the more familiar left to right formation of English, as I would consider math to be a separate language in its own right.  Numbers, though represented by different symbols by different cultures, are universal as a concept, and so it should follow that the process of division and other arithmetic functions are performed in similar ways.  That you would point out Arielâ€™s placement of the dividend on the left as illogical makes a cultural connection between mathematics and writing that Iâ€™m not sure exists.  Though the mechanics of physically writing numbers on a paper is similar to writing letters down, the mental actions are incredibly different.  This isnâ€™t at all related to the general argument you make in this post that Arielâ€™s actions are influenced by her cultureâ€™s history with division and its subprocesses such as subtraction, but I do think itâ€™s interesting that you state that writing the divisor to the left of the dividend doesnâ€™t make sense, and thus was most likely taught by somebody else and is a cultural mechanism.  I disagree that if the dividend is more important that it should be written first, and if you donâ€™t mind me saying, I think you are projecting some of your own cultural assumptions onto this external representation.  I think that your assumptions of the world add an interesting second layer to the analysis.',6,10,'2016-02-23 00:24:25','2016-02-23 00:24:25'),(29,'I heavily concur with the previous commenter. I feel that your script was a great addition to your post. It showed that you understood the purpose and breakdown of scripts as we learned in class and from the Clark reading. This assignment, however, was meant to focus on a small clip yet the majority of your post was a script of the entire video segment. You mentioned that you to were going to keep the lens \"tightly focused on the internal, free of mentionings of interaction\", what inspired you to do that? Would you really consider riding a bicycle to require \"little or no thought\"? Your text also seemed quite repetitive talking about Ariel\'s actions being taken with no obvious thought. These words were repeated almost verbatim at least four or five times in a row. It would have been nice for you to flesh out other findings or ideas, or maybe find a better clip.',15,5,'2016-02-23 00:27:03','2016-02-23 00:27:03'),(30,'You brought up great points in your commentary. Ken\'s zone of proximal development definitely benefited from his interactions with Rick. Could we say that Ken\'s progression and relearning of long division problem solving was interactionally managed, as without his interactions with Rick, it might have come to a standstill?',8,11,'2016-02-23 00:38:05','2016-02-23 00:38:05'),(31,'A great job defining what an \'interactive\' activity consists of as well as good overall understanding of Abby & Benedikt\'s issue completing the long division problem. The first paragraph can be confusing when you compared an interactive activity to that of a competitive process, where later on you describe the interaction between Abby & Benedikt as sort of teamwork. I recommend thinking about the first paragraph\'s wording to fix this small issue. You pulled a strong example from Abby and Benedikt\'s video, one that focused on their overall arching issue in their work together. You then go on to break down their interactive process into 5 steps, both creative and helpful to the reader. It easily clarified the points you wanted to get across in your analysis. Some helpful tips: try lining out the specific characteristics of interactive experiences in those five steps. For example: in your first step, you state that Abby & Benedikt begin their interactive process, nothing more. Maybe with the first step, outline the direct importance of vocal interactivity, then go on to physical in step two (if Benedikt points with his finger, et cetera), and so on and so forth. This would bring your whole analysis together: providing examples of Abby & Benedikt\'s interactive process and defining what interactivity is as well as answering the question: why did it take so long for Abby & Benedikt to solve the problem? where did they go wrong? what can they do better as an interactive team?',20,19,'2016-02-23 01:09:37','2016-02-23 01:09:37'),(32,'I agree that this is a challenging clip to analyze for the cultural historical framework, but you brought in an interesting perspective by comparing your personal method of solving long division to the method that she demonstrated. The above commenter highlighted why that comparison ties into the cultural historical framework so well: it was through generations of teaching this method to students, who had to learn and practice it so that they could teach it to future generations, that you are each familiar with your personal long division solving styles. An examination of this helps us to understand the role that the cultural historical plays in our own microgenesis. I also liked that you brought up her use of  internalization in solving the long division problem. I wonder if this analysis could be extended to incorporate movement from the inter psychological to the intra psychological, as that seems to be a key idea in the cultural historical framework.',8,23,'2016-02-23 01:12:58','2016-02-23 01:12:58'),(33,'Overall, your analysis has strong footing, pulls great examples from the video, and defines the terms, inter/intrapsychological from class (that unfortunately haven\'t appeared in other analysis\'; including mine) with context. This, along with the rest of your analysis shows immense attention to detail. I was confused however with the start of the analyses; it was missing a stronger definition of what \'Cultural Historic\' elements do. Although you do provide good examples of what Cultural Historic elements are (i.e. calculator, pencil & paper, etc), when I was finished reading I couldn\'t help but be slightly confused. Are Cultural Historic elements strictly mediating artifacts, problem solving techniques, or both? With your analyses, it is easily understandable the effect a Cultural Historic element has on solving a problem, like long division. You do this by referencing another group\'s YouTube video. I wish you were to go more in depth and point out strong differences between the two techniques of problem solving. Which one is more efficient? why are they different? Your ending paragraph of your analysis does not ever mention Cultural Historic elements. If so, please go back and clarify. All in all, an informative piece. ',20,6,'2016-02-23 01:34:40','2016-02-23 01:34:40'),(34,'It is a great idea to use a quote from a relative resource to initiate the discussion so that the reader can clearly see what this post is going to be about. However, a quote that occupies two-thirds of the spaces of the first paragraph will be too overwhelming. If you could pick up one or two sentences, or to sum up the authorâ€™s idea, the introduction part will be much better than this. I really like that you take the transcription of the video. However, since you are actually analyzing the external factors in this short video fragment, especially that you are discussing the effectiveness of pencil and paper in Willâ€™s expressing his idea, I think it is better for you to also add Willâ€™s movements and gestures, such as writing on the paper, to the transcription. With these movements and gestures, it will be easier to analyze more precisely and accurately on every detail, and easier to produce a better discussion.\r\n',13,21,'2016-02-23 01:51:08','2016-02-23 01:51:08'),(35,'Very clever post! The internal process of problem solving is always best explored by the person who solved the problem themselves, because they know what they\'re doing internally. A slight issue with looking at your own internal method is that although you understand what steps you took, but it might be difficult for your reader to follow. You could clarify that issue with the following: define what an internal process is within your first paragraph (also, there is no link to the YouTube video). A definition would help provide the reader a good basis to what you are trying to prove. Your post is incredibly descriptive, and helpfully chronological. But as I continue reading, I can\'t help but feel as if I\'m missing something. You describe your problem solving steps, but you don\'t relate those steps to internal problem solving characteristics. It would be helpful if you revised those areas. Also consider referencing the time in the video when you took each step you described above (so I can follow your thought process along with the video). Great post, incredibly detailed, and can\'t wait to read more!',20,4,'2016-02-23 01:56:52','2016-02-23 01:56:52'),(36,'I really like your idea of describing this long division process in terms of a script. I think this recursive cycle you describe articulates it well and would be perfect if we had to hard code the process of long division into a computer program. On a more serious note, there is a lot going on in the final paragraph and I think some of the wording can be confusing. So you can see into the mind of someone else reading your paper, I want to describe Scene 1, 2, and 3 in my own words. From what you said, I think Scene one is figuring out what subcases have to be solved to find the overall answer.  Additionally, I think this scene shares a lot of attributes with the â€˜spontaneous sub-plansâ€™ you describe in the previous paragraph. Scene two, then, is the solving of the sub-problems. Scene 3 comes after scene 2 and decides whether to go back and find another sub-problem or decide that an answer has been found. Hopefully these paraphrasing are helpful, and if I\'m wrong please comment on this to let me know where I went wrong in understanding your description! ',27,4,'2016-02-23 02:01:30','2016-02-23 02:01:30'),(37,'It\'s interesting you mention that physical objects repeatedly used for a task eventually become part of your mental operations, because immediately after Will asks for a calculator, he also mentions, \"It\'s funny being filmed, huh?\" If Will has used a calculator so many times that he pictures a calculator as integral to doing math, it\'s interesting to note the converse ... he probably doesn\'t do math while being watched or filmed. It\'s also interesting how cultural artifacts affect internal and externalization. Kathy probably didn\'t internalize the use of a calculator when doing basic arithmetic calculations, which is why she noticed Will not multiplying correctly. Instead of internalizing the use of a calculator, Kathy internalized the physical representation of the math problem (how to multiply on paper). By going through the exercise with Kathy, Will also learned (or recalled) the correct way to multiply, which ultimately will change his internalized idea of what it means to do math, and in the future, this experience becomes another cultural historic experience that he will draw from.',26,3,'2016-02-23 02:10:25','2016-02-23 02:10:25'),(38,'I agree with the person above me, and I think the segment of the video you chose to analyze was a good source for analysis. I also agree with the top person, and your having defined the terms you use is very helpful. \r\nAs far as I can tell, the video starts after they have set up the problem. This isn\'t a criticism of you, more of Kathy\'s quickness to bring out her phone and begin recording, but I think that a video where the process of setting up the problem was captured on video would have been a good opportunity to analyze production of a plan and employment of procedural knowledge. Your note of Will\'s comment at :15 is indicative (to me) that the procedural knowledge required to solve the problem wasn\'t immediately at hand, though, which is the sort of material I imagined the setup process providing, so I don\'t think your choice of video was flawed. \r\nI also think that you were right on the money at the end of the clip, and his comments about calculator use indicated to me that his initial plan was not perfectly tuned to the task and resources at hand. His actions and his approach to the problem show him to be confident and capable at arithmetic (as he did the sub-steps of the long division in his head and not on paper), but the numbers involved were too large for even his internal skills to be able to competently handle the work he had to do. ',18,2,'2016-02-23 02:13:30','2016-02-23 02:13:30'),(39,'Great analysis! My favorite part of your analysis is when you talk about how both a pen/paper and a calculator are tools for completing the long division problem. Your analysis in the first paragraph is good and interesting, however I think it would be a good idea if you included a section comparing and contrasting the cultural historic differences between a pen/paper and a calculator. Both have rich histories and have made impacts on every studentâ€™s in this classâ€™s life. Clearly at one point in our lives we had to learn how to do both, and judging from Willâ€™s comments in the video clip, we have preferences about which artifact is better. Ultimately, this is just a tangential suggestion about another layer of analysis you could add and I felt the need to share it. You could also connect this to the second paragraph because Will knows the procedure of how to do this problem on a calculator but is making mistakes about how to do it by hand. Several cultural historic factors can contribute to that. ',27,6,'2016-02-23 02:25:08','2016-02-23 02:25:08'),(40,'I think your choice for when in the video to analyze was smart. Because the interactive framework is inherently and foundationally social in ways that (it can be argued) other frameworks are more broadly social, you needed to choose a video clip where those interactions and their patterns were well-established and fluid. That wouldnâ€™t have worked if the clip you chose was at the beginning of the problem-solving process, because Talie and Ethan wouldnâ€™t have spent enough time solving the problem for them to have a basis of interaction in the ways that the interactive framework requires. \r\nI also agree with the person above, and I appreciate the depth with which you went into the interaction Your citation of specific sentences that they each said and specific arithmetical operations they performed allows you to apply the framework in detail to the operations that Ethan and Talie performed as they solved the problem. Particularly, it was smart to mention that they used sentences like â€œrightâ€ and â€œso now we have thisâ€ to affirm their knowledge of where the problem stood, and to confirm that they both had mutual knowledge of where in the problem they were. Similarly, your having noted of where in the process of solving the problem they were unsure of the accuracy of the otherâ€™s contribution was also smart to mention, such as when Talie told Ethan to add the 2 to the quotient and Ethan responded â€œokayâ€¦â€. and then detailing Talieâ€™s explanation of her reasoning and Ethanâ€™s subsequent acceptance of her explanation, was all good to mention. Nice work!',18,14,'2016-02-23 02:30:02','2016-02-23 02:30:02'),(41,'I agree with the above commenter that you could use some more examples. One thing I noticed in the Talie and Ethan video is that, at the very end of the clip you chose (close to 1:30), Ethan carries over the remainder in a way that\'s different than how most students in elementary school are taught, and Talie mentions something like, \"I usually do it in the other direction, but yeah.\" It\'s a bit hard to hear, but it\'s clear that since Talie learned the method a different way, she was originally slightly confused by what Ethan was doing, but then understood and verified that it was just as accurate as the way she was taught. In addition to having two different cultural and historic perspectives on something as tiny as carrying the remainder when doing subtraction, Talie and Ethan were also probably taught in their previous math classes that they should verify their calculations .. hence, why Talie mentioned that she did it differently, \"but yeah\", Ethan\'s way is also correct. You can also use this example of Ethan and Talie being taught to check their calculations and verify with their peers because, throughout the entire one minute segment, Ethan (who\'s doing the math) frequently asks Talie if she agrees with what he\'s doing. ',26,24,'2016-02-23 02:32:07','2016-02-23 02:32:07'),(42,'I think you selected a very good segment of the video to work on, and gave a detailed description of the important elements in it. For example, they were discussing on getting the correct answer from a calculator in order to reach the final answer efficiently, and also how Abby drew the arrows to align the digits, and many others. It is also what I could improve on my own writing to be more specific like you did. These are wonderful catches. It would be better if more analyses could be done on these observations. The part that Abby internalized as her conversation with Benedikt proceeded might need stronger evidences or analyses to support your argument. I assume it was because she accepted and internalized Benediktâ€™s rejection to her starting all over again and continued her division instead of insisting on her own ideas? Moreover, would there be any other inter to intrapsychological moments besides this one?\r\n\r\nYou compared the differences between your selection of video with Saad and Mojirâ€™s, which I also wrote about. It is true that they possibly learned different ways of solving division because of different school system and cultural background, it might also be related to historical reasons as their ancestors found different ways to lay out the division. \r\n\r\nPersonally I found how Abby decided to align the digits very interesting, which differs from people doing long division in other videos. It could be microgenesis â€“ a moment-by-moment decision because she found out there were too many digits to follow through along with doing the division. Hope these points could help.\r\n',25,20,'2016-02-23 02:36:10','2016-02-23 02:36:10'),(43,'I think this was a very good interactive analysis and I liked how you included the transcript of the specific part you\'re looking at. You completely broke down each microinteraction and analyzed every facet of that specific section of the transcript well. I especially liked how you analyzed Katherine\'s phrase, \"Then you can take the one down, right?\". You mentioned how Katherine, based on other small hints in their interactions, deduced that Ariel was having trouble with something, and volunteered a tip, and then at the end of her tip, offered up a, \"right?\" as an invitation to Ariel to attempt taking that step and respond to it. One thing I disagree with, though, is that you said that their conversation did not entirely follow the Sacks, Schlegoff, and Jefferson rules because their conversation was not entirely party administered. I agree that their conversation was not completely party administered, and that some rules were set before hand that changed this structure of this conversation, but still this conversation occurred between two peers with equal social status, and usual turn taking conventions did indeed occur. There was very little talking over each other, one person spoke at a time, and they went back and forth talking to each other- all in accordance with these rules, because they\'re equals in this scenario, and neither member had a higher status and dominated the conversation.',22,13,'2016-02-23 02:37:22','2016-02-23 02:37:22'),(44,'To first commenter:\r\nYou are right on the break-up of the paragraphs. When I was constructing the discussion, I only considered about the two main parts, the interaction management and the grounding knowledge. Since there are three managements and three pieces of grounding knowledge, I can definitely separate the paragraphs into six of them.\r\n\r\nTo second commenter:\r\nWhich part of Talie & Ethan\'s conversation could be more direct? I guess you are talking about the construction of the first grounding knowledge. I still think that Talie and Ethan didn\'t understand each other until the second half of the conversation. Talie was talking about the result of the divisor divides the first dividend, while Ethan was saying about how many digits should be the first dividend. This is the evidence that they misunderstood each other. And as the conversation went on, Talie and Ethan both somehow realized the misunderstanding and correct themselves in their turn. However, I should still try to make the argument clear and not confusing and articulate myself as well as possible.',13,17,'2016-02-23 02:45:32','2016-02-23 02:45:32'),(45,'Thanks to both commenters above for taking the time to read and comment on my post. I should have included information about whether the interaction was scripted/unscripted and egalitarian/autocratic as the first commenter suggested. You provide a good explanation of both too, which I agree with. In addition, I did include that Ethan and Talie self-select as a turn-allocation technique but I think I could have been more detailed about it. I am glad that both of you found the analysis easy to follow and that you agree with most of it.',10,14,'2016-02-23 02:53:09','2016-02-23 02:53:09'),(46,'This is a good internal analysis of this video segment because of how thoroughly you examine each action that occurs in the video and try to guess Chloe\'s thought process. Also, it\'s helpful that she\'s verbalizing some of her thoughts in the video, as makes her actions much easier to analyze and takes some of the guesswork out of it. Also, I like that you break down the problem into smaller subproblems of multiplication and division, and talk about how Chloe has procedural knowledge of those operations, which she uses to combat those subproblems and get to the bigger problem. I think that just about all of your projections about Chloe\'s thought process are correct and agree with them also- after each assumption you make about her thought process, you back it up with evidence in the video. Your projections are also very logical and seem to be completely accurate for a rational being. The reason your interpretation of Chloe\'s internal thought process is so accurate is probably because you can put yourself in her position, as a student who hasn\'t done long division in a while, and throughout the video, think about how you\'d approach each task in the problem, and assume that Chloe is thinking along similar lines. However, I disagree with your statement that her \"procedural knowledge has become embodied throughout her schooling career\", as I don\'t think the procedural knowledge for the steps of long division can be embodied, and her constant uncertainty in the video shows that the knowledge is not, in fact, embodied.',22,16,'2016-02-23 03:16:39','2016-02-23 03:16:39'),(47,'First of all, I appreciated the side note at the start of the analysis. I think a whole paper could be written on the cultural historic aspects of VVS could and should be written. Iâ€™d appreciate hearing an opinion of the external frameworks of VVS. \r\n\r\nOn a more serious note, this is a great analysis of the external frameworks of long division. The use of quotes from Kirsh makes for a strong argument. I specifically like the second quote where you talk about how Chloe becomes comfortable with an approach and her cognitive burden is subsequently lightened. I think writing more about that would be a good idea. You could say something along the lines of people start by looking for external frameworks that make them comfortable and allow them to continue at an easier pace. Alternatively, you could compare what you say about Chloe in the second paragraph with the quote from the first paragraph to tie the two together and create a more powerful conclusion. From what you say, I can tell that you mean her actions are â€˜[reducing] her cognitive load, so a transition to the first quote would be natural. All of this is just a suggestion though, the analysis is very good already.  \r\n',27,22,'2016-02-23 03:30:54','2016-02-23 03:30:54'),(48,'You did a good job analyzing how Will and Kathy managed to work together on the division problem and relating back to the article we read. I like how you point out that they talked about using a calculator is an internalization movement because previous calculator usage changed how people solve math problems like long division. It is very true that using a calculator almost became our intuition, whereas it used to be much different before the invention of calculator. It is also a good point to consider that later Will learned through his conversation with Kathy and that he corrected his answer to solve the multiplication as an internalization process. Additionally, you are showing that it is externalization that Kathy, using her knowledge, pointed out Willâ€™s mistake and gave him suggestions. I focused more on externalization to internalization, while I found your analyzed in both ways. Again, good job on relating the externalization with the reading and quoting Vygotskyâ€™s argument, which makes your argument strong. That gave me a new perspective to look at the video I chose. However, I did not really see the analysis of differences between your video and other videos in terms of the way of doing long division â€“ whether Will and Kathy did anything different from others and what kind of differences that would be. \r\n',25,3,'2016-02-23 03:40:36','2016-02-23 03:40:36'),(49,'I think overall you did a very good job. First, you gave a big picture description on the video you chose. The words informal, cooperative and verbal problem-solving highly summarized the video.  Then you explained the role for each person in the process of doing long division, which gave the readers a clear image about the interaction between the two people. On the second paragraph,  you had a through and detailed depiction on the interaction between Talie and Ethan. You also categorized the conversation into an interactionally managed model of turn taking.  I like you had a brief explanation on almost every movement of the two people, but it seems a little confusing to me how those movement related back to the interactionally managed model of turn-taking. Maybe it could be better if you add some explanation on the concept.\r\nI also like the choice of the video. It contains many interactions although it was not planned between the two. You paid much attention to the conversation between Ethan and Talie. And its good to see that you pointed out turn-taking even in words like: OK, Right, which reminds me that turn-taking lies in the nature of conversation. \r\n',28,14,'2016-02-23 03:42:17','2016-02-23 03:42:17'),(50,'I thought that this post was well-written, and well-constructed. I appreciated the quotes from the literature that we have read for class, because it allowed me to put the analysis of the clip into perspective in regards to what we have read so far. One particular piece of their post that I enjoyed was the paragraph that was centered around a quote from Alexander Luria, and the idea that tools â€œnot only radically change his conditions of existence, they even react on him in that they effect a change in him and his psychic condition.â€ This reminds me of a concept that Rick has discussed not only in this class, but in his other class, Human-Computer Interaction, and that is the idea of external cognition, of â€œleaning on the world.â€ External cognition is the act of using tools around us, both material and symbolic, to allow us to remember more information. A planner is one such example of this: a planner allows us to write down important dates to remember them, or to use to-do lists to keep track of what we need to get done. By allowing the planner to remember everything for us, we free up more space in our heads for other information. Because Will has â€œleaned onâ€ this calculator, and allowed it to do work for him, it has resulted in a â€œchange inâ€¦his psychic condition.â€ Another example of a tool that would to a change in his psychic condition could be a laptop, or a cell phone. A critique that I have for this post is the paragraph focusing on how internalization and externalization play a role in this clip. While this paragraph is interesting, it is not necessary for the post, and I feel that it could be better spent discussing how Willâ€™s method of completing the long division problem differs from another member of the class, or on a more in-depth analysis of the clip from a cultural-historic perspective, starting with the microgenesis plane, and working up to the physical plane. \r\n',24,3,'2016-02-23 04:35:46','2016-02-23 04:35:46'),(51,'I appreciated that a script of the clip was provided so that the reader could make references to it as they read. In regards to how well this post analyzes the clip from the perspective of interactive correspondence, the interaction between Talie and Ethan is not explicitly referred to this way. The dialogue between the two is described thoroughly, but not much reference is made to how the interaction between the two could be considered to be an interactive/collaborative model of communication. The post does discuss the act of exchanging ideas and acknowledgement that occurs between Talie and Ethan. Additionally, I appreciated how the interaction between Ethan and Talie was described as a party administered, interactionally managed system. Instead of spoon feeding the explanation of what that is to us, the author gives a brief overview of what that system entails, which allows the reader to better recall the subject matter without the author remembering everything for them. This post also does a good job of breaking down the internal versus the external interactive aspects of the clip; i.e., Talie and Ethanâ€™s interaction with the piece of paper Ethan is writing on is external interaction, and the exchange of ideas as well as Ethanâ€™s internalization of Talieâ€™s ideas and suggestions for solving the problem are an example of internal interaction. I also appreciated the mention of how the two use these interactions to increase the common ground between them, as this is an interesting concept to me in regards to communication. \r\n',24,9,'2016-02-23 04:37:48','2016-02-23 04:37:48'),(52,'Thank you so much for leaving such well thought-out comments! What I took away from both of these comments is that the weakest part of my post is the section about intra-/interpsychological interactions. After looking over my post and giving it more thought, I definitely agree with you guys about that. In order to more strongly make that point, I should have either provided better references/evidence from our readings for the clip that I did choose, or I should have picked a different part of the video. Both comments also indicated that I could have gone into more detail regarding the cultural-historic differences between how Abby and Mojir set up their long division problems. Part of the reason I avoided going too much into depth with that is because I did not want to make too many assumptions about their cultural backgrounds, but I see now that I could have added more depth to my analysis while still avoiding these assumptions. ',24,20,'2016-02-23 04:51:07','2016-02-23 04:51:07'),(53,'really good analysis and liked that part where you pointed out ken\'s confusion about the next phase of progress at 1:25. While i was watching the video, i thought he was questioning himself to get an answer rather than asking Rick. Although as a part of the process Rick helped him out and ken responded accordingly. Well I think when they both were participating in a same thing and their roles were different (Ken was analyzing the problem and writing that down, Rick was video recording and analyzing the problem as well) one common thing was they both were analyzing the problem in mind, hence Rick didn\'t wait for the confirmation whether Ken was asking that to himself or to Rick, and gave the idea of pulling the 1 down. I noticed Ken\'s growing confidence when he almost went silent (in the middle of the video) and started to solve rest of the parts faster. Kens acceptance of Rick\'s suggestion also shows that Ken was also thinking about something similar (i guess) and their ideas matched which led ken to react right away.  ',14,11,'2016-02-23 06:08:11','2016-02-23 06:08:11'),(54,'The Ultramarine Giraffe -- I appreciate your feedback. Regarding the last part of your comment, the mistake seems like a minor error. However, it brings light to the fact that Will has forgotten part of the method of long division. I\'m sure it\'s something he knew at one time. However, until Kathy prompts him, he doesn\'t realize there is a mistake. In fact, he begins to justify his choice before realizing that she is correct. It\'s subtle but it shows that part of the method of long division was forgotten. In particular, he has forgotten which numbers to multiply to complete the next substep of the bigger long division problem. It\'s similar to what we\'ve talked about in class with Maria and Zak\'s video in which Maria forgets how to line up the numbers. It\'s a seemingly minor error but still makes obvious the fact that she has forgotten a part of the method of long division. The partner prompt marks the beginning of a process of internalization, which is a key idea in the cultural historic viewpoint, allowing the process to be recalled and the partner who has made the error to re-internalize information that was previously forgotten.',19,6,'2016-02-24 16:31:24','2016-02-24 16:31:24'),(55,'The Turquoise Hedgehog -- Thank you for your feedback. Ultimately, I left out some of the details related to the definition of what constitutes a cultural historic analysis because I thought it was more reasonable to use the limited space to analyze the video specifically, assuming that all members of the audience had enough of a background on what CHAT is through reading the paper and discussions in class. Mediating artifacts are used to reduce the cognitive load for the individual solving the problem. Writing down the numbers prevents you from having to remember them all in your head. Organizing the use of the paper helps remind you what stage in the process you are. The mediating artifacts do this in different ways which is why the approach to the problem changes based on the tool used. The final paragraph discusses a shift from interpsychological to intrapsychological through the process of internalization. This is directly relevant to the cultural historic theory. CHAT presents an argument that all activities are social in some way. For example, children learn by being coached by their parents. The interaction begins as an interpsychological learning process with the parents telling the child, step-by-step, what to do. Over time, the coaching steps become internalized by the child and the child is coached by his/herself and the process becomes intrapsychological. ',19,6,'2016-02-24 16:44:51','2016-02-24 16:44:51'),(56,'The Blue Stingray -- I appreciate your suggestion. I do agree that more depth of analysis on that topic could have been included. Ultimately, I had limited space and wanted to include a discussion regarding the shift from interpsychological to intrapsychological as well. Using a calculator was not an option here so, without a transcript, I felt it would be mostly conjecture to try to analyze how a student would proceed with a calculator instead of a pen and paper. However, I think it would be interesting to compare the use of a pen and paper, a calculator that can only be used to solve substeps of the problem, and a calculator to solve the problem as a whole. I imagine the process would be really different for each situation, further illuminating the point that the tool used in a problem solving scenario is important to how the problem solver proceeds.',19,6,'2016-02-24 16:50:14','2016-02-24 16:50:14'),(57,'@MelonLion I agree the scope is pretty inexact.  I really wanted to show how the entire script applied to the activity, and I do want to include the script in my second analysis as I think it\'s a vital component to analyzing anything within the context of the Internal framework.  That said, I could limit references to events happening outside of the first 30 or so seconds.                                             @OrchidLlama Keeping the analysis tightly focused on the internal was something I did because that was my assignment -- while there are plenty of cool interactions to look at here, I was assigned the Internal framework, so I want to make sure I am focusing on that.  Yes I would really consider riding a bicycle to require little thought, but maybe that\'s just personal bias as it\'s something I grew up doing... so maybe it\'s not the best example of procedural knowledge.  I\'ll try to cut down my repetitive prose. ',12,5,'2016-02-25 03:09:28','2016-02-25 03:09:28'),(58,'Thank you all for your comments! I do think it was a little difficult sometimes to differentiate between the script and procedural knowledge since the concepts go so hand-in-hand with each other so trying to decide whether an action was one or the other proved harder to explain than I thought. I also agree with you all that I could have focused on the locus of control a little more.',9,2,'2016-02-26 15:40:52','2016-02-26 15:40:52'),(59,'That\'s a very interesting point! I suppose our interpretations of Ken\'s questioning (who it was directed to, at least) can\'t be totally objective, but whomever we assume the question was directed towards still poses an interesting consideration from the turn-taking phenomena\'s standpoint. I also really liked your point about their paralleled mental activity. Though Ken is the main physical \"solver,\" in this transcript we can tell that Rick is also attempting to solve the problem mentally. There might have been cases where the participant recording didn\'t invest as much of their immediate thought into the problem, or perhaps they became distracted and would have needed to synchronize their thoughts with those of their partner\'s. But because both Rick and Ken were very much in sync, their interactions and communication flowed well and was understood by one another quite readily.',8,11,'2016-02-26 20:20:17','2016-02-26 20:20:17'),(60,'I wasnâ€™t entirely confident about stating that this conversation doesnâ€™t â€œquite fit the definition of a conversation as defined by Sacks, Schegloff, and Jefferson,â€ which you both noticed and commented on.  I wish I had expanded more on this particular idea in the draft.  What I meant to say was that in this particular set up of solving the problem (Ariel writing and Katherine recording) I would not consider both to be peers.  Ariel has direct control over the development of the solution while Katherine offers advice and support.  Ariel, in the end, has the option to accept or deny Katherineâ€™s involvement in the process.  This power imbalance is one of the causes of the misunderstanding I analyze:  Katherine being unsure of Arielâ€™s place in the problem.  Regarding my original point, this conversation not fitting Sacks, et al.â€™s definition, Iâ€™m not sure if this power imbalance changes the rules of this conversation, but I think it was significant enough to mention, though I was unsure of where to go with the idea originally, thus my unfinished half thought.',6,13,'2016-02-27 17:06:27','2016-02-27 17:06:27'),(61,'External:\r\n\r\nDefinition: From the External framework in my group: â€œDavid Kirsh, a leading cognitive scientist, states that the external framework is â€œany organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loadsâ€ (Kirsh 212).  An external or complementary strategy is used in place or in addition to a normal strategy to solve a cognitive task.  For example, consider the problem of solving a long division problem first without a calculator or the aid of pencil and paper.  This would be a normal strategy of solving the long-division problemâ€” clearly impossible for some people due to limitations in working-memory, a cognitive resource.  Consider the use of paper and pencil in addition to strictly cognitive resources when solving the long-division problem.  Most normal people can solve a long-division problem using the regularly taught procedure of long-division by paper and pencil in elementary school.  The algorithm allows the person to write sub-steps of the long-division problem externally to reduce their working memory loads, and allows them to solve the problem when most likely they wouldnâ€™t be able to solve it in their head, overloading their working memory.  Thus, the long-division procedure is an organizing activity recruiting external elements, the paper and pencil, to reduce working memory, a cognitive load.  It is clear then that the long-division procedure using a paper and pencil is a complementary strategy.  We show an example of using a complementary strategy to reduce cognitive loads by example using a video of Will and Kathy (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&feature=youtu.be) [0:00, 1:16] attempting a long-division problem using the strategy above, that is using a paper and pencil to enhance cognition when solving the long division problem.\r\n\r\nExample: Will and Kathy were trying to solve the long division problem, 3437/9705159253.  Note that most people would not be able to solve 3437/9705159253 in working memory without the use of any such procedure, and that most people would not be able to solve 3437/9705159253 in their head even if they were using the long division procedure in working memoryâ€” without the use of paper and pencil.  Although, there was no video that showed Kathy and Will performing the long-division procedure without paper and pencil, I will show just the sheer amount of working memory that would probably be used in doing so modeling working memory by the set WM initially containing divisor = 3437, and dividend = 9705159253.  For simplicity the larger the cardinality of WM will mean higher working memory loads.  The notation := will be used to denote an update of WM.  I will show by Will and Kathyâ€™s YouTube video that the use of a paper and pencil will greatly reduce the amount of working memory (as simulated by the set WM) to execute the long division procedure on the problem 3437/9705159253.  Hence, substantial evidence will be presented that the paper and pencil will is indeed a complementary strategy for reducing the cognitive load of working memory when performing long-division.  At 0:02 Will puts a 2 on top of the line above the dividend, and WM:= WM union {2}.  At 0:11,  Will adds the concept of 2 things to WM, the problem of figuring out how many times 3437 goes into 9,705 which we will denote p1.  Hence WM:=WM union p1.  At 0:15, Will figures out the solution = 6874 to that problem, and WM:=WM - {p1} union {solution}.  Note {p1} is not in WM anymore, as that information is no longer needed to solve the long-division problem.  Whenever the difference operation is used in an update of WM one can conclude that this was the reasoning for the operation. At 0:22, the problem denoted p2 = 9705 - 6874 is added to WM such that WM: = WM union {p2}.  Will solves p2 and realizes p2â€™s solution is sol2 = 2941.  Hence WM:=WM union {sol2}.  Will must then add the concept that he must bring a 1 down from the dividend which will be denoted by concept1.  Hence WM:= WM union {concept1}.  WM is updated with 29411 since the operation of concept1 on 2941 is 29411.  Hence, WM := WM - {concept1, 2941} union {29411}.  At 1:16, Will is realizes he needs to find out how many times 347 goes into 29411, which we will denote as operation1.  Hence, WM := WM union {operation1}.  Will comes to a solution, denoted new_solution to operation1, so WM:= WM union {new_solution}, and realizes it is wrong, and the memory used to denote that realization is denoted realization.  Hence WM:=WM union {realization}, and quickly after WM:= WM - {realization}-{new_solution}.  Will then realizes that the 3437 probably goes into 29411 8 times, which we will denote as instinct, so WM:= WM union {instinct}.  Clearly instinct must be validated, and these WM updates will continue.  Note that WM is growing in cardinality throughout the process of the long-division exercise.  As an exercise you can keep track of the actual elements in WM, as described in the analyzation.  Note that throughout the whole process WM := {empty-set} if Will is allowed to use paper and pencil as he is in the corresponding video clips to what is written above.  Hence, there is sufficient evidence that using a paper and pencil, reduces Willâ€™s cognitive load (working-memory) to essentially nothing, IE THE EMPTY SET, when the external elements of a pencil, and paper are recruited.  Thus, using a paper and pencil to solve the long-division problem is a complementary strategy.\r\n\r\nWhen I used the internal framework to analyze the long-division problem, I proposed an instance of a procedure, (*) from the set of procedures in procedural knowledge.  Similarly, I proposed a script for long-division with the integer track (**).  I originally thought the point of this assignment was just to internalize the concepts of scripts and procedural knowledge when applied to an exampleâ€” to understand the theoretical models in the papers, using the video clips to give a concrete playing field to apply the model to.  However, I didnâ€™t realize that the point of the analyzation was to actually see what was going on in the actual concrete clips until Friday, the 25th in class. * and ** clearly werenâ€™t specialized enough for the task at hand.  When viewing otherâ€™s analyzations most of them had definitions of the form of analyzation they were using such as the external framework definition as well as clips to YouTube videos with second by second analysis of video. I didnâ€™t include definitions in my internal analyzation, or as tight an analysis on video clips.  I got great comments from others on my analysis.  Some of the helpful comments were to define what an internal framework is and, â€œrelating my problem solving steps to internal problem solving characteristicsâ€ instead of just listing the steps in * and **.  Thus, in my external analyzation I took this constructive criticism into account; I added a definition of the external/complementary strategy, had a link to my YouTube video, and focused on concrete video clips first and then used the external framework to make sense of the clips.  I think I gained a better idea of what was expected on the second iteration of my analysis. \r\n',7,4,'2016-02-29 22:07:21','2016-02-29 22:07:21'),(62,'@The Turquoise Hedgehog: Thanks for the positive feedback!  I appreciate the idea to put in a definition.  On almost every other analysis I read the definition helped get me refreshed with the concept almost instantaneously, even if I had read the paper before.  I have incorporated a definition on my newest post!  Also, I appreciate your advice to associate video clips times with the part of my analysis where the corresponding calculation is taking place.  I really didnâ€™t quite understand that the assignment wasnâ€™t supposed to be so generalized on first go, and looking at everyone elseâ€™s in the group has allowed me to see more of whatâ€™s expected.  Youâ€™re absolutely right that I didnâ€™t include what the relationships of the characteristics of the internal framework are to the minimal amount of problem solving steps Iâ€™ve described.  In my newest analysis I think I have made that relationship explicit and have incorporated times with each step.\r\n@The Blue Stingray: Thanks for the positive feedback!  I think youâ€™re absolutely right in the almost equivalent nature of paragraphs 1 (long-division as a procedure) and paragraph 2 (long-division as a script).  In a way the script has the procedure embedded in it.  I think you nailed the meaning of what I intended for the 3 scenes to be, and I think should have been a bit more clear about how I presented them as you said.',7,4,'2016-02-29 22:47:20','2016-02-29 22:47:20'),(63,'@AquaWombat, thank you for the input. There are two things that I want to hit one,  one is my competitive definition of interaction and the second is a response to your questions. \r\n\r\nYou said that interactions do not necessarily need to be competitive. Respectfully, I do not agree with that. the very notion of  problem solving implies that there is a problem that needs to be solved. in the interactive example of long division, the problem is a literal math problem. In football, the problem is that two teams want to win yet only one can. To add a new example, even talking can be competitive. In the class when we talked about turn taking in conversations, we discussed how people decide who gets to talk in order to get their point across. Obviously only one person can talk at a time for a conversation to be productive, and there is a competition (with rules and respect of course) between people trying to make their point. This is a critical and boarder line extreme view that puts a lot of interactions in a bad light for people who are less competitive, but in my definition I am not trying to frame being competitive as a bad thing. \r\n\r\nAlso in your response you ask what are the markers that signify whether forward progress has been made and, conversely, what are the markers for needing to do the opposite. Back in the video from 4:39 - 4:42 you see abby say â€œYeah, and the reminder always has to be less than this (the number). Thatâ€™s how you know you did it right. Uh-Oh the remainder is more. So it can go in a fourth time.â€ From that example, the evidence of forward progress is meeting some test or rule. In log division, it is doing subtraction between two numbers so that the result is less than the original divider number. In the same manor, if that test is failed, there is evidence that the person needs to retrace their steps. The point that I am trying to make is that in problem-solving, there is a test that has to be applied at the end of every interactive step that allows the person to keep progressing. \r\n',27,19,'2016-03-01 01:52:54','2016-03-01 01:52:54'),(64,'@TurquoiseHedgehog thank you for the constructive criticism. In my response to the AquaWombat I try to clarify the connection between interactivity and competition. I think my paragraph would have been a lot more clear if I was as detailed in my original post, but I also hear what you say about not addressing teamwork. Your comment made me realize that I never addressed the most serious sign over interactivity in this video: the teamwork between Abby and Benedict. I guess the reason I ignored it in the first place was that there seemed to be a weird teamwork dynamic in the video where Abby was doing the math and Benedict was videotaping and asking critical questions. I realize now that my interpretation of that was wrong. Benedict does ask productive questions in the segment and does try to help Abby (which I didn\'t notice at first). I think an entire paper could look at that perspective, but I\'ll try to connect it back to my original point of interactivity and competitiveness. Abby and Benedict working together as a team to solve the math problem does not change the fact that the core activity in this video is a team trying to solve an interactive problem. ',27,19,'2016-03-01 02:03:59','2016-03-01 02:03:59'),(65,'@theaquawombat, amazing point about considering other problem solving techniques. It would be interesting to see how different ways of the problem reduce the cognitive load. For example, in the video here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_E_xUgaDVa8 we can blame the use of a plain white sheet of printer paper as Abby & Benedikt\'s main struggle with solving the problem, organization. If they would have used a gridded piece of paper, the organization of the problem would be easier, giving them an easier time solving the problem, and reducing the overall cognitive load. As for certain cultural differences, I would have to research a bit more.',20,22,'2016-03-01 04:00:01','2016-03-01 04:00:01'),(66,'@theultramarinegiraffe You mention I should be more specific in terms of mentioning the use of different mental functions (i.e. memory). I was wondering if you could clarify?',20,22,'2016-03-01 04:05:06','2016-03-01 04:05:06'),(67,'@thebluestingray I\'m so glad you loved the beginning of my post...VVS is incredibly serious and I\'m glad you agree. And what\'s more serious than VVS!? Oh, external framework of course! You mentioned looking at external frameworks that people use first, and how they are more comfortable with it. I think it would be a good idea to continue with that train of thought, and analyze the internal thought processes when it comes to problem solving. If that\'s allowed of course. ',20,22,'2016-03-01 04:12:16','2016-03-01 04:12:16'),(68,'[0:48] Will: And how many times does this go into this? \r\n[0:48] Kathy: Yea\r\n[0:48] Will: Um. I donâ€™t know. Maybe 9. You think its 9? I don\'t know. I don\'t know. I wish we could use a calculator to do these sub steps. Maybe I should just multiply this out by 9 and see what it is. Yeah. I think thatâ€™s the best approach because I don\'t think that we are allowed to use calculators. Are we not allowed to use a calculator?\r\n[1:09] Kathy: I donâ€™t think so.\r\n[1:12] Will: So I have to multiply this by 9. Well I donâ€™t have to -- I could do something elseâ€¦\r\n[1:19] Kathy: Wait why would you multiply that by 9?\r\n[1:20] Will: Iâ€™m just seeing if, seeing if umâ€¦\r\n[1:23] Kathy: Youâ€™re supposed to multiply that by 9\r\n[1:24] Will: Well that was dumb. I was just being silly. Yeah. I forgot what we were doing.\r\n\r\nThis segment is very similar to Ethan and Talieâ€™s video as seen in â€œAnalysis of interactive elements in Ethan and Talie by: The Melon Lionâ€. Both Will and Kathy and Ethan and Talie held conversations which were locally managed, internally managed, and party administered. Both clips had group members valuing the ideas and questions of their partner, and not having one group member overpower or be subservient to the other during the long division problem solving.  In both sets of conversations only one person talked at a time -- both sets were fantastic at turn taking. For instance, Will would ask Kathy, â€œAre we not allowed to use a calculator?â€ (Pause) then Kathy would respond, â€œI donâ€™t think so.â€ At one point Will says, in a tone of certainty, â€œSo I have to multiply this by 9â€ (pause) then Kathy would follow with a questioning of his statement respectfully realizing that he had erred. Will then acknowledges his misstep and finishes his turn by fixing which number he actually meant to multiply by nine. Throughout both short clips many questions were asked and many suggestions were given between Ethan and Talie as well as Kathy and Will. The interaction management and the grounding knowledge was overall evident in this clip. With regard to grounding knowledge however, it was interesting to hear Will say, (at 1:45) \"I probably havenâ€™t done this since I was in third grade.\" In out clip Will interacted with the physical environment using a paper and pen.\r\n\r\nWhereas my first analysis was lacking much reading into the chosen segment I have felt that reading the comments of my fellow classmates and their own analysis posts have given me both the knowledge and ability to really flesh out more in depth thoughts and readings about these few filmed seconds. Though people donâ€™t like criticism, I felt that the anonymity of commenting and being commented on greatly strengthened our writing and analysis. This feature, let students really help their classmates out by crafting brutally honest responses. Because I received theses I know areas I need to focus on more and have new tools to utilize for future analyses. In addition, my last post followed the prompt posted on the Latte class using a short conference paper (complementary strategies) on external cognition as my guide. This analysis was modeled of peer posts and comments. \r\n',15,21,'2016-03-01 04:54:21','2016-03-01 04:54:21'),(69,'@thebluestingray. Thank you for clearing up the teamwork issue! Your thought process makes things clear, I never saw it that way either. ',20,19,'2016-03-03 21:59:42','2016-03-03 21:59:42'),(70,'@theaquawombat, Awesome!',20,6,'2016-03-03 22:02:14','2016-03-03 22:02:14'),(71,'@theultramarinegiraffe, glad I could help! I learned a lot as well',20,4,'2016-03-03 22:04:17','2016-03-03 22:04:17'),(72,'Thanks for both of your comments! I guess i could add more explanation on why the differences between the video I chose and Saad and Mojir\'s is cultural and historic. I also agree that it would be helpful to specify the examples i mentioned. Also using what the second commentary included, the part in 1:30, it is helpful to make my analyses more detailed.',25,24,'2016-03-04 20:42:35','2016-03-04 20:42:35'),(73,'PLEASE REFER TO THE FINAL DRAFT WHEN REVIEWING MY FIRST DRAFT! I WAS NOT ABLE TO SUBMIT AT 11PM BECAUSE I THOUGHT THE DEADLINE WAS AT MIDNIGHT!',9,26,'2016-03-09 05:29:06','2016-03-09 05:29:06'),(74,'Good start! Don\'t forget to include the typed out version of your transcript at the top to make it easier for your audience to read as it says in the assignment. It may also help to include line numbers next to the transcript so you can easily and clearly refer to specific pieces of the conversation. Think about how you can organize the space for your answer in order to make it easier for the reader to understand your points. I encourage you to be more specific in your analysis as a whole. It may help to split the analysis into subsections within each part. Particularly, in part B, doing an analysis that, in detail, ties your transcript into each of the four characteristics presented in the Person Plus paper would be beneficial. Overall, reasonable first draft.',19,30,'2016-03-09 14:58:14','2016-03-09 14:58:14'),(75,'Good structure to your response. Itâ€™s easy to see the part of the assignment youâ€™re working on which makes it easier for readers to understand your arguments and analysis. I find the use of arrows somewhat confusing. I encourage you to actually number them if you intend to refer to the arrows by number. I feel like the discussion is too far away from the arrows which requires more work from the reader to understand what youâ€™re referring to. It may be useful to transfer the transcript to text with line numbers and refer to line numbers instead, copying in the relevant text directly into your discussion and analysis. Part A of your analysis is good. You give good detail and convey understanding of the terms. Perhaps you can tie the components into each other in more depth. Each aspect is interrelated so it is important to discuss this relationship. Parts C and D could use more examples and analysis to make your discussion more concrete.',19,39,'2016-03-09 19:25:24','2016-03-09 19:25:24'),(76,'Good use of the papers in your response. Itâ€™s important to get up close to the transcript. Itâ€™s not simply about using the terms and definitions, but relating the terms to the specific transcript youâ€™re analyzing. The aspects that refer directly to the transcript could use more detail and depth in analysis. For Part C, I encourage you to physically break it up into subsections as you analyze each of the four characteristics. It might be easier for readers to understand your analysis for Part D if itâ€™s broken up as well. Keep in mind that the use of space can contribute by reducing cognitive load. Itâ€™s important for presenting analyses as well. Good first draft though.',19,40,'2016-03-09 19:38:56','2016-03-09 19:38:56'),(77,'Excellent analysis! Your thoughts are very clear, in depth and well organized. I am curious if you think one of these frameworks captures the underlying phenomena in this transcript better than the others? \r\nThere are a lot of frameworks going on in the transcript but I think that the most significant aspect of their conversation is the contribution and acceptance phases and how it lacks to establish common ground. Like you said, the two parties are constantly making contributions to their conversation and conveying their thoughts. In lines 1 through 7 person A is skeptical of the praise person B gave their work. Person A contributes examples of the weaknesses in his/her problem solving, expecting person B to agree and establish common ground. However, this does not happen. Instead person B never accepted the criticism person A gave to his/her own work. Person B decides to compliment the work done by person A, preventing any common ground from being established. In fact, it doesn\'t feel like the two ever established common ground when talking about the original problem solving done by person A. The only common ground established was in line 3, 13 and line 19, none of which had to do with the contributions person A made about his/her own problem solving.\r\n\r\n- Grey Crocodile',23,34,'2016-03-10 19:19:24','2016-03-10 19:19:24'),(78,'Hi Plum Penguin, I think you did a nice job covering all the bases of the problem. In terms of \"virtual\" co-presence, you looked it in a very interesting way. I would suggest maybe comparing the \"virtual\" co-presence interaction with how it would have been if they were face-to-face. A lot can be said. I liked what you said about the dialectic relationship and how this environment is not the best example. I was struggling myself with this concept and how it applied to the situation. I think you brought some nice insight on this particular case. Overall, I think you did a nice job. I would recommend maybe expanding your thoughts in the first part of your analysis just to be more thorough and clear about what you are saying and why your examples apply to that particular case. ',9,32,'2016-03-11 16:47:47','2016-03-11 16:47:47'),(79,'Hi The Green Impala, good work. The analysis you did on grounding and access framework was very clear and thorough. You did a good job indicating what it was you talked about and how the examples linked to the concepts. I think you could have followed through better in your joint problem space analysis. Turn-taking is a huge concept with lots of dynamics that I think you could think about to incorporate in your final draft. I think you laid down a good foundation by providing nice definitions, but you should get more in depth as to how those things actually apply.',9,45,'2016-03-11 16:56:05','2016-03-11 16:56:05'),(80,'I like how you structure your analysis! You gave very clear and specific examples, and did analysis of those examples directly under them, and this makes your points very clear and easy to understand. The separation of comments show which part is a presentation phase, and which part is a acceptance phase. I also like that you pointed out the \"plus\" refers to platform, and that helps your explanation of the four access characteristics. It\'s also good that you gave the definition of terms each time. The only thing that I feel confused is about how you explain \"knowledge\" in part c. I did not get the idea of what kind of knowledge is shared between the two students. It would be better if you could give a broader idea about what kind of knowledge it is besides the example you gave.',17,35,'2016-03-11 17:20:55','2016-03-11 17:20:55'),(81,'Your analysis was comprehensive, well thought out and seemed to cover what was expected of you. Two small points to consider with regard to the Access Framework. For knowledge you can also add that when commenting on their peerâ€™s work, each partner brought new knowledge to their analysis gained from their own experience doing of the same exercise on their own. When both partners joined forces to converse together they  brought all of their previous knowledge plus the new knowledge from commenting on their partners work. In addition, both partners were able to build knowledge between each other through their conversation during the third phase of analysis. Another point was with regard to construction. The partners were able to discuss together and have a collaborative process and through that joint effort students were able to make new things together ultimately expanding their understanding and thereby creating new pieces of knowledge into new knowledge structures. ',15,38,'2016-03-11 18:15:23','2016-03-11 18:15:23'),(82,'I had a bit of a difficult time reading the transcript because the text in the image appeared rather small, but generally I agree with your analysis of this transcript. I think your definitions of each aspect of the Access Framework were spot on, in that green was using procedural knowledge from other logic problems in order to surmount this one, and about the way in which green was representing her solution. However, in the joint problem space section of your post, you mention that Green collaborate with White to come to an answer. I don\'t believe there was any collaboration between the two to come to a solution. The code was Green\'s, and the chat section was not a transcript of them working together to solve the problem, but of them discussing it retroactively.',22,46,'2016-03-11 18:53:26','2016-03-11 18:53:26'),(83,'In your analysis, I like your initial interpretation of the common ground between the two participants. You mentioned that they both had a working understanding of Java, and that they had a grasp of the problem that is supposed to be solved. This common ground is important in establishing a Joint Problem Space. I like your analysis in the second paragraph about the participants reparing divergences, but I think you could have done more with their use of \"Yeah\", as a signal that they had established more common ground, had successfully made a repair, and could move on. Also, I like how you mentioned the initiation of an adjacency pair when the coder asked if the responder was the same person as before. And lastly, I also think you could have talked more about the second repair going on where the responder points out a flaw in the coder\'s program and how the coder notices and accepts that flaw. The coder then responds in the affirmative, letting the responder know that the divergence has been repaired and they\'re on the same page again.',22,43,'2016-03-11 19:37:17','2016-03-11 19:37:17'),(84,'Your analysis is well-organized. You first give the definition of the term, and then use a specific example from your transcript and analyze it using the term. That\'s a good way to analyze terms, and I probably should do that in my second draft. \r\nRegarding your problem in determining what could be an adjacency pair in this script, I think this could be an example:\r\nPerson 1: â€œand I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your answers were and suchâ€\r\nPerson 2: â€œlol YESâ€\r\nHere, the first part that Person 1 says is an assessment, and the second part is an agreement/disagreement. Since the second part is conditionally relevant to the first part, they are probably adjacent pairs.\r\nOverall, you did a really good analysis, and each example you gave explains the terms well.',17,27,'2016-03-11 20:45:05','2016-03-11 20:45:05'),(85,'Your analysis on the grounding section is pretty nice! You pointed out two conversational grounding and three adjacency pairs, each with a relatively detailed discussion. However, for the repair part, I would say that 1 is much more like repeating as he is in acceptance phase than making a repair. And I would say there is no evidence of repair in this conversation. In the virtual co-presence part, I would suggest you discuss about the occasionally disappeared virtual co-presence by talking about the disordered conversation. Think about in real-life conversation, who will keep talking when the other participant has already changed the topic? In the person-plus part, you did well on figuring out the surround in great detail and discussing the â€œresidueâ€ left by thinking using the access framework. I really like the analysis on the distribution of executive function, however there is no result shown in this conversation so we cannot analyze this more. Your discussion of JPS seems to be too short compare to other parts. I think you can do some analysis on the monitoring of on-going activity.',13,28,'2016-03-11 21:06:44','2016-03-11 21:06:44'),(86,'I very much enjoyed your analysis. Yet your documentation didn\'t seem to align with the code above, thereby making it hard for me to get a fully grasp of your findings. I think that had you posted the entire transcript at the top of your anylisis that would give your analysis a better read and make it more cohesive. In addition I feel that your section on Access Framework there was much more in depth analysis which could have been done i.e.  for knowledge you could\'ve added  that when commenting on peerâ€™s work, each partner brought new knowledge to their analysis gained from their own experience doing of the same exercise on their own. When both partners joined forces to converse together they  brought all of their previous knowledge plus the new knowledge from commenting on their partners work. ',15,48,'2016-03-11 21:32:00','2016-03-11 21:32:00'),(87,'I like that your analysis included definitions from the readings and the lecture notes before referring to specific examples in the transcript. It showed your understanding of these concepts. I felt your transcript is a challenging one, as a part of it got up there twice. I was a little confused of it as well, especially the order. I agree with you that the adjacency pair and the repair were not that obvious in your transcript, and the two utterances of the adjacency pair you found made sense to me. I do not see why the representation in the access framework for your transcript should be mental, though, because the two students could type/chat on the screen, and how one of them organized the code section to present the solution. Thatâ€™s also considered part of the representation in my opinion. Overall, it is a well-written analysis!\r\n',25,27,'2016-03-11 22:15:46','2016-03-11 22:15:46'),(88,'In the knowledge part, you articulate how both people used their old knowledge to work on the problem and how they used their work to gain new knowledge. And the example at line 7 is a great example reflecting this fact. In the representation part, the analysis on that the space to write code, comment and discuss helps students to externalize their idea is nice and interesting, but Iâ€™m really confused by your posting the original solution. How is this copy of code helping you analyzing the representation part? For the construction part, it would be better to quote some lines as examples from the conversation to indicate the features in your analysis. For the part on JPS, I think it would be clearer to use headline saying that this part is about JPS. At first glance I thought this was the only paragraph of JPS and the next one is about something else, and I thought you had no evidence for analyzing JPS. So please use headlines, also for the part on access framework. The discussion of executive function is pretty nice with good style and convincing evidence. I think we are also required to write about grounding, which is missing from your post.',13,31,'2016-03-11 22:40:12','2016-03-11 22:40:12'),(89,'The sectioning of your analysis is organized and clear. I would like to see more analysis done on the contribution of students as there are many places throughout the transcript. For the presentation phase and acceptance phase, it would be better if you had more specific analysis. The reference to the transcript is clear, but the analysis here is a little general. \r\n\r\nI like your analysis for the co-presence. Since this is a virtual co-presence, it is slightly different from co-presence and some of its features are lost. I wish I had discussed that in my own analysis. I also like what you did for the joint problem space, where you had a very thorough analysis!\r\n',25,36,'2016-03-11 22:57:57','2016-03-11 22:57:57'),(90,'@theaquawombat, will do, thanks for the input!',20,39,'2016-03-11 23:01:03','2016-03-11 23:01:03'),(91,'Great analyses, but could use a little tweaking (in the formatting area). It is hard to make clear what is the analyses and what are you thoughts in part A and B. I also had these issues in my analyses but found, with help from @theaquawombat, it would help to number each line of the transcript for reference later on. For part B, it seems as if you are providing vague descriptions of the examples you found in the transcript. Make sure to explicitly define what you are looking for and citing specific examples. This should make your analyses easier to read, and allow you to convey your ideas more fluidly. I would also like to encourage you to find more examples of each subpart of part B. All in all, good work, and can\'t wait to read more!',20,40,'2016-03-11 23:11:23','2016-03-11 23:11:23'),(92,'First of all, please do not make everything bold. And since you are introducing the original conversation in the front of each analysis but not the beginning of the entire post, I think it would be better for you to mark that conversation out, such as type in bold or with indentation. Though the post is hard to read at the first glance, the post itself is in high quality and is really interesting. I really like your style in part B, where you discuss the original conversation line by line and figure out every element in each line, and the analyses are concrete and convincing. However this style has a disadvantage on the rest of the post, where in part C and part D it is hard to quote from the original conversation as strong evidence. I also have the idea, as TheOrchidLlama says, that you can post the entire transcript at the very top of the post. ',13,48,'2016-03-11 23:19:14','2016-03-11 23:19:14'),(93,'It seems as if you have a firm understanding of the topics we discussed in class and read about (i.e. adjacency pairs, person-plus model, et cetera), but I would love to see more explicit examples that cater towards your transcript. I would also encourage you to read over the homework directions, I think you missed some requirements as well as some formatting things: your part A should be part B, part B part C (it\'s really a small issue). Honestly, you have a great, firm understanding of the global ideas we needed to address, it\'s just taking time to dive in and pick out specific examples from the transcript. Too include, as mentioned by @theaquawombat, make sure you list out the transcript above (with line numbers)! ',20,30,'2016-03-11 23:34:38','2016-03-11 23:34:38'),(94,'1. Love your organization, made it really simple to read and put your thoughts together. 2. The overall analyses of the transcript given is very thought out and thought provoking. 3. ',20,29,'2016-03-11 23:44:03','2016-03-11 23:44:03'),(95,'3. you display a in-depth understanding of the topics being talked about (sorry, accidentally pressed \'save comment\'). All sections were thorough, but I would focus your revisions on Part B: you provide some analysis of the subparts (i.e. grounding, adjacency pairs, et cetera) but not all. I would list out every occasion of those subparts, because it wasn\'t clear if you did include all the ones from the transcript. Another area worth improving, to make it easier for the reader, is to provide short definitions of the topics being discussed. This would allow the reader to better understand your analyses with context to the original problem established on the HW2 sheet. Can\'t wait to read more!',20,29,'2016-03-11 23:53:32','2016-03-11 23:53:32'),(96,'Overall, I think the Situated Activity framework applied the best to this transcript. The participants\' discussion of their solution organization, and what elements make or break it, was constantly evolving. This redefinition of the problem and continual effort towards the solution (it being the *best* way to organize their answers) seemed to fit with the framework well. Also, you brought up such an interesting point that I hadn\'t considered before. I was searching for established common ground in terms of the organization of their solutions, but I hadn\'t thought to consider the common ground made with compliments (and their common refusal, in this case!) Thank you for bringing this to my attention! :-)',8,34,'2016-03-12 00:18:58','2016-03-12 00:18:58'),(97,'Great analysis!  Your definitions of all the terminology such as adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, etc. were extremely useful for my own refresh of memory on this terminology.  In part a.) I noticed that you chunked grounding,  adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, and repairs into chunks presented serially.  The examples you gave were great for each chunk, and you had a great mix between generalization and examples/specialization.  A lot of the examples you used in each chunk were the same; for example some subset of lines 1-5 in part A. were in each chunk.  For me as a reader, I believe it would be helpful to just have your 5 lines and show how each is an example of an instance of the topics (adjacency pairs etc.) in your chunks.  That way the reader would be able to compare ideas like grounding and adjacency pairs for the same example. Space would be saved to.  Great definition for the items in the knowledge-processing system in person plus.  I would encourage you to discuss further how things like the terminal would allow the problem to be solved more easily.  For instance in relation to the problem in the transcript youâ€™re analyzing there are a lot of things that need to be kept track of like count, and the terminal allows users to record this information, so they can use their working memory for other parts of the problem.  In all 4 components in person-plus I would encourage you to look more closely at the transcript to find concrete details, as to how the components are exemplified in the transcript.  All in all great job, and not a lot of things I could say because it was a very good analysis.',7,39,'2016-03-12 00:23:14','2016-03-12 00:23:14'),(98,'To TheOrchidLlama:\r\nI agree with you that both participants brought new knowledge to the discussion from their own experience doing the original work, though they didn\'t talk much about their old knowledge in the transcript. But I can try to find some evidence of new knowledge brought at the discussion time. I don\'t quite understand what you mean on the second part. But I will try to read about construction again and make some improvement.',13,38,'2016-03-12 00:35:37','2016-03-12 00:35:37'),(99,'Hi.  I like your first analysis about grounding, adjacency pairs and etc. Your covered almost every line in the transcript and it gives readers a holistic view of the conversation. Besides, in your access framework analysis, you compared this transcript with long division in terms of the distribution of executive function.  I think that\'s a great way to highlight the characteristics of distribution of the executive function.  As to determine the part in the transcript that has distribution of the executive function, I think thereâ€™re might more that can be said.  I also like your throughout and clear analysis about situated activity and the fact that you related back to the supermarket arithmetic example.  Overall, I think its a very good job.',28,32,'2016-03-12 00:42:52','2016-03-12 00:42:52'),(100,'I really enjoyed reading this analysis, and its transcript, because you could see problem-solving happening so fully in the participants\' conversation. The transcript I analyzed was about a logic problem as opposed to a java problem, so it was hard to see how the participants collaboratively solved the problem at-hand. One aspect of this transcript that I found really interesting was the key role of grounding and its part in helping the participants reach their zones of proximal development. Each were trying to convey their own thought process in solving the problem and transform it into common ground, and by doing so, helped each other to extend beyond the learning they would have otherwise reached on their own.',8,47,'2016-03-12 01:02:53','2016-03-12 01:02:53'),(101,'You did a really great job on this analysis! Something that you highlighted, and that I found really insightful considering our upcoming final projects, is that the user was not fully informed about the siteâ€™s features, and that this hindered their ability to fully take advantage of the collaboration the site would otherwise facilitate. This disruption in their conversation provides us, as analysts and designers, with an excellent opportunity to improve their experience in the platformâ€™s next iteration. Ensuring that users have sufficient knowledge of the siteâ€™s functions before using it, and perhaps allowing students access to past conversations, would benefit them immensely.',8,33,'2016-03-12 01:24:14','2016-03-12 01:24:14'),(102,'You state that the transcript â€œis not exactly a perfect example of textbook conversational conventionâ€ due to the lack of apparent adjacency pairs or turn taking, but I think very few organic interactions are exactly as described by conventions.  There are multiple instances of contributions and acceptance phases where the reader refers to the writerâ€™s contributions as a form of acceptance (lines 12 and 14, for example). The confusion with turn taking is an interesting aspect to explore because it doesnâ€™t necessarily follow the same rules as a spoken conversation; two people can write messages simultaneously whereas two people canâ€™t speak at the same time and continue to be understood.  Two threads of a conversation can occur concurrently (lines 11 â€“ 14).  ',6,41,'2016-03-12 01:29:34','2016-03-12 01:29:34'),(103,'I really liked how clear and concise each of the three parts of the assignment were for your analysis.  This conciseness allowed for easy shift of focus between the transcript and your analysis.  For part a I would encourage you to look for more examples of some of the concepts we talked about such as grounding and co-presence.  For instance I see a great example of grounding when Student B says, â€œright, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words wonâ€™t be anagrams but word two will contain b for all bs.â€  When student A says â€œyeah, thatâ€™s trueâ€¦â€ student A is showing that student B that he knows what B means, and Aâ€™s knowledge is added to their common ground.  This is just an example you could use and there are many more!  Your description of how elements of the transcript fit the knowledge processing framework is great!  I really liked how you had each of the four elements of the framework and directly after each element had an example straight from the transcript.  I got up to speed very quickly and easily on knowledge processing systems after reading this!  All in all, I thought this was very good!\r\n',7,30,'2016-03-12 01:32:36','2016-03-12 01:32:36'),(104,'@Aqua the Wombat: I totally agree with you on getting up closer to the transcript.  With my transcript I felt like there was only a small subset of the analysis which was relevant to the concepts to be discussed, which was why I didn\'t feel like I could get as close as I wanted.  For the examples I did get up close to I will try to go more in depth in the next review; thanks for bringing that to attention!   Now that I look back at c.) you\'re absolutely right, it would be much more readable if there were line breaks at the different components in the knowledge processing system.  Yeah, part d could use some work in a manner similar to part c.) \r\n@the torquoise hedgehog: after reading both your comments and the aqua wombat is clear I need to get closer, for the examples I do have go slightly more in depth, and would benefit from a format change.  Thanks for pointing out putting in definitions of the topics of consideration.  This was something I did for my first analysis, and after reading everyone elses for this one it was clear the definitions made things more readable.  I\'m also going to label my transcript with line numbers to make citing easier.  Thanks!',7,40,'2016-03-12 01:50:48','2016-03-12 01:50:48'),(105,'This is a very good close up analysis of the transcript.  I think it was interesting that the responder repairs their previous statement and your insight into the meaning of â€œactuallyâ€ as a reference to a previous statement.  I also think you could explore the thread of â€œare you the same person I was talking to before?â€ because that doesnâ€™t appear to follow normal spoken conversational structure where only one topic occurs at a time, rather than referencing a past comment.  Nitpicky suggestion:  you can get rid of the sentence â€œThere is an assumption that the coder has tried to solve this problem in their code,â€ because that can be assumed.',6,43,'2016-03-12 02:20:15','2016-03-12 02:20:15'),(106,'Great analysis! I agree with the Turquoise Hedgehog, your organization of the analysis and the way you use relevant lines from the transcripts makes it really easy to follow your train of thought. I also liked that you started out by saying that both users are co-present in the problem space and that they are both using common vocabulary. I think you could expand on that idea by talking about the zone of proximal development and how this platform works best when the two users are in the same zone. I think you get close to saying that in the line \"the partners assume that the other has some basic knowledge of Java and programming in general\", but you could formalize and expand on the thought by using more vocabulary. Another thing I really liked about your analysis was your comments on the user\'s failure to retrieve relevant knowledge to do the problem.',27,29,'2016-03-12 02:36:39','2016-03-12 02:36:39'),(107,'Hi Brass Tortoise. Great job.  I think your analysis is very structure, detailed and clear.  One thing I like specifically is that you used line 13 as an example to show what kind of transcript is not grounded, and that help readers be more clear about the definition of \"grounded\". In the retrieval part, you talked about that the coder labeled the color so its easier to retrieve the information-what color is under consideration. I think it might be a good idea to also analyze it in terms of the transcript since there\'re many lines that\'re relevant to retrieval.  ',28,26,'2016-03-12 02:37:01','2016-03-12 02:37:01'),(108,'I think that this post is well-thought out, and well-constructed. The script was properly and effectively referenced, which allowed for better analysis and understanding for the reader. The only adjustment that I would maybe want to see is to have the analysis tied in more with the literature that we have been reading in class. This is not because I think that the writer should compensate for any potential lack of knowledge on the part of the reader, but because it can enhance understanding, and additionally makes it easier to place the script in context. \r\n\r\nI think that this post is well-thought out, and well-constructed. The script was properly and effectively referenced, which allowed for better analysis and understanding for the reader. The only adjustment that I would maybe want to see is to have the analysis tied in more with the literature that we have been reading in class. This is not because I think that the writer should compensate for any potential lack of knowledge on the part of the reader, but because it can enhance understanding, and additionally makes it easier to place the script in context. For me personally, I know that a reference to a paper always aids in my understanding not only of the analysis I\'m reading, but also of the paper that is referenced. ',24,44,'2016-03-12 02:53:05','2016-03-12 02:53:05'),(109,'Hi, good analysis! I really like your use of the arrows but I agree with the Aqua Wombat, I think sometimes they can be confusing because of how small the text is in the photos. You guys told me in the comments to my analysis that it would be helpful to include a copy of the transcript typed out with line numbers, I think if you did that as well and added line numbers next to your arrows your analysis would read even better! I also think you could use a little more content in your Person-Plus section. You bring up construction in your first paragraph of section c but you don\'t talk about about how it is relevant to this transcript. I think if you added a few sentences on what the platform allowed the users to construct (be it new ideas, a better understanding, etc) I think the section would be a lot stronger. ',27,39,'2016-03-12 02:59:09','2016-03-12 02:59:09'),(110,'I like that you included definitions from the reading, it helped to give me context before reading your analysis. I\'m thinking that it might be good to include some more examples of each interpretation, or maybe to analyze the transcript line-by-line in terms of ALL the terms instead of term-by-term. You also mention that the ordering of the text boxes is unclear. I think it actually goes up from the bottom (instead of down from the top) ... I totally made this mistake when reading my transcript, too. An example of a violation in turn-taking might be at the very end (the end of the text box, but the beginning of the conversation) where the person in green talks for several turns. I think they might be responding to the other person writing comments on other areas of the text file, like all the way at the top. I\'m not sure if this counts as fixing the violation, though.',26,27,'2016-03-12 03:00:58','2016-03-12 03:00:58'),(111,'Solid job. I appreciated your table display and how you were specific in referencing all of the things that you were talking about in the transcript. The whole thing was pretty easy to follow. However, I thought that you could have dove a bit more in a few places like on the side by side comment in part C. I think this was a more valuable piece of information you identified than you seemed to think in your analysis. It might have been a good place to go down a road of talking about the JPS as a whole and linking this distributed cognition factor that you identified to the overall set of factors that is present. ',30,28,'2016-03-12 03:02:20','2016-03-12 03:02:20'),(112,'I agree Olive Moose! The problem-solving was very clear and thorough in this transcript. I thought it was very interesting how their entire conversation was an effort to contribute improvements to the original code and in the process, reaching their zone of proximal development. The coder clearly had a lot of procedural knowledge about this type of problem solving. However, he/she hit their zone of proximal development when it came to the string operations.\r\n\r\n I think that the underlying phenomena in this interaction is the use of contributions and acceptances which resulted in the expansion of the zone of proximal development.',23,47,'2016-03-12 03:05:15','2016-03-12 03:05:15'),(113,'I think I should point out to you that the conversation progressed from the bottom of the transcript to the top. It may help you make more sense of the text.\r\nWhen it comes to the first part of your analysis, I see what you mean with the adjacency pairs not being very clear, but if you look at it in terms of grounding, there is a good amount to analyze there. For example, the reader explains what they liked about the writer\'s code, saying that \"the count was really useful,\" and the writer acknowledges the reader\'s compliment, saying they \"found the count really useful as well.\"\r\nFor the second part, perhaps take into account that once the writer writes down something they are thinking, they have at that point distributed their cognition, because they no longer have to remember whatever it was they chose to write down.',21,41,'2016-03-12 03:05:31','2016-03-12 03:05:31'),(114,'Yes absolutely! Providing sufficient knowledge of site functions prior to use is going to be very important to keep in mind in our final projects. I also think it\'s important to try and give the user control over their workspace. If the site has too much executive function over interactions, it could cause confusion and frustration. ',23,33,'2016-03-12 03:08:50','2016-03-12 03:08:50'),(115,'You should know that the conversation starts at the bottom and goes up. It may make it easier for you to see what is going on.\r\nYour last analysis is really good, I think, when you look at what is truly happening in the transcript. The writer of the code starts by responding to the commenter (who originally was reminded that \"charAt is a thing!\"), saying they had wanted to use substrings but couldn\'t remember how. At that point, the two converse and bounce various ideas back an forth, eventually converging to a single representation where they agree an array would work well.\r\nOnce you flip the transcript, you see that your assumptions on what /would/ have happened, actually did.',21,37,'2016-03-12 03:18:25','2016-03-12 03:18:25'),(116,'I felt like you did a good job of tying things together. You drew a line from the transcript to the effect on the JPS in a series of logical statements in the construction section, however I think the section was a bit scarce on support. For the retrieval section I would press you to consider a bit further though. In almost any JPS there will be retrieval occurring among the participants or they can\'t be getting any knowledge that is stored in the representation of the JPS, hence no knowledge can flow between people, hence the JPS can\'t function. ',30,31,'2016-03-12 03:19:41','2016-03-12 03:19:41'),(117,'You go pretty in depth with access characteristics: knowledge, representation, retrieval, constructionâ€¦ but I think this is sort of at the expense of other parts of your analysis.  For example, you didnâ€™t write much on adjacency pairs, grounding, or specific phenomenon in the transcript.  It seems you focused largely on the last question we were asked to answer in terms of the prompt â€“ the one pertaining to access characteristics.  Additionally, I think some emphasis on the person-plus, both the surround and the â€œresidue left from thinkingâ€ could help strengthen your analysis (and cover your bases grade-wise, as it is something mentioned in the assignment).  All this being said, your analysis of the access characteristics is accurate and in-depth, showcasing a strong understanding of what those principles are and a keen ability to identify them in a transcript setting.  With a little more spread of ideas (in order to hit the topics mentioned in the prompt) this is a strong offering.',12,31,'2016-03-12 03:23:44','2016-03-12 03:23:44'),(118,'Good analysis! I particulairly like your Section B. I think the way you break down each comment and connect it back to the paper is very effective. The one thing that I get caught up on is your use of current_state. I am assuming that you mean the current state of the common knowledge between A and B. I think the section would have made a lot more sense if you defined that formally or used a different name. Otherwise I like the iterative way you talk about it and how the state changes through each acceptance phase. I also think that there is a great opportunity to talk about the tone in your transcripts. \"Speaker A: I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didnâ€™t make it user friendly lol.  Iâ€™m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.  Lol yeah.\" Your transcript uses words like \'lol\' and has several self-depreciating comments like \'I didn\'t make it user friendly.\' I think at the very least you could include a comment on the relaxed nature of the users in Section D and have some lines about how it helps the problem space. I just think its something that sets your transcript apart from the rest of ours and is interesting enough to warrant a comment. That is just a tangent thought though. ',27,40,'2016-03-12 03:31:11','2016-03-12 03:31:11'),(119,'Please post the entire transcript at the top of your analysis â€“ in addition to enhancing readability, it is also part of this assignment.  Your formatting also makes this difficult to read â€“ everything is bold, and there is no obvious distinction between what are sections of transcript and what is your analysis (this can be picked up by context clues, but thatâ€™s making the reader do more work than they should have to).  This would be remedied by posting the transcript at the top of your analysis.  Additonally, if the transcript was posted, you could refer to line numbers rather than having to always post quotes (sometimes reduntantly).  All this being said, your analysis itself, as other have pointed out, is comprehensive, accurate, and shows a strong understanding of key concepts.  You clearly have a knack for finding the types of phenomena we have been discussing in class in â€œreal worldâ€ situations. ',12,48,'2016-03-12 03:31:45','2016-03-12 03:31:45'),(120,'Thank you for these well-written responses! \r\nGB: Thanks for that example for adjacency pairs! I think that adjacency pairs is a cool concept, but I was struggling with finding an example, as I mentioned, so I really appreciate you taking the time to point that part of the script out to me.\r\nPW: Good point, representation doesn\'t have to be mental. Thank you for that new perspective.\r\nTG: Thank you for clarifying the organization for me, I asked some questions about it in class, but I realized later that I didn\'t ask specific questions about my confusion about the structure of the chat. Also, thank you for the new perspective on the violation of turn-taking. ',24,27,'2016-03-12 03:33:55','2016-03-12 03:33:55'),(121,'The organization of your analysis is really good and understandable. The only thing is, it might be easier to re-state parts of the transcript every time you refer to them, or number the lines and just refer to them by lines. I\'m also confused by what you mean by the knowledge of java being represented by method names and code. Also, I totally made this mistake too, but the transcript is backwards - the discussion starts from the bottom and goes up.',26,36,'2016-03-12 03:44:21','2016-03-12 03:44:21'),(122,'I havenâ€™t seen this structure before in any other analysis, and I very much like it. In section B, when you break down the script piece by piece, and have the analysis right below that, I liked being able to read it all at once, rather than reading a block of text in one section, and reading a block text in another section. One thing I was wondering is if in the Distribution section if Student Aâ€™s ideas about code that are given to Student B could be viewed as teaching rather than distribution of executive function? Or as both teaching and executive function. \r\n',24,35,'2016-03-12 03:58:23','2016-03-12 03:58:23'),(123,'Your analysis was really nice. The simple explanation of every part made it easy to understand although it was bit confusing for me to get the first part as you (i presume) try to explain grounding , adjacency pair in mixed way. I agree with you and also Olive Moose that a better design would\'ve made it easier for the participants to solve problems easily. And very detailed explanation of situated activity, i\'m saving the text for the projects, i might find this useful. ',14,33,'2016-03-12 03:59:52','2016-03-12 03:59:52'),(124,'Great analysis. The explanation of individual section helped me to understand the analysis. I liked the part where you explained in the knowledge section that how externalization helped them to focus on other parts. I had trouble understanding the repair section which cleared by your detailed explanation. ',14,34,'2016-03-12 04:11:31','2016-03-12 04:11:31'),(125,'Thank you both. I agree that I should have said more about the usage of \"yeah.\" I actually ran out of time and it automatically posted, but I wanted to say more about the transcript. When it comes to the coder misunderstanding the responder and then repairing it, I don\'t think the coder actually understands what the responder meant at first, so there\'s an extra repair phase in there that I will definitely talk about in my final draft.\r\nThe thought that this conversation having multiple threads is odd is definitely interesting. I suppose that it does not follow the pattern declared within the papers we have read, and therefore would be a good think to talk about.',21,43,'2016-03-12 04:50:31','2016-03-12 04:50:31'),(126,'This is a really good analysis. Overall, you did a good job of not only identifying the phenomena, but explaining what they mean. I especially like your point about the environment limiting the problem and how the writers adjusted to that. I didn\'t really think about the limitations of the space and how that affected the entire mental process, and I think this transcript paired with your analysis does a good job of highlighting this. I agree with Vermillion Starfish, that in some places it seems as though you\'re analyzing the transcript backwards (although I find it interesting that a lot of what happens seems to make sense and be true whether you analyze the transcript forwards or backwards).',4,37,'2016-03-12 20:22:44','2016-03-12 20:22:44'),(127,'I think that there is some degree of distribution of executive function in this situation. While there are no outside resources available to the coder, the \"blank text editor\" allows the user to externalize their thoughts onto the screen. They must construct an answer from their internal thoughts and external notes. The editor also acts as a bridge between the two users and becomes a source of information for the partner who did not write this excerpt in addition to their own prior knowledge. While this is a pared down version of the person plus model, there are several factors that contribute to the distribution of executive function.',4,41,'2016-03-12 20:39:25','2016-03-12 20:39:25'),(128,'Thanks for the feedback. I will try to incorporate your comments into my final draft.',19,29,'2016-03-13 02:23:07','2016-03-13 02:23:07'),(129,'Hi Green Impala, thank you for your thoughts. Yes, I will definitely do some more analysis of the transcript in my second draft. ',9,26,'2016-03-14 19:32:47','2016-03-14 19:32:47'),(130,'Hi Violet Duck, I just wanted to point out that it would be good to include a larger transcript photo. It is hard to make out the words because the picture is so small.',9,42,'2016-03-14 20:21:55','2016-03-14 20:21:55'),(131,'Thank you all for your well comments! PW: Thank you for your suggestion about analyzing specifically on acceptance phase and presentation phase. Also, virtual co-present is different from co-presence gives me a new perspective to think about it. TG: I agree with you that the reference to the transcript is not clear in this way, and I appreciate you make this suggestion!',17,36,'2016-03-14 21:34:13','2016-03-14 21:34:13'),(132,'Awesome comments! I\'ll be sure to use you\'re advise.',20,39,'2016-03-14 23:12:48','2016-03-14 23:12:48'),(133,'Thank you for the suggestion. I will try to make more reference to the paper.',25,44,'2016-03-14 23:29:31','2016-03-14 23:29:31'),(134,'Indigo Eagle-- Thank you! I am so happy to hear that my explanation of the repair section was able to help with your understanding of the concept. Zone of proximal development applied to our own collaboration, I suppose!',8,34,'2016-03-15 01:44:49','2016-03-15 01:44:49'),(135,'@MelonLion I agree the grounds for stating there are repairs in this transcription are shaky at best -- I did denote that in my analysis.  For the sake of proving I understand the phenomena, I try my best to align what evidence there is in the transcript to what evidence would have to exist in order for that phenomenon to exist.  @JadeAnteater I disagree with your comment on delving deeper into the \"side by side\" -- whatever that is is unimportant to my analysis. For all we care, we can think of that as some \"black box\" -- whose components are largely unimportant, but the box itself lets us make arguments and reason about structure.  Think of some Java package -- we may not know how all the individual methods work, but we know they do work, and that is enough to begin reasoning about how to use them',12,28,'2016-03-15 12:54:50','2016-03-15 12:54:50'),(136,'Hi Brass Tortoise. Thanks for your comment. Yeah I also think that I need to be more in depth in terms of applying the framework to the transcript.  As for the JPS and turn-taking part, I\'d improve it by adding analysis from other perspectives. ',28,45,'2016-03-16 00:55:00','2016-03-16 00:55:00');
