s very apt, and I like how you took each defining point of a joint problem space, like introducing and accepting knowledge, and monitoring and repairing divergences, and then found examples of that in the transcript to prove your point.',NULL,NULL,-8385812,1,1,'2016-03-15 18:11:26','2016-03-17 22:32:10'),(118,32,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,'3. I like how you color coded the transcript, it made it very easy to read and analyze. In part B I really liked your analyses of virtual copresence and grounding. I especially agree that over an online platform like this we can\'t rely on pointing, gestures, body language, and eye contact to establish co presence, and give hints at what someone is trying to convey. I think your access framework analysis could have been more thorough, but nonetheless I agree with your assessment of it on this transcript and thought you made some good points, like how person 1 and 2 were more encouraged to discuss line 9 than anything else. Lastly, I completely agree with your situated activity analysis and agree that this is not a good example of a dialectic relationship between context and setting, and thought you brought up some valuable points, especially about how the participants in some cases would be more likely to use logic effectively than in this simulated, artificial example.',NULL,NULL,1553466,7,1,'2016-03-15 18:11:30','2016-03-17 22:32:10'),(119,31,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,'4. The analysis is really difficult to read because of the lack of indentation and separation between sections, and also the transcript is hard to read for the same reason. You did a good job of using examples from and directly referencing the transcript. Your analysis on adjacency pairs is also very thorough, as is your analysis of contribution and acceptance phases. Also, in your section on distributed cognition and executive function, you mentioned the use of the Internet, but I don\'t think the participants were allowed internet access for these problems, which would affect your interpretation of distributed executive function. Lastly, I think you made some good points in your argument for a joint problem space here and I agree with your interpretation of it being a JPS. Overall, you used a lot of direct examples from the transcript, but you used examples a lot of the time to further the same point instead of creating a more well rounded argument.',NULL,NULL,1642235,8,1,'2016-03-15 18:11:36','2016-03-17 22:32:10'),(120,33,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2. I think this is a very thorough analysis of the transcript, and I agree with each of your points and definitions. For part B, I think you did a good job of talking about virtual copresence, adjacency pairs, common ground, and grounding. I also had the same problem where my transcript was a continuation of a previous chat I couldn\'t see, but even though you lacked a full transcript to work with I think you did a great job of piecing together the conversation with what you had. For part C, I liked how you quoted from the Distribution of Executive function paper , and then proceeded to prove how that quote applied to this transcript. However, I think you could have done a slightly better job of making direct references to the transcript, and quoting specific lines. And lastly, I agree with your situated activity analysis, agree that context and setting are difficult over an online platform.',NULL,NULL,-8377316,2,1,'2016-03-15 18:11:42','2016-03-17 22:32:10'),(121,35,7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1819771,7,1,'2016-03-15 18:12:03','2016-03-17 21:29:40'),(122,46,7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,-8377229,2,1,'2016-03-15 18:12:07','2016-03-17 21:29:40'),(123,41,7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,1997308,8,1,'2016-03-15 18:12:16','2016-03-17 21:29:40'),(125,45,7,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,-8383038,1,1,'2016-03-15 18:12:49','2016-03-17 21:29:40'),(126,48,19,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Confusing organization in part B; aspects are interactive but presented disjointedly; decent analysis but should be more fluid',NULL,NU