INSERT INTO `posts` VALUES (2,'Internal Framework','<p>Please refer to the long division video below. The analysis will focus on the segment <strong>0:00 - 1:05</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4\">https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I chose to focus on the introductory segment of the video because the beginning of the process is when a lot of the internal framework is displayed. The internal framework in terms of the long division problem is made up of a combination of fundamental ideas: procedural knowledge and a plan. More specifically, the script is an example of procedural knowledge that is represented in the video. A script is specific detailed knowledge about a situation which represents our default, culturally-based knowledge about the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case, by the way Will knew where to position the dividend underneath the division line and the divisor to the left of the dividend and on the other side of the division line, it is clear that he was able to reference a script of how to set up a long division problem from previous knowledge. Moreover, he goes straight into placing a 2 above the fourth digit from the right of the dividend number with purposeful intent. The only hesitation that was displayed in this particular instance was whether or not 2 was the correct number to choose (because he was doing mental math). At the <strong>0:15</strong> second mark, it is also important to note that Will says <em>&ldquo;oh, this is kinda coming back, maybe&rdquo;</em> which is an indication that the process is familiar and that procedural knowledge is helping to solve the problem. The internal procedural script allowed Will to reference the method of how to do long division and the series of successive steps that needed to be made in order to solve the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition to procedural knowledge Will built a plan that helped him to solve the particular long division problem at hand. Internally, he does not have a script for how to divide 9,705,159,253 by 3437. A plan, a mental representation of intent before taking action, therefore was introduced in order to complete the specific long division problem. Each step presented a new math problem that Will had to work around. For most of the video segment, we can see that he did not have a clear plan because he was still trying to reference the script to remember what exactly he had to do. Additionally, he attempted to do parts of the problem using mental math which created a harder obstacle for him to try and hold all the information. At the <strong>0:57</strong> mark, he says <em>&ldquo;I wish we could use a calculator to do these substeps&rdquo;</em>. This is an indication that his initial plan of doing mental math was getting increasingly difficult. At the <strong>1:00</strong> mark he says <em>&ldquo;Maybe I should just multiply this out by 9 and see what it is. Yeah I think that&rsquo;s the best approach&rdquo;</em>. This last remark before the video segment ends highlights how Will&rsquo;s internal locus of control found satisfaction in his new approach and plan which he then implements through the rest of the video in order to complete the long division problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The internal framework reveals how important and useful the use of procedural knowledge and a plan helps us work through situations such as that of the long division problem.</p>\r\n','<p>As my second analysis, I would like to take the position of the <strong>interactive</strong> framework. Because the video segment must be the same, please refer to&nbsp;segment <strong>0:00 - 1:05&nbsp;</strong>of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4\">https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4</a>&nbsp;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will initiates the conversation at the very start of the segment by asking Kathy a witty question, &quot;Can we use calculators to multiply this by two?&quot; He follows up his question with a small chuckle. Because Will initiated the conversation, he selected himself as the current speaker. However, because he proceeds to ask a question, he was extending a gesture towards Kathy to join in on the conversation and become the next speaker. This gave Kathy the right to take the next turn which she does by responding with a small laugh. The laugh in response indicates to Will that, 1. she was being an active listener 2. she accepted the invitation to converse and 3. her response was appropriate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kathy then chooses not to say anything after her laugh which then leaves a moment of silence to fill the gap. The silence indicates that the floor is open for either speaker to take the next turn. Because the turns are not fixed (seeing as how this is a casually conversation between two peers working on a math problem together), Will takes the pause as an indication that he may take his turn again. He begins to think aloud trying to calculate the product of 2*3437. The initial coordination of conversation worked well because both parties were aware of their positions and there was no large transition gap and no overlap of people trying to talk over one another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the initial&nbsp;start, Will dominates the conversation with his train of thought thinking out loud for the remainder of the video segment. His thinking out loud leaves Kathy with hesitation as to where she can participate in the conversation again and this is where the interactive coordination falls a little short. At the <strong>0:40</strong> mark, Will comes up with a probable solution of 2,941 as the difference of 9,705 and 6,874. He poses the answer as a question, followed by a hesitant &quot;maybe&quot;. At this point, Kathy could have restated herself in the conversation but she does not speak. I would refer back to Rule 1c that stated &quot;If the turn-so-far is so constructed as not to involve the use of a &lsquo;current speaker selects next&rsquo; technique, then current speaker may, but need not continue unless another self-selects&quot;. So because Kathy did not self-select herself after Will gave her the chance to take a turn, he proceeds again to take position as current speaker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He makes a second attempt to give her a turn around the <strong>0:50</strong> mark when he tries to get feedback on if he is doing something correctly. She takes this opportunity to reply &quot;yes&quot; and nods (I assume so because the camera shakes up and down as she is saying yes). This is the extent to her participation within the segment of the video. I believe this was due to coordination problems that arose. It was sometimes uncertain whether Will was asking for input or just thinking out loud without the need for help or advice. There is the possibility that because he was talking the majority of the time, she feels like she didn&#39;t need to disrupt his flow and train of thought. Because the conversation was loose and locally managed, it is not uncommon to see coordination problems arise between two peers who may not be familiar communicating with one another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',9,1,1,0,1,'2016-02-04 20:25:52','2016-02-24 04:38:34'),(3,'Cultural mediation and Internalization in Practice','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Video Clip:&nbsp;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Time: 55 sec&nbsp;to 1 min 55 sec</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; This video clip about long division could be interpret from the prospective of &quot;cultural historic&quot;. Through this prospective, cultural mediation, externalization and internalization are involved through the process of two people collaboratively solving the long division problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In &quot;A cultural-historical approach to distributed cognition&quot;, Cole and Engestrom summarize the cultural-historical conception that &quot;cultural artifacts are both material and symbolic&quot;, and are &quot;tools broadly received&quot;. When Kathy and Will tried to figure out the reminder is how many times of the dividend, Will said that he wished he could use a calculator to figure out the correct answer. The calculator is a material cultural artifact and is a tool for solving the long division problem, whereas a pen and paper by which Will and Kathy were used in the video was another tool.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Alexander Luria argues that the tools &quot;not only radically change his conditions of existence, they even react on him in that they effect a change in him and his psychic condition&quot;. The tool that Will was given to solve the problem was a pen and paper, indicating that he was not allowed to use any other tools to help. However, when Will did not know what was the correct number, his first thought was not to find ways or procedures to solve it using pen and paper, but was to use the calculator to help. This indicates that calculator has made a change on Will and his psychic condition, since he relied more on calculator than his mind for calculation. Vygotsky provides a similar argument: &quot;Physical objects instrumental to the tasks you repeatedly accomplish in a given context, over time, become a part of your mental operations&quot;. The mental operations for calculation through using a calculator and through using a pen and paper would be totally different. That calculator changed Will&#39;s psychic condition more than pen and paper did might because that calculator involved less work in brain and avoided many mistakes that may produced through working in brain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Externalization and internalization are also included in this video clip. Will finally determined to use multiplications to check the correct times of dividend to the reminder. Kathy noticed that Will was incorrectly multiplying the reminder instead of the dividend, she then pointed out Will&#39;s mistake and suggested him to use the dividend. This is a process of externalization. During this process, Will was learning from Kathy that he should use the dividend in the multiplication process. Cole and Engestrom argue that &quot;externalization reaches it peak when a new model for the activity is designed and implemented. As the new model stabilizes itself, internalization of its inherent ways and means again becomes the dominant form of learning and developing.&quot; After Will and Kathy figured out that nine was not the correct multiplier, Will started a new multiplication testing whether eight was the correct one. He correctly used the dividend for the multiplication without any help from Kathy. This is an internalization process with externalization turns into internalization. During this process, Will remembered how Kathy taught him before, and inherently learned from Kathy to solve this multiplication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; In fact, the knowledge that people historically obtained and the tools that people historically learned to use helps to build people&#39;s internal and external way of thinking and solving problems.</p>\r\n','<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Video Clip:&nbsp;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Time: 55 sec&nbsp;to 1 min 55 sec&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This video segment could be also interpreted from the prospective of interactive. A lot of interactive actions occurred between Will and Cathy during their process of solving the long division problem. The initial common ground that both Will and Cathy agreed about the situation is that they have to collaborate to solve the long division problem. What they also mutually believed about the situation was that they had to use a pencil and paper to solve the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The common ground between Will and Cathy will change when they choose to ground more contributions, which will become part of the common knowledge. In The Tangerine Gopher&#39;s article, he argues that Ethan and Talie &quot;have to set up the physical representation of the math problem to match the next problem they are going to do&quot;. This is an example of contribution that Ethan and Talie have to make to change their common ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In my chosen video segment, when Will said, &quot;Are we not allowed to use a calculator?&quot; He was performing an individual act that contributing a question to the discourse. Will&#39;s individual act of posing a question is the presentation phase of the grounding interaction. He presented utterance, which is a question for Cathy to consider. He assumed that if Cathy gave him some evidence showed that she knew what he was saying, such as giving an answer to his question, he could believe that Cathy understood what he was saying. The Tangerine Gopher analyzed the same concept from a different prospective through arguing that Talie initiated a relevant contribution by telling Ethan to bring down the 2. This also shows the presentation phase of the grounding interaction, since Talie presented utterance &quot;bring down the 2&quot; for Ethan to consider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In my video segment, Cathy answered Will question by saying &quot;I don&#39;t think so&quot;. Cathy&#39;s individual act of answering the question is the acceptance phase of the grounding interaction. Her reply indicates that she accepted the question posed from Will by giving the answer to the question, which is evidence that showed that she believed she understood what Will meant. She answered the question with assumption that once Will registered such evidence, he would also believe that Cathy understood what he asked. In The Tangerine Gopher analysis, when Ethan repeated what Talie said before also showed that Ethan gave the evidence to Talie showing his understanding through repeating Talie&#39;s word.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The interaction between Will and Cathy was a process of question answering and the interaction between Talie and Ethan was a process of assertion and repeating the assertion. Even though the ways they interacted with one another were different, they changed their common ground through a similar way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The first analysis I did also focused on Will&#39;s question about &quot;Are we not allowed to use a calculator&quot;, the analysis for the question is that calculator as a tool changed Will&#39;s psychic condition. When the sentence is analyzed only from the perspective from Will, it showed how a material cultural artifact could change people&#39;s ways of thinking. However, when it is analyzed from the perspective from both Will and Cathy, the actions were no longer internal but interactive as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',17,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-06 02:39:01','2016-02-28 03:04:35'),(4,'Will Burstein\'s analyzation of the long division problem using internal frameworks ','<p>I chose the long division video with myself and Kathy. &nbsp;I&#39;ve chosen to analyze the clip from 0 seconds to one minute and fifteen seconds. &nbsp;I will first propose an analyzation of the video using an internal approach focusing on planning and procedural knowledge using the integer long division procedure to solve the problem at hand and various sub-procedures in the process. &nbsp;The initial plan of using the integer long division procedure will be shown to have flexibility in sub-plans depending on what comes up in solving the problem.&nbsp; I will then focus on a scripts analyzation&nbsp;approach for solving the long division problem focusing on the long division script with the integer track. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; At the beginning of the video clip I realize that I need to solve the problem 9705159253 divided by 3437 using the integer long division procedure.&nbsp; I call the procedure and know that I must place the dividend (3437) before the divisor (9705159253) in writing to carry out the task, as well as knowing the various subtasks such as subtraction and multiplication that will come up at various times to solve the problem. &nbsp;Thus, my plan is to use the integer long division procedure to solve the problem. &nbsp;As part of the integer long division procedure I know that the first step is to figure out&nbsp;what the smallest prefix, m of the dividend (9705159253) that is greater than or equal to 3437. &nbsp;There are various methods to figure this task out and I use estimation to figure out 3437 goes into 9705 twice (ie m = 2) and write m on top of the last integer of the prefix found. &nbsp;Thus my original plan to solve the problem was flexible enough to allow the incorporation of spontaneous sub-plans (IE using estimation to figure out 3437 went into 9705&nbsp;twice) to solve the problem at hand. &nbsp;I then returned to the long division procedure which says to multiply m (2) by the divisor (3437).&nbsp; Again, there are many approaches that I could use to solve the problem m*divisor (2*3437), and I choose to use mental multiplication to attack this part of the problem.&nbsp; The long division procedure tells me to subtract the product m*divisor from the prefix&nbsp;(9705) whose difference is n (2941).&nbsp; &nbsp;Thus, the next step of the integer long division procedure is to know how many times the divisor goes into n*10+k such that k is the digit to the right of the last digit of the prefix found above&nbsp;(2941*10+1) and see how many times the divisor (3437) goes into it (2941*10+1). &nbsp;The result will be m_1 (8), which we will write next to m (2) in the problem, and this process continues until I&#39;ve solved the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Alternatively, I could think about the long division problem in terms of the script model.&nbsp; The problem I needed to solve was how many times 3437 went into 9705159253 by hand.&nbsp; Thus I recognized an instance of d |&nbsp;n such that d (3437) and n into (9705159253) are integers and recognized right away an instantiated script of long division with the integer track.&nbsp; Note that track is important.&nbsp; For example, if n and d were members of the set of polynomials then the polynomial track of the long division script would be at play.&nbsp; The props in the script are paper, pencil, a divisor d, &nbsp;and dividend n such that n and d are integers.&nbsp; The roles are the problem-solver (PS)&mdash;me!&nbsp; The initial conditions is that PS wants to solve d|n (3437 | 9705159253) and the results are that PS no longer wants to solve d | n, as d | n has been solved.&nbsp; Thus, the first scene of the script is a realization that a dividend n (9705159253) needs to be divided by a divisor d (3437) by the PS.&nbsp; Also in scene one is the PS figuring out the smallest prefix m (9705 in my case) of the dividend such that m is less than or equal to d (3437).&nbsp; If no such m exists we write 0 on top of the last digit of n and&nbsp;let a = d, and go to scene 3 of the script. &nbsp;If such an m exists the PS calculates how many times&nbsp;d goes into m letting q be the result,&nbsp;and goes to&nbsp;scene two.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Scene two is as follows: PS writes a q (2 in my case)% on top of the final character of m if this is the first iteration of scene two and if not writes q directly to the right of the last character on top of n&nbsp;(5)% on the paper, and multiplies q by d (2*3437)%, writing qd (6874 in my case)% directly underneath of m on the paper such that the last digit of qd (4 in my case)% is directly under the last digit of m (5)% on the paper.&nbsp; PS subtracts qd from m (the result in my case being 2941)% and records the result underneath m such that the last digit of m and the last digit of a = qd &ndash; m line up on the paper.&nbsp; If the final digit of the recorded result on top of d on the paper is not above the last digit of d then m becomes 10*a+ k such that k is the digit to the right of the digit of d under the last digit of the number on top of d on the paper (ignoring all %s as those are specific instances of my first few steps of the long division problem).&nbsp; Otherwise we go to scene 3.&nbsp; Scene 3 goes as follows.&nbsp; The result of the long division problem, d | n&nbsp;is the integer written on top of n&nbsp;with a remainder of a.</p>\r\n','<p>Definition: From the External framework in my group: &ldquo;David Kirsh, a leading cognitive scientist, states that the external framework is &ldquo;any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads&rdquo; (Kirsh 212). &nbsp;An external or complementary strategy is used in place or in addition to a normal strategy to solve a cognitive task. &nbsp;For example, consider the problem of solving a long division problem first without a calculator or the aid of pencil and paper. &nbsp;This would be a normal strategy of solving the long-division problem&mdash; clearly impossible for some people due to limitations in working-memory, a cognitive resource. &nbsp;Consider the use of paper and pencil in addition to strictly cognitive resources when solving the long-division problem. &nbsp;Most normal people can solve a long-division problem using the regularly taught procedure of long-division by paper and pencil in elementary school. &nbsp;The algorithm allows the person to write sub-steps of the long-division problem externally to reduce their working memory loads, and allows them to solve the problem when most likely they wouldn&rsquo;t be able to solve it in their head, overloading their working memory. &nbsp;Thus, the long-division procedure is an organizing activity recruiting external elements, the paper and pencil, to reduce working memory, a cognitive load. &nbsp;It is clear then that the long-division procedure using a paper and pencil is a complementary strategy. &nbsp;We show an example of using a complementary strategy to reduce cognitive loads by example using a video of Will and Kathy (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be) [0:00, 1:16] attempting a long-division problem using the strategy above, that is using a paper and pencil to enhance cognition when solving the long division problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Example: Will and Kathy were trying to solve the long division problem, 3437/9705159253. &nbsp;Note that most people would not be able to solve 3437/9705159253 in working memory without the use of any such procedure, and that most people would not be able to solve 3437/9705159253 in their head even if they were using the long division procedure in working memory&mdash; without the use of paper and pencil. &nbsp;Although, there was no video that showed Kathy and Will performing the long-division procedure without paper and pencil, I will show just the sheer amount of working memory that would probably be used in doing so modeling working memory by the set WM initially containing divisor = 3437, and dividend = 9705159253. &nbsp;For simplicity the larger the cardinality of WM will mean higher working memory loads. &nbsp;The notation := will be used to denote an update of WM. &nbsp;I will show by Will and Kathy&rsquo;s YouTube video that the use of a paper and pencil will greatly reduce the amount of working memory (as simulated by the set WM) to execute the long division procedure on the problem 3437/9705159253. &nbsp;Hence, substantial evidence will be presented that the paper and pencil will is indeed a complementary strategy for reducing the cognitive load of working memory when performing long-division. &nbsp;At 0:02 Will puts a 2 on top of the line above the dividend, and WM:= WM union {2}. &nbsp;At 0:11, &nbsp;Will adds the concept of 2 things to WM, the problem of figuring out how many times 3437 goes into 9,705 which we will denote p1. &nbsp;Hence WM:=WM union p1. &nbsp;At 0:15, Will figures out the solution = 6874 to that problem, and WM:=WM - {p1} union {solution}. &nbsp;Note {p1} is not in WM anymore, as that information is no longer needed to solve the long-division problem. &nbsp;Whenever the difference operation is used in an update of WM one can conclude that this was the reasoning for the operation. At 0:22, the problem denoted p2 = 9705 - 6874 is added to WM such that WM: = WM union {p2}. &nbsp;Will solves p2 and realizes p2&rsquo;s solution is sol2 = 2941. &nbsp;Hence WM:=WM union {sol2}. &nbsp;Will must then add the concept that he must bring a 1 down from the dividend which will be denoted by concept1. &nbsp;Hence WM:= WM union {concept1}. &nbsp;WM is updated with 29411 since the operation of concept1 on 2941 is 29411. &nbsp;Hence, WM := WM - {concept1, 2941} union {29411}. &nbsp;At 1:16, Will is realizes he needs to find out how many times 347 goes into 29411, which we will denote as operation1. &nbsp;Hence, WM := WM union {operation1}. &nbsp;Will comes to a solution, denoted new_solution to operation1, so WM:= WM union {new_solution}, and realizes it is wrong, and the memory used to denote that realization is denoted realization. &nbsp;Hence WM:=WM union {realization}, and quickly after WM:= WM - {realization}-{new_solution}. &nbsp;Will then realizes that the 3437 probably goes into 29411 8 times, which we will denote as instinct, so WM:= WM union {instinct}. &nbsp;Clearly instinct must be validated, and these WM updates will continue. &nbsp;Note that WM is growing in cardinality throughout the process of the long-division exercise. &nbsp;As an exercise you can keep track of the actual elements in WM, as described in the analyzation. &nbsp;Note that throughout the whole process WM := {empty-set} if Will is allowed to use paper and pencil as he is in the corresponding video clips to what is written above. &nbsp;Hence, there is sufficient evidence that using a paper and pencil, reduces Will&rsquo;s cognitive load (working-memory) to essentially nothing, IE THE EMPTY SET, when the external elements of a pencil, and paper are recruited. &nbsp;Thus, using a paper and pencil to solve the long-division problem is a complementary strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When I used the internal framework to analyze the long-division problem, I proposed an instance of a procedure, (*) from the set of procedures in procedural knowledge. &nbsp;Similarly, I proposed a script for long-division with the integer track (**). &nbsp;I originally thought the point of this assignment was just to internalize the concepts of scripts and procedural knowledge when applied to an example&mdash; to understand the theoretical models in the papers, using the video clips to give a concrete playing field to apply the model to. &nbsp;However, I didn&rsquo;t realize that the point of the analyzation was to actually see what was going on in the actual concrete clips until Friday, the 25th in class. * and ** clearly weren&rsquo;t specialized enough for the task at hand. &nbsp;When viewing other&rsquo;s analyzations most of them had definitions of the form of analyzation they were using such as the external framework definition as well as clips to YouTube videos with second by second analysis of video. I didn&rsquo;t include definitions in my internal analyzation, or as tight an analysis on video clips. &nbsp;I got great comments from others on my analysis. &nbsp;Some of the helpful comments were to define what an internal framework is and, &ldquo;relating my problem solving steps to internal problem solving characteristics&rdquo; instead of just listing the steps in * and **. &nbsp;Thus, in my external analyzation I took this constructive criticism into account; I added a definition of the external/complementary strategy, had a link to my YouTube video, and focused on concrete video clips first and then used the external framework to make sense of the clips. &nbsp;I think I gained a better idea of what was expected on the second iteration of my analysis.&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n',7,1,1,0,1,'2016-02-06 20:56:54','2016-03-01 02:12:19'),(5,'Ariel/Katherine video, Internal Framework','<p>This is an analysis of the first 60 to 90 seconds of Ariel and Katherin&#39;s long division video, within the context of the internal framework. &nbsp;It represents an&nbsp;attempt to capture to embodied process(es) and procedural knowledge Ariel has for long division, and their resultant plan. &nbsp;While interaction with Katherine occurs regularly, it is not discussed her, as I have kept the lens of this piece tightly focused on the internal, free of mentionings of interaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel immediately writes out the equation with a specified format, showcasing very little or perhaps no thought at all being required.&nbsp; This is an example of an embodied practice -- one done with little or no thought, much like riding a bicycle. The locus of control -- that is, the extent to which control is administered -- within the framework of the internal processes is immediately given credence -- Ariel did not hesitate, deliberate or consult with her partner or anyone else to begin this activity.&nbsp; While the notion of the internal / embodied bearing great influence on the locus of control is immediately apparent, other internal activity quickly overrides such &quot;muscle memory&quot; sorts of thinking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; It becomes obvious shortly after that Ariel has some procedural knowledge when it comes to long division.&nbsp; This was apparent at the beginning with the way she formatted the problem, but that was, as previously mentioned, an embodied action -- one she took with no obvious thought.&nbsp; We can see the internalization of her procedural knowledge shortly after, as it coalesces into a plan, and the plan is undertaken before our eyes.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s most simple to view this plan as a script.&nbsp; Using a slight bastardization of the format outlined in Clark&rsquo;s &ldquo;Scripts, Plans, and Goals,&rdquo; we can write out this recursive script as something like:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">SCRIPT: LONG DIVISION</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Props:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">DR - divisor</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">DD - dividend</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">PR - Problem</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Roles:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">S - Problem solver</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">P0, P1... Pi - (other helpers, optional)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Entry conditions:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">PR is not yet solved (in other terms, step 2a has yet to complete)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">S is mentally capable of undertaking something like this (alert, attentive)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Results:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">PR is solved</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">S is perhaps somewhat mentally drained</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) Analyze DD in relation to DV; determine how many times DV goes into DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2a) Base case: DV goes into DD less than 1 full times, and it is represented as the remainder; PR is solved (exit condition)</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2b) Recursive case: Place the resultant number from step 1 over the correct place of DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3) Multiply DV by the resultant number from step 1, place it under DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 4) Subtract the resultant number from step 3 from DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 5) Bring down the next number from DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 6) Return to step 1, with this new number serving as the new DD</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\">Note: It&#39;s difficult to make the case she is aware of 2a&#39;s existence, as this analysis only covers the first minute or so of the video; however, for the patient viewer, at around 9:24, we see her know this to be the case.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; If we postulate this script to be the resultant cognitive plan generated from Ariel&rsquo;s procedural knowledge of long division, proving it is rather easy. Step 1 can first be seen at approximately 0:29; Step 2b can be seen at (0:33 &ndash; met with some interaction from Katherine, but this is not the place to discuss that); Step 3 can be seen from around 1:05 to 1:20 (some camera movement makes it less than ideal, but the idea is still clear enough); Step 4 and 5 can be seen being done simultaneously at 1:50 (which calls into question whether or not the ordering of the script I made from this transcript is correct, or perhaps does not matter, or perhaps something else entirely); Step 6 is seen at 2:45 (significantly out of the scope of this analysis, which should stay within the first 60 to 90 seconds, but for the complete proof of this script&rsquo;s existence, has been included).</p>\r\n','<p>Clip: 0:30-1:00</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Link to full video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WkgYYpVXdZA</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel: &hellip;OK.&nbsp; So that will go in&hellip;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine: &hellip;yeah&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel: Twice? (prepares to write on the paper)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine: Wait, wait, you have to say how it will go in twice&hellip; I don&rsquo;t &ndash;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel: (pointing to the numbers) that will &ndash; this number will go into this number twice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine: OK, I agree&hellip; that certainly is sound logical thinking</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel: So&hellip; one second, I&rsquo;m trying to multiply by two, this is going to be a struggle&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine: You can do that on a piece of paper&hellip; particularly this piece of paper</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am using the same clip of Katherine and Ariel&rsquo;s long division video, but this time I have made sure to constrict the scope to only thirty seconds (detailed above) and am analyzing it with the Interactive framework (instead of the Internal one I did before).&nbsp; When categorizing the nature of the model of this interaction, it seems to clearly fall into the delineation of &ldquo;locally managed&rdquo; &ndash; an observation I made with the assistance of my teammate &ldquo;Melon Lion&rdquo;&rsquo;s analysis of Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This system can be described as locally managed as it deals with single transitions at a time, meaning it allocates a single turn at a time.&nbsp; This can be seen in the above transcript, as there are no places in which Ariel or Katherine begin to talk over one another (if one skips to around 45 seconds, when Ariel says &ldquo;that will &ndash; this number will go&hellip;&rdquo; there is a slight interrupt, but Katherine immediately cedes her turn).&nbsp; In this way, we can also observe that the single turn the system allocates on each occasion of its operation is &lsquo;next turn&rsquo; &ndash; the second criteria for a locally managed system.&nbsp; Just look at how Ariel asks &ldquo;Twice?&rdquo; and then waits to proceed, leaving the next turn up for grabs for Katherine for an example of this phenomenon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lastly, we can see this system seems to handle transitions comprehensively, exclusively, and serially (the final criterion for being considered locally managed).&nbsp; We see the comprehensive part in the different kinds of transitions that occur; from Ariel questioning &ldquo;Twice?&rdquo; and waiting for her contribution to be grounded, to Katherine interrupting Ariel when she thought she needed a suggestion, such as when she says &ldquo;You can do that on a piece of paper&hellip;&rdquo;. The system can said to be managing transitions exclusively, as no other system is seen to be organizing transitions &ndash; i.e., there is no &ldquo;classroom&rdquo; type system at work, wherein one participant must raise their hand to speak or anything else &ndash; the system is locally managed, and managed locally alone.&nbsp; Thirdly, the system can be said to manage transition serially, as it handles all possibilities for transitions comprehensively via its use of &lsquo;next turn&rsquo; in whatever order these transitions come up.&nbsp; For example, Katherine immediately grounds something Ariel says with a simple &ldquo;&hellip;yeah&hellip;&rdquo; early on; later, Ariel asks a question (&ldquo;Twice?&rdquo;) to which Katherine freely responds; later still, Katherine grounds a statement made by Ariel &ldquo;OK, I agree&hellip;&rdquo;. It is an unboundedly reasonable assumption to make that the system is capable of continuing to handle these transitions serially, as it has done so with all these transitions in whatever order they come up.&nbsp; Thus, there is sufficient evidence this system is locally managed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>COMPARISON WITH OTHER TEAMMATE&rsquo;S PAPER</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I read &ldquo;The Melon Lion&rdquo;s paper on Interaction and I thought it was very factual and read smoothly.&nbsp; That said, I thought the focus was a bit too split (which is definitely a problem I had in my initial analysis as well), and wanted to limit the focus when I wrote for the Interaction framework. I realized most all these video clips could be categorized into the &ldquo;Locally Managed&rdquo; category, but wanted to do an in-depth exploration of that, rather than substantiate that claim in just a couple of sentences, as it was done in &ldquo;The Melon Lion&rdquo;s paper.&nbsp; I built off evidence they had suggested from their transcript, along with finding ways to align my transcript&rsquo;s interactions with the three main criteria for a locally managed interaction system, as defined on page 725 of &ldquo;Systematics for the Organization of Turn Taking.&rdquo;</p>\r\n',12,1,1,0,1,'2016-02-07 20:08:10','2016-02-29 00:37:55'),(6,'Cultural Historic','<p>Video:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4\" id=\"yui_3_17_2_3_1454870747713_260\">https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time: 1:04 to 1:51</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the first few seconds of this segment of video, Will asks Kathy if they are allowed to use a calculator to complete the substeps of the problem. The calculator represents a mediating artifact that, if used, would &quot;effect a change in him and his psychic state&quot; (Luria). The use of pen and paper (which are also mediating artifacts), in and of itself, changes the approach to the problem at hand. From a cultural historic perspective, both the pen/paper and the calculator are tools for completing a division problem as a whole. They are also tools for completing the substeps required of a division problem.&nbsp;Interestingly, the tool that is used in a particular instance will change one&#39;s approach to the problem. As discussed in class, individuals use the mediating artifacts as a way to benefit from the experiences of their ancestors.&nbsp;Using the pen and paper involves writing the problem in a certain way on the page in order to organize the steps of the problem. This aspect could&nbsp;also warrant an in-depth cultural-historic analysis since, as discussed in class, different groups of people&nbsp;have developed different methods for handling&nbsp;the problem of managing the space on the paper. Depending on the &quot;cultural environment into which children are born&quot; they will have learned how to manage the paper differently and have &quot;inherited&quot; different knowledge from their cultural environment (as contrasted with set up in this video:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/7xJO-aLqmok\" id=\"yui_3_17_2_3_1454878024971_254\">https://youtu.be/7xJO-aLqmok</a>).&nbsp;Also, there are substeps of each problem including multiplication and subtraction that must be managed differently than if a calculator is used for the substeps.&nbsp;On the other hand, using a calculator to solve a long division problem involves plugging in numbers to represent the problem you are trying to solve&nbsp;and then reading the answer given by the machine. The subproblems are not visible to the individual in this case (unless the calculator is being used only to solve each subproblem step by step, of course).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Later in the clip (around 1:18), Will begins multiplying a part of the larger number in the division problem&nbsp;by 9 to see if that&#39;s the next number in the solution. Kathy quickly interjects to ask why he&#39;s multiplying that number, instead of the divisor, by 9. This interaction represents an internalization, a shift from interpsychological to intrapsychological, for Will. Prior to the correction, he knows there is a number that needs to be multiplied by another number to help solve the subproblem of&nbsp;how many times the number goes into the other. However, he has forgotten which numbers to multiply. Kathy, on the other hand, appears to remember which numbers should be multiplied. She verbalizes her knowledge of the problem at hand. Will begins explaining his thought process to Kathy but then realizes she&#39;s correct. He then proceeds to change his external represenation of the problem by erasing what he had written before and writing the correct number that needs to be multiplied. In doing so, Kathy has passed along knowledge to Will and he has internalized that knowledge. In the future, he will have this knowledge and will be able to use that knowledge to complete the problem individually.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>Video:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4\" id=\"yui_3_17_2_3_1454870747713_260\">https://youtu.be/odr5wAqqpM4</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time: 1:04 to 1:51</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For my second analysis, I will complete it from an external framework. On a high level, it is worth noting how&nbsp;Will writes out the problem on the page. This is a complementary strategy because it reduces the cognitive load for him as it prevents him from having to remember all the numbers in the problem. He structures the problem on the page in a specific way. The structure of the problem is specifically designed to make it easier to complete the problem.&nbsp;Lining up the numbers helps him remember where he is in the problem. Aligning the subtraction reduces the cognitive load of the substeps within the long division problem. Simply by writing the problem down, Will is leaning on the world as a way to make the process of completing the problem easier for himself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As the video segment continues, at 1:23, Kathy catches an error made by Will. In making her point, she physically points at the page. Coupled with her comment &nbsp;-- &quot;Wouldn&#39;t you multiply this number?&quot; -- she simplifies the requirements of the explanation of the error to Will. Imagine if she had to make her point when they weren&#39;t face-to-face. For example, if this were done through a computer screen, Kathy wouldn&#39;t be able to point to the paper. Thus, it would require much more effort on her part to convey they error she has noticed. In fact, it is likely&nbsp;that Will wouldn&#39;t understand what she is referring to by her comment alone and she would have to find another way to make her point understood by her partner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will then proceeds by multiplying the number by nine. As he does this, he not only writes the problem down but he also speaks aloud through the problem. This could be his way of ensuring that his partner agrees with what he is doing by drawing her attention to the exact point he has reached in the problem. It makes his internal thinking apparent to her so that she can also contribute.&nbsp;It could also be his way to reminding himself where he is within the substep of the problem.&nbsp;Another aspect to notes is that he writes down the problem on the side of the page. He doesn&#39;t complete the multiplication substep in his head. As discussed above, this is a way to reduce cognitive load by externalizing the problem and using the physical world to make it easier for him to complete the substep at hand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From completing parts i-iii of the assignment I learned many things. First, a small portion of many of these videos can be analyzed by any of the above frameworks. Each video segment has aspects that can be analyzed from any of the frameworks which shows that there is a lot going on cognitively in the process of completing a long division problem. Second, commenting on the posts of others is a good exercise in seeing the things that others find important. It is a learning experience to critically read the analyses of others and learn from the points they have made. Third, it is interesting to read the comments made by others on my own post. This is also a learning experience. Different people notice different aspects of the video and it is useful to have a conversation regarding the different viewpoints of each member of the group.</p>\r\n',19,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-07 20:33:47','2016-02-27 19:17:33'),(7,'Brad\'s long division (2:50-3:50)','<p>While Roger videotapes, Brad is performing the long division. In analyzing this video, I gain an insight into the internal thinking of Brad. One of my first observations is how Brad structures his problem. Instead of attempting to visualize how many times 3,437 goes into 9,705 as most everyone else does, Brad decides to write out all the multiples of 3,437 on the side of the paper. He does this so he can refer to the table when he needs to divide a new number by 3,437, perhaps he has some procedural knowledge that this will make his life easier later on. Brad considered how the mediating artifact, the paper, could help him in solving the problem. The intra-psychological process of thinking ahead is observable in a few different ways as Brad works on the long division.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After discovering the first multiple is 2, Brad goes into the subtraction phase of long division. When he first starts the subtraction, he sets up the problem incorrectly but quickly catches his mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Wait, wait, wait, that&#39;s not how you do math&quot; (3:05). Using the eraser, he completely gets rid of the extra number and re-structures his problem correctly. Again, Brad is concerned by how he structures his writing. Instead of writing over the mistake (which is probably what I would have done) or crossing it out, he gets rid of it completely. I imagine he is thinking ahead again and is planning how he can manipulate the mediating artifact to make the problem visually clearer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brad interacts with the mediating artifact much more than I would have. As he subtracts numbers from 9,705,159,253, he draws a slash through the one&#39;s that have a number carried over from the previous subtraction. The slash probably helps him keep track of where he is in the problem and to remind him that there is a remainder. Once he finishes the first subtraction completely, he draws an arrow as he &quot;carries down&quot; the next digit in the 9,705,159,253. The arrow serves no real purpose in the multiplication problem but it does help visualize what he is doing with the numbers. He might have figured out that these marks help when he was learning long division long ago and now his procedural knowledge is coming back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brad also has an internal dialogue that he externalizes throughout the long division. He isn&#39;t explaining what he is doing but rather narrating his actions. Perhaps externalizing his actions helps him think it through. Or perhaps hearing it out loud helps him remember the next step in completing the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, Brad has a slow beginning to the long division problem but his procedural knowledge helps him make manipulate the problem to be clearer and simpler to solve. He initially questions himself on how to set up the subtraction and hesitates when numbers have a remainder.&nbsp; However, as he begins the long division, his calculations become smoother. He uses the table he made in the beginning as a reference and uses arrows and slashes to externalize his thinking. His confidence grows throughout the clip and his calculations become faster as the rules and tricks to long division come back to him</p>\r\n','<p>While Roger videotapes, Brad is performing the long division. In analyzing this video, I gain an insight into the internal thinking of Brad. One of my first observations is how Brad structures his problem. Instead of attempting to visualize how many times 3,437 goes into 9,705 as most everyone else does, Brad decides to write out all the multiples of 3,437 on the side of the paper. He does this so he can refer to the table when he needs to divide a new number by 3,437, perhaps he has some procedural knowledge that this will make his life easier later on. Brad considered how the mediating artifact, the paper, could help him in solving the problem. The intra-psychological process of thinking ahead is observable in a few different ways as Brad works on the long division.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After discovering the first multiple is 2, Brad goes into the subtraction phase of long division. When he first starts the subtraction, he sets up the problem incorrectly but quickly catches his mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Wait, wait, wait, that&#39;s not how you do math&quot; (3:05). Using the eraser, he completely gets rid of the extra number and re-structures his problem correctly. Again, Brad is concerned by how he structures his writing. Instead of writing over the mistake (which is probably what I would have done) or crossing it out, he gets rid of it completely. I imagine he is thinking ahead again and is planning how he can manipulate the mediating artifact to make the problem visually clearer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brad interacts with the mediating artifact much more than I would have. As he subtracts numbers from 9,705,159,253, he draws a slash through the one&#39;s that have a number carried over from the previous subtraction. The slash probably helps him keep track of where he is in the problem and to remind him that there is a remainder. Once he finishes the first subtraction completely, he draws an arrow as he &quot;carries down&quot; the next digit in the 9,705,159,253. The arrow serves no real purpose in the multiplication problem but it does help visualize what he is doing with the numbers. He might have figured out that these marks help when he was learning long division long ago and now his procedural knowledge is coming back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brad also has an internal dialogue that he externalizes throughout the long division. He isn&#39;t explaining what he is doing but rather narrating his actions. Perhaps externalizing his actions helps him think it through. Or perhaps hearing it out loud helps him remember the next step in completing the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, Brad has a slow beginning to the long division problem but his procedural knowledge helps him make manipulate the problem to be clearer and simpler to solve. He initially questions himself on how to set up the subtraction and hesitates when numbers have a remainder.&nbsp; However, as he begins the long division, his calculations become smoother. He uses the table he made in the beginning as a reference and uses arrows and slashes to externalize his thinking. His confidence grows throughout the clip and his calculations become faster as the rules and tricks to long division come back to him</p>\r\n',23,1,1,0,1,'2016-02-08 04:30:40','2016-02-08 04:30:40'),(8,'','<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-5bfe3114-c465-1a33-5b4a-cb66048520fb\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">Joel Betke</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">Richard Alterman </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">Cultural Historic Perspective</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:2.4;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">The cultural historic perspective excels when it looks at multiple different groups of people. Different people have different backgrounds, previous knowledge, approaches to problems, tool, rules, and customs in dividing labor that they use. In addition the hints on the cultural historic perspective that Professor Alterman put on LATTE said that in this approach we should focus on differences in approaches between groups. For these reasons I have decided to use not one video segment, but three. About 1 min from the beginning of 2 groups videos. The groups were Ethan and Tallie, and Katherine and Will. The beginning of the video is not an arbitrary pick, but rather I will focus mostly on the tools being used and the division of labor that ensues, and these are usually decided early in the videos. What are the important questions here? One is how effective are different groups being. The cultural historic perspective is a good lens for answering this question. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:2.4;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;text-indent: 36pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">We can judge the effectiveness of a group partly by how well they divide labor. We see two groups both do well here. In the group of Kathy and Will, Kathy is the camerawoman. Will does the computations for the math, and also talks through his thought process out loud, while Kathy mostly listens quietly, but then interjects when Will is stumped or when he hits an error. This is in contrast to Ethan and Tallie where Tallie is leading Ethan through the steps of the process, and Ethan is doing the computations. Both groups have a good division of labor here and are complementing each other well. I know that when I did this activity the labor was not divided well. We were both essentially trying to do the process at the same time, and this just didn&rsquo;t work out. The two strategies that have been laid out by these two groups are much more effective, because there is not much downtime between the two groups. They each are processing something different about the situation that complements the other, so there are not wasted mental computations. These effects are continued in a bit of a different lens below. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:2.4;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">The interaction between Kathy and Will is a good example of how viewing a situations&rsquo; inter to intra psychological shifts can be revealing. The Division of labor between Kathy and Will that was talked about earlier where Kathy did the error checking and general keeping on track of the situation, while Will did the computations and spoke his mind, created an interesting wave of shifts between inter and intra psychological. Mode 1 was that Will was talking and doing computations while Katherine was listening. Mode 2 was that Katherine was interjecting with either a correction or offering a direction for Will to go. In Mode one there are both inter and intrapsychological processes going on. Will is computing alone in his head and Katherine is error checking alone. Katherine&rsquo;s error checking is partly inter psychological with Will, because he is repeating his thought process out loud. Will is mostly in an intra mode because he is not receiving any input from Katherine. In mode 2, which is mostly interpsychological, it is the case that Katherine is mostly offering help to Will. </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">The cultural historic approach is a good lens for this transcript. For example, looking at the situation in this way answers the </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">question, why is Will talking more than Kathy. It is not that Kathy is lazy, but that she has effectively used inter to intra </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">psychological shifts to her advantage to divide labor well. Division of labor and inter intra psychological shifts prove to be </span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:16px;font-family:\'Times New Roman\';color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;\">good tools here.</span></p>\r\n','<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-509cf843-308b-04dd-4049-f98f273e53b3\">Second Analysis: The long division problem solving between Ethan and Tallie can be well understood in the interactive framework. Since this is something that neither of them have done in a long time, neither of them initially know what to do. What starts at the beginning of the video is a building of common ground through interactive exploration. Tallie chimes in, &ldquo;so it&rsquo;s how many times this number...&rdquo;. Tallie is silent for a second or two, indicating that maybe she is not sure on the direction to be headed. Ethan notes this gap in conversation and is also now remembering this general pattern and says, &ldquo;I think it goes into&hellip;&rdquo; He is now trying to remember the specifics. Tallie notes that Ethan is not totally sure either and finally takes back the lead to say it is how many times, &ldquo;3437 goes into 9700,&rdquo;. The group continues in this way for a while. They go through these waves of confusion, person knowing the most information filling in the gaps, and acceptance phrases. They do this at each stage until they have constructed the entire algorithm for long division. Turn taking and social cues give an effective analysis of how the group agreed on an approach here, and the basic common ground they agreed upon is the framework of the rest of the video, making the interactive framework another informative viewpoint.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-509cf843-308b-04dd-4049-f98f273e53b3\">Teammates Comments: The Rhinoceros looks at the proceedings of the group members through the lenses of embodied practice and procedural knowledge. This is an important observation because where everyone is in this situation with respect being able to solve about and communicate upon this problem is dependent upon the things that they have previously practiced. People try to construct their common ground from this procedural knowledge that they carried in. They go to try to start doing the problem and the embodied practice hits them and they can start to communicate about it a bit. I noticed in multiple videos that the realization of a solution was preceeded directly by appropriate pencil movements. The Llamma points out that simple things like using pencil and paper here are integral to the way that we are thinking about the situation at hand. Obviously without pencil and paper the entire process would have to be done in the head. I noted that groups that were using pencils as opposed to pen had small but present benefits in organization. The cognitive offload that the Llamma talks about makes this observation a formal statement. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<b id=\"docs-internal-guid-509cf843-308b-04dd-4049-f98f273e53b3\">Review of Assignment: The biggest thing I learned while doing this assignment is that no one approach can give you a satisfactory analysis of a situation. When I was doing the cultural historic approach I felt like I was ignoring more present psychological factors a bit too much compared to the interactive approach. It was the same the other way around. Talking about division of labor on a high level was useful for illuminating why each person was doing each set of tasks at hand, and would sometimes seem more appropriate to interject about than an interactive factor. </b></p>\r\n',30,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-08 04:40:34','2016-03-01 04:59:24'),(9,'','<p>Video: Ethan and Talie,&nbsp;4:54 - 5:40</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The joint goal of the collaborative activity in the video is to solve the math problem. However, this is composed of many small subgoals and subproblems - in this section of the video clip in particular, the main subgoal is to figure out how many times 3437 goes into 25082. In attempting to solve this problem, Talie and Ethan participate in a party administered, interactionally managed system. In this system, the participants usually speak one at a time, do not have a predefined set amount of time for how long they should be talking, and do not have a predefined order for who should speak when. In this video segment, Ethan and Talie never talk over one another, and usually switch off on talking except for when there is a pause in the conversation, and Ethan makes an observation even though he talked twice in a row.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>E: So let&#39;s just do this clearer, so we have 2508.<br />\r\nT: And then bring down the 2<br />\r\nE: Bring down the 2<br />\r\n(pause)<br />\r\nE: I would say probably 7 times<br />\r\nT: Ok yeah, so 3 times 7 is 21, so, uh, it may be able to go in 8 times<br />\r\nE: Ok, we can try<br />\r\nT: Oh, we checked 8 and 8 is too high<br />\r\nE: So it&#39;s 7?<br />\r\nT: Wait, is that, is that the answer, or is that after we multiplied? No that&#39;s what you multiplied.<br />\r\nE: That&#39;s where we multiplied.<br />\r\nT: So it&#39;s gonna be too high. So it&#39;s going to have to be 7.<br />\r\nE: So 7 times that. 3437 times 7. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reading the transcript above, it is clear that Ethan and Talie are tackling several problems and interacting with both each other and the physical paper in front of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>First, they have to set up the physical representation of the math problem to match the next problem they are going to do. Interacting with the paper, the physical representation of the math problem they are attempting to solve, Ethan notices that the writing is getting messy, says &quot;so let&#39;s just do this clearer&quot;, and writing 2508 lower down on the paper so it is easier to read. Talie acknowledges what Ethan is doing and initiates the next relevant contribution by telling him to bring down the 2. Ethan repeats &quot;bring down the 2&quot;, an acceptance phrase that displays Ethan&#39;s understanding of Talie&#39;s instructions. Ethan also interacts with the paper when he draws a line to bring down the 2, but does not draw over the already written parts because that would make them harder to read.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the paper is set up for the next problem, both Ethan and Talie understand that they need to think about how many times 3437 multiplies into 25082. While it is never outright said, it is within the common ground of the activity that this is the next step. Ethan says he thinks it would probably be 7 times and interacts with the paper again by pointing at the top of the page. Talie acknowledges Ethan&#39;s idea when she replies &quot;ok, yeah&quot;, then offers the suggestion that &quot;it may be able to go in 8 times&quot;. Ethan lets Talie know that her contribution was a good idea and he will follow through with it, but before he gets a chance to do the math, Talie moves her pencil and points at the page so Ethan can see where they previously tried to multiply by 8. After she points her pencil, Ethan points his pencil at the same spot to signal that he understood what she was pointing out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The exchange of idea and acknowledgments continues for the rest of the video segment, where Ethan and Talie go back and forth between asking questions and verifying each other&#39;s suppositions about the math on the paper and whether 7 is the answer. Throughout the minute-long segment, they are constantly interacting with each other and with their physical environment, all while doing things like constantly increasing the common ground between them by asking and answering each other&#39;s questions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>Video: Ethan and Talie: 4:54 - 5:40</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, I wrote about how the interaction between Ethan and Talie can be viewed as a party administered, interactionally managed system wherein the two participants interact with each other and the physical representation of the math problem in front of them. However, a lot of the discussion between Ethan and Talie in this segment can also be viewed from a cultural historic perspective, as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>E: So let&#39;s just do this clearer, so we have 2508.<br />\r\nT: And then bring down the 2<br />\r\nE: Bring down the 2 (pause)<br />\r\nE: I would say probably 7 times<br />\r\nT: Ok yeah, so 3 times 7 is 21, so, uh, it may be able to go in 8 times<br />\r\nE: Ok, we can try<br />\r\nT: Oh, we checked 8 and 8 is too high<br />\r\nE: So it&#39;s 7?<br />\r\nT: Wait, is that, is that the answer, or is that after we multiplied? No that&#39;s what you multiplied.<br />\r\nE: That&#39;s where we multiplied.<br />\r\nT: So it&#39;s gonna be too high. So it&#39;s going to have to be 7.<br />\r\nE: So 7 times that. 3437 times 7.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the transcript above, Ethan and Talie are working with the joint goal of figuring out how many times 3437 multiplies into 25082. Just looking at this video segment, it is unclear whether Ethan and Talie both knew how to do long division before doing this in-class assignment, but we can probably assume that they learned how to do long division if they both grew up around the same time in the United States. This is important because the physical representation of the math problem - the actual way they set up the long division on the paper - is a vital part of their interaction. By coming from the same cultural historic background of going through the United States common core school system, they are capable of using each other&#39;s language and physical models to solve the problem faster than if one of them had to teach the other how to do long division on paper.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, we can assume that Ethan&#39;s previous experience with doing computations in math class is that they had to be neat - if they weren&#39;t neat, he was probably docked points from his test or homework assignments. This comes through when he re-writes part of the problem at the very beginning of this video segment. Talie, because she does not question Ethan &quot;doing this clearer&quot; and even helps him with the next step, probably comes from the same cultural historic background.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of my classmates mentioned that cultural artifacts are an important part of any activity - basically, when a person uses an object during an activity enough times, their internal representation of that activity includes the object. This is clear in this video segment because Ethan and Talie both use the physical representation of the problem on the paper as well as their pens and pencils to do the math. In this video segment, Ethan and Talie both point their pencils on an area of the paper to signal to each other that &quot;8 is too high&quot;. Instead of saying, &quot;Well, we did this before, and it equaled this number, which was too high for what we&#39;re looking for.&quot;, Ethan and Talie both point their pens and pencils (an object they probably associate doing any sort of math with) at an area of the paper where they previously did that calculation, and both of them understood that action without having to verbally explain it. Math certainly doesn&#39;t require the use of pen and paper, but it looks like Ethan and Talie both internalized those objects as being associated with the activity of doing math, to the point where they can communicate through those objects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From writing both of these analyses and reading those of my classmates, I learned that there is more than just one correct way to view a particular interaction. Doing the first analysis, I was convinced that my interpretation of the scene was the best, most clear way to view it. After reading the analyses of my teammates, I was forced to think about how the interaction I thought I knew completely well was illuminated by examining it through a cultural historic perspective. By looking at it through this lens, I learned more about the common ground of information that Ethan and Talie must have been working from, as well as how they managed to non-verbally communicate through the cultural artifacts that they associated with doing math.</p>\r\n',26,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-08 04:41:09','2016-03-01 04:31:06'),(10,'Cultural Historic Analysis of Katherine and Ariel\'s Long Division','<p>Video Used: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WkgYYpVXdZA&amp;feature=youtu.be&amp;t=2m35s\">Katherine and Ariel</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Between 2:15 and 3:15</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When viewing this video in a cultural historic framework, we can see a number of actions that Ariel and Katherine make that point toward what they have learned from prior generations. Given the nature of long division, we assume that they have learned the technique either in school or from their parents, rather than developing this skill on their own. This automatically sets the action up as learned from their cultural history, given that things taught in schools are generally methods that have been used and developed for years. The very first thing we notice is the way Ariel writes the problem out. The divisor is placed on the left, while the dividend is on the right. Logically, this does not quite make sense, as in English we read from left to right. The first number we consider, the dividend, would therefore logically come on the left. The fact that this is not true in Ariel&rsquo;s case indicates that the formation in which she writes the problem is something she learned from someone else, likely her parents or teachers, and is therefore a cultural mechanism. The next thing we notice is the way Ariel writes the subtraction on her paper. She lines up the values, ones to ones, tens to tens, etc.. This notation aids in memory and allows for other cues to be written clearly and helpfully around the values. For example, the notation above the number being subtracted from shows that Ariel has decreased higher places and added ten to lower places in order to subtract digits where the subtracting number has a higher value from the number being subtracted from. This visual cue makes it easier for Ariel to subtract, as she doesn&rsquo;t have to think about other places, only the place she is currently working on. She changes 9 7 0 5 to 8 16 10 5. This crossing out and increasing method seems to also be a learned method. The uniform way that the notation is written demonstrates this. After attempting to subtract the two values she calculates, Ariel then adds the difference to value being subtracted in order to check if she got the correct answer. She does this by adding one place at a time, starting from the right to the left, and carrying over the tens place of any values that add to an answer greater than 10 to the next place over to the left. Often this technique is done by writing the carried 1 above the numbers being added, Ariel, however, did it in her head. This indicates that it is a technique she has often used and internalized to the point that she no longer needs external cues to keep track of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This framework gives us insight not only into Ariel&#39;s thought processes, but also into the general thoughts of the community and culture in which she grew up. It gives us a clue as to how these types of problems are solved in Ariel&#39;s community.</p>\r\n','<p>Video Used: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WkgYYpVXdZA&amp;feature=youtu.be&amp;t=2m35s\">Katherine and Ariel</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Between 2:15 and 3:15</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When viewing this video in a cultural historic framework, we can see a number of actions that Ariel and Katherine make that point toward what they have learned from prior generations. Given the nature of long division, we assume that they have learned the technique either in school or from their parents, rather than developing this skill on their own. This automatically sets the action up as learned from their cultural history, given that things taught in schools are generally methods that have been used and developed for years. The very first thing we notice is the way Ariel writes the problem out. The divisor is placed on the left, while the dividend is on the right. Logically, this does not quite make sense, as in English we read from left to right. The first number we consider, the dividend, would therefore logically come on the left. The fact that this is not true in Ariel&rsquo;s case indicates that the formation in which she writes the problem is something she learned from someone else, likely her parents or teachers, and is therefore a cultural mechanism. The next thing we notice is the way Ariel writes the subtraction on her paper. She lines up the values, ones to ones, tens to tens, etc.. This notation aids in memory and allows for other cues to be written clearly and helpfully around the values. For example, the notation above the number being subtracted from shows that Ariel has decreased higher places and added ten to lower places in order to subtract digits where the subtracting number has a higher value from the number being subtracted from. This visual cue makes it easier for Ariel to subtract, as she doesn&rsquo;t have to think about other places, only the place she is currently working on. She changes 9 7 0 5 to 8 16 10 5. This crossing out and increasing method seems to also be a learned method. The uniform way that the notation is written demonstrates this. After attempting to subtract the two values she calculates, Ariel then adds the difference to value being subtracted in order to check if she got the correct answer. She does this by adding one place at a time, starting from the right to the left, and carrying over the tens place of any values that add to an answer greater than 10 to the next place over to the left. Often this technique is done by writing the carried 1 above the numbers being added, Ariel, however, did it in her head. This indicates that it is a technique she has often used and internalized to the point that she no longer needs external cues to keep track of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This framework gives us insight not only into Ariel&#39;s thought processes, but also into the general thoughts of the community and culture in which she grew up. It gives us a clue as to how these types of problems are solved in Ariel&#39;s community.</p>\r\n',21,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-08 16:46:49','2016-02-09 03:22:44'),(11,'Coordination and Common Ground in Conversation','<p>Clip analyzed: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PHJlrJ7C9dU&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PHJlrJ7C9dU&amp;feature=youtu.be</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Timeframe analyzed: (1:24 - 2:24)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am analyzing the given clip through the interactive analytic framework. To give context to the situation, the first minute of the clip did not contain conversation: while the filmed participant, Ken, speaks aloud as he performs long division, there is little to no verbal interaction between him and the recording participant, Rick. However, at <strong>1:24</strong>, Ken asks Rick if he should add a zero, pointing to the area where he is unsure of the next step. Rick then answers at <strong>1:29</strong>, telling Ken to instead &quot;pull the one down.&quot; At <strong>1:31</strong> Ken responds by repeating Rick&#39;s directions (though with a slightly uncertain undertone) &quot;pull the one down,&quot; and then repeats that remark with certainty at <strong>1:34</strong>. After this confirmation, their conversation dwindles and they move forward with the given task.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Though seemingly insignificant, this video segment exemplifies a complex interaction involving both the turn-taking and common ground phenomena. Conversation is highly interactive. As a joint activity, it requires the participants to understand the conversation&#39;s context, actively collaborate in discussion, take turns in speaking, affirm that contributions made become common knowledge, and so much more. When conversation is combined with a collaborative task, such as long division, the complexity heightens. Together the participants strive towards a common goal, using conversation as a tool to question, clarify, confirm, and progress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Taking turns in discussion is absolutely imperative for a logically structured and comprehensible conversation, and is a core element in the interactive analytic framework. Its underlying component of coordination is key in achieving the shared and individual goals of the joint activity. Coordination can be carried out in various way. In the aforementioned example, Ken uses cadence to communicate to Rick that he is unsure about what to do next. This is interpreted by Rick as a question, designating himself the next speaker in conversation, and answering Ken&#39;s question. Ken then coordinates his confirmation of Rick&#39;s answer by first repeating it (once with a similar questioning intonation, and another time with certainty), and then converting it into an external representation (writing the one down in its proper location).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can now examine the role of grounded interactions in conversation, which epitomizes the interactive analytic framework. Maintaining common ground in a joint activity is mandatory for its functioning, with grounded contributions making it possible. Just as turns must be taken in a sequential order for clarity and comprehension, so must the contributions to a conversation. These contributions must ensure that all of the participants have a sufficient understanding of what was said, and that all are aware of this common understanding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order for the common ground to be made apparent, each grounding interaction has two phases: presentation and acceptations. These are demonstrated perfectly by Ken and Rick&#39;s conversation. In the presentation phase, Rick provides the utterance that Ken should &ldquo;pull the one down.&rdquo; Then, in the acceptance phase, Ken gives evidence of his understanding of Rick&#39;s assertion through acknowledgment/demonstration (repeating the given directions) and display (following the directions by carrying them out in the long division problem). This acts as sufficient evidence from Ken in proving that he understands Rick&#39;s utterance, and that they now share common ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What appeared to be a brief, minor interaction proved to hold a wealth of information using the interactive analytic framework.</p>\r\n','<p><strong>Clip analyzed</strong>: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PHJlrJ7C9dU&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PHJlrJ7C9dU&amp;feature=youtu.be</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Timeframe analyzed</strong>: (1:24 - 2:24)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will now analyze the given clip through the internal analytic framework, and reiterate the transcript&#39;s key interactions: while the filmed participant, Ken, speaks aloud as he performs long division, there is little to no verbal interaction between him and the recording participant, Rick. However, at <strong>1:24</strong>, Ken asks Rick if he should add a zero, pointing to the area where he is unsure of the next step. Rick then answers at <strong>1:29</strong>, telling Ken to instead &quot;pull the one down.&quot; At <strong>1:31</strong> Ken responds by repeating Rick&#39;s directions (though with a slightly uncertain undertone) &quot;pull the one down,&quot; and then repeats that remark with certainty at <strong>1:34</strong>. After this confirmation, their conversation dwindles and they move forward with the given task.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ken clearly has procedural knowledge of the long division activity: he remembers the general layout through which he represents the problem, and remembers how to solve the mathematical elements to it. However, because &quot;[he hasn&#39;t] done this since fourth grade,&quot; (<strong>1:32</strong>) he cannot clearly recall some of the steps to solving it. Though he most certainly has fully solved long division problems in the past and has solid prior knowledge of doing so, calling upon this information in his long-term memory has drawn up some blanks. Through asking his partner, Rick, and pointing to the area of confusion on his mediating artifact (the paper where the long division problem is externally represented), he is able to obtain the answer to his question.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this clip, Ken also demonstrates that he has an internal locus of control. Somebody with an internal locus of control believes that they can influence events and their outcome, while somebody with an external locus of control would believe that their environment and other external factors control their decisions and outcomes. When Ken does not immediately recall the next step to the math problem (<b>1:24</b>), he does not blame his surrounding environment, or claim that fate has decided to make him forget how to do long division, and believe that there is nothing he can do abut it. Ken instead decides to ask Rick to clarify what the next step would be. By initiating this exchange, Ken receives the information needed to continue the problem. He knew that he was in control of solving the problem, and could directly influence its outcome.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, this re-learning of a step in the activity through an external, verbal exchange with Rick is a perfect example of the shift from the interpsychological to the intrapsychological. At <b>1:29</b><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">, Rick dictates that Ken should &ldquo;pull the one down.&rdquo; Ken is receptive to this answer, and repeats it aloud to himself (</span><b>1:31</b><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">). He is transducing this information from a social exchange to an individual, intrapsychological understanding. He then demonstrates his understanding by carrying out the next step, and proceeding with the problem.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Grey Crocodile&#39;s analysis using the Internal framework inspired my second analysis. Their discussion of the participant&#39;s internal dialogue, and how this influences their representations of solving the long division problem, made me wonder what internal events were occurring in my selected transcript. The Indigo Eagle&#39;s analysis using the Cultural Historic framework was also thought-provoking, but I found that there was a greater wealth of information in my selected video that related to the internal framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I first examined this clip from the interactive framework. I chose a video segment that demonstrated plentiful interaction in hopes of making my analysis less of a stretch. I also selected this timeframe in hopes of there being &quot;something more&quot; that I had not yet noticed, so that I would still be able to unearth enough details from a second framework&#39;s viewpoint. It turns out that there was enough information for me to discover, and its discovery was made easier thanks to the Grey Crocodile&#39;s insightful analysis in their first draft. I realized the importance of looking at a specific event in the transcript, seeing what internal events might have contributed to that occurrence, and what phenomenon could explain this. The comments on my post revolved around Ken&#39;s questioning Rick about the next step, and what this meant for his understanding/re-learning of the activity, which made me more interested in analyzing that exchange further.</p>\r\n',8,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-08 19:59:53','2016-02-29 18:26:05'),(12,'The Use of External Elements to Reduce Mental Loads','<p>My assigned framework is external, and from this lens, I will be analyzing 0:50&nbsp;to 1:50&nbsp;of Zak and Maria&#39;s long division video. In the attached reading, it mentioned recruiting external elements to tackle different mental tasks. The example it used was the use of hands to help count coins. We see a lot of external organizing abilities in the long division clip with Zak and Maria as well. From the use of hands to stay oriented in a problem to using a pencil to write down subproblems to reduce the mental load, and in those subproblems even making markings or using little tricks to keep her spot and further reduce the mental load.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When this section of the video first starts, (approximately from 0:53 to 1:02) Maria is tasked with multiplying 3437 by two. Now, one could probably do some mental math and double this in their head, but in doing that, you would be using a portion of your working memory. In the same way a computer has RAM, we have this limited amount of fluid, working memory which we employ to solve tasks. Instead of putting a large burden on her working memory and risking making a mistake or losing her place in the main problem, Maria employs the use of a pencil to mark the subproblem 3437 * 2 and then breaks that subproblem down into even more subproblems: 2 * 7, carry the one, which she marks with her pencil so that she can remember to add one to the next place, 2 * 3 etc. Maria has just used external elements (the pen and paper) to mark her subproblem of 3437 * 2. Then, with the pencil, turned that subproblem into even more easily managed subproblems which require&nbsp;very little use of her working memory. Multiplying sets of single numbers is extremely simple for somebody who knows their multiplication tables, and is much simpler than trying to grind out 3437 * 2 in her head and risking a mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, after completing the subproblem of 3437 * 2, she must subtract the result from the first four digits of the dividend. Again, instead of performing the operation in her head and risking a mistake, she writes down the result with each digit lined up below the first four digits of the dividend, making it easier for her to know which numbers need to be subtracted from what. Next, while subtracting, she says &quot;... and this becomes six and this becomes ten...&quot;, at 1:18. While saying this, she marks off these changes on the paper. This helps her remember what changes she has made to the digits in order to perform the operation without error. This method of marking off certain elements reminds me of the counting coins example in the reading, where in some strategies the participants who were using their hands would cover a nickel to remind themselves that they &#39;stole a nickel&#39; in their counting. Maria is doing the same thing when she crosses out the number and changes it: she&#39;s using external elements to remind herself where she is in the problem, and what has already been subtracted from. Finally, after this subtraction operation is finished, she needs to bring down the next digit of the dividend. To do this, she draws an arrow down from the fifth digit which is another example of her using external elements (the symbols made by the pen on the paper), to reduce her mental load and keep track of her place in the problem.</p>\r\n','<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jrm3lXd3Zzo\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jrm3lXd3Zzo</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>My assigned framework is external, and from this lens, I will be analyzing 0:50&nbsp;to 1:50&nbsp;of Zak and Maria&#39;s long division video. In the attached reading, it mentioned recruiting external elements to tackle different mental tasks. The example it used was the use of hands to help count coins. We see a lot of external organizing abilities in the long division clip with Zak and Maria as well. From the use of hands to stay oriented in a problem to using a pencil to write down subproblems to reduce the mental load, and in those subproblems even making markings or using little tricks to keep her spot and further reduce the mental load.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When this section of the video first starts, (approximately from 0:53 to 1:02) Maria is tasked with multiplying 3437 by two. Now, one could probably do some mental math and double this in their head, but in doing that, you would be using a portion of your working memory. In the same way a computer has RAM, we have this limited amount of fluid, working memory which we employ to solve tasks. Instead of putting a large burden on her working memory and risking making a mistake or losing her place in the main problem, Maria employs the use of a pencil to mark the subproblem 3437 * 2 and then breaks that subproblem down into even more subproblems: 2 * 7, carry the one, which she marks with her pencil so that she can remember to add one to the next place, 2 * 3 etc. Maria has just used external elements (the pen and paper) to mark her subproblem of 3437 * 2. Then, with the pencil, turned that subproblem into even more easily managed subproblems which require&nbsp;very little use of her working memory. Multiplying sets of single numbers is extremely simple for somebody who knows their multiplication tables, and is much simpler than trying to grind out 3437 * 2 in her head and risking a mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next, after completing the subproblem of 3437 * 2, she must subtract the result from the first four digits of the dividend. Again, instead of performing the operation in her head and risking a mistake, she writes down the result with each digit lined up below the first four digits of the dividend, making it easier for her to know which numbers need to be subtracted from what. Next, while subtracting, she says &quot;... and this becomes six and this becomes ten...&quot;, at 1:18. While saying this, she marks off these changes on the paper. This helps her remember what changes she has made to the digits in order to perform the operation without error. This method of marking off certain elements reminds me of the counting coins example in the reading, where in some strategies the participants who were using their hands would cover a nickel to remind themselves that they &#39;stole a nickel&#39; in their counting. Maria is doing the same thing when she crosses out the number and changes it: she&#39;s using external elements to remind herself where she is in the problem, and what has already been subtracted from. Finally, after this subtraction operation is finished, she needs to bring down the next digit of the dividend. To do this, she draws an arrow down from the fifth digit which is another example of her using external elements (the symbols made by the pen on the paper), to reduce her mental load and keep track of her place in the problem.</p>\r\n',22,1,2,0,1,'2016-02-08 20:44:51','2016-02-08 22:13:11'),(13,'Interactive Framework','<p>Katherine and Ariel&#39;s video starting from 1:38:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/WkgYYpVXdZA?t=1m38s\">https://youtu.be/WkgYYpVXdZA?t=1m38s</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>State of long division problem:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/2/content_screen_shot_2016-02-08_at_4_16_48_pm.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 98px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Transcript of conversation:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rick in background: Remember to talk aloud while you&rsquo;re doing it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine: &nbsp;Yeah talk aloud</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PAUSE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel: &nbsp;Shit *laughs*</p>\r\n\r\n<p>K: &nbsp;What happened?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: &nbsp;Sorry</p>\r\n\r\n<p>K: &nbsp;Then you take the one down, right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: &nbsp;Yeah I took the one down.I&rsquo;m trying to like subtract here man</p>\r\n\r\n<p>PAUSE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>K: &nbsp;I can help subtract.But you take the next one down, right? &nbsp;Oh! are you seriously just trying to figure out how to subtract?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: &nbsp;Yeah *laughs*</p>\r\n\r\n<p>K: &nbsp;Oh okay um *pause* I can&rsquo;t see is that a 10 minus an 8? ---cause I think that&rsquo;s 2--</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: &nbsp;--No that&rsquo;s--- that&rsquo;s a 16</p>\r\n\r\n<p>K: &nbsp;16&nbsp;minus 8&nbsp;is 8</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The beginning of this segment, Rick told the class to talk aloud while doing the division.&nbsp; So, the cooperative long division activity, while interactionally and locally managed (as it is guided by Ariel and Katherine&rsquo;s contributions, writing and recording respectively), was not entirely party administered.&nbsp; Due to the nature of this assignment, the participants did not have full control over the nature of their interactions.&nbsp; It is very unlikely that Ariel would normally dictate her actions and thought process while dividing without explicit instruction to do so.&nbsp; As a result, this interaction does not quite fit the definition of a conversation as defined by the Sacks, Schegloff, and Jefferson, and thus does not necessarily follow the same rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After being prompted to speak her thoughts, Ariel signals some sort of situation when she says &ldquo;shit.&rdquo;&nbsp; Katherine interprets this as a sign of distress and attempts to assist Ariel with the long division.&nbsp; Her interpretation of Ariel&rsquo;s problem, influenced by the paper was incorrect, and thus their interaction for the next few turns is almost entirely repairing and forging common ground, which may have been lost when Katherine moved and lost track of the current state of the joint activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine, understanding there is an issue, looks to the paper for guidance as to Ariel&rsquo;s problem (as the paper is an externalization of Ariel&rsquo;s thought process). &nbsp;Katherine assumes, presumably from Ariel&rsquo;s lack of writing, that she has forgotten the next step in long division:&nbsp; &ldquo;Then you take the one down, right?&rdquo; referring to 1 digit in 9705159253.&nbsp; The &ldquo;right?&rdquo; is an invitation for Ariel to take her turn and respond to Katherine&rsquo;s proposed next step.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ariel states her current situation within the long division problem:&nbsp; &ldquo;I&rsquo;m trying to like subtract here man.&rdquo;&nbsp; Katherine accepts that Ariel&rsquo;s contribution that the difficulty stems from subtraction by offering her assistance (after a significant pause), providing evidence of understanding via &ldquo;initiation of the relevant next contribution&rdquo; (&ldquo;I can help subtract&rdquo;).&nbsp; At this point, it has been acknowledged by both parties that Ariel is subtracting and that some trouble has arisen.&nbsp; It is interesting then, that Katherine, despite accepting Ariel&rsquo;s contribution, repeats her advice to continue to the step after subtraction (&ldquo;but you take the next one down, right?&rdquo;). &nbsp;&nbsp;This implies a sort of paradox of understanding, in which Katherine has externally accepted that Ariel is subtracting, thus grounding the current situation, but still has the incorrect view of the current state of the joint activity.&nbsp; This conflict between her assumption and proof of the contrary is probably where the cause of the pause before Katherine offers her help with the subtraction, her false acceptance.&nbsp; Her exclamation of &ldquo;oh!&rdquo; after she urged Ariel to continue is the real acceptance of Ariel&rsquo;s contribution, and she retracts her original (false) acceptance by asking for clarification of Ariel&rsquo;s problem:&nbsp; &ldquo;Are you seriously just trying to figure out how to subtract?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Katherine, then having the correct context to view the problem and offer advice, assists in subtracting.</p>\r\n','<p>My initial analysis of the interaction between Ariel and Katherine completely ignored the experience of the external representation of the long division problem (as pointed out by a helpful commenter), and thus, externalization is my focus for this second analysis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Initially during this chosen time frame, there is little conversation between the two, and Katherine appears to be left to find Ariel&rsquo;s place in the problem based on her understanding of the external representation of the problem and Ariel&rsquo;s markings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a longer problem such as this, it is necessary for Ariel to reduce her cognitive load by writing down her previous calculations rather than keeping them all in her memory (a team member analyzed Maria&rsquo;s external calculations of similar multiplication subproblems in more detail). &nbsp;Due to these visual clues, Katherine sees that the multiplication aspect of this subproblem has been completed as the subtraction has been written out.&nbsp; Because Ariel stops writing for a significant pause, Katherine assumes that she has stopped calculating, due to the ingrained understanding that writing reflects the working thought process as referenced by this framework.&nbsp; Thus because she is not writing, Ariel must not be doing any calculation. Katherine offers help for how to proceed based off of her understanding that the subtraction is complete:&nbsp; &ldquo;and then you take the one down, right?&rdquo;&nbsp; Because Ariel&rsquo;s problem solving was being done internally, Katherine has no external representation to understand what Ariel&rsquo;s problem is.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the miscommunication is solved (as explored in my previous analysis), Katherine begins to help Ariel with the subtraction of the digits, she ensures that her understanding of the representation is correct:&nbsp; &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t see. Is that a 10 minus an 8?&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With this understanding grounded, they subtract with little other incident, but before continuing with the rest of the long division, Ariel asks for confirmation the subtraction was computed correctly, but she does so by referring explicitly to the representation:&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;Does that look right?&rdquo; she asks, which is synonymous with &ldquo;did I do this correctly&rdquo; because the externalization is a direct reflection of her thought process.&nbsp; Katherine answers similarly:&nbsp; &ldquo;It doesn&rsquo;t look wrong,&rdquo; presumably referring to the lack of any obvious mathematical misstep found on the paper.&nbsp; As mentioned by the CHAT analysis performed by a teammate, Ariel mentally recalculates the subtraction to ensure that it adds up correctly.&nbsp; She does not write anything more down during this addition, as the distribution has already occurred and Ariel does not need to recalculate to the extent of her original.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In performing this second analysis, I&rsquo;ve become more confident in the process one takes with applying the theoretical frameworks onto an actual conversation. The confidence comes not only from practice (though it is a big part), but also in comparing my initial analysis with others&rsquo;. Observing how others take on a similar assignment with different perspectives allowed me to then reflect and apply these differences in thought to my own analysis above, which I hope is more improved with these experiences and confidence.</p>\r\n',6,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-08 21:20:57','2016-03-01 00:42:37'),(14,'Interactive: HW1','<p>Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E<br />\r\nSegment Used: 3:05 &ndash; 4:05</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point in the video, Ethan and Talie have already established their goals and a common ground on how they will approach the long division problem. Their interaction is an informal, cooperative, and verbal problem-solving process. Ethan interacts with the physical environment by performing the calculations on paper while communicating with Talie to seek help and assurance about the process. Talie cooperates with Ethan to provide additional help and contributes especially more when she has a question in mind, or want to provide further explanation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their conversation is an Interactionally managed model of turn-taking where they self-select to contribute depending on the situation. Like in any joint activity, however, both Ethan and Talie have to coordinate many factors to achieve the desired goal of dividing the given two numbers. When Ethan is silent for few extra seconds when subtracting two numbers (3:25), Talie takes it as a cue to help him and speed up the process. By writing (and saying it aloud) the next two digits of the answer, Ethan demonstrates that he understands the process even though he has to stop once in a while to calculate. When a segment of the process is complete, by saying &quot;Ok, now we have this&quot;, Talie provides the initiation to the next relevant segment, which also serves as an acknowledgment that she is on the same page as Ethan. Similarly, Ethan provides evidence of understanding as well as reaches an agreement with Talie about the answer at this point by saying &quot;We have 815&quot; (3:32) and Talie provides both acceptance to the answer by saying &quot;right&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After reminding Ethan to pull down &quot;5&quot; for further calculation (3:45), Talie continues with the process by calculating that &quot;2&quot; should be added to the quotient. Ethan takes a moment, possibly double-checking or calculating himself, before responding with a not-so-sure &quot;OK&quot;. Talie provides her reasoning and both finally come to an agreement thereafter. Since both already have an understanding of how the process should move forward, a common ground, they proceed to the next step without delay and there is no confusion about this even though neither of them explicitly say what has to be done next.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The frequent reasoning behind any specific process by Talie and the confirmation of answer by Ethan is an evidence of their understanding and continued attention to each other&#39;s contribution to the discourse. Similarly, &quot;OK&quot; and &quot;Right&quot; used by them are examples of acknowledgements to the contribution of what the other is saying. These evidences reveal the details about the collaborative effort between the two to solve the long division problem. Furthermore, the recognition by both also form an acceptance about what the last speaker said when transitioning between the segments of the problem (and their turn) or an initialization of a repair of the problem they ran into in accepting it; for instance, Talie frequently provides info about why the process is correct (&quot;And the reason this is correct&quot;) when she finds that Ethan hasn&#39;t accepted the answer yet (or provided the cue that he has).</p>\r\n','<p>Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E<br />\r\nSegment Used: 3:05 &ndash; 4:05</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the post on internal framework by The Brass Tortoise, I also think the introductory segment of the video would have provided more opportunities to analyze about their plan, procedural knowledge, and script because this is where Ethan and Talie establish their goals and a common ground on how they will approach the long division problem. However, this segment of the video from Ethan and Talie&#39;s long division from 3:05 to 4:05 also demonstrates multiple aspects of internal framework.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Firstly, the format that Ethan chooses to write for doing long division problem is evidence of his application of previous knowledge to solve the problem. The divisor is placed on the left, the dividend on the right, quotient is placed on the top, and the calculation is done just below. We can safely infer that he would not have been able to use such a widely-used and easy format for division had he not learnt it in school or encountered it beforehand. In fact, this in turn provides further affirmation that Ethan is simply following a default script for division.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, Talie demonstrates her understanding of the calculation done by Ethan by saying &quot;oh yeah&quot; (3:05) and &quot;then you get&quot; (3:11), which also serves as a confirmation that, like Ethan, she too is familiar with the process. Similarly, when Talie says &quot;and then you get&quot;, it also implies that now she is thinking about the next phase in her internal script, her detailed knowledge about how the calculation is done. Ethan also shows us the next step in the calculation while saying &quot;this becomes 5, this becomes 2&quot; (3:18), which clearly demonstrates that he is following a step that he is familiar with from before &ndash;the procedural knowledge of doing subtraction. Talie&#39;s procedural knowledge about division is also further seen when she asks Ethan, &quot;make sure you pull down the 5&quot; (3:35), the next part of what she knows to be done in order to do division. Similar to Will in The Brass Tortoise&#39;s post, Ethan&#39;s internal procedural script allows him to repeat the successive series of steps done before in search of an adequate quotient and remainder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While both Ethan and Talie have an internal script about long division, it is highly unlikely that they would have encountered the same numbers before. Therefore, similar to what Will and Kathy did in The Brass Tortoise&#39;s analysis, Ethan and Talie also formed a mental representation of how they would solve the given numbers. While Will decides to solve all the sub-parts of the problem mentally, Ethan and Talie follow a plan of writing all the sub-problems involved in the long division. They have also planned that Ethan will do the calculation and write down the solution while Talie provides additional support. It is interesting to note how Ethan and Talie use both their plan and procedural knowledge together to press on with the problem. For instance, both Ethan and Talie know from their procedural knowledge that they have to find an adequate estimate for quotient (3:47) and the use this in conjunction with their plan of writing the calculation down (already written in this case) to make the process easier while accomplishing the task at hand.</p>\r\n',10,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-08 21:51:37','2016-03-01 04:52:06'),(15,'External Framework','<p>The video I chose was of Ethan and Talie, and I used the section from the beginning of the video until around 1:15 into it. There are several external constraints on this situation that lead to it playing out as it did.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first of these constraints is the fact of the problem itself. The problem that Ethan and Talie (and the rest of us as well) were tasked to solve was a math problem consisting of dividing one number by another. Immediately, this sets certain expectations on them: that the goal of mathematics is to manipulate numbers and get the correct answer and that that correct answer is (in this case) one specific number rather than a range of numbers or an infinite set of them, and to call to their memory the process of long division, among others. This one external factor (that is, the sentence that Professor Alterman said to instruct us, which may have been &ldquo;I want you to get into pairs and do this long division problem that&rsquo;s written on the board while the other films it,&rdquo;) primed Ethan and Talie in a myriad of ways, many of them subconsciously inbuilt into the situation, as they began the process of this math problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another constraint is the educational system in which Ethan and Talie were taught, and specifically, the methods by which they learned to do long division. Had they grown up in Latin America, they would have set the problem up differently, in a similar way as we would write on paper (9,705,159,253 &divide; 3437 rather than 3437 âŸŒ 9,705,159,253 ); had they grown up in Mexico their method would be the same except with mental subtraction (such that only the numbers that were being subtracted from the original would be written down, and their difference would be held mentally; had they grown up in Europe the divisor would be placed to the right of the dividend and separated by a vertical bar, and the quotient would be written underneath the dividend. These differences in layout affect how they approached the problem and the process they used to do the equation, and so affected their interaction. They discussed the formatting of the numbers from around :30 to :45, and eventually came to an agreement based on how they were taught how to frame&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A third external constraint is the particular math problem that they were tasked to solve (9,705,159,253 &divide; 3437). This external factor on their interaction framed their approach to the problem, simply because the numbers involved were large enough that they needed to write the problem down in order to manipulate external representations of the numbers if they wanted to get the right answer. If the problem they were asked to solve by long division was something like 125 &divide; 5, aside from not having much to analyze now, they would have likely been able to do the math in their heads, with internalized representations of the numbers involved. Since the numbers were as large as they were, they weren&rsquo;t able to simply use those internalized representations, and they had to physically write down and manipulate the numbers on the paper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>The video I chose was of Ethan and Talie, (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E) and I used a section from the beginning of the video (0:00-1:15). Ethan and Talie&#39;s process of working through the math problem is highly interactionally managed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Early in the problem, it is evident that they know one another and are friendly, given the fluidity with which they talk and discuss the problem as they set it up. They make frequent reassurances towards one another&rsquo;s contributions allow them to ensure that their common ground always reaches the third state of understanding with regard to their utterances. That is, they undergo grounding interactions, wherein once one of them (A) presents an utterance (u) to the other (B), B responds with evidence that they understanding what A meant by u (e).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethan establishes this collaborative atmosphere in the first few seconds of the video where he says &ldquo;&hellip;and record, and we could do it together&rdquo;. Immediately, he sets the expectation that he hopes for the problem-solving to be an interactive, collaborative process wherein he and Talle work together towards the solution, rather than merely a monologue of his thought process. She responds &ldquo;okay&rdquo;, indicating that they share common ground on Ethan&rsquo;s proposition. She continues that grounding interaction by reading the numbers of the problem to Ethan as he transcribes them from the board. In doing this, she affirms that they both are working towards the same end and that she will offer contributions to expedite that process. In this first case, Ethan&rsquo;s first sentence (&ldquo;we could do it together&rdquo;) u is accepted by Talie&rsquo;s response (&ldquo;okay&rdquo;) e, and then e is reinforced by Talie reading the numbers to Ethan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once the problem is transcribed, they move to solving it. As they shake off the cobwebs of their knowledge of the long division process, they talk through exactly what they will need to do in order to solve the problem. At 0:31, Talie begins, &ldquo;usually it&rsquo;s how many times this number [pointing at the divisor] goes into this number [pointing at the four largest digits of the dividend], but since it&rsquo;s even and that&rsquo;ll take you over, i think you have to do it one time.&rdquo; Ethan clarifies: &ldquo;You&rsquo;re saying&hellip; 3437 goes into 9705?&rdquo; to which she responds &ldquo;yeah&rdquo;. He says &ldquo;&hellip;which is 2&rdquo; and writes that down, to which Talie agrees, saying, &ldquo;right&rdquo;. In this second case, Talie&rsquo;s sentence (ending &ldquo;I think you have to do it one time&rdquo;) u is met by a new utterance, Ethan&rsquo;s clarification (&ldquo;You&rsquo;re saying&hellip;&rdquo;) u<sub>1</sub>, which itself it met by Talie&rsquo;s response (&ldquo;yeah&rdquo;) e. This case, where u from person A is met with u from person B to clarify and then given e from person A, is not specifically described but an important type of interactive collaborative effort.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Going into this assignment, I had much more of a big-picture, theoretical view of the frameworks and their application to this problem, and as a result my analysis was more big-picture, describing trends I saw through the video I chose. The other analyses I saw gave very good examples of how to get into the fine-grain detail of the videos while keeping the frameworks in mind, and I was able to learn well from my classmates based solely on that.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',18,1,2,0,1,'2016-02-09 01:17:55','2016-03-01 04:37:25'),(16,'Chloe and Joe â€“ Internal Analysis','<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1:38-1:55</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>0:38 &ndash; Chloe: &ldquo;So I&rsquo;m guessing [the divisor] goes in [the dividend] twice, it might go in there a third time&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chloe has done long division in the past and the process has become procedural knowledge. While it has presumably been a long time since she last performed long division, she forms a plan: she estimates how many times the divisor can be multiplied to be smaller than the dividend. Settling on two as an appropriate number, she multiplies the divisor by two &ndash; she has the procedural knowledge that multiplication is involved within the process of long division. She also has procedural knowledge of long multiplication to complete this step. She makes the decision to write the process on the paper instead of doing it in her head to make it easier to solve. She then goes through the same process for subtraction: applying prior knowledge of subtraction and writing it on the paper. &nbsp;After completing the subtraction, she sees that the divisor does not fit into the difference any more. She knows she completed the first step correctly and but &ldquo;just [doesn&rsquo;t] know how to proceed because this number&rsquo;s so big.&rdquo; She begins by separating the process of dividing &ldquo;small&rdquo; numbers from &ldquo;big&rdquo; numbers in her head, but then continues by moving the next digit down to repeat the same process as the first step.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Almost all of Chloe&rsquo;s actions in this minute of video are driven by the internal. She does not ask Joe any questions and only occasionally speaks her thought process aloud. As she moves through the first step, she uses her procedural knowledge to break the process down into a plan: estimate the number of times the divisor will fit into the first &ldquo;chunk&rdquo; of the dividend, multiply the estimate by the divisor, subtract the result from the &ldquo;chunk,&rdquo; and repeat the process. This procedural knowledge has become embodied throughout her schooling career. In the beginning and end of the clip, she does not think that she remembers how to perform long division, let alone apply it to &ldquo;big&rdquo; numbers. However, she has presumably carried out the process enough times in her life that she is able to work through it without assistance. She eventually separates the notion of dividing &ldquo;big&rdquo; numbers from the process of long division as a general concept so that she can execute her plan in steps. She also executes each small step with ease &ndash; multiplication and subtraction are two more sets of procedural knowledge she has embodied throughout her academic career. The combination of procedural knowledge of all these techniques (the general process of division, multiplication, and subtraction) helps her to work through the problem internally.</p>\r\n','<p><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>0:38-1:55</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Externalization</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite having originally viewed this only through a strictly internal framework, I now realize that there are a lot of external things happening too. The first externalization is when she writes the numbers down as she speaks them. She writes every step out so that she can free up her working memory. By doing this, she can focus solely on the next step without having to remember the main numbers. &nbsp;Although she briefly estimates the number of times the divisor can go into the dividend, she writes the multiplication portion down and completes it on paper so that she doesn&#39;t need to do the calculation in her head. She breaks down the multiplication process into one digit at a time. This makes it easier by allowing her to perform smaller calculations in her head that only involve multiplying single digits at a time. This would make the process difficult if she needed to remember all of the individual digits, but by externalizing them onto the paper, she is able to keep her working memory clear to focus on the smaller steps. She works through this at a reasonably quick pace and with more confidence than when she just estimated in her head.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not only does this externalization help Chloe to solve the problem, but it also helps to make sure that she and Joe are on the same page. Joe is her partner in the exercise and needs to know what Chloe is thinking. While Chloe doesn&rsquo;t talk to Joe directly throughout the clip, he is able to follow along with her mental process because she puts everything on paper. He knows exactly where she is in the process. He can see each individual step that she completes and verify that she is working along in the right direction. This makes the problem solving more efficient because she is able to convey her thoughts to him without having to pause to explain, which makes the process faster and allows her to concentrate on the math at hand. This also gives both Joe and Chloe a chance to catch and correct any mistakes Chloe might make. Even if they don&rsquo;t catch it right away, they can go back and retrace the individual steps to pinpoint where something goes wrong. They don&rsquo;t need to repeat the mental process because each point is written down on the paper.</p>\r\n',4,1,1,0,1,'2016-02-09 01:43:25','2016-03-01 07:06:25'),(17,'Analysis of interactive elements in Ethan and Talie','<p>Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:22] Talie: So how many times&hellip; ok, so how many times this number goes (pointing the pen at 3437)?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:29] Ethan: (pointing the pen at the fourth digit from left in 9705159253,) I think until uh&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:31] Talie: (Pause.) Usually to how many times this number (pointing the pen at 3) goes into this number (move the pen to 9). But since it&rsquo;s even and that will take you over, I think you&rsquo;ve to do 1 less (pointing the pen back and forth between the two numbers).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:39] Ethan: You&rsquo;re saying&hellip; so three hundred and forty-three (pointing the pen at 3437), uh, three thousand four hundred and thirty-seven goes into nine thousand seven hundred five...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:47] Talie: Well, usual&hellip; Yeah.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:48] Ethan: &hellip;which is 2? Right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:48] Talie: Right. And you&rsquo;ve to subtract them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:49] Ethan: So let&rsquo;s just do that quickly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video of solving long division, the conversation between Ethan and Talie is locally managed, party administered and interactionally managed, and the grounding knowledge is interactively constructed. First, the conversation is locally managed because, in the conversation, only one turn takes place at a time, and every turn after each turn is a &ldquo;next turn&rdquo;. As Talie asks: &ldquo;Ok, so how many times this number goes?&rdquo;, she finishes her turn as a question and leaves the next turn to speak on the table. Then Ethan picks up the next turn and answers that &ldquo;I think until uh&hellip;&rdquo; and finishes his turn by pointing at the fourth digit from the left in the dividend, indicating which two numbers they are dealing with currently. The rest of the conversation is also made up with this &ldquo;turn-by-turn basis&rdquo; that Ethan and Talie are speaking one by one, by asking questions and answering them, which are the features of a locally managed system. Second, the conversation is party administered because neither Ethan nor Talie is making decisions with hierarchy or authority. Ethan and Talie are always asking for their partner&rsquo;s idea or making suggestion to the other person when they are trying to make a decision, such as Talie&rsquo;s &ldquo;I think you&rsquo;ve to do 1 less&rdquo; (0:31), and Ethan&rsquo;s &ldquo;Right?&rdquo; (0:48). The final decisions that they should first do division between the deviser (3437) and the first four digits of the dividend (5703) and that 3437 goes two times into 5703 are obtained through Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s discussion and are agreed by both people in the party. So this conversation can be categorized as a party-administered system. Third, the conversation is interactionally managed because the actions such as &ldquo;asking questions&rdquo; and &ldquo;giving suggestions&rdquo; are interactions between Ethan and Talie. These interactions are the driven force which drives the conversation towards its goal, the final decision of dividing two numbers and the result being 2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, there are three grounding knowledge constructed between Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s conversation, which enables the conversation to move on. The first grounding knowledge begins with Talie&rsquo;s question &ldquo;so how many times this number goes?&rdquo;(0:22) Talie contributes to the conversation by starting with a question to make sure what digits in the dividend should be taken into the division in the first step and what the answer should be. Ethan contributes to the conversation by uttering the phrase &ldquo;I think until uh&hellip;&rdquo;(0:29) and the gesture pointing the pen after the fourth digits in the dividend. With the gesture, Ethan is actually answering to the question what digits in the dividend should be taken into the division in the first step. At this point, the grounding knowledge of digit should be constructed firmly, since Talie&rsquo;s next utterance indicates that she agrees to the decision of the fourth digit from left in the dividend. Talie does so by saying &ldquo;I think you&rsquo;ve to do 1 less&rdquo;(0:31), which actually is her answer to the second grounding knowledge what the answer should be. Talie would move on to solve the problem only when she is done with the first. But the first grounding knowledge is actually not constructed at all because Talie doesn&rsquo;t make strong evidences for Ethan to know that she has already accepted what Ethan means for the first problem. Thus, at this point, while Talie accepts Ethan&rsquo;s solution for the firt problem, Ethan is not sure if Talie accepts his solution. We can see this from Ethan&rsquo;s words &ldquo;You&rsquo;re saying&hellip;&rdquo;(0:39), which indicates that Ethan is trying to make sure what Talie really means and Talie actually knows. On the other hand, Talie realizes that she accepts Ethan&rsquo;s solution but doesn&rsquo;t tell Ethan that she accepts only after Ethan&rsquo;s re-confirmation. When Talie says &ldquo;Well, usual&hellip; Yeah.&rdquo;(0:47), she is sure that Ethan&rsquo;s previous repetition is for making sure that she accepts his first solution. The &ldquo;yeah&rdquo; is not only indicating that Talie understands Ethan&rsquo;s repetition, but also representing an obvious acceptance to the first solution. Until now, the first grounding knowledge is constructed for sure. The second grounding knowledge, what is the answer for the division, almost finishes construction simultaneously with the first grounding knowledge. Talie proposes her contribution to the solution of the second grounding knowledge after she individually solved the first problem. Ethan proposes his contribution to the solution right after the first grounding knowledge is constructed, by saying &ldquo;&hellip;which is 2? Right?&rdquo;(0:48). Then, after Talie says &ldquo;Right.&rdquo;(0:48), indicating that she accepts Ethan&rsquo;s contribution, the second grounding knowledge that the result of the division is 2 is constructed. The third grounding knowledge is pretty simple. Talie says &ldquo;And you&rsquo;ve to subtract them.&rdquo;(0:48), proposing a suggestion for determining the remainder for the rest of the division. And Ethan replies &ldquo;So let&rsquo;s just do that quickly.&rdquo;(0:49), demonstrating his acceptance to Talie&rsquo;s suggestion. Thus the third grounding knowledge that they are going to get the remainder and move on is constructed.</p>\r\n','<p>Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:22] Talie: So how many times&hellip; ok, so how many times this number goes (pointing the pen at 3437)?</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:29] Ethan: (pointing the pen at the fourth digit from left in 9705159253,) I think until uh&hellip;</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:31] Talie: (Pause.) Usually to how many times this number (pointing the pen at 3) goes into this number (move the pen to 9). But since it&rsquo;s even and that will take you over, I think you&rsquo;ve to do 1 less (pointing the pen back and forth between the two numbers).</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:39] Ethan: You&rsquo;re saying&hellip; so three hundred and forty-three (pointing the pen at 3437), uh, three thousand four hundred and thirty-seven goes into nine thousand seven hundred five...</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:47] Talie: Well, usual&hellip; Yeah.</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:48] Ethan: &hellip;which is 2? Right?</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:48] Talie: Right. And you&rsquo;ve to subtract them.</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p><tt>[0:49] Ethan: So let&rsquo;s just do that quickly.</tt></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video of solving long division, the conversation between Ethan and Talie and the solution of the problem demonstrate Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s internal knowledge, presented as a script. The conflict in their conversation also shows the differences in detail between individual scripts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After writing out the long division in some form, Talie immediately points at the divider and says &ldquo;Ok, so how many times this number goes&hellip;&rdquo; (0:22). Not until she finishes her words, Ethan continues by pointing the pen at the fourth digit from left in the dividend and saying &ldquo;I think until uh&hellip;&rdquo; (0:29). With this segment, we can easily know that both Ethan and Talie master the internal procedural knowledge for solving long division. We notice that Talie doesn&rsquo;t set up the equation by herself, but watches Ethan setting up it. Talie can still discuss the lineup with Ethan because she understands the meaning of Ethan&rsquo;s setup. She cannot do this without the procedural knowledge of solving long division. Furthermore, while both of them do not finish their word but use gestures to demonstrate their meaning (e.g. pointing the pen at the digits), Ethan and Talie still can have a discussion on solving long division. This fact also indicates that both of them master the procedural knowledge of solving long division, and their internal procedural knowledge are the same. Otherwise they could not communicate as they do in the video segment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Byzantine Rhinoceros&rsquo;s post, he summarizes the script of solving long division as following:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1) Analyze DD in relation to DV; determine how many times DV goes into DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2a) Base case: DV goes into DD less than 1 full times, and it is represented as the remainder; PR is solved (exit condition)</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2b) Recursive case: Place the resultant number from step 1 over the correct place of DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3) Multiply DV by the resultant number from step 1, place it under DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4) Subtract the resultant number from step 3 from DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5) Bring down the next number from DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;6) Return to step 1, with this new number serving as the new DD</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is apparent that, in this segment of Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video, the two people are always staying in step 1, analyzing the dividend in relation to the divider. However, Ethan and Talie are doing different analyzes. By saying &ldquo;So how many times this number goes&hellip;&rdquo;(0:22), Talie actually goes one step forward for the calculation, while Ethan is still determining the digits for calculation in the dividend, with his words &ldquo;I think until&hellip;&rdquo;(0:29). With this fact, we can divide step 1 into more details as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1.1) Count the digits of DV. Set the digit number to be n. Choose the first nth digits from left in DD. Set those digits to be nDD.</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1.2a) If DV &lt; nDD, find out how many times DV goes into nDD.</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family:courier new,courier,monospace;\"><tt>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1.2b) If DV &gt; nDD, get one more digit from DD and add to nDD. Then find out how many times DV goes into nDD.</tt></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>With this detailed script, we can see that at the beginning of the conversation, Ethan is in step 1.1, while Talie has already been in step 1.2a. Due to the fact that two people don&rsquo;t proceed with the same pace, we finally know the reason why they cannot construct the grounding knowledge until the end of the conversation, as stated in my previous post. Ethan and Talie are in different steps, while each of them assume the other person is in the same step as he/she is. This misunderstanding and misplacement interrupt the construction of the grounding knowledge between two people. However, despite the fact that they are in different steps, because two people share the same script and they have the same procedural knowledge, the conversation can still go on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Byzantine Rhinoceros analyzes in his post what Ariel&rsquo;s procedural knowledge of solving long division is and how that knowledge works by writing out the corresponding. I did similar analysis in this post, and added some detail to his script. What I&rsquo;ve done more is that I combined my analysis of internal procedural knowledge with my previous analysis of interactive grounding knowledge, proposing a reasonable explanation of the conflict between the two people in the first part of the video segment. Going through part i to iii in this homework, my analysis over the video segment becomes more concrete and more convincing.</p>\r\n',13,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-09 02:19:12','2016-03-01 04:05:34'),(18,'Analysis of interactive elements in Ethan and Talie\'s video','',NULL,13,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-09 02:19:40','2016-03-02 20:53:05'),(19,'Interactive Mistakes ','<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Solving a math problem&nbsp;is an interctive process.&nbsp;An &lsquo;interactive activity&rsquo; can be defined by there being an organization to the activity that requires one party to act &lsquo;upon or with the other&rsquo; (Dictionary.com). Football, for example, is a clear example of what an interactive activity is. In football, a team has to strategize, plan, act, and re-act while trying to beat their opponents. Math is also a battle between two teams. One team, the human, has to strategize, act and react to solve a math problem (beating the other team). When a person solves a math problem, long division for example, they start with a plan and adjust at each new step to react to new information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The long division problem by Benedict and Abby clearly demonstrates how math is interactive because of how they plan each step and react to mistakes. From 3:58 to 4:24 we see Benedict and Abby do five things to work on part of the math problem. &ldquo;How many times do you think [3,437] goes into 12,842, 3 times? Or 4 times?&rdquo; In this first step, the two started their interactive process by creating a plan of action &ndash; finding out how many times 3,437 goes into 12,842. The second part of the process was to decide if it went in 3 or 4 times. To do this, the two talked and decided it went in three times. Interestingly, after they talked, Abby then went and wrote out the math of 3,437 by hand to verify their decision. The third part of their plan was to subtract the product of 3,347 and 3 from 12,842. This is one of the main parts that makes math interactive. Abby and Benedict have to take their guess and subtract it from the current value in order to move to the next step. The fourth step of their process was also interactive but in a different way. In this video clip, Abby and Benedict have a problem with the third step because their math suggested that 3,437 went into 12,842 more than 3 times. In the fourth step of their solution they had to back track and find out where they had made their mistake. Ultimately, Abby realized that she miswrote one of the numbers in the subtraction from part 3. The fifth and final step of the video clip was them trying to fix their previous mistakes in order to move on. Unfortunately, Abby and Benedict&rsquo;s mistake happened much earlier than they had thought (they missed a miscalculation in step 2) and they wouldn&rsquo;t move on for a while.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Benedict and Abby&#39;s problem solving is interactive becuase they are constantly reacting to the changing state of the problem. They started with a plan but realized they had to change it when they caught a mistake. This give and take, dynamic process makes math interactive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>External:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How does one know when they have made a mistake and how do they know what to fix in order to change it? When we try to solve problems these questions are paramount in coming up with the final solution. In the example I look at, Benedict and Abby are working on a long division problem and have to address these two questions. By looking at evidence from the video, I believe that the answer to both questions lie in external cognitive process that the two are using.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To begin, an external framework is &ldquo;any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads&rdquo; (Kirsh 212) (Quoting the same section as Benedict/The Turquoise Hedgehog). In terms of long division, we can see external cognitive skills when we watch Abby write down the steps on the piece of paper. To quote the Aqua Wombat, the pen and the paper are mediating artifacts that help solve the math problem. In this problem, Abby and Benedict are dealing with a lot of numbers and a lot of steps. Without the paper, they cannot be expected to remember each step. Without the pencil, they cannot be expected to clearly define the next step. Additionally, the process of writing down the steps allows them to externalize the memory. In the video we see Abby write down what 3*3,347 is. By writing it down, she does not need to internalize that number into her long-term memory. Later in the segment when she needs to use that value, she simply has to look back to the math she wrote down on the paper. With these descriptions, I think it is clear that Abby and Benedict are using external cognitive processes as a tool in trying to solve the math problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that we have defined what basic processes Benedict and Abby are using in the video, we can tackle the two main questions. Because the two of them are using external cognition, we can visually trace what happens when they make a mistake. In this segment, Abby does two things, multiply 3 and 3,347 and subtract the product from some number. All the parts of the multiplication and subtraction are written out by hand. After doing that, she defines what rule she has that signifies she can move forward in the problem. The reminder always has to be less than this (the number). That&rsquo;s how you know you did it right. Uh-Oh the remainder is more. So it can go in a fourth time.&rdquo; Because she sees that her math produces a value that fails her test, she realizes that she needs to find a mistake in her earlier work. To do that, she looked the two math problems she wrote down and found a subtraction mistake that she had made. Since she used external cognition, she was able to efficiently identify and resolve her mistakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mistakes in math problems can be hard to handle. In this analysis I focused on how using external cognitive techniques could make dealing with them easier. In my first analysis, I detailed how there is a competitive interaction between a person and a problem. When I started this project, I can honestly say that I took troubleshooting problems for granted. Long division is middle school math and it seems so simple. This analysis made me realize why it isn&rsquo;t so simple. Without external cognition, we wouldn&rsquo;t be able to quickly find mistakes in long division. Without an interactive approach, we wouldn&rsquo;t know how to go about solving the problem. Even with simple procedures, we need cognitive processes to problem solve.</p>\r\n',27,1,3,0,1,'2016-02-09 02:59:41','2016-03-01 04:18:45'),(20,'Interactive analysis','<p>Video: Benedickt and Abby</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time frame: 5:00 - 6:00</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The video begins with Abby hitting a snag while she is doing her long division. It is then that her and Benedikt begin talking back and forth about what might have gone wrong while Abby was performing the long division. In this exchange, Abby is voicing her concerns aloud to Benedikt. During the last few seconds of the discussion, Abby decides that she will check what the actual answer to the problem is by finding the answer on her phone, so that she can ensure that she is not working in the wrong direction.&nbsp;During their exchange, Abby asks Benedikt if she can begin the problem over again. At first, Benedikt says no, which Abby interalizes, then agrees to (inter to intra). Later, Benedikt alters his view point, saying that she could begin the problem again, but that he would continue recording, and not start the video over.&nbsp;In addition to seeing some inter to intrapsychological exchange, the viewer can also see an example of Abby is using a tool to mediate her solving of the math problem. The tools she is using in this case are a pencil and paper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the video, the viewer can see that Abby has set up the long division problem in a way that is familiar to many other students in the class: she has placed the number being divided within the division &quot;box&quot;, and has placed the number she is dividing with outside of that box, to the left. As she is working through the problem, Abby writes how many times the dividing number goes into the number being divided above the box, aligning it with the last digit of the number that it can fit into. She also uses arrows as the brings the remainder down so that she can keep track of where each number is going, and when. One example of a video in which a very different method is used is that of Saad and Mojir. In their video, Mojir has set up the long division problem in a way that is seemingly opposite: the division box is underneath the number that is dividing, and both are placed to the right of the number being divided. Additionally, as he solves the problem, Mojir will put the number of times the dividing number goes in underneath the dividing number and the division box to the right. To some, this may seem completely counterintuitive. But for Mojir, it seems to come fairly easily to him. This is evidence of how Abby and Mojir&#39;s ontgenic and microgenic timelines differ. It may also be evidence of how their cultural-historica timelines differ. Abby and Mojir most likely grew up in different places, and received different schooling from different education systems. Even if they had received schooling in the same area, they may still have had different methods, because even in like school systems, teachers often differ in how they teach a subject.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>Video: Abby and Benedikt&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_E_xUgaDVa8\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_E_xUgaDVa8</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clip: 5:01-6:03</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abby and Benedikt&#39;s conversation during this clip of their long division video provides for an interesting and easy-to-recognize example of interaction in terms of conversation and turn taking. Below I have provided a script of some of their conversation as they go over a mistake that Abby has made in her calculations:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: No, ok... (laughs)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Exactly, ok, so never mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: No, this is...how did this happen? Oh, it&#39;s not 7, 12 minus&nbsp;9 is 3....</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Interesting...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: But it&#39;s still bigger. 2 minus&nbsp;1 is 1, so that&#39;s a problem. 5 (laughs)&nbsp;minus 1 is 4, 8 minus (laughs)&nbsp;3 is 5 -&nbsp;how is it only a little bit bigger?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Long pause)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Can we start over? (laughs)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: No, we&#39;re not starting over - A: Please? (laughs) - B: It&#39;s says mistakes are good data points.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: I don&#39;t know what I did wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: I mean, you can start the problem over, but we&#39;re not starting the video over (laughs).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Hold on, can we figure out what the actual problem - what the answer is supposed to be, - B: Alright - A:&nbsp;so I can work toward the correct answer?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Alright, that, that&#39;s perfectly fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This conversation is governed by the structure of conversation examined in&nbsp;<em>A Simplest Systematics for the Organization of Turn-Taking for Conversation</em>&nbsp;on page 699.&nbsp;Additionally, we are seeing many, if not all of the 14 phenomena that occur in turn taking, such as speaker change occurring/recurring, and varied turn order and size. Speaker change occurring/recurring is exemplified by the way in which who is speaking switches back and forth between Abby and Benedikt; Abby will speak, then she will cue the speaker change to Benedikt by either giving a long pause, or asking a question. Benedikt responds with his own input, then signals the speaker transition in the same way as Abby, by either asking a question, or giving a long pause. Additionally, this is an example of the &quot;current selects next&quot; rule, in which the current speaker selects the next speaker. There are also examples of self-selection, in which one or the other will elect themselves to speak after the other has spoken, or briefly during the speaker&#39;s sentence. Because there are only two &quot;parties&quot; present in this conversation, it is an unspoken understanding that once one person speaks, afterward, it is the next person&#39;s turn to speak. The only violation of the rule of one speaker at a time is twice during the script, the first&nbsp;in which Abby speaks during Benedikt&#39;s sentence -&nbsp;&nbsp;B: No, we&#39;re not starting over - A: Please? (laughs) - B: It&#39;s says mistakes are good data points. - and the second&nbsp;in which Benedikt speaks during Abby&#39;s sentence -&nbsp;A: Hold on, can we figure out what the actual problem - what the answer is supposed to be, - B: Alright - A:&nbsp;so I can work toward the correct answer?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Transitions (from one turn to a next) with no gap and no overlap are common&quot; (708). Frequently throughout this interaction, the transition between speakers is signaled by either a question, a long pause, or both. The transition that is most incongruent with this cardinal rule of turn-taking is the one that occurs after Abby has corrected some of the math she has performed in the long division problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: But it&#39;s still bigger. 2 minus&nbsp;1 is 1, so that&#39;s a problem. 5 (laughs)&nbsp;minus 1 is 4 , 8 minus (laughs)&nbsp;3 is 5 -&nbsp;how is it only a little bit bigger?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Long pause)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Can we start over? (laughs)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After speaking, Abby pauses for a long time; this pause is most likely meant to act as a signal to Benedikt that the responsibilities of speaker have transitioned to him, but he does not speak during this pause. It is unclear as to why this is, but it can be extrapolated that he does not speak during this pause because he is thinking about what Abby has told him in regards to the mistakes she made in her calculations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When comparing my two posts, I find that I prefer this post over my original one written in the framework of cultural historic. My original post, while not necessarily poorly written, was not as specific in its analysis as it could and should have been, and I did not make references to existing literature, which would not only have enriched the content of the post, but would also have enriched the knowledge of the reader, and given greater context to the analysis that I was attempting to build. For this post, I took the feedback that I received for my previous post, and attempted to tailor it to improve this second post. To do this, I attempted to better reference the existing literature for interaction, and to refine my analysis make it more concrete and meaningfully in regards to the clip I have chosen. During segments i-iii of homework 1, I have learned more about the cultural historic framework, and how it can be applied to something as unassuming as a 1-minute video clip. Through analyzing my chosen clip, I have learned how to analyze a script, and how to construct applicable content around that analysis to better my knowledge about that framework and about the literature written about that framework. I have also gained a deeper understanding of the mechanics of interaction, and of cognitive functioning in terms of problems solving. I noticed this increase in my own knowledge when I returned to this clip to analyze it using the interactive framework.</p>\r\n',24,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-09 03:09:12','2016-03-01 04:36:35'),(21,'Pencil and Paper: A complementary Strategy','<p>In David Kirsh&#39;s&nbsp;conference paper: <em>Complementary strategies: Why we use our hands when we think,&nbsp;</em>he states that &quot;a complementary strategey can be defined as any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads. The external elements may be our fingers or hands, pencil and paper...Typical organizing activities include pointing...&nbsp;writing things down. An obvious example of a complementary strategy is using pencil and paper to help add a list of several two and three digit numbers.&quot; The long division data which I chose to analyze was that of Kathy and Will (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be</a>).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At 0:48&nbsp;(for a little over a minute)&nbsp;Will trys to decipher what the 2nd step of the long division problem is:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And how many times does this go into this? Um. I dont know. Maybe 9. You think its 9? I don&#39;t know.&nbsp; I don&#39;t know.&nbsp;I wish we could use a calculator to do these substeps. Maybe I should just multiply this out by 9 and see if it is. Yeah it is. Thats the best approach because I don&#39;t think that we are allowed to use calculators...So I have to multpily this by 9. Well I dont have to -- I could do something else...30. Well that was close! So it&#39;s probably 8.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kirsh did an experiment to show how humans adapt to their environments to ensure the best results for their cognative resources and how &quot;complementary strategies enhance performance&quot;. His study tested subjects who were shown two sets of coin images and had to figure out how much the coins combined were worth as fast as they could. In the first condition, subjects were not allowed to move their hands or&nbsp;point at the images while they were allowed to in the second condition. On average the subjects from condition two performed faster and with less error than condition one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kirsch writes that &quot;Most of us find it easier, faster and more reliable to write down incremental sums, and carry overs, than to do the summing entirely in our heads.&quot; This is exactly what Will does in our segment. He is unsure as to how many times a number goes into the next. He makes an educated guess that it goes in 9 times. He then tests his hypothesis on a lower portion of the page, for he cannot use a calculator, though he hoped he could, and with these large numbers writing them down deeped more sound and productive than doing the math in his or Kathy&#39;s head.&nbsp;&nbsp;Writing this math down &quot;offloads&nbsp;that portion of working memory required to store intermediate results.&quot;&nbsp;At points,&nbsp;Ken uses his pencil on the formula as a pointer by which to keep organized and keep his place.&nbsp;This too is another action that Kirsch would say has a&nbsp;cognitive benefit which&nbsp;offloads the&nbsp;working memory by helping individuals&nbsp;direct their attention and not require people to have to store those numbers in their working memory.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>In David Kirsh&#39;s&nbsp;conference paper: <em>Complementary strategies: Why we use our hands when we think,&nbsp;</em>he states that &quot;a complementary strategey can be defined as any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads. The external elements may be our fingers or hands, pencil and paper...Typical organizing activities include pointing...&nbsp;writing things down. An obvious example of a complementary strategy is using pencil and paper to help add a list of several two and three digit numbers.&quot; The long division data which I chose to analyze was that of Kathy and Will (<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=odr5wAqqpM4&amp;feature=youtu.be</a>).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At 0:48&nbsp;(for a little over a minute)&nbsp;Will trys to decipher what the 2nd step of the long division problem is:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And how many times does this go into this? Um. I dont know. Maybe 9. You think its 9? I don&#39;t know.&nbsp; I don&#39;t know.&nbsp;I wish we could use a calculator to do these substeps. Maybe I should just multiply this out by 9 and see if it is. Yeah it is. Thats the best approach because I don&#39;t think that we are allowed to use calculators...So I have to multpily this by 9. Well I dont have to -- I could do something else...30. Well that was close! So it&#39;s probably 8.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kirsh did an experiment to show how humans adapt to their environments to ensure the best results for their cognative resources and how &quot;complementary strategies enhance performance&quot;. His study tested subjects who were shown two sets of coin images and had to figure out how much the coins combined were worth as fast as they could. In the first condition, subjects were not allowed to move their hands or&nbsp;point at the images while they were allowed to in the second condition. On average the subjects from condition two performed faster and with less error than condition one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kirsch writes that &quot;Most of us find it easier, faster and more reliable to write down incremental sums, and carry overs, than to do the summing entirely in our heads.&quot; This is exactly what Will does in our segment. He is unsure as to how many times a number goes into the next. He makes an educated guess that it goes in 9 times. He then tests his hypothesis on a lower portion of the page, for he cannot use a calculator, though he hoped he could, and with these large numbers writing them down deeped more sound and productive than doing the math in his or Kathy&#39;s head.&nbsp;&nbsp;Writing this math down &quot;offloads&nbsp;that portion of working memory required to store intermediate results.&quot;&nbsp;At points,&nbsp;Ken uses his pencil on the formula as a pointer by which to keep organized and keep his place.&nbsp;This too is another action that Kirsch would say has a&nbsp;cognitive benefit which&nbsp;offloads the&nbsp;working memory by helping individuals&nbsp;direct their attention and not require people to have to store those numbers in their working memory.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:48] Will: And how many times does this go into this?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:48] Kathy: Yea</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[0:48] Will: Um. I don&rsquo;t know. Maybe 9. You think its 9? I don&#39;t know. I don&#39;t know. I wish we could use a calculator to do these sub steps. Maybe I should just multiply this out by 9 and see what it is. Yeah. I think that&rsquo;s the best approach because I don&#39;t think that we are allowed to use calculators. Are we not allowed to use a calculator?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:09] Kathy: I don&rsquo;t think so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:12] Will: So I have to multiply this by 9. Well I don&rsquo;t have to -- I could do something else&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:19] Kathy: Wait why would you multiply that by 9?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:20] Will: I&rsquo;m just seeing if, seeing if um&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:23] Kathy: You&rsquo;re supposed to multiply that by 9</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[1:24] Will: Well that was dumb. I was just being silly. Yeah. I forgot what we were doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This segment is very similar to Ethan and Talie&rsquo;s video as seen in &ldquo;Analysis of interactive elements in Ethan and Talie by: The Melon Lion&rdquo;. Both Will and Kathy and Ethan and Talie held conversations which were locally managed, internally managed, and party administered. Both clips had group members valuing the ideas and questions of their partner, and not having one group member overpower or be subservient to the other during the long division problem solving. &nbsp;In both sets of conversations only one person talked at a time -- both sets were fantastic at turn taking. For instance, Will would ask Kathy, &ldquo;Are we not allowed to use a calculator?&rdquo; (Pause) then Kathy would respond, &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think so.&rdquo; At one point Will says, in a tone of certainty, &ldquo;So I have to multiply this by 9&rdquo; (pause) then Kathy would follow with a questioning of his statement respectfully realizing that he had erred. Will then acknowledges his misstep and finishes his turn by fixing which number he actually meant to multiply by nine. Throughout both short clips many questions were asked and many suggestions were given between Ethan and Talie as well as Kathy and Will. The interaction management and the grounding knowledge was overall evident in this clip. With regard to grounding knowledge however, it was interesting to hear Will say, (at 1:45) &quot;I probably haven&rsquo;t done this since I was in third grade.&quot; In out clip Will interacted with the physical environment using a paper and pen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whereas my first analysis was lacking much reading into the chosen segment I have felt that reading the comments of my fellow classmates and their own analysis posts have given me both the knowledge and ability to really flesh out more in depth thoughts and readings about these few filmed seconds. Though people don&rsquo;t like criticism, I felt that the anonymity of commenting and being commented on greatly strengthened our writing and analysis. This feature, let students really help their classmates out by crafting brutally honest responses. Because I received theses I know areas I need to focus on more and have new tools to utilize for future analyses. In addition, my last post followed the prompt posted on the Latte class using a short conference paper (complementary strategies) on external cognition as my guide. This analysis was modeled of peer posts and comments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',15,1,2,0,1,'2016-02-09 04:18:40','2016-03-01 04:55:19'),(22,'External Framework for Chloe & Joe\'s Video','<p>I chose to analyze &ldquo;Chloe&#39;s Math Wizardry, Joe&#39;s Dubious Camerawork&rdquo; by none other than Chloe and Joe (their video can be found here: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be</a>). The portions I&rsquo;ll be analyzing are sections 3:45-4:45.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Side-note: the reason why I chose their video was because they were one of the few that were shot in landscape mode. Vertical Video Syndrome (VVS) is a pressing issue and should not be taken lightly, as stated by this incredibly serious PSA: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt9zSfinwFA\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt9zSfinwFA</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before I dive in, it&rsquo;s best to understand what an external framework is. David Kirsh, a leading cognitive scientist, states that the external framework is &ldquo;any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads&rdquo; (Kirsh 212). Several external elements are our fingers and hands, pencil and paper, movable icons, et cetera. We use these external elements to solve problems; in our case, it would be impossible to complete long division problems without the use of pencil and paper. We jot down the original problem on a scratch sheet of paper to help us remember the numbers we are dividing (perhaps one of the most worrisome cognitive burdens for subjects doing long division is memory/remembering what elements are part of a problem). The scratch sheet of paper also gives us ample room to work out the subsets to the long division problem (i.e. multiplying, adding, subtracting), as we slowly progress to finding the correct answer. By breaking down the problem into subsets, we&rsquo;re offloading our cognitive loads to make the whole problem solving process easier and faster, instead of attacking the ten digit number head on. In the end, &ldquo;the best way to solve a cognitive problem is by adapting the world rather than adapting oneself.&rdquo; (212).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chloe is using several external elements: her hands/fingers, pencil, and paper. At 3:45, we see her use of these elements, specially with the scratch sheet of paper and her notes. Surrounding the original problem are Chloe&rsquo;s attempts at multiplying numbers to hope to find what fits in the first four digits of the original, gigantic number being divided. Chloe is showing how the use of breaking down the bigger number into subsets, checking her math, and eventually plugging in the correct answer is only achievable with the external framework. At 4:11, Chloe is waging/pointing her pen between the corresponding numbers she is multiplying. She points between numbers to make sense of their association. At 4:26, she switches between external and verbal frameworks. As Kirsh points out, &ldquo;once a comfortable strategy was found, subjects usually continue using it&rdquo; (214). In Chloe&rsquo;s case, she wasn&rsquo;t incredibly comfortable writing out the problems. She actually says, &ldquo;I cannot think with my brain right now.&rdquo; Once she finally solved the first part to the problem, it looks as if she moves forward and is comfortable with solving the rest of the problem. It seems as if, the biggest cognitive burden for subjects doing long division is mental math and her use of dividing the cognitive load by &ldquo;showing all her steps&rdquo; allows her to solve the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>I chose to analyze the external framework found in the video, &ldquo;Chloe&#39;s Math Wizardry, Joe&#39;s Dubious Camerawork&rdquo; by none other than Chloe and Joe (their video can be found here: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wenZk4-jeuQ&amp;feature=youtu.be</a>). The portions I&rsquo;ll be analyzing are sections 3:45-4:45.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Side-note: the incredibly important reason why I chose to analyze their video in opposition to others&rsquo; was because Chloe and Joe were some of the few that shot their video in landscape/horizontal mode, as opposed to portrait/vertical mode. Vertical Video Syndrome (VVS) is a pressing issue and should not be taken lightly, as stated by this incredibly urgent PSA: <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt9zSfinwFA\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bt9zSfinwFA</a>.&nbsp;In the end, Joe&rsquo;s camerawork isn&rsquo;t dubious at all, but saving all of our lives (and necks)!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before we dive into the analyses, we should have a strong understanding of external frameworks: what are they? why are they important? and how do they influence Chloe and Joe&rsquo;s long division problem solving skills? David Kirsh, a leading cognitive scientist, states that the external framework is &ldquo;any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads&rdquo; (Kirsh 212). Several external elements are our fingers and hands, movable icons, pencil and paper, et cetera. We use these external elements to solve issues, from everyday problems to the more uncommon predicament. For example, we use our fingers to count, our computer&rsquo;s desktop icons remind us of our computer&rsquo;s functions and show that those functions are easily available for us to use, and in Chloe and Joe&rsquo;s case, when solving long division problems, it would be impossible to solve without the use of pencil and paper. With long division, we jot down the problem on a scratch sheet of paper to help us remember the numbers we are dividing (perhaps one of the most worrisome cognitive burdens for subjects doing long division is memory/remembering what elements are part of a problem). The scratch sheet of paper also gives us ample room to work out the subsets to the long division problem (i.e. multiplying, adding, subtracting), as we slowly progress to finding the correct answer. By breaking down the problem into subsets, we&rsquo;re offloading our cognitive loads to make the whole problem solving process easier and faster, instead of attacking the ten digit number head on. In the end, &ldquo;the best way to solve a cognitive problem is by adapting the world rather than adapting oneself.&rdquo; (212).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But why must we use external frameworks? why can&rsquo;t we just solve 10 digit long division problems in our heads? what kind of cruel world do we live in? This is because of the very human trait of short-term and working memory. Short-term or working memory (STM) retains the most recent experience or material that is currently being thought about. The amount of information that can be retained is something between five and seven items at one time, with it constantly being replaced by other stimuli that are all around us. So when dividing 9,705,159,253 by 3437 in your head, you would be unable to hold all the digits, subsets, and intervening answers within your STM. Your pencil and paper are in a way acting as a tool for your mind to remember large bits of information in a more effective way. In the end helping you solve the problem in a relatively small amount of time. Pencil and Paper minimizes the burden on the working memory.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chloe is using several external elements to minimize the burden on her working memory with her hands/fingers, pencil, and paper. At 3:45, we see her use of these elements, specially with the scratch sheet of paper and her notes. Surrounding the original problem are Chloe&rsquo;s attempts at multiplying numbers to hope to find what fits in the first four digits of the original, gigantic number being divided. Chloe is showing how the use of breaking down the bigger number into subsets (with pen and paper), checking her math, and eventually plugging in the correct answer is only achievable with the external framework. At 4:11, Chloe is waging/pointing her pen between the corresponding numbers she is multiplying. She points between numbers to make sense of their association. This pointing also represents an external framework as it reduces cognitive load, allowing her to focus on one number pair at a time when producing arithmetic. At 4:26, she switches between external and verbal frameworks. As Kirsh points out, &ldquo;once a comfortable strategy was found, subjects usually continue using it&rdquo; (214). In Chloe&rsquo;s case, she wasn&rsquo;t incredibly comfortable writing out the problems. She actually says, &ldquo;I cannot think with my brain right now&rdquo; and uses verbal frameworks to make sense of the problem she is trying to solve, trying to &ldquo;wrap her brain around it.&rdquo; Once she finally solved the first subset, it looks as if she moves forward and is comfortable and repeats the steps she took with pen and paper to solve the rest of the problem. It seems as if, the biggest cognitive burden for subjects doing long division is mental math and her use of dividing the cognitive load by &ldquo;showing all her steps&rdquo; allows her to solve the problem. Like Kirsch said, &ldquo;any organizing activity which recruits external elements to reduce cognitive loads&rdquo; makes the whole problem solving process possible, especially long division.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',20,1,2,0,1,'2016-02-09 04:52:20','2016-03-04 01:06:56'),(23,'Cultural Historical Activity on long division.','<p>Video link:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://youtu.be/meycPSzokU8?t=35s\">https://youtu.be/meycPSzokU8?t=35s</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Time: 0.35-1:35</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The way of solving the problem:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The way she (Chenxi) started to solve the wrong division problem is ok. The method of solving problems (not only the long division but any) varies from person to person and also from region to region. Usually one learns how to divide from the schools by the teachers or at home by the parents. No matter what is the learning source, it is not same in different parts of the world. The way she started to solve the problem is completely different from the way I learned how to divide any number (big or small). For example, the way I&rsquo;d do is something like &rarr;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>39 / 2&nbsp; = 2|39| &rarr; 2|39|1&rarr;9&rarr;.(to add 0)&rarr;5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Answer: 19.5<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2_</u><br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 19<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>18</u><br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 10<br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<u>10</u><br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">If I had to do the long division, I would follow the same procedure I learned from my school. Comparing these two methods, we can easily get the cultural difference of the way of solving the problem. I selected the timeframe of 0:35&rarr;1:35 where she (Chenxi) was calculating the second number in mind without knowing the correctness of the output. When I continued to watch further, I saw that her first and second attempt were wrong which led me to think that she was doing the trial-and-error. Historically it is pretty common to solve things by doing trial-and-error by any culture and eventually she got the right one for solving the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Although she was communicating with her partner about the problem but she was thinking about the problem more in mind while solving the problem. According to the definition of internalization, it is internal reconstruction of an external operation which is the solving the long division problem in our case.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','Internal:\nIn this video chenxi was performing the long division operation while ryan was recording. While I was analyzing the video, I tried to analyze what chenxi was doing and thinking since the operation didnâ€™t begin with a conversation with partners. She wrote down the numbers for the operation as it was shown on the lecture slide. That I figured when I was doing this analysis so it is hard to tell whether itâ€™s a a common procedure or she wrote that down after seeing that portion on the slide. It didnâ€™t take her long to write down number 2 for the multiplication and by that headstart, I figured she already done first couple of multiplication with the number 3437 in mind and realized 3 times multiplication goes beyond the first four digit 9705 and with the flow of confidence she already did her first mistake. Without realizing that she moved to the subtraction phase. By analyzing the speed of her writing while speaking the numbers out loud, I presume its easy to get that sheâ€™s pretty much confident what sheâ€™s doing and she already calculated the result in her mind for the first part. Instead of writing 6874 as the result of 3437 x 2, she wrote 6974 by mistake. I think she was trying to get the result in a hurry since there are more numbers to go and thereâ€™s not much time left. The urge of finishing the whole operation as fast as possible led her to the first and very common mistakes by the people who solves the mathematical problems in short time. \nDuring the subtraction part, she did that right with the wrong result of first multiplication which was 6974 instead of the correct result 6874. For the second part she picked number 7. It took her a while to pick that number without asking the partner which led me to believe she was multiplying the numbers in head but not for long time. Here she made her second mistake. May be she guessed the number she picked is correct and multiplied with 3437 at pace and due to that she multiplied 7 with 2437 instead of 3437. As she started multiplying the numbers from right to left, she picked the wrong number which was on the far left and wrote down the result right away and moved to the subtraction part. It clearly shows that she was doing the operation in a hurry which led her 2nd consecutive multiplication mistake. Of course picking 2 instead of 3 as far left of a four digit number gives a lower result and by seeing that she thought 8 might give her the closest result and picked number 8 instead of checking the multiplication with number 7 once again. She used eraser and erased everything she wrote while multiplying with number 7 and started fresh with number 8 which gave her a higher result than the number for the subtraction. Then she realized it has to be number 7 which she expressed by saying â€˜lets try this againâ€™ while writing down 7. I believe she also realized that she did some mistake during the multiplication when she got the higher value with the other multiplier and kept on doing the multiplication with 7 again.\nIn the end sheâ€™d never get the correct answer as she did mistake with the multiplication at the very first place and didnâ€™t check that. No matter how many times she keeps correcting the following multiplier, that first mistake is always there. I believe her overconfidence on picking numbers plus solving the problem in a rush led her to those mistakes continuously. May be she was getting those numbers right by calculating in mind correctly but she kept failing to transfer that from internal to external.\nAs I did the analysis considering the internal, I tried to follow Gray Crocodileâ€™s analysis a bit. While s/he was analyzing Roger and Bradâ€™s problem solving process, Gray found that Brad was doing something different from the other people might do which was writing down a multiplication table. A well thought process and time saving too in some cases. As I watched that video too, brad proceeded accordingly and taking time while in my analysis, Chenxi didnâ€™t have such multiplication table on the side but started solving the long division right away like sheâ€™s already running out of time. Using of eraser as artifact is common here as they (Brad and Chenxi) did mistakes. As Gray mentioned the intra-psychological process, which was being interrupted in Chenxiâ€™s case heavily due to the rush I believe. She was not trying to think much what she was doing due to the high confidence and rush. As mentioned Grayâ€™s analysis, Brad had a slow beginning which helped him later by finish the long division fast and correctly where in Chenxiâ€™s case, she has a fast beginning with high level of confidence although that problem was very new to her (considering the digits) which led her to an incorrect result and killed more time.\n',14,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-09 04:54:06','2016-03-01 16:22:25'),(24,'COSI 111a HW1 Part I','Â https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E 0:30-1:30Â  \n\nIn the segment of video I selected, in 0:30 Talie says â€œusually itâ€™s how many times this number goes into this numberâ€, apparently her thinking is based on what she learned previously that now became her own knowledge. In terms of doing long division itself, this is an activity that, in a cultural-historical perspective, requires knowledge that developed inter psychologically and eventually, intra psychologically. As most of the students learned in math classes possibly during elementary school, we acquired this skill from the teachers, who used speech to teach us what division is, and gave illustrations of how to do division most likely by writing on a blackboard or a piece of paper. Through communicating with the teachers, working with division problems together with other students, and maybe asking parents for help, these interpersonal and social interactions enabled us to internalize the basic principle of how to do division so that it became the knowledge in ourselves. From the long division videos, even though individuals have various extent of familiarity with division (since it is a quite complicated one), we all have an idea of how to solve a division problem. The two students in this video use their knowledge acquired from their previous experiences, following the general rule of doing long division and planning out their solutions. In the videos, not all use the exact same method to solve the long division problem. For example, in Saad and Mojirâ€™s video, the way Mojir wrote on the paper is different from others. I think that is cultural historic as he learned to do it this way probably from his teachers or those around him. Human cognition is influenced by culture which, according to Geertz, is a set of control mechanism located in our head. Also I noticed people have different way of keeping track of the carry the subtraction. Some wrote down the exact digit, some wrote dots, and some did it mentally. These might be cultural historic differences, if they these different habits from their teacher. These could also be ontogenic as they developed different habits on their own from experiences. Another difference I noticed, though minor, is that several of the students wrote the partial steps on the right side of the paper, some wrote on the top, and some didnâ€™t write down those notes. This is probably microgenesis, as it is more of a moment-by-moment decision of where to right the supplementary calculations. It might also be ontogenic that during individualsâ€™ development and the accumulation of experiences, one might find one way is better than the other.\n','<p>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5oFCF7O-f8E (By Talie and Ethan)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Segment: 0:30 - 1:30&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the segment of the video, Talie and Ethan was trying to solve the long division problem by using their prior knowledge. As they wrote down the long division box on the paper as their beginning step, they started a conversation to plan out the solution. &ldquo;Usually it&rsquo;s how many times this number goes into this number,&rdquo; said Talie. The keyword &ldquo;usually&rdquo; suggested that she was using her prior knowledge &ndash; how she usually would do the long division. She expressed her thoughts to Ethan that they could get the first digit of the answer from how many times the divisor goes into the first four digits in the dividend. After Ethan confirmed with her, she replied, &ldquo;Yeah, and then you have to subtract it.&rdquo; Subtraction, according to her prior and procedural knowledge for doing long division, is the next step after getting the first digit in the answer. Finishing the multiplication of 3437 times 2 on the side, Ethan directly aligned the result under the first four digits of the dividend, 9705. There was not much discussion about this step between the two people, but their cooperation went on without a problem, because they shared this prior knowledge that it is default to put the multiplication result where they put (they probably learned the similar way to do division).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In terms of the structure of the activity in the segment of video, it is internal, embodied, external and interactive. First of all, as previously said, Talie and Ethan were using their procedural knowledge on division. Before they wrote down anything, the conversation revealed what they were thinking, which was how many times 3437 goes into 9705. Having a plan enabled them to get to the right solution efficiently instead of writing before thinking. It was also embodied, as Ethan knew where to align the result of 2 times 3437 with. Certainly it was from his knowledge and mental process, but the action of writing down the result at the right place was done so quickly and naturally, that I think it is also embodied. It was probably because he was familiar with doing division. The activity was very much internal; but it was also external and interactive. They were in a situation of a classroom, given this task to perform. Talie was supposed to film and Ethan played a more dominant role as he held the pen to write. This hierarchy shaped the way they interact &ndash; as their cooperation progressed, Ethan seemed to take more initiative asking Talie if he was doing each step right. Since Talie and Ethan were asked by the instructor to work on this problem together, the activity involved interaction between the two, and therefore, what they did had much to do with the other person&rsquo;s responses. For example, when Talie gave her ideas of how many times 3437 should go to 9705, Ethan was checking with Talie by saying, &ldquo;you are saying&hellip;&rdquo; Then he needed to agree or disagree (through conversations) with her in order to proceed. In this case, he agreed with her, but if he disagreed, what they would do might be different &ndash; perhaps they would figure out another way to solve the problem due to a different opinion. Later Ethan checked with Talie again, &ldquo;we are adding them right?&rdquo; The interaction made the activity very different from doing a long division problem by oneself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comparing the two analyses I did, the second one had more examples and details, since the commentaries suggested. As I did the first analysis, I was not so sure that I needed to be specific. But seeing the commentaries, being specific made sense to me. Going through homework part i to iii, it was interesting to look at the same thing with different perspectives, which help me to understand an activity like doing long division with depths. It was quite helpful to have someone write commentaries on my analysis, read other people&rsquo;s analyses and make commentaries. It enabled me to see how other people think regarding the same issue with the same given angle, and to notice what I missed. I could also use others&rsquo; suggestions, to improve my analyses. Without the interactions with others, I would probably just remain the same way of thinking. From the interactions, I can see how language plays an important role. By agreeing with some of the points, I have been internalizing those ideas into my second writing, even the small things like adding summarizing sentences. Writing an essay is usually an internal-dominant activity, but through the interactions on the platform, I was influenced by external factors and driven by the dictates and design of the situation &ndash; the homework instructions.</p>\r\n',25,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-09 14:38:44','2016-03-01 04:33:37'),(25,'Homework 1','The video I chose for this assignment is from Maria and Zak. In this video clip Iâ€™m going to use a cultural historic approach to do the analysis. \n\nThe first piece of video Iâ€™m using is the one at the beginning of the video. As Maria tried to write down the first digit of the result, she asked Zak whether the first digit should be 3 or 2. Zak suggested it should be 2. Then Maria multiplied 3447 with 2 to see if that works, and it turned out to be the correct number.  In this transcript,  thereâ€™re two types of cognitive activities happened according to Vygotskyâ€™s framework.  The one that happened first was the inter psychological activity, in which Maria asked Zak for what number to put as the first digit. After Maria get the suggestion from Zak, she did the multiplication to make sure the number is correct.  That was the intro psychological activity since she was doing the multiplication without any communication with Zak. Vygotsky famously stated: â€œEvery function in the child\'s cultural development appears twice: first, on the social level, and later, on the individual level; first, between people (interpsychological) and then inside the child (intrapsychological)â€ . In this transcript, even though doing long division is not directly related to child cultural development, we can still get some idea of the structure of the learning process. The structure of learning activity in this video was that inter psychological process happened before the intrapscyhological process. \n People have different ways to do long division. If we compare Maria and Zakâ€™s video with Saas and Mojirâ€™s , we can find that Mojir has an alternative way to write the number and symbols. Rather than putting the divisor on the left, he put it on the right.  I think that was a cultural historic difference since it was caused by the different ways to teach long division from education systems in which Mojir and Maria grew up. \n ',' ',28,1,4,0,1,'2016-02-11 13:54:36','2016-03-03 03:08:33'),(26,'Transcript 1: Logic Problem (Riddle)','<p><em>The riddle was not provided with the transcript. Luckily, I was able to find it on the internet. Here is a transcription of the riddle below to better help understand the code, comments, and discussion.&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><b>RIDDLE</b></h3>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>In total there were four colours and each rose colour appeared twice.</li>\r\n	<li>From the clues below can you tell who had which colour roses?</li>\r\n	<li>Mr&nbsp;Green had a yellow rose.</li>\r\n	<li>Mr&nbsp;Yellow did not have a red rose.</li>\r\n	<li>Mr Red had a blue rose but not a green one.</li>\r\n	<li>Mr Blue did not have a yellow one.</li>\r\n	<li>One person with a red rose also had a green one.</li>\r\n	<li>One person with a yellow rose also had a blue one.</li>\r\n	<li>One of the persons with a green rose had no red rose.</li>\r\n	<li>Neither of the persons with a yellow rose