e mutual understand that the code could have been better understood if the coder had time to complete the problem. This information is now grounded. These two lines are also a prime example of an adjacency pair. It includes two ordered utterances, the first and second parts were produced by two different speakers, where the first part was the question and second was the answer that depended on the question of the first speaker. Lines 13 and 14 showcase the depth of communication that a two line conversation can be explained.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>c. Do an analysis of your transcript in terms of the access framework (four access characteristics) described in Perkins paper Person-plus: a distributed view of thinking and learning. Is there a distribution of executive function? Explain.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Please refer to the &quot;YOUR CODE&quot; &amp;&nbsp;&quot;YOUR COMMENTS/DISCUSSIONS&quot; section for this part of the analysis.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For this particular question, I will be focusing on the comments which are lines 1-11.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The comments section are a prime example of the access characteristics of the system because it includes all four parts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. <em>Knowledge:</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The commenter&#39;s declarative knowledge comes from the information she picked up from the riddle. This information was given to both participants, it is apparent, and it is factual. The procedural knowledge is exercised in the performance of extracting and deducing knowledge from the coder&#39;s code. To gain knowledge about the code, the commenter had to&nbsp;delve&nbsp;into &quot;higher-order&quot; knowledge to&nbsp;figuring out the coder&#39;s method of problem-solving strategies, styles of justification, explanation, and inquiry characteristic&nbsp;of the domain. Therefore, the commenter&#39;s knowledge is a combination of the declarative and procedural knowledge from the riddle and the coder&#39;s code.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 8-9 show an example of the commenter trying to use her procedural knowledge to gain more information from the code. &quot;&nbsp;I am assuming that the colors before the parentheses are concrete answers, the ones in&nbsp;parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her guesses&quot;. Based upon the riddle, the commenter was able to predict the strategy that the coder was using in order to solve the problem. This is an example of how the commenter used her declarative knowledge in order to help her gain procedural knowledge. If she was not aware of the riddle, it would have been impossible for her to figure out what kind of strategy the coder was using.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>2. <em>Representation</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The representation concerns how the information is presented. The coder used very minimal words to explain their strategy and method of problem-solving. However, the code was organized well enough for the commenter to pick up and recode. In the code lines 4-8, the coder labeled the gardeners and what the potential combination of flowers could have been. This information was enough for the commenter to pick up and understand because in the comments section the commenter wrote in lines 3-4 &quot;From line 4-8, I had a similar way of representing my thoughts externally, through listing&nbsp;the 4 gardeners and identifying the colors I knew they had, and the colors they could have&quot;. This comments solidify that the information was represented in a way that could be understood.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>3. <em>Retrieval</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main retrieval key that the commenter used to be able to represent the information was the code line 4-8 where the coder labeled the gardeners. Because the information was properly labeled Mr Green, Mr Red, Mr Yellow, Mr Blue, this helped the commenter focus her attention on this piece of code and extract the necessary information.&nbsp;Not all of the code was useful in information retrieval because the commenter indicates in line 10, &quot;Why is Mr Yellow repeated?&quot; This question indicates that the commenter was confused about this particular line of code and that it did not present any information that could have been retrieved.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In terms of the overall structure of the platform, the format was decently structured in the sense that the code section was colored differently than the comments sections and so it was easy to identify the different areas of text and locate what you were trying to look at. If you wanted to look at the code, it was clear to look inside the black box labeled &quot;Your Code&quot; and if you were commenting, it was easy to see where you could input text under &quot;Your Comments/Discussions&quot;. One improvement that I would suggest to ease the retrieval process would be for all the lines to be numbered as they are in the code section. If the comments were labeled by line or if they could expand to fit a whole thought about a particular line of code rather than having to jump down to the next line, I think the process of retrieving information would be even more clear.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong style=\"line-height: 1.6;\">4. <em>Construction</em></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Memory aside, the platform was a useful tool in helping the commenter assemble pieces of information into a new knowledge structure. The platform aided in viewing the code and make comments. This would have been much more difficult if they had to do it in their heads or talk about it after without the visual aid of the platform that provides them the information and doesn&#39;t make memorizing it necessary. If the participants had more time to complete the riddle as well as their discussion, this would have been a better example of construction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Explain your transcript from the perspective of situated activity. What is the the context and arena while the participants did the java exercise? Does the transcript provide an example of the dialectic relation between context and setting? Are there elements of the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Context:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.6;\">The overarching context of the exercise is virtual logic problem-solving in same time, different place. There were&nbsp;two participants who were both &quot;coders&quot; then &quot;commenters&quot; and then &quot;discussion-ers&quot;. Although&nbsp;context can also be experienced differently by different individuals, it does not apply in this particular exercise because the structure of the arena.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong style=\"line-height: 1.6;\">Arena:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The arena of the virtual problem-solving was the computer platform. The arena is non-negotiable and concrete because the participants did not have a choice on how they would be performing the exercise. The arena provides the necessary grounds to perform the task. It is also a personal space for problem-solving activity to take place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Dialectic relation:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am not sure if the transcript provides an example of the dialectic relation between context and setting. Dialectic relation refers to when the setting is generated out of the activity while simultaneously generating the activity. This concept is really difficult for me to wrap my head around. My guess would be that the setting of the discussion is generated from the participants doing the logic problem but by solving the problem they are also generating the activity of problem-solving.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After being able to read The Plum Penguin&#39;s post who also had the other half of the logic problem, I think it is fair to say that this particular problem does not showcase a dialectic relationship well because of the levels of restriction of the problem&#39;s context. It is similar to the exercise we did in class where we compared the supermarket to doing math problems in class. This exercise would represent a situation closer to doing math problems in class than a supermarket simply because the problem lies within the online platform itself. The logic is not being tested outside of the boundaries of the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Gap-closing:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are elements of the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing. Take for example, the problem that the commenter must understand what the coder wrote in order to gain knowledge and close the gap between the commenter&#39;s understanding of how the coder attempted to solve the problem. Instead of having two separate parts that is the problem and then the solution, the commenter redefined the problem into smaller, simpler parts that she was able to reuse to help her solve the problem. The commenter used her knowledge which she gained from doing the problem and the solution and method she used in order to better understand the coder&#39;s code. In the comments, she referenced back to how they had similar methods which helped her to gain insight on what strategy the coder used without actually having to ask the coder what she did. She also picked up information from the code that looked unfinished. This smaller piece of information allowed the commenter to figure out that the coder was not completely done.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><strong>Reflect on the impact of part 2 of this assignment on your revisions to the first draft of the assignment. What did you learn by reviewing the analysis work of other members of your team? Did it change your level of confidence in your own work? et cetera</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although I did not do a lot of text revisions, I believe that part 2 of the assignment helped me on my second draft a lot. By reviewing the analysis work of other members of my team, it allowed me to highlight things I believe they did well and things they could improve upon. From the things that I liked from their posts, I noted so that I could compare my post to theirs and see if I included enough of the detail or organization that they did. Also, one particular post helped me with the dialectic relation that I was having some trouble with. After reading their thoughts about the idea, it helped me solidify my thoughts. From the things that I thougth people could improve, I made sure that I was taking the same constructive outlook on my own post. This helped me review my work and look out for specific things that I thought should or shouldn&#39;t be there. The process of review did not change my level of confidence dramatically, however, I do believe that it instilled a little more confidence that I did not have prior.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',9,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-04 14:52:31','2016-03-14 20:20:27'),(27,'Logic problem analysis','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://argument.cs-i.brandeis.edu/assets/transcript1-372a5f52f55f22c3db747dbb1908cc8005631e3f6b2294b2145009b62b5644d6.jpg\" style=\"width: 1000px; height: 750px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Clark &amp;&nbsp;Schaefer&rsquo;s <u>Contributing to Discourse</u>, grounding is defined as &ldquo;the contributors and the partners&rdquo; having mutual belief &ldquo;&hellip;that the partners have understood what the contributor meant to a criterion sufficient for current purposes&rdquo; (262). Simply put, grounding is a process in which members of a conversation check with each other to ensure that there is common ground, or common understanding as to their goal. A good example of grounding that can be seen in the transcript is at the first sentence from the commenter:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person 1: &ldquo;and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your answers were and such&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Person 2: &ldquo;lol YES&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The commenter (person 1) is checking in with person 2 to gain support for their assumption that if person 2 had more time for the exercise, that they would have been able to make their answer more concise, and &ldquo;user friendly&rdquo; to read. Person 2 grounds this assumption by giving an affirmative response to person 1&#39;s comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clark &amp; Schaefer (1989) defines adjacency pairs as &ldquo;&hellip;two ordered utterances, the first and second pair parts, produced by two different speakers&rdquo; (270). That is, an idea that is spoken by one speaker, contributed to by the other speaker mid-sentence, then either concluded by the second speaker, or by the first speaker with the addition of another part of the sentence. Because of the organization of the conversation between the two participants, it was difficult for me to determine what could have been an adjacency pair in this script. The exchange below could be interpreted as an example of an adjacency pair:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person 1: &ldquo;agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Person 2: &ldquo;which you pointed out&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, person 2 is finishing the thought that person 1 had about not being able to remember their answers by acknowledging that they remembered this comment. However, I am unsure as to whether or not this is an actual example, because the ordering of the text boxes in the script becomes unclear as person 2 continues to type, and some boxes are repeated. It is unclear if this is due to user error, or to an error with the program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Contribution and acceptance are two phases a grounding interaction. The contribution phase may also be referred to as the presentation phase. The same example that was given before for the grounding process can be used for these two phases.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Contribution phase:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Person 1: &ldquo;and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your answers were and such&rdquo;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Acceptance phase\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Person 2: &ldquo;lol YES&rdquo;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Person 1 presents their contribution that they believe that person 2 would have had more time to make their final answer more explicit and easy to read if they were given more time. Person 2 then acknowledges and accepts this contribution by responding with an emphatic &ldquo;lol YES.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Schegloff &amp; Jefferson (1974) define repairs as &ldquo;&hellip;mechanisms&hellip;for dealing with turn-taking errors and violations&rdquo; (701). An example of this would be if two members of a conversation were to find themselves speaking at the same time; one would stop mid-sentence in order to repair this violation of turn-taking. In this script, I do not think that repair mechanisms are applicable, as I do not see any examples of any violations in turn-taking, or errors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, the co-presence heuristic is being used because both participants are present and observing the same problem, i.e., the logic problem. During the discussion phase, the participants are able to view their answers to the problem. This allows for better discussion, because they are able to directly to refer to their answers instead of having to recall them from memory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case, the knowledge that is available is whatever knowledge the two participants possess about logic puzzles. The level of knowledge that each pariticipant possesses about logic puzzles will vary depending on their experience with them, and additionally on their experience with computer programming. The latter is due to the dependency of programming and computer languages on logic; in order to have a good understanding of computer science and programming, one must have a concrete understanding of logic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Access framework:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Knowledge - In this situation, it can be assumed that neither the learners nor the surround contained much higher-order knowledge about logic problems. However, it can also be assumed that the participants did have some content-level knowledge about logic puzzles.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Representation - For this example, the representations used by the participants would have to be mental, since they were not allowed outside resources, such as text or online articles.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Retrieval -&nbsp;In this particular situation, the two students were most likely restricted to retrieving their knowledge about logic puzzles from their memories, or from each other. In most situations, the participants would be able to retrieve knowledge about logic puzzles not only from memory, but also from text or online sources.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Construction -&nbsp;In this situation, the surround that is used by the two students is their computers. The students use their computers to create the necessary data structures for this logic puzzle. In this particular case, the data structures that are created or would be created is the participants&#39; proposed solution to this problem.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Lave et al. (1984) define the arena as a &ldquo;higher-order institutional framework within which setting is constituted&rdquo;, and setting as a &ldquo;personally ordered and edited version of the arena&rdquo; (71). For this example, I would argue that the arena is the platform on which the logic problem is presented, and the setting is the logic problem itself. The platform acts as the arena in the same way that the grocery store acts as an arena; it is an environment that contains many different options for an individual to explore. However, much in the same way that a shopper only interacts with and goes to certain aisles in a grocery store, creating their personal setting for that particular arena, the participants in this problem solving activity are only offered one problem to solve, which establishes that specific problem as the setting; in this example, the setting is a logic problem. For other groups, the setting was a Java program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, there is a dialectic relation between the context and the setting. The setting, the logic problem, is being generated by the activity &ndash; that is, the logic problem is being generated in order to promote collaboration between the two participant members. At the same time, the activity &ndash; the logic problem &ndash; is generating the setting.</p>\r\n','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://argument.cs-i.brandeis.edu/assets/transcript1-372a5f52f55f22c3db747dbb1908cc8005631e3f6b2294b2145009b62b5644d6.jpg\" style=\"width: 1000px; height: 750px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: One of my group members kindly pointed out to me that the chat part of the script should be read from the bottom-up, instead of from the top-down. This altered the way in which I viewed the script, and thus altered the way in which I analyzed it. I have made the corresponding changes below in this new, final draft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Clark &amp;&nbsp;Schaefer&rsquo;s <u>Contributing to Discourse</u>, grounding is defined as &ldquo;the contributors and the partners&rdquo; having mutual belief &ldquo;&hellip;that the partners have understood what the contributor meant to a criterion sufficient for current purposes&rdquo; (262). Simply put, grounding is a process in which members of a conversation check with each other to ensure that there is common ground, or common understanding as to their goal. A good example of grounding that can be seen in the transcript is at the first sentence from the commenter:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person 1: &ldquo;and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your answers were and such&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Person 2: &ldquo;I hope so&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The commenter (person 1) is checking in with person 2 to gain support for their assumption that if person 2 had more time for the exercise, that they would have been able to make their answer more concise, and &ldquo;user friendly&rdquo; to read. Person 2 doesn&rsquo;t respond with an affirmative answer, but they do put forth the hope that their answers would have been more user friendly if they had been given more time to finish the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clark &amp; Schaefer (1989) defines adjacency pairs as &ldquo;&hellip;two ordered utterances, the first and second pair parts, produced by two different speakers&rdquo; (270). That is, an idea that is spoken by one speaker, contributed to by the other speaker mid-sentence, then either concluded by the second speaker, or by the first speaker with the addition of another part of the sentence. Because of the organization of the conversation between the two participants, it was difficult for me to determine what could have been an adjacency pair in this script. The exchange below could be interpreted as an example of an adjacency pair:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person 1: &ldquo;agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha&rdquo;</li>\r\n	<li>Person 2: &ldquo;lol yeah&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, person 2 shows their agreement with the previous statement of person 1 by giving an affirmative answer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Contribution and acceptance are two phases a grounding interaction. The contribution phase may also be referred to as the presentation phase. The same example that was given before for the grounding process can be used for these two phases.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Contribution phase:\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Person 1: &ldquo;and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your answers were and such&rdquo;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>Acceptance phase\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Person 2: &ldquo;I hope so&rdquo;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Person 1 presents their contribution that they believe that person 2 would have had more time to make their final answer more explicit and easy to read if they were given more time. Person 2 then acknowledges and accepts this contribution by responding with the statement, &ldquo;I hope so.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Schegloff &amp; Jefferson (1974) define repairs as &ldquo;&hellip;mechanisms&hellip;for dealing with turn-taking errors and violations&rdquo; (701). An example of this would be if two members of a conversation were to find themselves speaking at the same time; one would stop mid-sentence in order to repair this violation of turn-taking. In this script, I do not think that repair mechanisms are applicable, as I do not see any examples of any violations in turn-taking, or errors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, the co-presence heuristic is being used because both participants are present and observing the same problem, i.e., the logic problem. This enables them to better discuss the problem later, because they are both able to observe and review their answers after solving the problem, which allows for better discussion, because they are able to directly to refer to their answers instead of having to recall them from memory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case, the knowledge that is available is whatever knowledge the two participants possess about logic puzzles. The level of knowledge that each participant possesses about logic puzzles will vary depending on their experience with them, and additionally on their experience with computer programming. The latter is due to the dependency of programming and computer languages on logic; in order to have a good understanding of computer science and programming, one must have a concrete understanding of logic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Access framework:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Knowledge - In this situation, it can be assumed that neither the learners nor the surround contained much higher-order knowledge about logic problems. However, it can also be assumed that the participants did have some content-level knowledge about logic puzzles.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Representation - For this example, the representations used by the participants could be mental, since they were not allowed outside resources, such as text or online articles.&nbsp;Additionally, their representations could have been physical, as the students were able to type back and forth and maintain a conversation, while one of them organized the format of the solution.</li>\r\n	<li>Retrieval -&nbsp;In this particular situation, the two students were most likely restricted to retrieving their knowledge about logic puzzles from their memories, or from each other. In most situations, the participants would be able to retrieve knowledge about logic puzzles not only from memory, but also from text or online sources.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>Construction -&nbsp;In this situation, the surround that is used by the two students is their computers. The students use their computers to create the necessary data structures for this logic puzzle. In this particular case, the data structures that are created or would be created is the participants&#39; proposed solution to this problem.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Lave et al. (1984) define the arena as a &ldquo;higher-order institutional framework within which setting is constituted&rdquo;, and setting as a &ldquo;personally ordered and edited version of the arena&rdquo; (71). For this example, I would argue that the arena is the platform on which the logic problem is presented, and the setting is the logic problem itself. The platform acts as the arena in the same way that the grocery store acts as an arena; it is an environment that contains many different options for an individual to explore. However, much in the same way that a shopper only interacts with and goes to certain aisles in a grocery store, creating their personal setting for that particular arena, the participants in this problem solving activity are only offered one problem to solve, which establishes that specific problem as the setting; in this example, the setting is a logic problem. For other groups, the setting was a Java program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example, there is a dialectic relation between the context and the setting. The setting, the logic problem, is being generated by the activity &ndash; that is, the logic problem is being generated in order to promote collaboration between the two participant members. At the same time, the activity &ndash; the logic problem &ndash; is generating the setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reviewing the analyses that were completed by my teammates gave me new perspective on some of the concepts that I thought I previously had an adequate understanding of. Being able to see the structure of these analyses gave me more confidence in my own analysis, as it provided support for how I had structured my own post, and how I analyzed my script. On the other side of the coin, seeing posts that were structured differently than mine did not make me lose or gain confidence in my own analysis, but allowed me to see other perspectives of how a script can be viewed and written about, which only serves to enhance my own knowledge of analysis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',24,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-05 20:17:30','2016-03-15 01:00:50'),(28,'Homework 2','<p><strong>A) Transcript</strong> (only the first 11 lines, as after that only one person was active in the chat, ending the interaction)</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:40px;\">\r\n			<p><strong>Line</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:37px;\">\r\n			<p><strong>Participant</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:546px;\">\r\n			<p><strong>Statement</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:40px;\">\r\n			<p>1</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:37px;\">\r\n			<p>1</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:546px;\">\r\n			<p>I hope so</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:40px;\">\r\n			<p>2</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:37