g when they said &quot;which you pointed out.&quot;&nbsp; This clues person 2 into the notion that person 1 has understood their new contribution, and it has been grounded collaboratively into the conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>- Adjacency Pairs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As the note above states, I am going to have to infer in a few places what I think the &quot;correct&quot; order of this interaction is in order to identify adjacency pairs.&nbsp; The first occurs in lines 2 and 3, wherein person 2 informs person 1 of their hypothesis regarding person 1&#39;s success with the assignment had they been given more time.&nbsp; Person 1 then accepts this -- this is a model example of the inform/ acknowledge adjacency pair.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The next resembles a complaint/remedy adjacency pair, and takes place in lines 5 and 6 (which I suspect should be in the opposite order for this interaction to make any sense).&nbsp; Person 1 implicitly complains about their own work, stating they didn&#39;t make it very user friendly.&nbsp; Person 2 then offers a sort of remedy (albeit a highly simple, unsubstantiated one), in saying simply &quot;very user friendly.&quot;&nbsp; While this may not be an entirely clear response, no request for clarification was made (see previous section for more on this), and it is clearly in response to person 1&#39;s implicit complaint, making it an example of the complaint/remedy adjacency pair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A final example of an adjacency pair occurs in lines 6 and 8, and is an example of the compliment/acceptance pair.&nbsp; Person 2 compliments person 1&#39;s work, saying &quot;It made sense to me!!&quot; to which person 1 responded &quot;I&#39;m glad you could figure out my thought process...&quot; therefore accepting the compliment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>- Repairs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this very brief interaction, there are no explicit places wherein either person 1 or person 2 is obviously confused by some divergence in conversation and must try and repair it so both return to the same page.&nbsp; However, one can imply the last two lines, lines 10 and 11, could be some sort of implicit repair, or at the very least, an implicit request for clarification on the part of person 1.&nbsp; Person 2 (in line 11) states they would like to see a &quot;side by side,&quot; to which person 1 says &quot;which you pointed out.&quot;&nbsp; This is likely a reference to some earlier (undocumented) point in a conversation they&#39;d had, and person 1 might have been implicitly trying to clarify that was what person 2 was referencing.&nbsp; Had this been the case, then person 1&#39;s reference to the previous mentioning of a &quot;side by side&quot; could be seen as an attempt to repair some divergence in the conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>- Virtual co-presence</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There exists evidence of co-presence, the sense of &quot;being together&quot; with others, in this conversation quite obviously in its participants&#39; diction.&nbsp; For instance, as I write this paper, in solitude and with a (hopefully) academic sort of rigor and word choice, I would be quite unlikely to use colloquial or slang terms.&nbsp; However, in this transcript, both person 1 and person 2 make use of such terms on more than one occasion.&nbsp; These terms include &quot;lol&quot; (twice), &quot;haha&quot;, and &quot;A+&quot; (in a nonacademic sense).&nbsp; Additionally, there is a certain disregard for absolute formality, such as proper capitalization and punctuation, which is certainly an indicator of virtual interaction (but would rarely be found in a non-interactive written work).&nbsp; As such, these slang terms and colloquialisms result in some evidence that both conversation participants were aware of one another&#39;s presence -- that is, they had a sense of &quot;being together,&quot; even in a virtual environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>C) Access Framework</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>- Person-plus, 4 characteristics</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The person-plus is often broken down into two pieces -- the surround and the &quot;residue&quot; left by thinking.&nbsp; With regard to the surround of both participants -- that is, the &quot;immediate physical and social resources outside the person&quot; -- they were placed in a room (presumably Ken Harsch&#39;s office) and sat across from one another on separate computers.&nbsp; The surround included these computers, the desk or table they sat at, and the electronic platform they used to communicate with each other -- the exact chat interface, the colors, the location of objects on the screen... Participants (to my knowledge) were instructed to communicate largely over the computer, rather than in person, thus somewhat constricting their social resources to the virtual entirely.&nbsp; By forcing thoughts to be expressed in a somewhat rigid, written-only format, it forced brevity and perhaps a lack of clarity.&nbsp; In addition, the platform used for communicating (part of the surround) often experiences glitches or lags, resulting in a messy ordering of participants&#39; contributions to conversation.&nbsp; This undoubtedly affected their ability to communicate effectively.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The &quot;residue&quot; portion of person-plus is slightly less concrete -- it pertains largely to what is learned in both the mind and the arrangement of the surround.&nbsp; For a better look at this, we can examine the &quot;access framework,&quot; as described by Perkins, by four discrete characteristics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Knowledge</em>: The participants all had similar knowledge when discussing the solution -- they both knew the problem that was assigned, and they both were looking at a proposed solution to that problem.&nbsp; What may not have been as clear to each was the exact nature of the approach, or the underlying rationale behind it (this knowledge may have been clearer to whomever came up with the solution that was being discussed).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Representation</em>:&nbsp; The conversation was represented in the platform as colored chat bubbles -- each person had their own color.&nbsp; These bubbles were supposed to appear in the order each chat request was sent, but there is some evidence to suggest this was not the case due to lag (see lines 7-9; observe how it seems some contributions that were made later should have appeared sooner).&nbsp; This lack of entirely accurate representation could have had a negative impact on the fluidity and effectiveness of the conversation, impacting the access framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Retrieval</em>: The access framework allowed for retrieval of knowledge rather easily -- the proposed solution was on screen at all times, along with the ongoing chat.&nbsp; Particpants could easily reference both.&nbsp; Additionally, participants were able to directly post comments pertaining to particular lines of a proposed solution, and enter dialogues specifically for these particular lines (which is what this transcript is, a dialogue pertaining to a comment that was made on a certain line of the proposed solution).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Construction</em>: The system lent itself to the assembly of pieces of knowledge into new knowledge structures by providing a space for a dialogue -- however, the surround of the person-plus environment that prohibited non-virtual contributions likely impacted how richly textured these new knowledge structures could go.&nbsp; Unfortunately, the greatest construction of &quot;new knowledge structures&quot; that is evident in this 11 line transcript alone is simply the notion that both person 1 and person 2 are on the same page about the user-friendliness of the proposed solution (see lines 5 and 7).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>- Distribution of executive function</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A distribution of executive function occurs when a learner &quot;...cedes executive function to the surround and gradually gets it back as he or she gains mastery of the new knowledge...&quot;.&nbsp; There are no strong examples of either participant yielding executive function in the 11 lines of this transcipt; however, I can and will grasp at some straws in an effort to demonstrate my knowledge of this phenomenon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Line 10 demonstrates a desire to cede executive function to a &quot;side by side,&quot; when person 2 says &quot;agreed, I would also like to see a side by side...&quot; In this instance, they are admitting they would benefit from yeilding their executive function to something else (in this instance, a &quot;side by side&quot;) in order to gain further knowledge about this particular proposed solution in relation to their own.&nbsp; This is evidenced by the confession &quot;...because I can&#39;t remember my answers haha.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>D) Analysis of problem solving / JPS</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This could certainly be considered a joint problem space, as the range of components needed in solving the &ldquo;problem&rdquo; &ndash; that is, explaining how they solved a logic or Java problem to another and sharing alternate solutions and/or comments regarding the currently proposed one &ndash; includes social interaction, albeit virtual interaction.&nbsp; We can further substantiate this claim by observing how the transcript supports the notion that collaborators have ways of &ldquo;&hellip;introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning [and] repairing divergences&hellip;&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The participants of this transcript clearly were able to contribute and accept new knowledge into the JPS. The first example of this occurs in lines 2 and 3, wherein person 2 makes a statement speculating the improved quality or potential success person 1 would have had given more time to complete the task.&nbsp; This is a new contribution, and the system allowed for it to be introduced into the JPS.&nbsp; What is more, person 1 is able to accept this new knowledge by their response in line 3 (this also grounds the new contribution as now mutual knowledge, see the first section of this paper for more).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is possible this new contribution into the JPS could have gone misunderstood. Had person 1 have been unable to decipher what person 2&#39;s was trying to say with this new contribution (that is to say, detected &ldquo;evidence of divergence in meaning&hellip;&rdquo;) a repair exists to address this.&nbsp; In accordance with Clark&rsquo;s theory of conversational grounding, in this even it is likely they would have attempted to ground the new contribution by a request for clarification, thus hopefully repairing the potential divergence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',12,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-06 18:53:25','2016-03-06 18:53:34'),(29,'Transcript 3','<p>Section A:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &nbsp; &nbsp; A:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, ...]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: oh that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: idk how well it would work</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: You could have used a map maybe</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: but that accounts for the &quot;what if they have the same letters and same length but different repeated letters&quot; question</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&#39;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah exactly. then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&#39;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section B:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this platform, participants are virtually co-present. During the interaction portrayed by this transcript, both partners are simultaneously attending to the same section of code. Based on the co-presence heuristic, there is an assumption of mutual knowledge made. This becomes evident in the transcript in multiple places. For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A is assuming that Partner B knows what an array is and the significance of making it of size 32. As this is a platform for an introductory Java class, the partners assume that the other has some basic knowledge of Java and programming in general. Using specific terms like &ldquo;array&rdquo; or &ldquo;data structure&rdquo; implies that they both have a common vocabulary for referring to aspects of the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, they are both attending to a specific piece of the code. The comments are organized line-by-line. A comments:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A has forgotten a string operation and contributes a possible other method for tackling the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the first section of the transcript:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &nbsp; &nbsp; A:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, ...]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: oh that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A contributes an alternative method for approaching the problem. Partner B seems to accept that contribution from the beginning. In line 3, she says &ldquo;I like that&rdquo; which appears to be an acceptance of the alternative method. However, Partner A continues explaining her idea. This indicates that Partner A is not convinced that her contribution has been sufficiently grounded. The partners proceed with proposal and acceptance adjacency pairs. Partner A proposes more details and partner B expresses her acceptance of the new detail saying things like &ldquo;oh that&rsquo;s smart&rdquo; and &ldquo;yeah that would have been good&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interestingly, there is overlap of turns within this transcript. In face-to-face conversation, transitions between turns exhibit very little or no overlap. However, in computer-mediated collaboration, this is harder to achieve.&nbsp; In lines 9-15, turns tend to overlap quite a bit. Line 9 and 13 by Partner B seem to be part of the same turn but Partner A has inserted a turn before Partner B has finished their thought. Partner A hasn&rsquo;t finished their turn quite yet when Partner B continues in line 13. Line 14 seems to be a continuation of the turn by Partner A in lines 10-12. As there is no mechanism such as &ldquo;partner A is typing&hellip;&rdquo; to make the other partner aware that a turn has completed, the platform leaves room for overlap in turns. It also may cause adjacency pairs to not be exactly adjacent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good example of a presentation and acceptance in this transcript is as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&#39;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah exactly. then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner B presents an idea in line 15. Partner A demonstrates understanding of that presentation by asking a followup question. This demonstrates that Partner A has understood the utterance so far and is willing to move on to the next step in the explanation. In line 17, Partner B accepts the question by Partner A as a valid contribution by saying &ldquo;yeah exactly.&rdquo; and continuing on with her discussion. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section C:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this context, both partners have knowledge about how to program in Java. They know about data structures including things like Maps and arrays. They know about syntax and convention in the language. They also have general knowledge about how the use the platform (for example, they know how a chat works).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part of this transcript that is interesting is exemplified in the following line:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip;]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A wants to make their point clear. She gives an example of what she is saying and represents it in a visual way. For someone with knowledge regarding data structures, they know she is expressing an array of numbers that is, in some way, related to the string abcc. In fact, she is representing the string in a new way. The string is no longer a list of characters, but a count of the characters in which the index relates to the letter and the number relates to the count of which that letter appears within the string. This exemplifies a change of representation so that Partner A can make her idea for tackling the problem more obvious to Partner B. Changing the representation of the problem makes it easier for Partner B to understand and perhaps make tackling the larger problem overall, easier as well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retrieval</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The last line of the transcript:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&#39;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the very end, Partner B makes a comment that alludes to a failure in retrieval of knowledge. She knows that there are string operations in Java that would do what she wanted them to do with substrings. However, because she couldn&#39;t remember those operations, she resorted to using another data structure. She seems to understand the concept of how to proceed but can&rsquo;t retrieve the relevant information regarding Java syntax and operations to proceed with that idea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I imagine that, had they had the opportunity to use online resources, the partners could have made more progress toward a solution. While they discuss possible ideas, it seems like they need to rely on the world to support their memory. Using each other helps support the memory of any one partner. However, it seems as though neither really recalls specific syntax for approaching this problem. Perhaps a Java IDE or access to Java documentation or lecture slides would have helped.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The executive function seems to be distributed between partners as well as on the platform. Both partners are contributing to the discourse in order to make progress toward a solution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section D (option ii):&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The context in which this collaborative activity is situated is within that of an introductory programming class. The arena consists of a lecture in which students are taught concepts about Java and possibly some data structures. There is a structure of lecture and exercises to make the concepts being taught concrete.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The partners problem solve together. They proceed using gap closing in that they redefine the problem in terms of different data structures as a way to get closer to the solution. First they consider using an array that holds a count of the number of times a particular letter appears in the string. Then they redefine the problem when Partner B says:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, partner B has expressed a different approach to the problem (i.e. using substrings instead). Partner B thinks this representation of the problem is closer to a final solution because it involves less looping than representation as an array. The transcript ends before the partners reach a final conclusion but, I imagine, had they been allowed to continue, they would have continued in this manner until finding the appropriate approach to solving the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p>Section A:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &nbsp; &nbsp; A:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, ...]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: oh that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: idk how well it would work</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: You could have used a map maybe</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: but that accounts for the &quot;what if they have the same letters and same length but different repeated letters&quot; question</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&#39;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah exactly. then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&#39;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section B:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this platform, participants are virtually co-present. It is important to note that this is not the same as being physically co-present. However, there are still some assumptions that come along with this knowledge of virtual co-presence by both of the partners.&nbsp;During the interaction portrayed by this transcript, both partners are simultaneously attending to the same section of code. As such, they are reading the same chat transcript. The system only allows one chat to be open at a time so, therefore, it is reasonable to assume that both partners are reading the same chat (assuming they are paying attention to the screen and participating in the activity). Since they are both participating in the conversation, it is evident that this is, in fact, true.&nbsp;Based on the co-presence heuristic, there is an assumption of mutual knowledge made as a result. This becomes evident in the transcript in multiple places. For example:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A is assuming that Partner B knows what an array is and the significance of making it of size 32. As this is a platform for an introductory Java class, the partners assume that the other has some basic knowledge of Java and programming in general. Using specific terms like &ldquo;array&rdquo; or &ldquo;data structure&rdquo; implies that they both have a common vocabulary for referring to aspects of the code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, they are both attending to a specific piece of the code. The comments are organized line-by-line and the chat is related to the line of code that the comment&nbsp;is aligned with. Partner A comments:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A has forgotten a string operation and contributes a possible other method for tackling the problem. This serves as a point of entry into a conversation regarding how to approach the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the first section of the transcript:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &nbsp; &nbsp; A:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, ...]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: oh that&#39;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A contributes an alternative method for approaching the problem. Partner B seems to accept that contribution from the beginning. In line 3, she says &ldquo;I like that&rdquo; which appears to be an acceptance of the alternative method. However, Partner A continues explaining her idea. This indicates that Partner A is not convinced that her contribution has been sufficiently grounded. In order for a contribution to be grounded, both partners must believe that the contribution has been understood by both of them.&nbsp;The partners proceed with proposal and acceptance adjacency pairs. Partner A proposes more details and partner B expresses her acceptance of the new detail saying things like &ldquo;oh that&rsquo;s smart&rdquo; and &ldquo;yeah that would have been good&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interestingly, there is overlap of turns within this transcript. In face-to-face conversation, transitions between turns exhibit very little or no overlap. However, in computer-mediated collaboration, this is harder to achieve.&nbsp; In lines 9-15, turns tend to overlap quite a bit. Line 9 and 13 by Partner B seem to be part of the same turn but Partner A has inserted a turn before Partner B has finished their thought. Partner A hasn&rsquo;t finished their turn quite yet when Partner B continues in line 13. Line 14 seems to be a continuation of the turn by Partner A in lines 10-12. As there is no mechanism such as &ldquo;partner A is typing&hellip;&rdquo; within this system to make the other partner aware that the partner has completed their turn, the platform leaves room for overlap in turns. It also may cause adjacency pairs to not be exactly adjacent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A good example of a presentation and acceptance in this transcript is as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&#39;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yeah exactly. then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner B presents an idea in line 15. Partner A demonstrates understanding of that presentation by asking a followup question. This demonstrates that Partner A has understood the utterance so far and is willing to move on to the next step in the explanation. In line 17, Partner B accepts the question by Partner A as a valid contribution by saying &ldquo;yeah exactly.&rdquo; and continuing on with her discussion. At this point, the contribution has been accepted as mutual knowledge for both partners and the contribution has been grounded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section C:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this context, both partners have knowledge about how to program in Java. They know about data structures including things like Maps and arrays. They know about syntax and convention in the language and share a vocabulary about how to discuss concepts in this context. They also have general knowledge about how the use the platform (for example, they know how a chat works).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part of this transcript that is interesting is exemplified in the following line:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip;]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partner A wants to make their point clear. She gives an example of what she is saying and represents it in a visual way. For someone with knowledge regarding data structures, they know she is expressing an array of numbers that is, in some way, related to the string abcc. In fact, she is representing the string in a new way. The string is no longer a list of characters, but a count of the characters in which the index relates to the letter and the number relates to the count of which that letter appears within the string. This exemplifies a change of representation so that Partner A can make her idea for tackling the problem more obvious to Partner B. Changing the representation of the problem makes it easier for Partner B to understand and perhaps make tackling the larger problem overall, easier as well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retrieval</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The last line of the transcript:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&#39;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the very end, Partner B makes a comment that alludes to a failure in retrieval of knowledge. She knows that there are string operations in Java that would do what she wanted them to do with substrings. However, because she couldn&#39;t remember those operations, she resorted to using another data structure. She seems to understand the concept of how to proceed but can&rsquo;t retrieve the relevant information regarding Java syntax and operations to proceed with that idea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I imagine that, had they had the opportunity to use online resources, the partners could have made more progress toward a solution. While they discuss possible ideas, it seems like they need to rely on the world to support their memory of available string operations and the like. Using each other helps support the memory of any one partner. As a result, it is evident that they are working within their zones of proximal development.&nbsp;However, it seems as though neither really recalls specific syntax for approaching this problem. Perhaps a Java IDE or access to Java documentation or lecture slides would have helped.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The executive function seems to be distributed between partners as well as on the platform. Both partners are contributing to the discourse in order to make progress toward a solution and it is not evident that either one has more knowledge than the other. They seem to have different types of knowledge and are sharing that knowledge with each other to make progress.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Section D (option ii):&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The context in which this collaborative activity is situated is within that of an introductory programming class. The arena consists of a lecture in which students are taught concepts about Java and possibly some data structures. There is a structure of lecture and exercises to make the concepts being taught concrete.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The partners problem solve together. They proceed using gap closing in that they redefine the problem in terms of different data structures as a way to get closer to the solution. First they consider using an array that holds a count of the number of times a particular letter appears in the string. Then they redefine the problem when Partner B says:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 &nbsp; &nbsp; B: but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, partner B has expressed a different approach to the problem (i.e. using substrings instead). Partner B thinks this representation of the problem is closer to a final solution because it involves less looping than representation as an array. The transcript ends before the partners reach a final conclusion but, I imagine, had they been allowed to continue, they would have continued in this manner until finding the appropriate approach to solving the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reflection:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My group members provided good insight regarding aspects of my analysis that could have used more clarity and depth. By reading the analyses of other group members, I realized the importance of structuring my analysis in a manner that was easy to read. Particularly, it was useful to have specific lines of the transcript copied directly into the analysis. It prevents the reader from having to go back and forth between the transcript and discussion when reading the analysis and makes it easier to follow one&rsquo;s train of thought as a result. I also realized the importance of getting up close to the transcript and tying&nbsp;in all the concepts we have learned thus far to the transcript as a whole. The ideas we&rsquo;ve discussed in class are all related and applicable to the transcript.&nbsp;It helps to provide a comprehensive analysis in applying the terms to this context. This was a good exercise in combining many of&nbsp;the concepts we have talked about to a real world example.</p>\r\n',19,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-06 21:18:49','2016-03-15 22:40:06'),(30,'Transcript 4: A Failure To Communicate ','<p><em>Disclaimer: In the following analysis I will refer to the author of the code as Student A (in green) and the second student who is commenting on the code as Student B (in white).&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part A. How do the participants understand the conversaition?<br />\r\nIn the window above we see a conversation between two students, Student A and Student B. In the transcirpt we can see several attempts between the two users to discuss segments of the code, however there is evidence that much of their attempts to communicate clearly failed. In the white line by Student B &quot;Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D&quot; and the subsiquent response &quot;Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?&quot;&nbsp;we see a failure to communicate. Expressions like this, where one person tries to confirm the identity of their conversation partner, are examples of adjacency pairs. If the comminucation between the students&nbsp;was successful, the response from Student A should have been something like &quot;Yes, I am the same person.&quot; Instead of that, we saw Student A say &quot;Now are you the same person I was talking to before?&quot; Becuase Student A&#39;s response did not match the expected response, that means A did not understand Student B properly when he sent the message. One possible explanation is that the two students sent the message at the same time and we are seeing it out of order. There isn&#39;t much evidence to back up that claim, however. If that was the case, we would see a delayed response from either Student in the form of &quot;Yes, we talked earlier.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part B:&nbsp;When we talk about a Person-Plus model, we have to look a conversation in its physical and mental context. In this example, the conversation between Student A and Student B is taking place as they both look over the code written by Student A. There are four main access characteristics of Person-Plus and all can be explained by Student B&#39;s line &quot;Actually what if...&quot;. The first characteristic is knowledge. The code on the left uses Student A&#39;s knowledge of how to write code in Java and how he thinks an anagram checkking program should be written. The second is representation. This one is simply&nbsp;the representation of&nbsp;the written code that we are reading. The third characteristic is retreval. In Student B&#39;s quote she says what &#39;word one&#39; and &#39;word two&#39; should be for a specific test. In saying that, she is 1. retrieving what information is needed in order to do a test by looking at the code&#39;s representation, 2. internalizing part 1 and coming up with what testable values are, and 3. picking test cases that can be used to construct a case that will point out a problem to Student A. The final characteristic is construction. As a result of this analysis by Student B, a new test case is constructed that fails Student A&#39;s code.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part C:&nbsp;This website was created with the goal of being a collabarotive learning platform for students. In the transcript above we see the beginnings a conversation that shows why this is a joint-problem space. In order to be a joint-problem space, according to Rochell &amp; Teasley, &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration.&quot; In the first white line, we see Student B introduce new knowledge to the JPS when they suggest a new test case that would fail Student A&#39;s code. In the subsiquent response, &quot;Yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;, we see Student A accept that knowledge. In Student B&#39;s next three lines, we see them make a personal comment to Student A, a correction to a previous message, and a new idea to improve the test case they created earlier. These three messages demonstrate that Student B feels comfortable talking freely and that there is an on-going attempt to moniter activity (in the form of correcting mistakes). Judging by the fact that the last comment by Student A stops in the middle of a sentence, this transcipt only reflects a proporiton of the dialogue. Becuase we see evidence of adding and accepting ideas as well as a free and open dialogue, this is clearly a joint problem space.&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p><em>Disclaimer: In the following analysis I will refer to the author of the code as Student A (in green) and the second student who is commenting on the code as Student B (in white).&nbsp;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part A: Transcipt Text&nbsp;</u></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong>: Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagrams proceeds checks if two strings are anagrams of each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">Person A</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">;</span> yeah, that&rsquo;s true! I over looked those cases</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&rsquo;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">Person A</span></strong>: yeah that&rsquo;s true. If both words have the same characters then it will say that its an anagram even though they&rsquo;re in a different order.</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong>:Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong>: Sorry word1 and word2 are reversed</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> Actually what if word1 has ababab and word two is bob. Wouldn&rsquo;t the method fail to work?</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">Person A</span>:</strong> Thanks, not are you the same person I was talking to before?</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span>:</strong> Very good and clever!</li>\r\n	<li><strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">Person A</span>:</strong> Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just checks that if that idea of word1 is in word2. If it&rsquo;s not, then they aren&rsquo;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part B. Grounding and Adjacency Pairs: Demonstrating Co-Presence</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcirpt, we are seeing a virtual conversation between two students over&nbsp;an introductory level Java problem. In this portion of the script in particulair we are looking at the start of Student B&#39;s analysis and critic of Student A&#39;s work. In line 1 (Logic looks good...) we see Student B setting the course of the conversation. By initializing the conversation with a comment about the functionality and problem of Student A&#39;s code, they ground the rest of the conversation. By grounding the conversation, I mean that Student B laid the framework for the rest of the conversation by formalizing the common ground and purpose with Student A in the first line. We see another&nbsp;example&nbsp;of Student B grounding the conversation in line 7 (where they focus the conversation on a test case) and we see Student A grounding the conversation in line 10 when they clarify and reaffirm what the intent of a segment of code was. Grounding examples like this are important because they keep Student A and B on the same page during the conversation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While there are good examples of Student A and B grounding the conversation, there are also examples of failed ajacency pairs in this transcirpt. In line 5 we see student B say</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;5 -&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong>:Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Normally, contributions such as this are met with responses like &quot;Yes, we talked earlier&quot; or &quot;No, we have never met.&quot; In this case, Student A responded by saying</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"background-color:#00FF00;\">&nbsp; 8 - Person A</span>:</strong> Thanks, not are you the same person I was talking to before?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>which is basically the same message that was sent by Student B. What this means is that Student B&#39;s message was not recieved by Student A. One explanation could be that the two students sent the message at the same time (which is unlikely because Student B has enough time to type two more responses) and another is that Student A failed to see Student B&#39;s first message before responding. Either way, a clear failure to communicate is troubling. An example like this would not happen if two students where physically co-present in the same room talking face to face. In that case, the students would take turns talking and would understand each other better. Since the students are only virtually co-present, communication can be harder. Ultimately, while the adjacency pairs give evidence of lack of co-presence, the grounding examples do show the opposite.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<u>Part C:&nbsp;Person Plus: Knowledge, Representation, Retrieval, and Construct&nbsp;</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Person-Plus is a type of analysis that looks at both the participants and the environment to understand what cogninitive frameworks are at work in a transcript. In this example, the environement is the box-chat on the left side of the screen and Student A&#39;s block of code on the right. There are four main characteristics of a person-plus framework and I will explain them bellow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Knowledge:</strong><br />\r\nKnowledge is this context stands for the&nbsp;&quot;rich techincal repertiore&quot; that each student brings to the conversation. Judging by the coding ability and technical speak, both students have at least an introductory level of knowledge java. We can see that in line 1 where Student B points out an error in the code and line 10 where Student A explains the architecture of his code. Going forward, knowledge stands as a psuedo pre-requistie for the other characteristics because this transcipt can only be fully appreciated by someone who is coding literate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Representation:&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nRepresentation in this analysis stands for both physical representations (lines of code, boxes of comments, etc) and mental representations (mental pictures and explanations). If we look the following line:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;7. Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> Actually what if word1 has ababab and word two is bob. Wouldn&rsquo;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>we can see Student B articulating a problem in Student A&#39;s code by writing a test case that would fail. By representing the error as an example, Student B can have an easier way communicating with Student A where the problem is and why it matters.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Retrieval:&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nThe third characteristic is retreval. In Student B&#39;s quote:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&rsquo;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>she says what &#39;word one&#39; and &#39;word two&#39; should be for a specific test. In saying that, she is 1. retrieving what information is needed in order to do a test by looking at the code&#39;s representation, 2. internalizing part 1 and coming up with what testable values are, and 3. picking test cases that can be used to construct a case that will point out a problem to Student A.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Construction:&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nConstruction is the end-goal of the three earlier characteristics. In this transcipt, Student B is using their knowledge to understand the code and their representation and retrieval to communicate and error with it. Once that is done, Student B can help Student A construct better code by sparking the idea of what to change. Construction could not be possible wihtout the other frameworks laying the fondation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part D: Joint Problem Space&nbsp;</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This website was created with the goal of being a collabarotive learning environements&nbsp;for students that allows for effective student-environment interactions (person-plus) as well as student-to-student conversation. As demonstrated by the analyses in Part B and C, there is evidence that this platform can allow for effective learning and communication. This transcirpt also shows that the platform is a joint problem space. Firstly, one of the most important things to a JPS is co-presence. The analysis from part B explains how there is evidence of co-presence in this transcipt - even though there are some minor problems. Secondly,&nbsp;according to Rochell &amp; Teasley, &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration.&quot; In the line by student B:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;3. Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&rsquo;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;we see Student B introduce new knowledge to the JPS when they suggest a new test case that would fail Student A&#39;s code. In the subsiquent response, &quot;Yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;, we see Student A accept that knowledge. In Student B&#39;s next three lines</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">&nbsp; 5 Person B</span></strong>:Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D<br />\r\n<strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;6 Person B</span></strong>: Sorry word1 and word2 are reversed&nbsp;<br />\r\n<strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">&nbsp; 7 Person B</span></strong><span style=\"background-color:#FFFF00;\">:</span> Actually what if word1 has ababab and word two is bob. Wouldn&rsquo;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;we see them make a personal comment to Student A, a correction to a previous message, and a new idea to improve the test case they created earlier. These three messages demonstrate that Student B feels comfortable talking freely and that there is an on-going attempt to moniter activity (in the form of correcting mistakes). Judging by the fact that the last comment by Student A stops in the middle of a sentence, this transcipt only reflects a proporiton of the dialogue. Becuase we see evidence of adding and accepting ideas as well as a free and open dialogue, this is clearly a joint problem space.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Reflection/ Analysis of Homework</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>From parts 1 and 2 of this assignment, I learned a lot about how to effectively communicate. Not just because the analysis this week is about effective communication, but because the first two parts showed me I was clearly not communicating effectively. In my first analysis, I was way to consice and did not give nearly enough analysis - partly because I was confused on how long to make the assignment, but mainly because I did not know how to articulate ideas in context of the transcript. From readings the other papers in step two, I realized quote analysis was a lot clearer when the quote was put directly into the paragraph and that line spacing could be used to add extra emphasis.&nbsp;Without part two of this assignment I do not think I could have improved upon my first analysis in part 1.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',27,2,8,0,1,'2016-03-08 01:49:26','2016-03-15 02:40:11'),(31,'','<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copy of Transcript: (W corresponds to the person whose text had a white background. G corresponds to the individual with the green background. The transcript structure is based off of Ken&rsquo;s lecture JPS Lecture 9. The line numbers correspond to turn taking. Each turn was locally managed by a &ldquo;turn-by-turn basis&rdquo;, party administered and interactionally managed. This conversation is also an adjacency pair for the conversation contains an exchange of one turn each by two speakers.&nbsp; )</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; W:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.75in;\">lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">&ldquo;______&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; G: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; W:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">but it was too much lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">with the ( ) and the ?</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">then I kept changing the system I had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">yeah I think I put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; G:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; W:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">So when I looked back at the problem and my solution, I got a little confused</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">I put the mr.&rsquo;s out of order</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; G:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">I found the count really useful as well</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">Yours seems to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in the parenthesis</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; W:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">The counts is also really useful</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">It was a lot easier when its organized</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">Mine was all over the place</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">It helped mine</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">Yours was more organized than me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; G:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Knowledge:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both students brought their own personal knowledge from previous experiences to the problems they were given to solve aka &ldquo;long-term memory.&rdquo; When commenting on their peer&rsquo;s work, each partner brought new knowledge to their analysis which they gained from their own experience doing of the same exercise themselves. When both partners joined forces to converse together they again brought all of their previous knowledge plus the new knowledge from commenting on their partners work. Lastly, both partners were able to build knowledge between each other through their conversation during the third phase of analysis in tandem. A perfect example of this can be seen in line 7 when W says to G &ldquo;The counts is also really useful&hellip; Mine was all over the place. It helped mine.&rdquo; This quote vividly exhibits that W was able to gain new insight and knowledge from G thus enabling him/her to come to a more concrete answer/way to tackle this problem and similar problems in the future. Another example could be seen in line 2. G says: &ldquo;&hellip;it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on.&rdquo; G was able to help W in his/her problem solving based on G&rsquo;s knowledge from doing the problem him/herself as well as the knowledge received from analyzing and interpreting W&rsquo;s solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Representation:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representations are the non-mental representations such as &ldquo;text, mathematical tables and formulas, and drawings&rdquo; which the students used to do their java or logic problem. In this scenario, the representation was the space they had to write code, comment and discuss and the chat feature. Students used that space to make their thinking clearer and build some artifact that helped their thinking and externalized their thinking &ndash; externalized cognition &ndash; using that space to solve problems. These spaces greatly aided the problem solving and knowledge process for they enabled the solvers to properly express their thoughts in easier to interpret forms such as charts and tables. How we are using this space to solve these problems is also part of representation. I believe that the conversations themselves can also be considered as representations for they are printed discussions of the logic on how to solve the problem at hand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the code I received that &ldquo;your code&rdquo; table had very interesting tables and representations which this individual used to help solve their logic problem. These tables (and their disorganization) were highlighted in the conversation between G and W.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1&nbsp; MR G &ndash; Y R (could be: B) (cant be: G)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2&nbsp; MR Y &ndash; G B &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(cant be R</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3&nbsp; MR R &ndash; B Y&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (coud be:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (cant be: G)</p>\r\n\