ve the problem together. The continued attempt is highlighted in the stages of problem solving. First is the lone attempt, then commenting on their counterpart, then attempting to correctly complete the question through discussion and further analysis. At each stage partners are aware of the current problem state of their partner and what stage they are at in solving the problem. They constantly are monitoring the activity of their partner to help them reach the ultimate goal and not to diverge in meanings. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A collaborative problem solving requires building a joint problem space and requires solving a problem together.&nbsp; The transcript above clearly shows narrations as well. W had some trouble in his/her initial test code, so he/she narrated to G where he/she think he/she went wrong. W informs his partner of his intentions corresponding to his actions. This was partially prompted by G&rsquo;s comments from the second phase of the problem solving. In line 2, G respectfully questions W, &ldquo;it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo;. To which W responded/narrates in line 3 &ldquo;with the ( ) and the ? then I kept changing the system I had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses yeah I think I put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order.&rdquo;&nbsp; In line 4, G poses a follow up question which leads into a repair for W. G helps break down W&rsquo;s thought process so both of them can better understand W&rsquo;s logic. &ldquo;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&rdquo; On the note of repair, Roschelle and Teasley wrote &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration. W had a very mismanaged time in trying to solve the logic problem. Building on knowledge, representation, retrieval and construction, 