ple above. After analyzing the transcript in terms of the four access characteristics described in the Perkins paper it appears to be evident that there is a distribution of executive function. It seems that W cedes the executive function to G. In line 7 W says &ldquo;Mine was all over the place. It helped mine. Yours was more organized than me&rdquo; saying that G had a much more organized structure and due to that, G&rsquo;s wisdom and skill influenced W&rsquo;s mismanaged attempt. We can say that in this scenario, that G left W with an adequate scaffold and an adequate executive function. Line 7 is also an example of an acceptance phase in which W acknowledges and accepts G&rsquo;s problem solving tactics. In line 8 G says (in response to line 7) &ldquo;Thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!&rdquo; Thus signaling an agreement of both parties on the tactic and solution.</p>\r\n',15,2,6,0,1,'2016-03-08 03:31:23','2016-03-15 02:12:11'),(32,'Transcript 2','<h1><u>Transcript</u></h1>\r\n\r\n<p>(Blue = the person whose logic is being discussed, person 1; red = the person analyzing, person 2)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">lol</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">-____-&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">but it was too much lol&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">with the ( ) and the ?&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">i put the mr.&rsquo;s out of order&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">i found the count really useful as well&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">the count is also useful&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">it was a lot easier when it&rsquo;s organized&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">mine was all over the place&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">it helped&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">mine&rsquo;&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">yours was more organized than me&nbsp;</span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">thank you! i feel pretty confident in what i arrived at!</span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n\r\n<h1><u>Analyses</u>&nbsp;</h1>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><u>Grounding, Adjacency Pairs, Contribution and Acceptance Phases, Repairs, and &ldquo;Virtual&rdquo; Copresence</u></h2>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">The first contributions (in lines 1 and 2) express sheepishness with way that person 1&nbsp;wrote out their system, and constitute a contribution of implicit appology for what person 1 seems to feel is unsatisfactory work. Person 2&#39;s response in line 3&nbsp;constitutes several things simultaneously: an adjacency pair (of appology and acceptance), grounding (that they both feel that the work could have been done better), and acceptance of person 1&#39;s contribution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Person 1 then continues by solidifying that grounding in line 4 and then explains in several contributions&nbsp;the reasoning for the choices they made. In line 8, person 2 seeks to repair an unclear contribution and clarifies the &quot;order&quot; to which person 1 refers in line 7. This repair (and person 1&#39;s response in line 10)&nbsp;constitutes a contribution and acceptance.&nbsp;Lines 11 and 13 also form a contribution and acceptance, where person 2 talks about the usefulness of a particular technique and then person 1 responds by agreeing, accepting that contribution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">Co-presence is assumed in much of this conversation, and forms the backbone of many of the interactions here. A few times (lines 1-3, line&nbsp;7-10, and lines 11-14), they both make reference to the logic operations that are in front of both of them, but they don&#39;t specifically cite the lines that they&#39;re talking about because of their co-presence. They know that the other has the same materials in front of them and can opt to use less energy in their conversation (referencing a line rather than citing it or quoting it).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><u>Access Framework&nbsp;</u></h2>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">In this case, the system contains representations of the information that person 1 and 2 are given, which itself allows retrieval and construction of that problem&#39;s solution. The system doesn&#39;t contain a lot of the knowledge that they were given to start the problem (in fact, having only done the Java program I&#39;m not sure what the problem they were given was, and I can&#39;t confidently say I understand the problem they were trying to solve) but instead contains the representations they have created to enable them to keep track of that which the problem asks them to do and to&nbsp;help to solve the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">This computer environment operates in a similar way to that of writing down a long division problem, although less of the information of the actual problem is contained within the environment (i.e., a long division problem contains the question in its representation, while this environment does not). It is because of this reason (that the representation does not contain the content of the problem) that executive function is not wholly distributed but is instead held within the minds of the people working on the problem.&nbsp;However, there is a partial distribution of executive function in the way that comments are created off of specific lines of the logic problem (in this case, the transcript above comes from line 9 of the logic problem). This structuring of the environment encourages person 1 and 2 to talk about the issues that are specific to line 9, rather than branching off to talk about the question at large, and for this reason there is at least partial distribution of executive function.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><u>Situated Activity&nbsp;</u></h2>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">In this situation, the arena is the computer environment in which person 1 and 2 are typing, which constitutes both their discussion in the transcript above and also person 1&#39;s original contributions to the logic problem, and the context is this problem-solving assignment. In my opinion, this environment is not the best example of the dialectic relationship between context and setting, merely because the assignment itself is a much stronger limiting factor on the participants&#39; activities than the problem itself. There are other contexts in which the participants are likely to use logic in the ways that they used it to solve the problem (and, like the supermarket arithmetic example they would in all probability&nbsp;be more likely to come to the correct answer than in this more regulated and artificial arena) and so this problem shows that the dialectic relationship is dependent on the level of restriction of the problem&#39;s context.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 80px;\">However, the problem does show some examples of gap closing as a method o