by commenting that,&nbsp; user2 understands that they have established common ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This interaction is also a good example of an assessment adjacency pair. The very first comment assesses the work that was done by user2, &quot;It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts....&quot; says user1. &quot;I hope so,&quot; responds user2. The following pair part of utterances &quot;I think if you had the time to finish...&quot; is conditionally relevant to this pair of utterances. In other words, it is expected and directly relevant to what was said earlier. In the following interaction, the two parties come to an agreement that user2&#39;s assessment was accurate and relevant to the original problem solving.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the first two interactions between user1 and user2, both parties establish common ground through presentation, acceptance and an assessment pair that resulted in a mutual agreement about the problem solving done by user2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot; The nuances of the game are all important. Not infrequently a person-plus fails in an activity because neither the person nor the surround nor the two in combination provides for a good executive function for the activity.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This quote from the Distribution of Executive Function reading is relevant to this transcript. In a non-virtual person-plus work-space, the user often has the ability to arrange the surround as they desire. The web application used in this activity did not grant that freedom and as a result did not function well as a work-space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, you can recognize frustration as a result of poor access characteristics in the application. &quot;I wasn&#39;t done... :( a few more minutes would have helped&quot;. The problem this user found was that while they were in the middle of a response, the application switched code and all unfinished comments were lost. If the users were given more knowledge about the functionality of the application, this frustration could have been prevented. In this example, the surround is given full executive function over the conversation and collaboration of the individuals. &quot;In the most familiar pattern, the learner cedes executive function to the surround and gradually gets it back as he or she gains mastery over the knowledge and skills in question.&rdquo; In this case, the surround does not offer any executive function to the users. In addition, the users probably did not know that commenting on each others work was making it more difficult for the other to finish their comments. A better design would have let the user organize their own work-space. If the user was able to comment, respond to comments and switch between their code and their partners code freely, no work would be lost and conversations wouldn&#39;t have been cut short by the application.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D) ii. Situated Activity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the perspective of situated activity, this transcript sheds light on the difficulties of context and setting in an online interactive activity. In the TPS java coding program, the arena can be defined as the program itself and the context is the commenting and collaboration part of the exercise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The program is dialectically constituted because the setting is both generated out of the problem solving activity in part 1 and at the same time generates the activity in part 2. In part 1, the users independently problem solved and then in part 2 they interacted by discussing each others answers. Part two is a give-and-take activity that each user contributes to by commenting on their partners code and responding to comments on their own. In this sense, the activity is also co-constructed by both parties.&nbsp; In this transcript, user1 couldn&#39;t finish one of their comments on time, user2, the one whose code is being commented on, responds, &quot;I think if you had the time to finish, it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such&quot; user1 responds &quot;lol YES&quot; then later &quot;I&#39;m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.&quot; In this interaction, user2 acknowledges how the give-and-take that was supposed to happen in this activity was difficult to follow. In this situated activity, the setting fostered a dialectic relationship between the two parties even though it caused some confusion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, there is no gap-closing problem solving. Neither user attempted to redefine or simplify the problem as a means to solve it. Instead, the users converse about each others comments and never really go back to looking at the original problem. It looks each person was commenting on their partners code as they were having this conversation. As a result, I mostly see just one side of the conversation. It could be that there was some redefining and simplification of the original problem in this conversation but it is not visible in this transcript as it is not complete.</p>\r\n','<p>1. A)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1:&nbsp;&quot;It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts....&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2:&nbsp;&quot;I hope so&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1:&nbsp;&quot;I think if you had the time to finish, it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2:&nbsp; &quot;lol YES&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1: A+</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1: Very user fiendly</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1: It made sense to me!!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&#39;t make it user friendly lol&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;Im glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;Lol yeah&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User1: &quot;Agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&#39;t remember my answers haha&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;Which you pointed out&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;There was a similar method in place though&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;I wasn&#39;t done lol&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot; :( &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;A few more minutes would have helped</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;I know we had the same answer for mr. blue&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;I think I was stopped as I was changing my answer for mr. green&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;WHICH ONE IS IT&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;which you pointed out&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;there was a similar method in place though&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>User2: &quot;I wasn&#39;t done lol&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The very first interaction between the two users is an attempt to establish common ground. User2 says, &quot;I think if you had the time to finish, it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such&quot; user1 responds &quot;lol YES&quot;. This brief interaction establishes copresence between both parties by acknowledging that user1 did not get the opportunity to finish writing his/her code. In establishing copresence, grounding is also achieved. In the presentation phase, user2 commented to user1 on the assumption that, user1 will give evidence of understanding. User1 accepted the comment by user2 and gave evidence of his/her understanding by saying &quot;YES&quot;.&nbsp; User1 also assumes that by commenting that,&nbsp; user2 understands that they have established common ground around how user2 didn&#39;t have enough time to finish their probelm solving.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This interaction is also a good example of an assessment adjacency pair. The very first comment assesses the work that was done by user2, &quot;It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts....&quot; says user1. &quot;I hope so,&quot; responds user2. The following pair part of utterances&nbsp;is conditionally relevant to this pair of utterances because user2 accepts the comments made by user1 as the truth. User2&#39;s responses could have seemed&nbsp;expected and were directly relevant to what was said before. In the following interaction, the two parties come to an agreement that user2&#39;s assessment was accurate and relevant to the original problem solving.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I believe the two users attempted to repair their problem solving but only part of the conversation is visible in this transcript. It sounds like the comment&nbsp;&quot;I think I was stopped as I was changing my answer for mr. green&quot;-user2 and &quot;I think I was stopped as I was changing my answer for mr. green&quot;- user2&nbsp;is part of a discussion the two users were having about their code. However, user1&#39;s responses are not visible so it might have gotten lost in the platform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the first two interactions between user1 and user2, both parties establish common ground through presentation, acceptance, co precence and an assessment pair that resulted in a mutual agreement about the problem solving done by user2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot; The nuances of the game are all important. Not infrequently a person-plus fails in an activity because neither the person nor the surround nor the two in combination provides for a good executive function for the activity.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This quote from the Distribution of Executive Function reading is relevant to this transcript. In a non-virtual person-plus work-space, the user often has the ability to arrange the surround as they desire. The web application used in this activity did not grant that freedom and as a result did not function well as a work-space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, you can recognize frustration as a result of poor access characteristics in the application. &quot;I wasn&#39;t done... :( a few more minutes would have helped&quot;. The problem this user found was that while they were in the middle of a response, the application switched code and all unfinished comments were lost. If the users were given more knowledge about the functionality of the application, this frustration could have been prevented. In this example, the surround is given full executive function over the conversation and collaboration of the individuals. &quot;In the most familiar pattern, the learner cedes executive function to the surround and gradually gets it back as he or she gains mastery over the knowledge and skills in question.&rdquo; In this case, the surround does not offer any executive function to the users. In addition, the users probably did not know that commenting on each others work was making it more difficult for the other to finish their comments. A better design would have let the user organize their own work-space. If the user was able to comment, respond to comments and switch between their code and their partners code freely, no work would be lost and conversations wouldn&#39;t have been cut short by the application.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The knowledge the participants had about the problem were externalized in the first part of the activity. In this transcript we are looking at the work done by user2. His/her internal knowledge about the problem was externalized in the platform and then instigated the following discussion. The discussion was mostly centered around the knowledge that went into their solutions rather than trying to collaboratively repair the solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The retrieval is made very easy by the platform. The discussion section is placed directly next to the problem solving that is being commented on. The participants can easily point to specific lines and discuss syntax or logic issues. These users discussed both syntax and logic issues, making direct references to how user2 set up his/her solution. The construction of these responses was also made easy by the design of the platform, since both users could assemble pieces of the solution to form new knowledge structures. It is interesting how there is no correct way of setting this solution up so I&#39;m both participants solutions looked very different.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D) ii. Situated Activity</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the perspective of situated activity, this transcript sheds light on the difficulties of context and setting in an online interactive activity. In the TPS java coding program, the arena can be defined as the program itself and the context is the commenting and collaboration part of the exercise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The program is dialectically constituted because the setting is both generated out of the problem solving activity in part 1 and at the same time generates the activity in part 2. In part 1, the users independently problem solved and then in part 2 they interacted by discussing each others answers. Part two is a give-and-take activity that each user contributes to by commenting on their partners code and responding to comments on their own. In this sense, the activity is also co-constructed by both parties.&nbsp; In this transcript, user1 couldn&#39;t finish one of their comments on time, user2, the one whose code is being commented on, responds, &quot;I think if you had the time to finish, it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such&quot; user1 responds &quot;lol YES&quot; then later &quot;I&#39;m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.&quot; In this interaction, user2 acknowledges how the give-and-take that was supposed to happen in this activity was difficult to follow. In this situated activity, the setting fostered a dialectic relationship between the two parties even though it caused some confusion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, there is no gap-closing problem solving. Neither user attempted to redefine or simplify the problem as a means to solve it. Instead, the users converse about each others comments and never really go back to looking at the original problem. It looks each person was commenting on their partners code as they were having this conversation. As a result, I mostly see just one side of the conversation. It could be that there was some redefining and simplification of the original problem in this conversation but it is not visible in this transcript as it is not complete.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think that part 2 of this assignment was the most beneficial to my own learning. I had some great practice looking at the transcript with different frameworks in part 1, but the collaborative effort of part 2 taught me more. When I read the posts by my classmates, I was expanding my zone of proximal development just learning from their excellent analysies. It was also helpful to look at different transcripts and how those transcripts have a different underlaying phenomena&nbsp;than the one I analized. It was very interesting to see how the same problem can result in such different conversations and how different personalities effect the focus of them. Looking back at my own post was helpful in expanding my knowledge but I learned most from reading the posts done by my peers and having conversations about their analysis.&nbsp;</p>\r\n',23,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-08 16:36:59','2016-03-15 02:51:28'),(34,'Analysis of Transcript 2','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>A. Transcript</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 A: lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 A: -_____-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 B: haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 A: but it was too much lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 A: with the ( ) and the ?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 A: then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 A: yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 B: oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 A: so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 A: i put the mr.&#39;s out of order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 B: i found the count really useful as well</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 B: yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilites put in parentheses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 A: the count is also useful</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 A: it was a lot easier when its organized</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 A: mine was all over the place</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 A: it helped</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 A: mine</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 A: yours was more organized than me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 B: thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>B.&nbsp;Analyze the chat in your transcript in terms of grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; copresence.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Grounding</u>: Grounding occurs continuously in this conversation--as new knowledge and opinions&nbsp;are introduced&nbsp;by&nbsp;each participant, the other participant must demonstrate that they understand and accept this contribution, establishing that it is now common knowledge. For example, at line 11, person B says &quot;i found the count really useful as well,&quot; to which person A responds in line 13 saying &quot;the count is also useful.&quot; Person B introduces their opinion, aiming to establish it as commong knowledge. Person A not only recognizes this piece of information, but agrees to it, confirming its shift into their common knowledge base.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Adjacency Pairs</u>: Adjacency pairs also occurred frequently in this transcript. At line 18, person A compliments person B by saying that &quot;yours was more organized than me,&quot; in reference to their solutions for the problem. Person B responds in line 19 by saying thank you. This example of a compliment given by one participant and ensuing acceptance&nbsp;by the other would be identified&nbsp;as an adjacency pair. Another example of an adjacency pair occurred at line 7, when person A states &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order,&quot; and person B responds by asking for clarification in line 8: &quot;you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Contribution and Acceptance Phases</u>: Contributions are constantly made by the participants to convey their thoughts (i.e. &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; in line 3),&nbsp;which their partner must attempt to register and accept, similar to grounding. This particular instance of the contribution phase was then followed by the acceptance phase of their partner replying &quot;but it was too much lol / with the ( ) and the ?&quot; on line 4 and 5. Another example of this occurs at line 18, when person A says &quot;yours was more organized than me.&quot; This contribution was registered by person B and accepted, with their response being &quot;thank you! I was pretty confident in what I arrived at!&quot; (line 19).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Repairs</u>: In lines 7-10, the participants discuss the order of the user&#39;s answers. When person A first says &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&quot; in line 7, person B requests clarification of this statement&#39;s meaning by asking &quot;you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot; in line 8. A repair must then be made by person A to reaffirm the meaning of their statement, and then is done in line 10 when they say &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>&quot;Virtual&quot; Copresence</u>: As demonstrated in their&nbsp;conversation,&nbsp;both participants are present in discussion, making them&nbsp;virtually proximal&nbsp;despite the potential existence of physical distance. A major contributor to this sense of virtual copresence would be the bounds of the virtual environment. The environment is self-contained: they have easy access to all that they need on this one page of the online platform. Had there been the necessity to browse the web, or access a different application during their problem-solving or discussion, the two participants would certainly not be as present. For example, references are constantly made to the structure of the user&#39;s solution (lines 3-19).&nbsp;Had the&nbsp;solution been located anywhere else besides the same page as the chat panel, the conversation would be more disconnected and the participants less present.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">C.&nbsp;Do an analysis of your transcript in terms of the access framework.&nbsp;Is there a distribution of executive function? Explain.â€‹</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. <u>Knowledge</u> (kinds of): The knowledge of each user for the logic exercise&nbsp;was formatted in their left-hand workspace to their own liking. This way of externalizing internal knowledge added to the user&#39;s surround, especially when it came time to&nbsp;share their work&nbsp;with their partner. Without this externalization, it would be unclear to the other participant what the user&#39;s solution was, and how they reached this solution. In conversation, the discussion of their&nbsp;knowledge that went into their solutions never occurred. Instead, the participants decided to focus on the style and organization of their external representations of knowledge, which I found very interesting. This topic was at the forefront in line&nbsp;3 through line 19, but some specific examples of this include &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; (Person B, line 3), &quot;then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&quot; (Person A, line 6), &quot;yours was more organized than me&quot; (Person A, line 18).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. <u>Representation</u> (how): Representations of the user&#39;s thought process and solution are housed in the left-hand panel. What&#39;s interesting about this problem is that there isn&#39;t a &quot;right&quot; way to go about setting this up. For a Java exercise, representations are clearly made and understood by others (who share knowlege of the programming language), and comments can be placed throughout to explain the mental representation that went into the virtualized one. However, with a logic exercise, the users don&#39;t get to see the full thought process and progress towards a solution, which likely drove the participants to discuss their methods more in-depth (lines 3-19), and explain their representational systems to one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. <u>Retrieval</u> (can it find it and how effectively): Because the user&#39;s solution is placed directly next to the conversation panel, it is easy for the participants to refer back to the work and retrieve pieces of information from it to be discussed. However, as discussed in the Representation section, much discussion was centered around the structure of one&#39;s solution and thought process represented on-screen. At line 12, person B notes the organization of person A&#39;s work, and how it is similarly organized to their own. Their following discussion of what helped make solving the problem, and now reading each other&#39;s solutions, more useful demonstrated how effectively they could retrieve information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. <u>Construction</u> (assemble pieces of knowledge into new knowledge structures): This characteristic appeared in the user&#39;s solution--the user had to consider the given knowledge about the logic problem, and solve the problem by assembling new knowledge structures that could then be shared with their partner. In the conversation itself, little construction is made, and little discussion of the actual content of their constructions were discussed (what was the right answer?). Instead, the formatting of their constructions dominated the conversation, as stated previously (line 3-19).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By the end of their conversation, both participants seemed to have gained back executive function from their surround, which would signify a distribution of executive function. This was reached by the participants through discussion of their representations and retrieval.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">D.&nbsp;ii. Explain your transcript from the perspective of situated activity. What is the the context and arena while the participants did the java exercise? Does the transcript provide an example of the dialectic relation between context and setting? Are there elements of the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing?</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because activity and setting are dialectically constituted, the setting is generated out of the activity and at the same time generates the activity. This is the basis of the situated activity perspective. The arena is defined as&nbsp;encompassing&nbsp;the individual, providing a higher-order institutional framework within which setting is constituted. So, for this activity, the arena for the participants would be the online platform. Much like the aisles of the grocery store, each potential exercise that a student could be assigned to exist within the platform and as a part of the arena, but because they are not relevant to the user, they are not a part of the user&#39;s setting. The user&#39;s personal setting is their assigned problem, their solution space, their partner&#39;s solution space, and the area for designed dialogue. This setting not only is generated out of the logic exercise problem, but also generates the activities that occur in it (writing down solutions, looking over partner&#39;s solution, conversing with partner about solutions).&nbsp;Together, the arena and personal&nbsp;setting make up the context of the activity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Problem solving through gap closing, or looping between redefining and solving the problem, does not occur in the transcript in regards to the actual solution for the logic exercise. However, the participants are problem-solving the best way to externalize and organize their thought process in the workspace. Different aspects of their solutions&#39; organizations are discussed in terms of their effectiveness in helping to ease their cognitive workload. At first, person B points out that person A &quot;had 2 different systems going on&quot; (line 3), and person A agrees, saying &quot;it was too much&quot; (line 4). So, the organization problem is redefined as using too many systems, which would require an easy solution of using only one system to improve organization. The problem is again redefined starting at line 7, where person B states &quot;i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order / so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused.&quot; This redefinition now places emphasis on the order of information in the solution&#39;s organization, and the solution is derived from the issue itself: fixing the order of Mr. Red and Mr. Yellow would have improved the overall&nbsp;organization.</p>\r\n','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>A. Transcript</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 A: lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 A: -_____-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 B: haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 A: but it was too much lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 A: with the ( ) and the ?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 A: then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 A: yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 B: oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 A: so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 A: i put the mr.&#39;s out of order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 B: i found the count really useful as well</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 B: yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilites put in parentheses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 A: the count is also useful</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 A: it was a lot easier when its organized</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 A: mine was all over the place</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 A: it helped</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 A: mine</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 A: yours was more organized than me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 B: thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>B.&nbsp;Analyze the chat in your transcript in terms of grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; copresence.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Grounding</u>: Grounding occurs throughout this conversation--as new knowledge and opinions&nbsp;are introduced&nbsp;by&nbsp;each participant, the other participant must demonstrate that they understand and accept this contribution, establishing it as common knowledge. For example, at line 11, person B says &quot;i found the count really useful as well,&quot; to which person A responds in line 13 saying &quot;the count is also useful.&quot; Person B introduces their opinion, aiming to establish it as common knowledge. Person A not only recognizes this piece of information, but agrees with it, confirming the information&#39;s shift into their common knowledge base.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Adjacency Pairs</u>: Adjacency pairs also occurred frequently in this transcript. At line 18, person A compliments person B by saying that &quot;yours was more organized than me,&quot; in reference to their solutions for the problem. Person B responds in line 19 by saying thank you. This example of a compliment given by one participant and ensuing acceptance&nbsp;by the other would be identified&nbsp;as an adjacency pair. Another example of an adjacency pair occurred at line 7, when person A states &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order,&quot; and person B responds by asking for clarification in line 8: &quot;you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot; These paired, turn-taken utterances exemplify adjacency pairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Contribution and Acceptance Phases</u>: Contributions are constantly made by the participants to convey their thoughts (i.e. &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; in line 3),&nbsp;which their partner must attempt to register and accept, similar to grounding. This particular instance of the contribution phase was then followed by the acceptance phase of their partner replying &quot;but it was too much lol / with the ( ) and the ?&quot; on line 4 and 5. Another example of this occurs at line 18, when person A says &quot;yours was more organized than me.&quot; This contribution was registered by person B and accepted, with their response being &quot;thank you! I was pretty confident in what I arrived at!&quot; (line 19).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Repairs</u>: In lines 7-10, the participants discuss the order of the user&#39;s answers. When person A first says &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&quot; in line 7, person B requests clarification of this statement&#39;s meaning by asking &quot;you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot; in line 8. A repair must then be made by person A to reaffirm the meaning of their statement, and then is done in line 10 when they say &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>&quot;Virtual&quot; Copresence</u>: As demonstrated in their&nbsp;conversation,&nbsp;both participants are present in discussion, making them copresent despite the potential existence of physical distance. This was emphasized by the system&#39;s design of Same Time Different Place partnering. A major contributor to this sense of virtual copresence would be the bounds of the virtual environment. The environment is self-contained: they have easy access to all that they need on this one page of the online platform. Had there been the necessity to browse the web, or access a different application during their problem-solving or discussion, the two participants would certainly not be as present. For example, references are constantly made to the structure of the user&#39;s solution (lines 3-19).&nbsp;Had the&nbsp;solution been located anywhere else besides the same page as the chat panel, the conversation would be more disconnected and the participants less present. Another aspect of the virtual copresence is the fact that whichever chat panel that the directing user selects is the panel that their partner is brought to. This essentially places the two partners into the same arena, and brings with them their attention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">C.&nbsp;Do an analysis of your transcript in terms of the access framework.&nbsp;Is there a distribution of executive function? Explain.â€‹</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. <u>Knowledge</u> (kinds of): The knowledge of each user for the logic exercise&nbsp;was formatted in their left-hand workspace to their own liking. This way of externalizing internal knowledge added to the user&#39;s surround, especially when it came time to&nbsp;share their work&nbsp;with their partner. Without this externalization, it would be unclear to the other participant what the user&#39;s solution was, and how they reached this solution. In conversation, the discussion of their&nbsp;knowledge that went into their solutions never occurred. Instead, the participants decided to focus on the style and organization of their external representations of knowledge, which I found very interesting. This topic was at the forefront in line&nbsp;3 through line 19, but some specific examples of this include &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; (Person B, line 3), &quot;then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&quot; (Person A, line 6), &quot;yours was more organized than me&quot; (Person A, line 18).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. <u>Representation</u> (how): Representations of the user&#39;s thought process and solution are housed in the left-hand panel. What&#39;s interesting about this problem is that there isn&#39;t a &quot;right&quot; way to go about setting this up. For a Java exercise, representations are clearly made and understood by others (who share knowlege of the programming language), and comments can be placed throughout to explain the mental representation that went into the virtualized one. However, with a logic exercise, the users don&#39;t get to see the full thought process and progress towards a solution, which likely drove the participants to discuss their methods more in-depth (lines 3-19), and explain their representational systems to one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. <u>Retrieval</u> (can it find it and how effectively): Because the user&#39;s solution is placed directly next to the conversation panel, it is easy for the participants to refer back to the work and retrieve pieces of information from it to be discussed. However, as discussed in the Representation section, much discussion was centered around the structure of one&#39;s solution and thought process represented on-screen. At line 12, person B notes the organization of person A&#39;s work, and how it is similarly organized to their own. Their following discussion of what helped make solving the problem, and now reading each other&#39;s solutions, more useful demonstrated how effectively they could retrieve information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. <u>Construction</u> (assemble pieces of knowledge into new knowledge structures): This characteristic appeared in the user&#39;s solution--the user had to consider the given knowledge about the logic problem, and solve the problem by assembling new knowledge structures that could then be shared with their partner. In the conversation itself, little construction is made, and little discussion of the actual content of their constructions were discussed (what was the right answer?). Instead, the formatting of their constructions dominated the conversation, as stated previously (line 3-19).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After reading the Grey Crocodile&#39;s analysis, my understanding of the distribution of executive function was improved. The surround for the users did not allow for arrangement to the user&#39;s preferences. With this inherent and unmovable structure, users lack control, giving the distribution of executive function to the system and not the user. According to the Grey Crocodile, &quot;if the site has too much executive function over interactions, it could cause confusion and frustration&quot; (Grey Crocodile, HW 2 Draft 1).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">D.&nbsp;ii. Explain your transcript from the perspective of situated activity. What is the the context and arena while the participants did the java exercise? Does the transcript provide an example of the dialectic relation between context and setting? Are there elements of the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing?</span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because activity and setting are dialectically constituted, the setting is generated out of the activity and, at the same time, generates the activity. This is the basis of the situated activity perspective. The arena is defined as&nbsp;encompassing&nbsp;the individual, providing a higher-order institutional framework within which setting is constituted. So, for this activity, the arena for the participants would be the online platform. Much like the aisles of the grocery store, each potential exercise that a student could be assigned to exist within the platform and as a part of the arena, but because they are not relevant to the user, they are not a part of the user&#39;s setting. The user&#39;s personal setting is their assigned problem, their solution space, their partner&#39;s solution space, and the area for designed dialogue. This setting not only is generated out of the logic exercise problem, but also generates the activities that occur in it (writing down solutions, looking over partner&#39;s solution, conversing with partner about solutions).&nbsp;Together, the arena and personal&nbsp;setting make up the context of the activity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Problem solving through gap closing, or looping between redefining and solving the problem, does not occur in the transcript in regards to the actual solution for the logic exercise. However, the participants are problem-solving the optimal way to externalize and organize their thought process in the workspace. Different aspects of their solutions&#39; organizations are discussed in terms of their effectiveness in helping to ease their cognitive workload. At first, person B points out that person A &quot;had 2 different systems going on&quot; (line 3), and person A agrees, saying &quot;it was too much&quot; (line 4). So, the organization problem is redefined as using too many systems, which would require an easy solution of using only one system to improve organization. The problem is again redefined starting at line 7, where person B states &quot;i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order / so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused.&quot; This redefinition now places emphasis on the order of information in the solution&#39;s organization, and the solution is derived from the issue itself: fixing the order of Mr. Red and Mr. Yellow would have improved the overall&nbsp;organization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Part 3 - Reflect on the impact of part 2 of this assignment on your revisions to the first draft of the assignment. What did you learn by reviewing the analysis work of other members of your team? Did it change your level of confidence in your own work?</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:12px;\">After reading my teammates&#39; posts and engaging in discussion with them, I learned a significant amount that I would not have otherwise reached on my own. (Not only did I learn more about how the zone of proximal development was reached by participants in The Indigo Eagle&#39;s analysis, but I can apply the concept to my own learning stretch--very cool!) </span>The area I felt most uncertain about in Part 1 was the distribution of executive function and how it applied to the given transcript. The Grey Crocodile helped me substantially in understanding this concept. Their discussion of the user not having control over the arrangement of the surround giving executive function to the system really helped me to understand the concept and its application to my own transcript. I had not thought of how much control of the workspace lies in the system itself, and how this may affect user performance and interdependent collaboration. Grey Crocodile also highlighted how the user should rightfully have greater executive function over the system, as without this, the user may become easily confused and/or agitated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, I found an element of Grey Crocodile&#39;s transcript and analysis very interesting. It was found that the participants were not fully informed of the system&#39;s functions, and this caused a disruption in their workflow and their overall collaboration. I thought this was a very important finding with our final projects coming up. Informing users of the platform of its proper usage, being explicit, etc. is very important if we want to see an undisturbed flow of collaboration. This implication is so important for us both as designers and analysts of systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I did not choose the Joint Problem Space analysis for Part D, so it was quite informative to read The Indigo Eagle&#39;s analysis through this framework. I learned that a Joint Problem Space is allowed by the chat section of the platform, as Eagle pointed out. Though the two student worked first on their own, they were able to jointly problem solve, share and gain knowledge, and discuss in the given chat panel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I remained confident in most of my analysis after receiving positive feedback from my peers. I especially was made happy to see that one of my teammates had a clarified understanding of one of the frameworks after reading my analysis.</p>\r\n',8,2,6,0,1,'2016-03-08 18:15:55','2016-03-15 01:42:50'),(35,'','<p><u>Part A:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is the transcript I was assigned. Student B is the commenter, and Student A is the writer of the code sample.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B</strong>: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: and then count down as you come across those numbers<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: so like abcc would be [ 1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip; ]<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: oh that&rsquo;s smart<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: with each being a letter<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: and put in numbers for each location<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: you could have made an array size 32<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: idk how well it would work<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: You could have used a map maybe<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: but that accounts for the &ldquo;what if they have the same letters and the same length but different repeated letters&rdquo; question<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: that&rsquo;s smart<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: yeah exactly. Then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?<br />\r\n<strong>B</strong>: How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?<br />\r\n<strong>A</strong>: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part B:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the snippet of the transcript below, the Student A (the writer of the code) and Student B (the commenter) contribute new ideas to the conversation, thus increasing the common ground between them. They also use acceptance phrases to indicate their understanding of the other&rsquo;s new ideas, and make repairs when there appears to be a misunderstanding.&nbsp;The interaction also has several adjacency pairs. They are mainly of types question-answer, apology-acceptance/rejection, thanks-acceptance/rejection, and assessment-agreement/disagreement, mainly because this is not a &ldquo;traditional&rdquo; conversation and is very focused on a set problem space.&nbsp;I&rsquo;ve made more detailed comments about the interaction underneath the corresponding section:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring<br />\r\nB: and then count down as you come across those numbers</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student B makes a contribution right at the start by suggesting that Student A could use an array where each index corresponds to a letter and the contents are the amount of each letter that appear.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A communicates their understanding of Student B&rsquo;s proposition, and contributes another thought to the conversation &ndash; the issue of efficiency. This comment and the one above it are also a assessment/agreement adjacency pair, because Student B gives an idea and Student A agrees that it is a good one.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: so like abcc would be [ 1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip; ]</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student B, sensing that their initial explanation wasn&rsquo;t clear and thus attempting to repair any potential misunderstanding, shows that the array would hold numbers that correspond to a letter by giving an example of how it would work. They are also contributing to the common ground of the conversation by explaining what they meant.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: oh that&rsquo;s smart</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A now understands what data structure Student B was talking about, and says an acceptance phrase &ldquo;oh&rdquo; to indicate that they understand.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: with each being a letter<br />\r\nB: and put in numbers for each location<br />\r\nB: you could have made an array size 32</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student B continues to contribute to the common ground of the conversation by explicitly detailing how they would implement their data structure.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A responds to B with another acceptance phrase &ldquo;yeah that would have been good&rdquo;. They also further indicate their understanding by rephrasing and summarizing what Student B was saying.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The two students are not actually able to physically point at the parts of code that they are looking at, so they are not physically co-present. However, Student B&nbsp;correctly recognized that the comments on the side line up with the line numbers in the code, and left comments that correspond to a section of the code at the same line number. Because the two students are still capable of indicating which sections of the code they are looking at, they are virtually co-present.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part C:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each of the four access characteristics are present in this interaction. If we view the collaborative learning tool as the&nbsp;<em>plus</em>&nbsp;part of Person Plus, then the student has access to all the insights of the person they are collaborating with, and any insights they make while communicating through the platform are documented in the comments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation is present because the code Student A wrote is represented as a code sample on the screen&nbsp;and the conversation is represented as a physical, text conversation, as opposed to Student A verbally Student B about how their code works on a high level, and then the two having a verbal conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge is present because the student has access to the other student&#39;s knowledge, as well as any information on the internet they look up. In this transcript, an example of this is when Student B says &quot;oh right charAt is a thing!&quot;. The knowledge was given to them by the collaborative learning tool because they saw that Person A used charAt and it jogged their memory. In addition to that, the insight of &quot;oh charAt is a thing!&quot; is solidified in the collaborative learning tool and capable of being retreived.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retreival is present through the organization of the website. If one of the students wishes to look back at their conversation, they would just have to click on the exercise, and read the code and comments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction occurs when Student A talks to Student B about their code, Student B contributes an insight that Student A had not thought about, and Student A responds with a follow-up question or proposal based on that insight. In the case of this transcript, Student B gives a suggestion for implementing a 32-indexed array where the value of each index corresponds to the number of letters of that type. Student A thinks about their proposal, decides it is not efficient enough, and then proposes to do it with one pass through the array instead. Neither Student A nor Student B would not have gotten to the better, more efficient solution had it not been for the other.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Distribution of executive function occurs when Student B concedes to Student A&#39;s ideas about the code, because they were the one to implement the code sample and Student A has a slight advantage in familiarity with their own code. I don&#39;t really think this happens that often or that obviously, but it seems like Student B will accept Student A&#39;s suggestions for making the code more efficient and incorporate that view into their own ideas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part D:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A joint problem space is a &ldquo;shared knowledge structure that supports problem solving by integrating goals, descriptions of the current problem, awareness of problem solving activities, and associations that relate goals, features of the current problem state, and available actions&rdquo;. The online coding tool provides a joint problem space because the two students are problem solving with the goal of:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Writing code to check whether two words are an anagram</li>\r\n	<li>Improving Student A&#39;s code</li>\r\n	<li>Having a discussion about the differences between Student A and B&#39;s code</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem space also has a description of the current problem by detailing exactly what the students are supposed to do, and only making certain actions available at a time (the students cannot comment on code before it is written, and they cannot change their code after they have started commenting).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not much work is done to maintain the infrastructure in terms of staying on topic&nbsp;while the students are working together, as both are pretty on-topic and goal-oriented in their discussion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both students maintain the infrastructure in terms of communicating clearly and repairing 