ray where the value of each index corresponds to the number of letters of that type. Student A thinks about their proposal, decides it is not efficient enough, and then proposes to do it with one pass through the array instead. Neither Student A nor Student B would not have gotten to the better, more efficient solution had it not been for the other.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Distribution of executive function occurs when Student B concedes to Student A&#39;s ideas about the code, because they were the one to implement the code sample and Student A has a slight advantage in familiarity with their own code. I don&#39;t really think this happens that often or that obviously, but it seems like Student B will accept Student A&#39;s suggestions for making the code more efficient and incorporate that view into their own ideas. Their interaction could also be viewed as teaching - Student A teaches Student B about their own code. I&#39;m not sure whether teaching describes the interaction more than distribution of executive function ... I just think neither terms are particularly correct. Both students have gone through the same assignment, so I don&#39;t particularly think one student is teaching the other, but at the same time, their interactions do tend to be more equal than a distribution of executive function explanation would imply.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Part D:</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A joint problem space is a &ldquo;shared knowledge structure that supports problem solving by integrating goals, descriptions of the current problem, awareness of problem solving activities, and associations that relate goals, features of the current problem state, and available actions&rdquo;. The online coding tool provides a joint problem space because the two students are problem solving with the goal of:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Writing code to check whether two words are an anagram</li>\r\n	<li>Improving Student A&#39;s code</li>\r\n	<li>Having a discussion about the differences between Student A and B&#39;s code</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem space also has a description of the current problem by detailing exactly what the students are supposed to do, and only making certain actions available at a time (the students cannot comment on code before it is written, and they cannot change their code after they have started commenting).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not much work is done to maintain the infrastructure in terms of staying on topic&nbsp;while the students are working together, as both are pretty on-topic and goal-oriented in their discussion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both students maintain the infrastructure in terms of communicating clearly and repairing any misunderstandings.&nbsp;The quote, &quot;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration&quot; applies because:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Students have a way to introduce and accept knowledge into the JPS - making comments and replying to each other&#39;s comments. The online collaborative tool does not make it difficult to communicate.</li>\r\n	<li>Students have a way to monitor on-going activity for miscommunications - reading each other&#39;s comments. As in any conversation, the students scan the conversation for any possible misunderstandings.</li>\r\n	<li>Students have a way to repair divergences by replying to each other with clarification.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.6;\">These principles are all evident in the section of the transcript below. Like earlier, I made comments underneath the relevant section.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A</strong>: <strong>yup! I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A introduces new knowledge into the JPS by saying how they would have solved the problem. They are able to add this new information by commenting to something Student B said.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student B was monitoring the conversation for miscommunications, and realized that there may be a misunderstanding, so they ask a question for clarification.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah exactly. Then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time<br />\r\nA: Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A repairs the confusion by giving clarification.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?<br />\r\nB: How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Like earlier, Student B asks a question for clarification.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Like earlier, Student A clarifies what they meant, and thus repairs the common ground.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Reflection</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>After reading the comments of my teammates and viewing their analyses, I realized there were some parts of my analysis that were unclear. Not unpredictably, they were the parts of the analysis that I myself was a little bit unsure about, and didn&#39;t explain correctly. I tried to go into more depth when explaining the parts that were unclear - most of them were in Part C. From reading my teammate&#39;s analyses, I realized that there are some parts I didn&#39;t adequately explain, and that there are always unique ways of looking at transcripts. I also felt good about my organization of the analysis (which was something I was concerned was unclear)&nbsp;because I saw that some of my teammates had organized theirs similarly.</p>\r\n',26,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-08 21:25:33','2016-03-15 02:34:21'),(36,'Assignment 2','<p align=\"left\">a. <strong>Copy of transcript</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>B&#39;s comments: Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks if the two strings are anagram to each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: yeah, that&#39;s true, if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: sorry word1 and word2 reversed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: very good and clever!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just check that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">b. <strong>grounding</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In this transcript, person A and person B already have an initial common ground that the goal for both of them is to analyze and discuss the code written for the computer science program about whether two words are anagrams. In the comments, B writes: &quot; I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal? &quot; When B states his assumption about how this program works, he wants to contribute his assumption to the conversation with person A. This is a presentation phase, as he presents his assumption for A to consider. Then A relies &quot;yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;, and this reply is in an acceptance phase. Person A accepts the assumption made by B through giving evidence, which is a reply, that he believes he understands what B means. A also believes that through the reply, he gives the evidence that B will understand. Then the contribution initiated by person B is now grounded and become part of their common ground, since they mutually believe that the partners have understood what B meant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When B writes his assumption about how the program works, he states it in a form of asking for agreement from A. This is a first pair part of the adjacency pairs. Given this first pair as asking for agreement, it is relevant and expectable for A to show his agreement or disagreement to B. And the reply that person A makes shows his agreement. Thus, this turn of contribution is organized in adjacency pairs, since the second pair part is conditionally relevant in this case. When B writes &quot;sorry word1 and word2 reversed&quot;, he is referring to his previous contribution indicating word1 is bbbb and word2 is abba. Through this process, B initiates a repair of the problem that they ran into in accepting it. Then both of them will revise their previously grounded common ground and change it from that word1 is bbbb and word2 is abba to that word1 is abba and word2 is bbbb. In this script, most of the time person A and person B are co-present since they are simultaneously chatting with each other online. Also, they are both paying attention to the code solving the anagrams problem, and they are both rational. Their chat can be initiated due to such co-presence, since they have the common ground that they know they are chatting with one student in class through Internet, and their goal is to discuss the code about solving the anagrams problem. However, their co-presence is partially lost during some specific time when both A and B are not sure whether the other one was the same person he was talking before. This may happen because they are chatting through Internet instead of face-to-face. When the Internet is disconnected or something wrong happens with the system through which they are chatting, they will lose their co-presence for some time. Thus, A and B need to check whether the other one was the same person before to rebuild their co-presence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">c. <strong>access framework</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The four access characteristics of relevant knowledge are knowledge, representation, retrieval and construction. This transcript shows all of these access characteristics and reflects person A and person B&#39;s thinking and learning process. &nbsp;&nbsp; First, both A and B show that they have some knowledge about programming in Java. When B writes &quot; word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2&quot;, he shows his knowledge the string.contains() method in Java can check if a string contains a given substring. Person A also shows his knowledge about how a for-loop method works in Java when he says; &quot; the for-loop just runs through each letter of word1&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Second, the knowledge of programming in java is represented through java codes and method names. The java codes written by A, which include methods, variable names, class names, etc. absolutely shows how java programming is represented. The knowledge is also represented in their dialogue, when B refer to word2.contains(), which is the way in which people represent a string contains a character or another string in Java.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Third, the construction of knowledge about java programming is also reflected in this transcript. B shows his assumption about how A&#39;s program work, and then A explains her logic as &quot;for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just check that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are&quot;. Through this process, they assemble their pieces of knowledge about java programming into new knowledge structure about how anagram problem can be solved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; There are few direct or obvious evidences that show the retrieval of information in this transcript, but they may retrieve information during their process of chatting without actually writing down how they retrieve in the transcript. It&#39;s likely for A who wants to write a method to check whether a string contains a character or a substring to look up the API about string when he forgets which method of string does this function. It&#39;s also likely for B who is looking at A&#39;s code and do not understand what a specific method in A&#39;s code means to look up the API for java and retrieve the related information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The transcript also includes a distribution of executive function. Person B writes: &quot;actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?&quot; Here, B is a learner and he cedes executive function to the surround as he doubts whether the program works and does not really understand how the program works. Then A replies to B and explaining to B the logic behind the program, and helps B to understand the program that B could not understand by himself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">d. <strong>joint problem space</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, there is a joint problem space between person A and person B. First, both of them have shared knowledge about how to programming in Java, and they both know that their goal is to analyze how the codes that deal with the anagram problem works. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B says &quot; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks if the two strings are anagram to each other&quot;, and then A replies &quot;yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;. The quote in Rosechell &amp; Teasley that &quot;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS&quot; is relevant here. In this process, both A and B are introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS, as they both agree on generally what the program should do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, person B describes the current problem state by saying &quot; I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?&quot; Here, common understanding for how word2.contains() work is not certain, since B is not very sure about whether his assumption is right or not. A replies to B&#39;s problem by saying &quot;that&#39;s true&quot;, so the current problem for them is solved and they move to another problem state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new current problem state is described when B says &quot; they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs&quot;. Here, the common understanding is again not certain, as B doubts whether the program works through giving an example that two strings are not anagram. Then A replies &quot;if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order&quot;. Such interaction between person A and B can be related to the quote &quot;monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning&quot;. Here, there are divergences in meaning between A and B. B thinks that when the two words are in different order and have different number of a same character, then they are not anagrams. However, A thinks that this will not be the case, and argues that they will be anagrams even though they are in a different order. What B means here is that two words in different orders but also having different characters, but what A understands is that two words having same characters. Thus, there is a divergence in meaning between A and B, and this divergence impedes the progress of the collaboration since they are now not working on the same problem here.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Then B says &quot; Sorry word1 and word2 reversed. Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?&quot; Person B realizes that there are divergences in meaning between them, so he tries to &quot; repair divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration&quot;. He repairs the divergences through fixing the mistakes he made in his previous sentences, and gives an example that illustrates his idea better. This time, person A understands what B means and gives his reply correctly by indirectly pointing out B&#39;s misunderstanding about the codes, and explains to him about how the codes actually work. Even though there is no obvious evidence that shows they reach a goal state, but they will finally reach it after they discuss the problem for more time.</p>','<p align=\"left\"><u>a. <strong>Copy of transcript</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>B&#39;s comments: Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks if the two strings are anagram to each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: right, but they may not be anagrams because if word1 is bbbb and word2 is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word2 will contain b for all bs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: yeah, that&#39;s true, if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: sorry word1 and word2 reversed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B: very good and clever!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A: Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just check that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>b. <strong>grounding, </strong><strong>adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; co-presence</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, person A and person B already have an initial common ground, which is that the goal for both of them is to analyze and discuss the code written for the computer science program about whether two words are anagrams. During their process of conversation, A and B make contributions through presenting their new ideas, and grounding their contributions to their common ground:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person B wants to make a contribution to their common ground through stating his assumption/understanding about how this program may work.</li>\r\n	<li>This is a presentation phase: person B is presenting his assumption for A to consider.</li>\r\n	<li>It&#39;s interesting that B&#39;s comment ends up with a question mark. It indicates that B is not sure about the correctness of his assumption and is waiting for A&#39;s reply to tell him whether his assumption is right or not. Once A makes a proper reply to his question, he will believe that A understands what he is saying.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person A understands what B is talking about and agrees with his assumption saying &quot;yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;.</li>\r\n	<li>This is an acceptance phase: person A is accepting B&#39;s assumption through giving evidence, which is a reply, that he understands what B means.</li>\r\n	<li>This reply is also the evidence that once person A sends to B, person B will realize that A understands what he is saying.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Then, B makes a contribution about how this program may work. This contribution is grounded to A and B&#39;s common ground since they both understand and agree with it and believe that their partners agree with it as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given the same example, we can see how adjacency pairs work in the transcript as well:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person B states his assumption about how the program may work in the form asking for agreement from A.</li>\r\n	<li>This is a first pair part of the adjacency pairs. Given this first pair as asking for agreement, it is relevant and expectable for A to show his agreement or disagreement to B.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person A shows his agreement with B&#39;s assumption.</li>\r\n	<li>This is the second part of the adjacency pairs, and it is conditionally relevant to the first part.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In the transcript, they also initiate repairs to their words when misunderstanding exists:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: right, but they may not be anagrams because if word1 is bbbb and word2 is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word2 will contain b for all bs.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah, that&#39;s true, if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person A seems not to understand what B means here. Even though he says: &quot;yeah, that&#39;s true&quot;, A&#39;s idea is not consistent with what B is saying. Thus, there is a problem of misunderstanding between them.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: sorry word1 and word2 reversed</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>With a problem of misunderstanding, B initiates a repair of his previous statement.</li>\r\n	<li>Then, word1 is changed from bbbb to abba, and word2 is changed from abba to bbbb. And both of them will make this revise to their previously grounded common ground.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In the script, person A and B are virtually co-present for most of the time since they are simultaneously chatting with each other online. It is also because that they are also both paying attention to the code solving the anagrams problem, and both rational. Their chat can be initiated due to such co-presence, since they have the common ground that they are chatting with one student in class through Internet, and their goal is to discuss the code about solving the anagrams problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, their virtual co-presence is partially lost during some specific time period:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Both person A and B do not sure whether their partner is the same one before.</li>\r\n	<li>This may happen because the co-presence they have is &quot;virtual&quot; instead of &quot;actual&quot;, as they are chatting through Internet instead of face-to-face. When the Internet is disconnected or something wrong happens with the platform, they will lose their virtual co-presence for some time.</li>\r\n	<li>Thus, A and B need to check whether their partner is the same one before in order to rebuild their co-presence.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\"><u>c. <strong>access framework</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The four access characteristics of relevant knowledge are knowledge, representation, retrieval and construction. This transcript shows all of these access characteristics and reflects person A and person B&#39;s thinking and learning process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The transcript shows that both people have some knowledge about programming in Java:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person B has some knowledge about string.contains() method, which can check if a string contains a given substring.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just check that if that index of word1 is in word2.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Person A has some knowledge about the for-loop method in Java, which can check each letter of a word.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The knowledge of programming in java is represented through java codes and method names. The java codes written by A, which include methods, variable names, class names, etc. absolutely shows how java programming is represented. The knowledge is also represented in their conversation, when B refer to word2.contains(), which is the way in which people represent a string contains a character or another string in Java.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Here, the surround that provides short-term and long-term memory support is the computer. It enables them to use methods and data structures in Java to solve the anagram problem. The computer also enables people to Google search knowledge that they are temporarily forgot to help solving the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retrieval</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The two people can retrieve information about the java code for the problem through directly looking up the left part of the platform. And they can retrieve information of their previous conversation through moving scrollbar position. It&#39;s also likely for them to look up the API for Java when they forget how a specific Java method works.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The transcript also includes a distribution of executive function:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>B is a learner and he cedes executive function to the surround, as he doubts whether the program works and does not really understand how the program works.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just check that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are. </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A replies and explains the logic behind the program to B, helping B to understand the program that B could not understand by himself.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p align=\"left\"><u>d. <strong>joint problem space</strong></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this transcript, there is a joint problem space between the two people, as they have shared knowledge structure that supports problem-solving activity:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Their integrated goal is to analyze the A&#39;s Java codes to determine how it works for the anagram problem.</li>\r\n	<li>Descriptions of the current problem state are integrated since they both work on the same specific problem until it is solved and then they move on to the next problem.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>They have integrated awareness of problem solving activities, as they are both know that they are analyzing the code in order to figure out how it solve the anagram problem.</li>\r\n	<li>Associations that relate goals, features of the current problem state, and available actions are integrated: each step they go to or each specific question they ask is related with their goal.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to maintain the infrastructure, the students need to introduce and accept knowledge into the JPS, monitor on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning, and repair divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To quote Roschelle &amp; Teasley: &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration.&quot; This quote is reflected in the transcript:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks if the two strings are anagram to each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in word2 and if not says strings are not equal? </strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The current problem state is described. Common understanding for how word2.contains() work is not certain, since B is not very sure about whether his assumption is right or not.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A agrees with B&#39;s assumption, so the current problem for them is solved and they move to another problem state.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Here, the two students are introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS: student B introduces his assumption of how the program may work and student A accept B&#39;s assumption. They have the way to do this since they can comment and reply to one another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The new current problem state is described. The common understanding is again not certain, as student B doubts whether the program works and gives an example to illustrate his idea.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A: if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student A does not show his agreement here. This reply seems not relevant to B&#39;s idea, since A probably does not understand B&#39;s words correctly.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a divergence in meaning here. B thinks that when the two words are in different order and have different number of a same character, then they are not anagrams. However, A thinks that this will not be the case, and argues that they will be anagrams even though they are in a different order. What B means here is that two words in different orders but also having different characters. But what A understands is that two words have same characters. This divergence impedes the progress of the collaboration since they are now not working on the same problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two students will be aware of the divergence, when their partner does not give them a response as they expected. Thus, they have a way of &quot;monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>B: Sorry word1 and word2 reversed. Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Student B realizes that there are divergences in meaning between them, and he tries to repair the divergences.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Student B has a way of &quot;repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration&quot; through fixing the mistakes he made in his previous sentences, and gives an example that illustrates his idea better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This time, person A understands what B means and gives his reply correctly by indirectly pointing out B&#39;s misunderstanding about the codes, and explains to him about how the codes actually work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Reflections</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through reading and commenting on my teammates&#39; drafts, I realized that the structure of my first draft is not well organized. Examples from the transcript are difficult to refer since they are all in quotes and are mixed with my analysis. Thus, for my second draft, I separate my examples from my analysis and then do analysis directly below it. The comment I received from my teammate also provide me with new perspectives about the &quot;virtual&quot; and &quot;actual&quot; co-presence, so I apply it to my second draft as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides the structure of the draft is not good, I also realized that I previously misunderstood the meaning of the concept &quot;construction&quot;. Through reading others&#39; analysis, I realized that that surround can be the computer and I revised my part about &quot;construction&quot;. Reading others&#39; analysis also makes me realize that my analysis is not very specific and is not enough. Even though I did use&nbsp;examples to illustrate the terms, I did not explain why the term applies to the example very detailedly. Reading others&#39; drafts does change my level of confidence about my own work, and I think my drafts may still have a lot to improve.</p>\r\n',17,2,8,0,1,'2016-03-08 23:39:46','2016-03-15 02:33:05'),(37,'Communication and Problem Solving','<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Transcript</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1:&nbsp;Oh right charAt is a thing!&nbsp; I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 W:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 G:&nbsp; I like that.&nbsp; That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 W:&nbsp; so like abcc would be {1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip;}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 G:&nbsp; oh that&rsquo;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 W:&nbsp; with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 W:&nbsp; and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 W:&nbsp; you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 G:&nbsp; yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 W:&nbsp; idk how well it would work</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 W:&nbsp; You could have used a map maybe</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 W:&nbsp; but that accounts for the &ldquo;what if they have the same letters and same length but different repeated letters&rdquo; question</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 G:&nbsp; but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 W:&nbsp; that&rsquo;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 G:&nbsp; yup!&nbsp; I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 W:&nbsp; ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 G:&nbsp; yeah exactly. Then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 G:&nbsp; Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 W:&nbsp; like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 W:&nbsp; How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 G:&nbsp; I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Part B: &nbsp;Contributions</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The transcript has two students (W for white text box and G for green text box) explore various approaches to determine anagrams passed into a Java program.&nbsp; In order to have an understanding, they must develop common ground, and they do so via adjacency pairs.&nbsp; Lines 1 through 14 contain mostly W explaining their thought processes as one contribution.&nbsp; G interrupts at certain points to accept W&rsquo;s contributions.&nbsp; Lines 3 and 5 are acknowledgements of W&rsquo;s actions (&ldquo;I like that&hellip;&rdquo;, &ldquo;oh that&rsquo;s smart.&rdquo;) in order to maintain copresence within a virtual space, as it is the least effort evidence of understanding because continued attention cannot be assumed through a computer screen and virtual interaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>G&rsquo;s interruptions do not act as contributions, as they are not accepted by W explicitly, and presumably G attempts to contribute more substance to the common ground in line 9, when G acknowledges (&ldquo;yeah that would have been good.), and demonstrates understanding via paraphrase (&ldquo;like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for a letter&rdquo;).&nbsp; This adjacency pair closes with W&rsquo;s acceptance on line 11, by elaborating on the possibility of using one particular data structure (&ldquo;You could have used a map maybe&rdquo;).&nbsp; These acceptances via demonstration also serve to reinforce the copresence of both participants, as they serve to give evidence of rationality, that is, that both are drawing the same conclusions, and that they have equivalent knowledge of Java.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On line 15, G explains their plan to solve the anagram problem with an array, and W makes a quick repair and asks for clarification of G&rsquo;s meaning (&ldquo;and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?&rdquo;).&nbsp; W makes similar repairs in lines 19 and 20, with only the first one being accepted with an answer (&ldquo;I wanted to use substrings to replace&hellip;&rdquo;).&nbsp; The transcript ends before the second question (&ldquo;How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?) is answered.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Part C: &nbsp;Person-Plus</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This platform is interesting to analyze in terms of distributed cognition, as it is likely that it gave the programmer less than they would have under different circumstances (e. g., inability to look up Java API, sparse syntax highlighting, etc.).&nbsp; With this lack of physical support, the comments and chatting takes on a new importance as the only other member in this cognitive system, that is to say, they are each other&rsquo;s only resource in the problem-solving task and the surround is created through social support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Line 1 of the transcript (I am unsure of who wrote it, so it is unlabeled) begins with this sharing of information via the written code as a representation of knowledge.&nbsp; The writer is reminded through the code used that &ldquo;charAt is a thing!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because of this lack of remembrance, the writer was forced to use substrings as an alternative, and thus, their plan is dependent on outside resources, that is to say, that their executive function is distributed in their environment.&nbsp; This altering of plans to satisfy forgotten functions is repeated again in line 21 (&ldquo;I wanted to use substrings&hellip; but I couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations.&rdquo;).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Part D: &nbsp;Situated Activity</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both participants begin their problem solving task with the same goal and within the same arena, in this case the goal is to detect anagrams and the arena is the platform.&nbsp; Despite the same starting place within the problem, they redefined the problem of detecting anagrams using the tools they had at their disposal.&nbsp; For example, W uses a &ldquo;data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter&rdquo; (line 9).&nbsp; After redefining the problem to be represented in that way, the setting is transformed (due to its dialectical constitution) to how best apply that data structure to detect anagrams as implied in line 13:&nbsp; &ldquo;I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops&hellip;&rdquo; The activity changes with the setting, in this case deciding how efficient this data structure is, and the setting then changes with the activity again as G offers up a different suggestion of using substrings to solve the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Iteratively reforming the problem, as both W and G have just done, constitutes gap-closing.&nbsp; This example is interesting as a joint problem space, as both parties come at the problem from different perspectives and so gap-closing must happen with both parties redefining the other&rsquo;s representation rather than an individual facing a problem alone.&nbsp; This redefinition of the other&rsquo;s representation occurs on lines 9 (G understanding W&rsquo;s representation) and 19-20 (W understanding G&rsquo;s representation).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given sufficient time, it&rsquo;s probable to assume that the two representations/definitions of the problem would converge as the two participants collaboratively discover the best solution.&nbsp; This begins to occur through the critiques of the other&rsquo;s proposed solution (lines 13 and 20) before the transcript ends.</p>\r\n','<p><strong>Transcript</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 Reader: Oh right charAt is a thing!&nbsp; I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 Writer:&nbsp; I wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string to avoid creating another data structure, but I couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 R:&nbsp; How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 R:&nbsp; like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 W:&nbsp; Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 W:&nbsp; yeah exactly. Then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 R:&nbsp; ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 W:&nbsp; yup!&nbsp; I was going to try to do something similar with the array, changing each value to null as I found it</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 R:&nbsp; that&rsquo;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 W:&nbsp; but I think that would have caused a lot of extra loops versus doing it with a substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 R:&nbsp; but that accounts for the &ldquo;what if they have the same letters and same length but different repeated letters&rdquo; question</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 R:&nbsp; You could have used a map maybe</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 R:&nbsp; idk how well it would work&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 W:&nbsp; yeah that would have been good. like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 R:&nbsp; you could have made an array size 32</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 R:&nbsp; and put in numbers for each location</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 R:&nbsp; with each being a letter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 W:&nbsp; oh that&rsquo;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 R:&nbsp; so like abcc would be {1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip;}</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 W:&nbsp; I like that.&nbsp; That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 R:&nbsp; and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part B: &nbsp;Contributions</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The transcript consists of two students exploring various approaches to detect anagrams passed into a Java program.&nbsp; In order to have a successful conversation, they must have mutual understanding and develop common ground, which occurs through the use of adjacency pairs.&nbsp; The entire transcript is filled with small acknowledgements of acceptance (&ldquo;I like that&hellip;&rdquo;, &ldquo;oh that&rsquo;s smart&rdquo;) in order to maintain a semblance of co-presence within a virtual space, as it is the least effort evidence of understanding because continued attention cannot be assumed through a computer screen and virtual interaction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The transcript begins when the reader (R) comments on the code writer&rsquo;s (W) use of charAt instead of substrings.&nbsp; W accepts the initial contribution by continuing with another relevant contribution: an explanation of their original plan involving substrings, and their inability to implement it because they &ldquo;couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations&rdquo; (line 2).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In line 3, R asks for clarification about the intended result of W&rsquo;s substring implementation plan, and in the next comment offers up a possible answer to their own question.&nbsp; W, presumably answering R&rsquo;s initial question, misses R&rsquo;s offered answer and falls behind in the thread of conversation and essentially repeats R&rsquo;s previous response. In other words, W didn&rsquo;t have a chance to read R&rsquo;s option for an answer in line 4 (&ldquo;like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?&rdquo;) and comment, but instead says the same thing in their own answer (&ldquo;Once I found a common letter, I was going to replace it with a symbol or something&rdquo;).&nbsp; Though technically paraphrasing is a form of contribution acceptance, W&rsquo;s response is not evidence of understanding R&rsquo;s contribution through paraphrasing but acts as an answer to the original question.&nbsp; This can be confirmed when, in the next line W begins with &ldquo;yeah exactly.&rdquo; That is the acceptance of R&rsquo;s offered answer.&nbsp; A conversation &ldquo;overlap&rdquo; is not uncommon in a virtual environment without co-presence (despite their attempts to make it appear so), and actually occurs at the transcript as well (lines 20 &ndash; 21).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; When responses are written to one another, the conversation may become slightly asynchronous because both participants can contribute simultaneously and still have their contribution be noticed. As opposed to a spoken conversation, where only one speaker may contribute at a time to ensure being heard.&nbsp; Simultaneous contributions do cause problems, as demonstrated above, when one participant makes two separate contributions before their first one is grounded.&nbsp; It becomes unclear what is being accepted or understood, and the conversation could unravel into multiple threads with ambiguously accepted contributions, few successful adjacency pairs, and no clear common ground.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luckily, the two participants in this transcript caught up and solidified the understanding in line 7, where R acknowledges W&rsquo;s explanation and their past confusion with &ldquo;ohh,&rdquo; and continues the repair with a demonstration their knowledge:&nbsp; &ldquo;and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?&rdquo;&nbsp; Acceptances via demonstration may serve to reinforce the semblance of co-presence of both participants, as they serve to give evidence of rationality, that is, that both are drawing the same conclusions, and that they have equivalent knowledge of Java.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Line 8 marks a shift in the conversation.&nbsp; W applies the previous statements (about the substring plan) to the actual array implementation and questions the efficiency of this approach.&nbsp; In line 11, R implicitly argues against using efficiency to measure the quality of the implementation, as it would still &ldquo;account for the &lsquo;what if they have the same letters and same length but different repeated letters&rsquo; question.&rdquo; But they accept efficiency as a quality measurement in suggesting a map, and then they evaluate its efficiency (&ldquo;idk how well it would work&rdquo; rather than <em>if </em>the map would work).&nbsp; W accepts the contribution in line 14 (&ldquo;yeah that would have been good&rdquo;) and expands on this idea of a map, applying it to the context of the problem of counting letters.&nbsp; R redefines the existing array in the problem to work as a letter counter like a map. W accepts this implementation based off of the choosing criteria &ldquo;That seems a lot more efficient&rdquo; (line 20).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part C: &nbsp;Person-Plus</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This platform is interesting to analyze in terms of distributed cognition, as it is likely that it gave the programmer less than they would have under different circumstances (e. g., inability to look up Java API, sparse syntax highlighting, etc.).&nbsp; With this lack of physical support, the comments and chatting takes on a new importance as the only other member in this cognitive system, that is to say, they are each other&rsquo;s only resource in the problem-solving task and the surround is created through social support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Line 1 of the transcript begins with this sharing of information via the written code as a representation of knowledge.&nbsp; R is reminded through the code used that &ldquo;charAt is a thing!&rdquo;&nbsp; Because of this lack of remembrance, R was presumably forced to use substrings as an alternative, and thus, their plan is dependent on outside resources, that is to say, that their executive function is distributed in their environment.&nbsp; This altering of plans to satisfy forgotten functions is mirrored with W, who intended to use substrings, but &ldquo;couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using one another as resources, they end up working through the problem together, but obviously people are not as &ldquo;user friendly&rdquo; as one might wish.&nbsp; Using language as a representation of individual knowledge and retrieving via direct questions, the two are able to construct a shared solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part D: &nbsp;Situated Activity</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both participants begin their problem solving task with the same goal and within the same arena, in this case the goal is to detect anagrams and the arena is the platform.&nbsp; They redefine the problem of detecting anagrams using the tools they had at their disposal.&nbsp; W explains they &ldquo;wanted to use substrings to replace each letter in the original string&hellip; but couldn&rsquo;t remember enough about string operations,&rdquo; and so they used an array instead.&nbsp; When writing the code, W had to reconceptualize the problem and determine how to use an array to mimic the functions of the substring as an acceptable replacement to distinguish anagrams.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Line 10 can be seen as a similar situation, redefining the conversation to detecting anagrams without substrings.&nbsp; This new setting excludes the possibility of substrings. Due to its dialectical constitution, the setting is transformed twice to exclude substrings from the problem solving process.&nbsp; The first occurs when W originally wrote the code, and the second follows in the transcript during the discussion. They begin to discuss efficient data structures and thus, their activity changes with the setting, in this case deciding how efficient this data structure is, and the setting then changes again when W suggests using maps to solve the problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Iteratively reforming the problem, as both R and W have just done, constitutes gap-closing.&nbsp; This example is interesting as a joint problem space, as both parties come at the problem from different perspectives and so gap-closing must happen with both parties redefining the other&rsquo;s representation rather than an individual facing a problem alone.&nbsp; This redefinition of the other&rsquo;s representation occurs on lines 4 and 14.&nbsp; In both cases a representation is defined before (&ldquo;I wanted to use substrings&hellip;&rdquo; and &ldquo;you could have used a map maybe&rdquo;) and then reworded by the other participant to cement and show their understanding (&ldquo;like, replace each corresponding letter as it came up?&rdquo; and &ldquo;like some kind of data structure that holds a letter and a count for that letter&rdquo;). In this way, the two representations or definitions of the problem converged as the two participants collaboratively discover the best solution, &ldquo;an array of size 32&rdquo; (line 15) as agreed upon on line 20.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reflection</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was a distinct evolution between my first and second drafts because I did the first draft incorrectly, analyzing the transcript backwards.&nbsp; As a result, I am more confident in my second draft, as the conversation makes more sense and thus my arguments more grounded in reality.&nbsp; Apart from that (rather large) difference, my teammates&rsquo; drafts helped me see these concepts from different perspectives and thus helped me focus on what made my transcript unique (i.e., joint problem solving, overlapping contributions, convergence on a final solution).</p>\r\n',6,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-09 00:06:46','2016-03-17 15:11:25'),(38,'','<p>1. B: Oh right charAt is a thing! I was going to use substring</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. A: and then count down as you come across those numbers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. B: I like that. That seems a lot more efficient</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. A: so like abcc would be [1, 1, 2, 0, 0, &hellip;]</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. B: oh that&rsquo;s smart</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. A: with each