tters, B notices that the map structure may generate extra loops when handling the duplicated letter problem. This action indicates B is aware of monitoring the activity. Then B says that, instead of using map structure, substring could be a better solution (line 13), avoiding the possibility that the team starts to discuss a more complicated and less efficient solution. This action shows B&rsquo;s awareness of repairing the divergence. On the other hand, A also shows his awareness of monitoring and repairing by asking &ldquo;How would you have done that to find anagrams, though?&rdquo; (line 20). A asks this question because A is not sure of how B&rsquo;s suggestion can help solving the problem of finding anagrams, and A asks this question to avoid B from talking about ideas that are irrelevant with current problem.</p>\r\n',13,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-09 00:48:44','2016-03-15 01:31:41'),(39,'','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/8/content_transcript2-277b19599de22d1a80380d0789a974379ac4903d1e5da66c276f57da6bf54644.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Part A.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The analyses of the transcript (above) is broken up to the areas that are designated in the homework assignment. Following this short description (Part A), will follow part &ldquo;B,&rdquo; &ldquo;C,&rdquo; and so on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I will be referring to the participants in the transcript as Person A and Person B. Person A is the person who attempted to solve the problem in the black terminal and who&rsquo;s thoughts are the white text bubbles in the chat. Person B is the author of the comment box above the chat as well as the green text bubbles in the chat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m also adopting Ken&rsquo;s nifty arrow system he used in class when speaking about certain topics of a transcript. Before talking about each subpart in Part B (i.e. grounding, adjacency pairs, et cetera), there will be a picture that correlating&nbsp;to each subpart with arrows pointing at the areas of discussion.&nbsp;Each arrow will also have a corresponding description of why that section of the transcript resembles grounding, adjacency pairs, et cetera. Those descriptions will be numbered after the placement of the arrows. A low number, 1, will be the highest arrow and a higher number, 7, will be a lower arrow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Part B.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Grounding (red arrows)&nbsp;</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/6/content_grounding_001.jpeg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In short terms, grounding or common ground, is the establishment of mutually understood terms between two or more parties. The way these terms are established are through interactions. In our case, conversation through text messaging.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Grounding also is consisted of presupposed knowledge (the problem, online co-presence, &amp; simultaneity)&nbsp;and the current state of reviewing each others&rsquo; work (1, 2, 3, 4, and 5,&nbsp;below).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Both participants were asked to solve a logic problem, and their orientation around this problem allows for them to work together. It is mutually assured that both person A and person B read the same problem and recognize the Joint Problem Space (more on JPS below).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Online Co-presence/Co-temporality</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A &amp; B can expect to receive a timely reply, thanks to the helpful invention of the internet and text messaging.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Simultaneity</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A &amp; B know that they can send and receive messages at the same time. This allows for interruption as well as backchannel feedback.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>B&rsquo;s comments\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>the key word here, as well as marked by a red arrow in the image above is &ldquo;PLAUSIBLE.&rdquo; In context to the rest of the line, B, in the comments, is checking the logic of A. As well as with the rest of the comments, B is agreeing and has come to terms with B&rsquo;s logic and reasoning.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;haha yeah it seems like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<li>B points out A&rsquo;s organization which leads to A&rsquo;s realization of poorly organized data. Most of the rest of A &amp; B&rsquo;s transaction are on correcting A&rsquo;s organization in the black terminal.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 3. &ldquo;yeah I think I put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different color&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<li>A is starting a new train of thought as B agrees. They are now on the same &ldquo;information plane.&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4. &ldquo;I found the count really useful as well&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<li>Both A &amp; B are agreeing the use of A&rsquo;s count is useful. Because they are agreeing, they have come to a mutual understanding of the information being dictated (in this case, the count in the black terminal). A quick note, there was a delay in time for A to respond to be, so if you look at the image above, another text message from B separates the grounding pair: B&rsquo;s &ldquo;I found the count really useful as well&rdquo; and A&rsquo;s &ldquo;the count is also useful.&rdquo;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 5. &ldquo;yours was more organized than mine&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul style=\"margin-left: 40px;\">\r\n	<li>agreeing that the organization of B&rsquo;s problem solving in the terminal was better than A&rsquo;s.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Adjacency Pairs (orange arrows)</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/7/content_adjacency_pairs_001.jpeg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adjacency pairs are the ordered utterances produced by two different speakers. These ordered utterances can be: question-request, request, proposal, offer, invitation, apology-thanks-assessment, compliment, and summons-greetings-farewell.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>The adjacency pair in this case is a direct interaction between A &amp; B. Here B is observing A&rsquo;s work, which later goes on to the assessment of A&rsquo;s organization.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;yeah I think I put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different color&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>This sections falls in the question-request category where A realizes a mistake and brings it up to start a new topic of conversation with B, who then asks a question.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>This section is an ordered utterance where B makes a realization and implies clarification from A&rsquo;s side.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;yours was more organized than me&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>This is a compliment. Compliments are adjacency pairs.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phases (blue arrows)</u><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/9/content_contribution_acceptance_001.jpeg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Contribution Phases include when A gives B something to consider, and vice versa. Acceptance phases follow a contribution and can be: continued attention, answer question, acknowledgement, demonstration/paraphrase, and a display of feedback/certainty. Contribution and acceptance phases are subsets of adjacency pairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>In context to contribution/acceptance phases, B was affirming information from his/her analyses of A&rsquo;s work. A quickly accepts B&rsquo;s analyses.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;yeah i think I put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>B acknowledges A&rsquo;s statement.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;I found the count really useful as well&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>this interaction was a extremely quick acknowledgement and feedback of the statement.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Repairs (purple arrows)</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/10/content_repairs_001.jpeg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Repairs are quick reactions to a party&rsquo;s realization of a mistake and is an attempt to fix that mistake. Repairs are done within the turn the mistake was made.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>A is addressing his/her thought process and making sense of her mistake.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>&ldquo;so when I looked back at the problem and my solution, I got a little confused&rdquo;\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>A is admitting he/she has gotten confused when looking back at her work, and then acknowledging his/her mistake by letting B know what went wrong.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part C.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Person Plus</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Person Plus is the considerable debate behind &quot;knowledge in the head&quot; and &quot;knowledge in the world.&quot; Knowledge in the head is rote, memorized, as well as&nbsp;studied items. The example given with the Person Plus paper is an engineer and his/her principles/education. That engineer studied mathematics, mechanics, etc. and from their studies, have taken away the abstract thinking involved as well as major principles involved with engineering. Knowledge in the world is Person Plus. It is a tool&nbsp;that helps the engineer complete a task. This could be notes, software, books, calculators, etc. Person Plus is split into four characteristics: knowledge (long-term knowledge), representation (helpful tools), retrieval (search for useful information), and construction (the setting that affords creative outlet).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this example there are several identifies to the Person Plus model. For example the black terminal. The terminal helps A explore and convey information (long-term knowledge/logic)&nbsp;to solve the original problem. Without the terminal (and any other tools) solving the problem would be more improbable. The instant messaging is another identifier of Person Plus (representation). Instant messaging allows collaborative teamwork (where &ldquo;two minds are better than one&rdquo;; i.e. representation) and permeant retention of the conversation (A or B can go back and reread through their analyses; i.e. retrival). External Elements are identifies of Person Plus. This means anything physical that allowed A and B to communicate: the computer, keyboard, feedback from their screen (representation). And last but not least, the possibility of the internet, or seamless online data transfer. This collaborative space would not have been possible without it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Executive Functions</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Executive Functions are the limits of the program that streamline thinking/problem solving. In context to this problem space, the grounded goal between A &amp; B to solve the problem is an executive function. A &amp; B are both contributing/dividing their attention to solve a problem. A&rsquo;s representation of the problem is also an executive function. By this I mean the conversation between A &amp; B only happened because of the displayed work in the Black Terminal, which happened to be A&rsquo;s work. It paved way for conversation, since the instructions were to solve the problem as a group with the displayed information. Text messaging is also and executive function. The quick, corrective comments between A &amp; B are only possible by the rules of turn taking and the even more limited rules of turn taking within text messaging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part D.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Joint Problem Space</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within the transcript there is a Joint Problem Space. For a Joint Problem Space to exist, there must be collaboration between two or more participants to solving a problem. It is apparent that A &amp; B are collaborating to find solution C. Though C has already been found before direct collaboration, A &amp; B are agreeing to and checking solution C.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In response to Rochelle &amp; Teasley&rsquo;s quote, &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration,&rdquo; we see all these actions within the transcript.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge is introduced to the JPS via the executive function of the original problem. The original problem is grounded between both parties as well as helping the parties streamline their thoughts to eventually solve the problem. In a way, the grounding of the original problem established the JPS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New information is introduced via B&rsquo;s direct comments to A&rsquo;s problem solving that happened in the terminal and through the direct conversation with text messaging. Not only does text messaging allow new knowledge to be introduced, like A&rsquo;s repair of his/her organization to his/her problem solving in the terminal (&ldquo;so when I looked back at the problem and my solution, I got a little confused&rdquo;), but it also allows for on-going, continuous activity, the adjacency pairs (&ldquo;It seems like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo; to &ldquo;the [organization] was too much&rdquo;).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The text messaging allowed for a continuous back and forth, as well as clarification of mistakes in the problem solving activity, correctly establishing a impactful Joint Problem Space. Collaboration was available, as well as clarification. It was as if the problem was solved as I&rsquo;d like to call it, &ldquo;the communal brain.&rdquo; Where two parties aptly help each other in an effective way, with each other, not split up, to solve the same problem and reach the same goal.</p>\r\n','<p><b>Part A.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This analyses of the transcript (above) will be divided into four parts: Part A (what you&rsquo;re reading), Part B (an analyses of elements&mdash;grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution &amp; acceptance phrases, repairs, &amp; virtual copresence&mdash;within the transcript), Part C (understanding &amp; applying Person-Plus elements to the transcript), &amp; Part D (proficiency of the transcript&rsquo;s Joint Problem Space).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Major revisions to this analyses:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>For readability purposes, the transcript will be typed out (below) and will include line numbers for efficient future references. The parts of the transcript that will be written out are the comment box in the upper right-hand corner and the chat below the comment box.</li>\r\n	<li>In the draft, I gave each element of Part B its own reference image of the transcript with colored arrows pointing to examples of those elements. The issue: multiple pictures disallowed the reader to compare multiple/differing elements. Simple fix: since several of the elements share the same transcript lines, the transcript below will point out (with colored asterisks) all the examples I will be referencing. Below the transcript descriptions will define, reference, and compare all elements that are asterisked in the transcript.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two participants in this transcript, Person A &amp; Person B. Person A has attempted to solve the logic problem, given by Rick &amp; Ken, in the terminal on the upper left-hand corner of the transcript. To include, he/she wrote the white text bubbles in the chat. Person B is the author of the comment box as well as the green text bubbles in the chat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typed out transcript:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: given: yellow rose, cannot be green, either red or blue &mdash;&gt; YOUR GUESS IS PLAUSIBLE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: given: not red, can be yellow/blue/green but yellow cant be with green &mdash;&gt; G&amp;B b/c no red</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: given: blue but not green, can be B&amp;R, B&amp;Y &mdash;&gt; has to be B&amp;Y because MR B ha no yellow</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: given: not yellow. can be B&amp;R, B&amp;G, G&amp;R &mdash;&gt; has to be G&amp;R because of the rest of the people</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: what is the count for?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: overall, i think you&rsquo;re right!! good job!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A: lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A: -______-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;A: but it was too much lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;A: with the ( ) and the ?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: i put the mr.&rsquo;s out of order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: i found the count really useful as well</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: the count is also useful</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: it was a lot easier when it&rsquo;s organized</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: mine was all over the place</p>\r\n\r\n<p>22 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: it helped</p>\r\n\r\n<p>23 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: mine&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>24 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: yours was more organized than me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>25 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now onto Part B&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Part B.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part B addresses the underlying collaborative phenomena of the transcript. These are: <i>grounding, adjacency pairs, contributing &amp; acceptance phases, repairs, and virtual copresence. </i>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Grounding, or common ground, is the establishment of mutually understood terms between two or more parties. The way these terms are established are through interactions. In our case, A &amp; B interact through text messaging (<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><b>*</b></span></span> in transcript below). Grounding can also be presupposed knowledge. Some presupposed knowledge that A &amp; B share are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Logic Problem</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Both participants were asked to solve the <i>same </i>logic problem. Therefore it is assured that A <i>knows</i> B read the logic problem, and vice versa. This allows for faster collaborative problem solving.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Virtual Copresence</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>A <i>can expect</i> to receive a timely reply from B, and vice vera thanks to the invention of the internet and instant messaging. This means of communication assures both participants thoughts won&rsquo;t go unnoticed.&nbsp;</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>Simultaneity&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>A &amp; B <i>know</i> that they can send and receive messages at the same time. This allows for interruption as well as backchannel feedback. The rules of turn-taking applies as means for efficient communication.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adjacency pairs (<span style=\"color:#00cc33;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span><b> </b>in transcript below), are the ordered utterances produced by A &amp;B. These ordered utterances can be:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>question-request</li>\r\n	<li>request</li>\r\n	<li>proposal</li>\r\n	<li>offer</li>\r\n	<li>invitation</li>\r\n	<li>apology-thanks-assessment</li>\r\n	<li>compliment</li>\r\n	<li>summons-greetings-farewell.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Contribution Phases (<b><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">*</span></span> </b>in transcript below) occur when A gives B something to consider, and vice versa. Acceptance phases follow a contribution phase and can be:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>continued attention</li>\r\n	<li>answer to a question</li>\r\n	<li>acknowledgement</li>\r\n	<li>demonstration or a paraphrase&nbsp;</li>\r\n	<li>display of feedback/certainty&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: contribution and acceptance phases are regularly subsets of adjacency pairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Repairs (<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"color:#9900cc;\"><b>*</b></span></span> in transcript below) are quick reactions to A or B&rsquo;s realization of a mistake and is an attempt to fix that mistake. Repairs are done within the turn the mistake was made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Transcript w/ Colored Elements:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, <span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pairs</span>, <span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phases</span>, <span style=\"color:#990099;\">Repairs</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1<span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: given: yellow rose, cannot be green, either red or blue &mdash;&gt; YOUR GUESS IS PLAUSIBLE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2<span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: given: not red, can be yellow/blue/green but yellow cant be with green &mdash;&gt; G&amp;B b/c no red</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3<span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: given: blue but not green, can be B&amp;R, B&amp;Y &mdash;&gt; has to be B&amp;Y because MR B ha no yellow</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4<span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: given: not yellow. can be B&amp;R, B&amp;G, G&amp;R &mdash;&gt; has to be G&amp;R because of the rest of the people</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: what is the count for?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: overall, i think you&rsquo;re right!! good job!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: -______-</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\"><b>*&nbsp;</b></span><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\"><b>*&nbsp;</b></span><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><b><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b></span><b><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">*</span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</b>A: but it was too much lol</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: with the ( ) and the ?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12<span style=\"color:#9900cc;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;A: then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><b><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><b><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><span style=\"color:#9900cc;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp;&nbsp;A: yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><b><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;B: oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15<span style=\"color:#9900cc;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: so when i looked back at the problem and my solution, i got a little confused</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16<span style=\"color:#9900cc;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: i put the mr.&rsquo;s out of order</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;</b><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;B: i found the count really useful as well</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18<span style=\"color:#00cc33;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">*</span></b></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;A: the count is also useful</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20<span style=\"color:#00cc33;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b>*</b></span></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: it was a lot easier when it&rsquo;s organized</p>\r\n\r\n<p>21 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: mine was all over the place</p>\r\n\r\n<p>22 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: it helped</p>\r\n\r\n<p>23 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: mine&rsquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>24<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">*</span></b></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A: yours was more organized than me</p>\r\n\r\n<p>25<span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><b><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">*</span>&nbsp;<span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">*</span></b></span>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; B: thank you! I feel pretty confident in what I arrived at!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, <span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pairs</span>, <span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phases</span>, <span style=\"color:#990099;\">Repairs</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Analyses</u>:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 1-4:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, the key word here &ldquo;PLAUSIBLE.&rdquo; In context to the rest of the line, B is checking the logic of A. B is agreeing and has come to terms with B&rsquo;s logic and reasoning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 9-10:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, B points out A&rsquo;s organization which leads to A&rsquo;s realization of poorly organized data. Most of the rest of A &amp; B&rsquo;s transaction are on correcting A&rsquo;s organization in the black terminal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pair</span>, this case is a direct interaction between A &amp; B. Here B is observing A&rsquo;s work, which later goes on to the assessment of A&rsquo;s organization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phase</span>, B was affirming information from his/her analyses of A&rsquo;s work. A quickly accepts B&rsquo;s analyses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 12-13:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#990099;\">Repair</span>, A is addressing his/her thought process and making sense of his/her mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 13-14:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, A is starting a new train of thought as B agrees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pair</span>, these lines fall in the question-request category where A realizes a mistake and brings it up to start a new topic of conversation with B, who then asks a question.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phase</span>, B acknowledges A&rsquo;s statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 15-16:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#990099;\">Repair</span>, A is admitting he/she has gotten confused when looking back at her work, and then acknowledging his/her mistake by letting B know what went wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 17 &amp; 19:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, both A &amp; B are agreeing the use of A&rsquo;s count is useful. Because they are agreeing, they have come to a mutual understanding of the information being dictated (in this case, the count in the terminal). A quick note, there was a delay in time for A to respond to be, so if you look at the image above, another text message from B separates the grounding pair: B&rsquo;s &ldquo;I found the count really useful as well&rdquo; and A&rsquo;s &ldquo;the count is also useful.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#0000FF;\">Contribution &amp; Acceptance Phase</span>, this interaction was a extremely quick acknowledgement and feedback of the statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 18 &amp; 20:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pair</span>, this section is an ordered utterance where B makes a realization and implies clarification from A&rsquo;s side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lines 24-25:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#FF0000;\">Grounding</span>, agreeing that the organization of B&rsquo;s problem solving in the terminal was better than A&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left: 40px;\"><span style=\"color:#00cc33;\">Adjacency Pair</span>, this is a compliment. Compliments are adjacency pairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Part C.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Person Plus</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To understand Person Plus, we must understand the difference behind &ldquo;knowledge in the head&rdquo; and &ldquo;knowledge in the world.&rdquo; Knowledge in the head is rote, memorized, and/or studied items. The example given with the Person Plus paper is an engineer and his/her principles/education. That engineer studied mathematics, mechanics, etc. and from their studies, have taken away the abstract thinking as well as major principles involved with engineering. Knowledge in the world is Person Plus. It is a tool that helps the engineer complete a task. This could be notes, software, books, calculators, etc. Person Plus is split into four characteristics: <i>knowledge</i> (long-term knowledge), <i>representation</i> (helpful tools), <i>retrieval</i> (search for useful information), and <i>construction</i> (the setting that affords creative outlet). In the transcript there are several identifies of the Person Plus model.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Knowledge</u>: A and B both understand how to use a computer, the internet, how to read and write in English, and most importantly, how to communicate effectively. These are all skills that have developed and have been learned over time. This knowledge allows for better collaborative learning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Representation</u>: the terminal in the upper left-hand corner helps Person A explore and convey information to solve the logic problem. The terminal acts as a way to keep track of count, and allows A to use the rest his/her working memory on the problem. This can be seen in LINE 11, when A expresses his/her workflow and organizing techniques in the terminal. Without the terminal, A would have a far less-efficient time solving the problem. Similarly, the comment box in the upper right-hand corner allows B to use more working memory and make sense of A&rsquo;s work in the terminal, especially LINES 1-4. The instant messaging used between A &amp; B is another representational identifier of Person Plus. Instant messaging is a tool that allows collaborative teamwork (&ldquo;two minds are better than one&rdquo;).&nbsp; Other helpful tools/representation are: the computer, keyboard, feedback from A &amp; B&rsquo;s screen, seamless online data transfer from the internet, et cetera.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Retrieval</u>: the terminal, comment box, and the chat room allows A &amp; B to retrieve information of the logic problem and conversation. In other words, the software allows A &amp; B can go back and reread through their analyses, effortlessly. This speeds up the problem solving process by establishing references for A &amp; B, letting their working memory focus on the logic and conversing. A &amp; B&rsquo;s retrieval can be seen directly in all of their conversation, especially when B&rsquo;s discussing A&rsquo;s organization method, LINES 9-19. B is making a direct reference to A&rsquo;s work in the terminal</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Construction</u>: is a combination of all the above elements. If the design of the system is good, then those elements are invisible to A &amp; B, and allow them to focus on the logic problem at hand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Executive Functions</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Executive Functions are elements of the program that streamline thinking/problem solving. In context to this transcript, the grounded goal between A &amp; B to solve the logic problem is an executive function. A &amp; B are both contributing/dividing their attention to solve the logic problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A&rsquo;s representation of the logic problem in the terminal is also an executive function: the conversation between A &amp; B only happened because of A&rsquo;s work in the terminal. It paved way for problem-solving conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Text messaging is also and executive function. The quick, corrective comments between A &amp; B are only possible by the rules of turn-taking and the even more limited rules of turn taking within text messaging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Part D.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Joint Problem Space</u></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within the transcript there is a Joint Problem Space. A Joint Problem Space is the collaboration between two or more participants when solving a problem. It is apparent that A &amp; B are collaborating to find solution C. Though C has already been found before direct collaboration (A&rsquo;s work in the terminal), A &amp; B are agreeing to and checking solution C.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In response to Rochelle &amp; Teasley&rsquo;s quote, &ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration,&rdquo; we see all these actions within the transcript.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Introducing and Accepting Knowledge</u>: is possible via the executive function of the original problem and the collaborative software. The original problem grounds both parties and the software helps parties streamline their thoughts to eventually solve the problem (LINES 1-4, 9-10, 13-14, 17 &amp; 19, and 24-15). In a way, the executive functions allow for the introduction and acceptance of new knowledge. New information is introduced via A&rsquo;s work in the terminal and A &amp; B&rsquo;s direct conversation in the chat box (LINES 13-14 when A repairs his/her work in the terminal).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><u>Monitoring On-Going Activity &amp; Repairing Divergences</u>: Instant messaging between A &amp; B allows for a continuous back and forth, as well as clarification of mistakes in the problem solving activity, correctly establishing an impactful Joint Problem Space. As explained above, A &amp; B exist in a virtual copresence that possesses simultaneity. This allows for efficient collaboration and instant clarification, but also can cause interruption (LINES 17-20, where conversation pairs are 17 &amp; 19 and 18 &amp; 20). But the instant communication and the executive function of turn-taking in instant messaging allows for repairs (LINES 12-13 and 15-16).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A &amp; B did exist in a Joint Problem Space, and without a doubt, that Joint Problem Space allowed them to effectively create an efficient collaborative environment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>E. What I Learned</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>I learned from this assignment and from my peers that communicating information effectively and clearly is key. I have made sure to notice my peers&rsquo; organization methods in their analyses&rsquo; and how that allowed themselves to understand more about their transcript. And in the end, write more about their transcript as well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have realized the value of review, that there is always a better design solution to your problem, and how between two or more parties ideas can be conveyed easier. In my case, all my commenters made the point to, for me, to reorganize my image system (as seen in my draft) as well as go more in depth with Person Plus and Joint Problem Spaces. With this, I believe I have a better grasp of the underlying collaborative phenomena that are essential in establishing collaborative work environments and Joint Problem Spaces. I couldn&rsquo;t have done that by myself, because I might never have realized something was wrong or never realized as quickly that something was wrong with my draft analyses.</p>\r\n',20,2,6,0,1,'2016-03-09 00:55:32','2016-03-15 02:59:42'),(40,'','<p>Question 1.) from HW 2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a.) Speaker B. From line 4-8, I had a similar way of representing my thoughts externally, through listing the 4 gardeners and identifying the colors I knew they had, and the colors they could have.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker B: The placement of some colors before/after the options in parenthesis seems like it has meaning.&nbsp; I am assuming that the colors before the parenthesis are concrete answers, the ones in parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses.&nbsp; Why is Mr. Yellow repeated?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker B: It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom.&nbsp; It seems like visually organizing thoughts and less like a a&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker A: I hope so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker B: and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker A: lol YES</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker B: A+.&nbsp; Very user friendly.&nbsp; It made sense to me!!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker A: I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly lol.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.&nbsp; Lol yeah</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker B: agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaker A: which you pointed 