ds what A means by current_state.&nbsp; B&rsquo;s assumption is that once A registers this evidence, that A will believe that B understands what A meant by current_state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the right hand side of the TPS platform, participant B remarks, &ldquo;The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning.&nbsp; I am assuming that the colors before the parenthesis are concrete answers&hellip;&rdquo; Clearly B thinks that he understands what A means by current_state.&nbsp; &ldquo;the ones in parenthesis are the options this is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses?&rdquo; But as the second part of B&rsquo;s question shows, B needs some evidence from A that indeed B&rsquo;s interpretation of current_state is correct.&nbsp; A then proceeds to say, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.&rdquo;&nbsp; A gives B sufficient evidence that B had the correct interpretation of current_state, and hence A believes that B understands what A means by current_state.&nbsp; Since B doesn&rsquo;t make any further comment to his interpretation of current_state we can assume that B believes that he correctly understands what A means by current_state, and the acceptance phase ends.&nbsp; The grounding criterion is satisfied and current state is added to A and B&rsquo;s common ground.&nbsp; Note that Both A and B believe that B understands what A means by current_state, and hence current_state has been <strong>grounded</strong> into A and B&rsquo;s common-ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clark and Shafer define <strong>adjacency pairs</strong> as follows: &ldquo;Adjacency pairs consist of two ordered utterances, the first and second pair parts, produced by two different speakers.&nbsp; The two parts come in types that specify which is to come first and which second; the form and content of the second part depends on the type of the first part.&nbsp; For example.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>when B says &ldquo;It made sense to me!!,&rdquo; (q1) and then A says &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad you could figure out my thought process&rdquo; (q2), (q1, q2) is an adjacency pair.&nbsp; (q1) and (q2) are clearly the first and second parts respectively.&nbsp; When B says &ldquo;It made sense to me!!&rdquo;, A&rsquo;s response, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad you could figure out my thought process&rdquo; clearly depends on (q1).&nbsp; Moreover,&nbsp; q1 is addressed by speaker B, and q2 is addressed by A, in that order.&nbsp; q2 is conditionally relevant to q1.&nbsp; Thus, (q1, q2) satisfies the properties of an adjacency pair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>c.)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The access framework</strong> can be broken up into four parts: 1.) knowledge, 2.) representation, 3.) retrieval, and 4.) construction.&nbsp; Definitions by Perkins in Person-plus will be given with examples from the transcript of each part of the access framework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1.) <strong>Knowledge</strong>: &ldquo;knowledge concerns what kinds of knowledge are available, including declarative and procedural knowledge, facts, strategies, and skilled routines,&hellip;&rdquo;&nbsp; Example: Speaker A (who created current_state) clearly has some knowledge of *.&nbsp; At line 1 and 2 of current_state, A writes &ldquo;8 roses total and 4 colors each appearing twice&rdquo;, which clearly indicates that A has some facts regarding *.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; A could have worked on problems similar to * in the past and through going through solving these types of problems could have gained some sort of higher-order knowledge in regards to the problem that would allow * to be more easily solved, but this is not clear from the transcript.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2.) <strong>Representation</strong>: &ldquo;representation concerns how the knowledge is represented &ndash; in particular, whether in ways that make it easily picked up, transported in the system, and recoded.&rdquo; Example: current_state fits into the access framework as a representation of knowledge.&nbsp; In this case current_state is an external visual representation of A&rsquo;s current state toward solving *, a visual representation of part of A&rsquo;s current knowledge.&nbsp; Note that the knowledge representation, current_state also includes what A thinks might be true about the problem.&nbsp; &ldquo;Mr. Green - YELLOW (BLUE/RED) BLUE.&rdquo; A thinks Mr. Green might currently has a yellow rose, and might have a blue or red rose, but leaning towards deciding a blue rose.&nbsp; One thing about knowledge representations is that they can be recoded.&nbsp; Thus, if A decides that Mr. Green definitely has a red rose in addition to a yellow rose , A can update her knowledge representation accordingly as well as her knowledge.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3.) <strong>Retrieval</strong>: &ldquo;retrieval concerns whether the system can find the knowledge representations in question, and how efficiently.&rdquo;&nbsp; Example: Note that if A had solved a problem similar to * before that she could retrieve a schema or methodology of solving the problem that yielded success in the previous problem and try to use it to solve *.&nbsp; This would be a retrieval of knowledge.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4<strong>.)&nbsp; Construction:</strong> &ldquo;concerns the system&rsquo;s capacity to assemble the pieces of knowledge retrieved into new knowledge structures.&rdquo;&nbsp; Example: Note that if A did happen to use a methodology for * used in a separate problem, A would be assembling the methodology retrieved into new knowledge structures for use in solving *, a process known as construction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Regarding a distribution of executive function:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;From line 4-8, I had a similar way of representing my thoughts externally, though listing the 4 gardeners and identifying the colors I knew they had, and the colors they could have.&rdquo;&nbsp; Note that the preceding quote from B shows that he also had knowledge of * and had an external and visual representation of * similar to that of B.&nbsp; If A either A or B were to steer the other on a way to proceed to solve the problem then the partner giving the other a tip would gain partial control of the others executive function, which would mean the executive function was distributed.&nbsp; From the transcript it is not clear as to how A or B made decisions in regards to how to solve the problem, or if these decisions were guided by an external source.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>d(i)):</strong>&nbsp; Jeremy Roschelle and Stephanie D. Teasley define a <strong>joint problem space</strong> as follows: &ldquo;The Joint Problem Space (JPS) is a shared knowledge structure that supports problem solving activity by integrating <strong>(a) goals</strong>, <strong>(b) descriptions of the current problem</strong> <strong>state</strong>, <strong>(c) awareness of available problem solving actions</strong>, and <strong>(d) associations that relate goals</strong>, <strong>features of the current problem state, and available actions</strong>.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>a.) <strong>goals</strong> (An example):&nbsp; Both subject A and subject B were trying to solve *.&nbsp; In a sense the problem that A and B were trying to solve together wasn&rsquo;t actually *, it was that of critiquing each others method of problem solving and by Rochelle and Teasley&rsquo;s definition, A and B both had the goal of getting more insight from each other about how to go about solving the problem.&nbsp; A has her external representation, current_state on screen.&nbsp;&nbsp; For instance, A says, &ldquo;I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly.&rdquo;&nbsp; Thus B was prompted by B in some way that the presentation of the problem wasn&rsquo;t necessarily as visually organized as it could be.&nbsp; Now A knows this, and when B says &ldquo;agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha.&rdquo;&nbsp; B is letting A know that he is aware of the insight A got.&nbsp; A doesn&rsquo;t question what B just said, so that insight is added to A and B&rsquo;s current problem state</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b.) <strong>descriptions of the current problem state </strong>(An example): descriptions of the current problem state was the dialogue A and B had going on between each other and each other&rsquo;s mutual understanding of the dialogue.&nbsp; One thing in A and B&rsquo;s problem space is current_state, as that is information that is crucial to both A and B&rsquo;s continued dialogue regarding how to get insight to solve further problems.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c.) <strong>awareness of available problem solving actions</strong> (An example): This was demonstrated by a dialogue that reflected various parts of the problem that subject B had solved.&nbsp; B is critiquing A&rsquo;s work with the hope that both will get insight from this critique in regards to how to solve the problem.&nbsp; An action that B took in this transcript was when B asked, &ldquo;Why is Mr. Yellow repeated?&rdquo;.&nbsp; In current_state Mr. Yellow appeared both on line 5 and on line 9 as descriptions of the different roses associated with Mr. Yellow.&nbsp; B had the hope to gain a further understanding of * in hopes to assist A with insights regarding the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Note: I couldn&rsquo;t see how d.) <strong>associations that relate goals</strong>, <strong>features of the current problem state, and available actions</strong> was as relevant for the transcript at hand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rochelle and Teasley say, <em>&ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration.&rdquo; </em>&nbsp;When B asked about Mr. Yellow, A never responded, so that information wasn&rsquo;t added to A and B&rsquo;s common ground, a divergence from A and B&rsquo;s shared knowledge.&nbsp; If B had asked A again about Mr. Yellow and A had understood what B meant, responded with the answer, and both A and B knew that A understood what B meant, then B&rsquo;s answer would be added to A and B&rsquo;s common ground/problem-space, and that divergence would be repaired.&nbsp; There is much evidence that both A and B are trying to maintain the infrastructure of the problem space.&nbsp; For instance when B says, &ldquo;The placement of some colors before/after the options in parenthesis seems like it has meaning.&nbsp; I am assuming that the colors before the parenthesis are concrete answers, the ones in the parenthesis are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses?&rdquo;&nbsp; B thinks he knows what A means by current_state, but isn&rsquo;t quite sure, so B asks A the question.&nbsp; A says, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things.&rdquo;&nbsp; This question answer pair form and adjacency pair between A and B, adding to the common ground of the problem space just exactly what A meant by current_state, something both A and B have knowledge of and know each other has that knowledge.&nbsp; Now that B knows what current_state means, B can add more constructive critiques to A&rsquo;s stab at *.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What did I learn?&nbsp; </strong>Part two had a positive impact on my revisions of my final draft.&nbsp; I noticed how organized each of the following analyses of my fellow group members were relative to mine, and how most of the group members provided definitions before they gave examples of concepts.&nbsp; This is something I didn&rsquo;t do on my draft of homework two, but incorporated into my final draft since the definitions made it easier for me to recall the concepts at hand instead of just trying to remember just by the relevant examples alone.&nbsp; Team members gave me different types of suggestions; mainly to be more organized in my formatting, and to get closer to the transcript with more examples.&nbsp; I definitely agree with the organization.&nbsp; However, I felt like my transcript didn&rsquo;t have too many examples to discuss the concepts at hand, and the examples I chose were sufficient at explaining the relevant concepts.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t think looking at others work helped raise my confidence on this homework assignment.&nbsp; However, this type of work can&rsquo;t be completed with any recipe; one needs to create their own path to do this type of analysis, and looking at others work can help see if you are indeed on the right path.&nbsp; Looking at others comments for the analysis of other students perhaps gave me more confidence that I was writing okay commentaries.</p>\r\n',7,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-09 01:08:22','2016-03-14 22:33:50'),(41,'Rough Transcript Analysis: Context Clues','<p>TRANSCRIPT</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 Reader: &quot;lol&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2 Reader: &quot;-_______-&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3 Writer: &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4 Reader: &quot;but it was too much lol&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5 Reader: &quot;with the () and the ?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6 Reader: &quot;then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7 Reader: &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8 Writer: &quot;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9 Reader: &quot;so when i looked back at the problem and my solution i got a little confused&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 Reader: &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>11 Writer: &quot;i found the count really useful as well&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>12 Writer: &quot;yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>13 Reader: &quot;the count is also useful&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>14 Reader: &quot;it was a lot easier when its organized&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 Reader: &quot;mine was all over the place&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>16 Reader: &quot;it helped&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>17 Reader: &quot;mine*&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>18 Reader: &quot;yours was more organized than me&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>19 Writer: &quot;thank you! I feel pretty confident in what i arrived at!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ANALYSIS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>b.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When first looking at this transcript, I feel as if I&#39;m missing a piece of the conversation and I&#39;m joining somewhere in the middle. Although I have no doubt that this is the full transcript, I believe that this transcript is a continuation of something these two students were talking about in the previous discussion section. For example, the writer said, &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; in line 3. The &quot;haha&quot; the reader said should be response to something humorous, but the writer said nothing humorous in the transcript prior to that. In that line, the writer also referenced something about the reader having &quot;2 systems&quot;, which seems to be referring to the reader&#39;s code, making me think they just finished talking about the reader&#39;s code and then the chatroom switched, so they just carried the conversation over to this chatroom. The reader&#39;s &quot;lol&quot;, and &quot;-____-&quot; in lines 1 and 2 may be their reaction to the abrupt chatroom switch in the middle of their conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This transcript is not exactly a perfect example of textbook conversational conventions. For example, the adjacency pairs in this transcript are not abundantly clear, nor is the presence of turn taking. In this transcript, the reader will often write a sentence and then continue talking after making that point, seeming to abuse the turn taking rule stating that if somebody finishes saying something, and nobody else follows up with a turn of their own, then that person may continue speaking. However, because of how the reader is typing, it&#39;s difficult to tell when their point is over. Also, I believe that this program reports when one user is typing, so the reader will most likely say something, then continue typing, discouraging the writer from responding, or saying anything until the reader is done typing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>c.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this scenario, the person plus setup for the writer of the code would have just been the text editor on the argument website, as the students were not allowed to recruit any outside resources or help to solve the problem. All the thinking was done on the text editor in the browser, so the surround and residue of their thought processes would be in the editor on the site. In this situation, I also don&#39;t think that there is any ceding or distribution of executive function. The writer of the code is faced with a prompt and a blank text editor; they have nothing to fall back on or rely on. Every resultant piece of code was the product of an executive decision that came directly from the user. There were no mitigating rules or tools to help them out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>d.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I would say that the two participants are in a joint problem space, because they&#39;re peers engaged in the same activity: the discussion and analysis of the same piece of code. To maintain the infrastructure and introduce new topics into the joint problem space, the two participants don&#39;t really have to refer to specific line numbers, because the piece of code being discussed is so small. They can just speak conceptually without getting into the nitty gritty of the code. Unfortunately, almost all of the discussion isn&#39;t even about this code- it&#39;s about the reader&#39;s code from the last section. However, it is clear that the two are in the same joint problem space because of how they repair divergences while collaborating and introduce knowledge. In line 8, the writer asks, &quot;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot;, indicating that there&#39;s a divergence in the joint problem space, and the reader said something that the writer is confused about. To repair this divergence the writer asks this question and the reader, although their initial response is not the repair, but in line 10 the reader repairs the situation by saying &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order&quot;. Also, the way knowledge is introduced indicates the nature of this interaction as a joint problem space. On line 11 the writer says, &quot;i found the count really useful as well&quot;. The topic of the count now is in its transitionary phase before being grounded and introduced to the conversation. Then, on line 13 the reader says, &quot;the count is also useful&quot;, grounding this point and introducing it into their common ground as a useful tool in solving the problem. In line 14 the reader expounds on how helpful it is, saying, &quot;it was a lot easier when its organized&quot;, further grounding the point of the count and how it helps keep the problem organized.</p>\r\n','<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">TRANSCRIPT</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">1 Reader: &quot;lol&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">2 Reader: &quot;-_______-&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">3 Writer: &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">4 Reader: &quot;but it was too much lol&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">5 Reader: &quot;with the () and the ?&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">6 Reader: &quot;then i kept changing the system i had of keeping the possibilities and my guesses&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">7 Reader: &quot;yeah i think i put mr. red and mr. yellow in a different order&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">8 Writer: &quot;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">9 Reader: &quot;so when i looked back at the problem and my solution i got a little confused&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">10 Reader: &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">11 Writer: &quot;i found the count really useful as well&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">12 Writer: &quot;yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with the possibilities put in parentheses&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">13 Reader: &quot;the count is also useful&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">14 Reader: &quot;it was a lot easier when its organized&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">15 Reader: &quot;mine was all over the place&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">16 Reader: &quot;it helped&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">17 Reader: &quot;mine*&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">18 Reader: &quot;yours was more organized than me&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">19 Writer: &quot;thank you! I feel pretty confident in what i arrived at!&quot;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">&nbsp;</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">ANALYSIS</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">b.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">When first looking at this transcript, I feel as if I&#39;m missing a piece of the conversation and I&#39;m joining somewhere in the middle. Although I have no doubt that this is the full transcript, I believe that this transcript is a continuation of something these two students were talking about in the previous discussion section. For example, the writer said, &quot;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&quot; in line 3. The &quot;haha&quot; the reader said should be response to something humorous, but the writer said nothing humorous in the transcript prior to that. In that line, the writer also referenced something about the reader having &quot;2 systems&quot;, which seems to be referring to the reader&#39;s code, making me think they just finished talking about the reader&#39;s code and then the chatroom switched, so they just carried the conversation over to this chatroom. The reader&#39;s &quot;lol&quot;, and &quot;-____-&quot; in lines 1 and 2 may be their reaction to the abrupt chatroom switch in the middle of their conversation.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">This transcript is not exactly a perfect example of textbook conversational conventions. For example, the adjacency pairs in this transcript are not abundantly clear, nor is the presence of turn taking. In this transcript, the reader will often write a sentence and then continue talking after making that point, seeming to abuse the turn taking rule stating that if somebody finishes saying something, and nobody else follows up with a turn of their own, then that person may continue speaking. However, because of how the reader is typing, it&#39;s difficult to tell when their point has been made. Also, I believe that this program reports when one participant is typing, so the reader will most likely say something and then continue typing, discouraging the writer from responding or saying anything until the reader is done typing.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">I&#39;d say that lines 7 -13 of this transcript are in the contribution and acceptance phases of a conversation. Line 7 starts with a contribution (not about the code we&#39;re seeing, but of the writer&#39;s code from the previous chat room), about how they ordered their code. This is a contribution to the conversation. Then on line 8, it appears the writer is not completely sure of what the reader is talking about- a slight divergence occurs here. So the writer asks a counter question to clarify. The reader doesn&#39;t respond immediately to the question to make a repair, but instead continues making their point and talking about their code, until on line 10, they respond to the writer&#39;s question from line 7 saying, &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order&quot;, effectively repairing the divergence, and then on line 11 the writer continues the conversation, making another contribution about the count. This signifies that their question has been answered, and the divergence has been repaired, since that participant is ready to move on. This contribution on line 11 by the writer, saying &quot;i found the count really useful as well&quot;, is accepted by the reader on line 13, with them reiterating &quot;the count is also useful&quot;. This affirmative reiteration shows their acceptance of the writer&#39;s contribtion.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">c.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">In this scenario, the person plus setup for the writer of the code would have just been the text editor on the argument website, as the students were not allowed to recruit any outside resources or help to solve the problem. All the thinking was done on the text editor in the browser, so the surround and residue of their thought processes would be in the editor on the site. In this situation, I also don&#39;t think that there is any ceding or distribution of executive function. The writer of the code is faced with a prompt and a blank text editor; they have nothing to fall back on or rely on. Every resultant piece of code was the product of an executive decision that came directly from the user. There were no mitigating rules or tools to help them out. Also, I liked The Charcoal Sea Lion&#39;s person plus analysis and how they mentioned that there is less person-plus in this situation than the average Java programmer is used to, so this could have an effect on distributed executive function since because of their lack of Internet access they don&#39;t have the freedom to look up any command they want. I will still stick to my initial point that distributed executive function is largely unchanged because of the nature of the assignment though, because if one does not know how to use a certain technique is that really part of one&#39;s executive processes in the first place? I think the Internet connection augments one&#39;s knowledge, but doesn&#39;t necessarily diminish it or take anything away from their executive function.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">d.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">I would say that the two participants are in a joint problem space, because they&#39;re peers engaged in the same activity: the discussion and analysis of the same piece of code. To maintain the infrastructure and introduce new topics into the joint problem space, the two participants don&#39;t really have to refer to specific line numbers, because the piece of code being discussed is so small. They can just speak generally without complicating the conversation with line numbers and specific details. Unfortunately, almost all of the discussion isn&#39;t even about this code- it&#39;s about the reader&#39;s code from the last section. However, it is clear that the two are in the same joint problem space because of how they repair divergences while collaborating and introduce knowledge. In line 8, the writer asks, &quot;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&quot;. This indicates that there&#39;s a divergence in the joint problem space, because the writer is confused about something the reader said, and is asking a question for clarification. To repair this divergence the writer asks this question and the reader, although their initial response is not the repair, but in line 10 the reader repairs the situation by saying &quot;i put the mr.&#39;s out of order&quot;. Also, the way knowledge is introduced indicates the nature of this interaction as a joint problem space. On line 11 the writer says, &quot;i found the count really useful as well&quot;. The topic of the count now is in its transitionary phase before being grounded and introduced to the conversation. Then, on line 13 the reader says, &quot;the count is also useful&quot;, grounding this point and introducing it into their common ground as a useful tool in solving the problem. In line 14 the reader expounds on how helpful it is, saying, &quot;it was a lot easier when its organized&quot;, further grounding the point of the count and how it helps keep the problem organized.</font></font></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><font color=\"#000000\"><font face=\"Times New Roman, serif\"><font size=\"3\">After reviewing the analysis of my teammates and editing my own work I do feel much more confident in my own analysis. Before, I felt like my person plus section was a bit lacking, but after reviewing my teammates&#39; work and using some of their points for my argument, I feel like I&#39;ve definitely made that section, which was in my opinion the weakest aspect of my analysis, much stronger. Reading all their analyses also made me think a little deeper and understand some of the concepts being applied, which allowed me to take my analyses of these concepts to the next step in my revision. Also, looking at their work made me realize that they&#39;re also just students with the same grasp on this material as I have, and reminded me that we&#39;re all pretty much on the same level here and have analyses of a similar caliber.</font></font></font></p>\r\n',22,2,6,0,1,'2016-03-09 01:37:51','2016-03-15 00:19:19'),(42,'HW2: Communication and Problem Solving','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/11/content_transcript.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 (a) Grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; compresence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the beginning of the transcript, participant 1 says &quot;I was going to use substring&quot; but participant 2 is using charAt for the same problem, which makes it clear that the participants had a different viewpoint on solving the problem and there is no mutual approach yet about how it could be solved. On the other hand, there is an implicit initial common ground between the participants because they presuppose that the other participant knows about the problem itself (what the problem is and that there can be myriad ways on how it can be solved) and are aware of common syntaxes for java. However, a common ground that using substring is quickly reached when the participant 2 says &quot;oh that&#39;s smart&quot;, and &quot;yeah that would have been good....&quot;, thereby agreeing with each other and reaching a common ground on the approach. A presentation phase of a separate grounding interaction occurs when participant 1 utters &quot;you could have used a map maybe&quot;, but participant 2 responds their reason for not using it by saying &quot;would have caused a lot of extra loops doing it with a substring&quot;. They both reach a common ground that a map is not feasible for this problem once the participant confirms their agreement when they utter &quot;that&#39;s smart&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While attempting to solve the problem and reach a common ground, the two participants interact in way that can be viewed as adjacency pairs. For instance, when participant 1 says &quot;you could have made an array size 32&quot;, the participant 2 utters a conditionally relevant statement by saying &ldquo;like some kind of data structure that holds a letter...&quot;. They interact turn by turn such that their conversation contributes to acknowledge what the previous speaker said or add another point to the conversation. Their continued turn by turn discussion progresses in a sequential manner. For example, participant 2 says &quot;I was going to try to do something similar with the array...&quot;, participant 1 continues the discourse by adding &quot;ohh and then see if there were any characters that weren&rsquo;t the symbol in the end?&quot;, and participant 2 continues the process again by uttering &quot;yeah exactly, then if a letter came up twice I could find it a second time.&quot; These statements always remain relevant to what was said immediately before throughout the conversation and lead to a common ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, throughout the conversation, the participants use many phrases that function to merely show that they understand or agree with what the other participant is saying. When participant 2 says &quot;oh that&#39;s smart&quot;, it not only functions as an acknowledgment to what participant 1 had said before but also shows their acceptance to participant 1&#39;s example that &quot;so like abcc would be...&quot;. Participant 1 also uses similar phrase &quot;that&#39;s smart&quot; to show their agreement with participant 2&#39;s comment that &ldquo;...would have caused a lot of extra loops&hellip;&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lastly, while there is not a lot of commenting on the specifics about the code from the participants, the fact that they can refer to the use of charAt, substring, and maps, is because they can look at the code written by participant 1 on their screens. While they cannot point by use of their hand, the code and the commenting platform provides the participants to maintain a &quot;virtual&quot; co-presence, where they can &quot;point&quot; to a specific line if they chose to.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(b)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge:&nbsp;Each participant of the exercise has their own set of understanding about the problem as well as java programming. The platform allowed the reconstruction of this understanding in the form of code, which could be discussed with the other participant. It allowed for the sharing of this externalization of their understanding and initiated a discussion between the two participants about their take on the solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation: Using their knowledge, the participants were able to represent their solution or their internal thought-process in the form of code shown in the left-side of the transcript. While the platform does not allow for showing the step-by-step process taken by the participant in reaching the solution shown, it does show the final answer reached. The comments, while incomplete, show the thought-process (or reasoning of the elements they used in their program) of the participants when they were trying to solve the solution themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retreival:&nbsp;In addition, the coding section and the commenting/chat section is placed right next to each other in the platform, which made retrieval of the information (code) being discussed fairly easy. When referring to &quot;charAt&quot;, the other participant does not find it hard to refer to the code to understand what their partner meant. While much of the discussion between the participants does not directly refer to any specific part of the code for the majority of the part, it still has allowed them to view this information to form their own idea for the solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction: The participants already had knowledge about the problem itself as well as structures or methods they could use in the program. A construction of new knowledge that could be applied to this existing idea is seen in their discussion when they debate about whether an alternate methods or structures like maps or substring could be used to solve the very same problem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(c)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the context of the java exercise, the arena is the online platform that allows java programming as well as commenting and chatting between the participants. The context is the commenting and discussion that occurs between the participants of the exercise. The transcript is a good example that that there is a dialectic relation between the context and the setting. The setting is provided or formed because of the problem-solving activity given to the participants, which in turn provides the foundation for the establishment of the second activity, which involves the participants discussing about their programming work. To find a way to know whether a word was an anagram or not, the two participants wrote their own version of program. This, in turn, provided them with the opportunity to comment on each other&#39;s work and find the best possible solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are elements in the transcript that show problem solving as gap-closing. While the visible part of the transcript only shows that the participants are focused on discussing about whether charAt, substring, or map should be used to solve the problem, it is a good example of gap-closing. For instance, when participant 1 says &quot;I was going to use gap closing&quot;, participant 2 responds by saying &quot;that seems a lot more efficient&quot;. Later, in an attempt to find a better solution, the participants discuss whether a map could be used. Participant 1 says &quot;you could have used a map maybe&quot; and they proceed to discuss the feasibility of using a map for this problem. Throughout the process, the participants are testing (mentally during the discussion) whether their solution works and if not, they proceed to redefine the problem to find the solution from a different route.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckeditor_assets/pictures/11/content_transcript.jpg\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1 (a) Grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; c