cess characteristics, Brass tortois&#39;s identifying that the commenter&#39;s knowledge is a combination of the declarative and procedural knowledge provided a greater insight &ndash;that I did not distinguish&ndash; of the knoweledge about the participants. The construction characteristic of the access framework was something that everyone had a differnet opininon about. The argument presented in Bras Tortois&#39; analysis that the platform makes memorizing unnecessary is a peritnent and evident argument. Lastly, after reading the other posts from group members, it seems that everyone has a similar analysis but are still not clear about the dialectic relation between context and setting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',10,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-09 02:44:55','2016-03-15 02:59:14'),(43,'','<p>A) <strong>Transcript</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Responder</em>: Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks to see if the two strings are anagrams of each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings are notequal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Coder</em>: Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just checks that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>: Very good and clever!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>:&nbsp; Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sorry word1 and word2 reversed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: yeah, that&#39;s true. if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>: right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B) <strong>First Analysis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder and responder first start with some initial common ground. Both know the end goal of the code, to compare two words to see if they are anagrams of each other, and they both have a background in Java, and therefore supposedly know the available methods, primitives, and structures of the languages. There is an assumption that the coder has tried to solve this problem in their code.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case, the initial contribution was given by the coder, who wrote their code using variable and method names that would hopefully allow for easier understanding for the responder. The responder then read the code to the best of their ability and provided evidence that they understood the goal of the coder (&quot;Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks to see if the two strings are anagrams of each other&quot;). The responder then asked a question in attempt to clarify a part of the code that they found confusing (&quot;Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings ar notequal?&quot;). The coder accepts the response and believes that they understand the question the responder is asking, and that the responder understood their goal correctly. The coder therefore responds &quot;Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just checks that if that index of word1 is in word2.&quot; Their use of &quot;Yeah&quot; indicates agreement with the responder&#39;s assesment of the code. The coder continues on to say &quot;If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are&quot;, giving additional explanation to make sure that the responder correctly understands what is happening in the code. The coder&#39;s lack of response to the first statement made by the responder, commenting on the main goal of the program, is verification and grounding of that piece of information. The responder then acknowledges the answer given by the coder and accepts it by saying &quot;Very good and clever!&quot;, grounding the information up to this point, as well as implying that the answer to the problem that the coder gave was sufficient to solve the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder then starts a new adjacency pair, trying to establish if they are communicating with the same person as previously. The responder then initiates a repair to their previous statement (&quot;Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?&quot;). The &quot;actually&quot; indicates that they are returning to a previous statement, in this case where they had accepted the solution as correct. The responder then starts a second repair on this statement, as they had accidentally mixed up the variable names (&quot;sorry word1 and word2 reversed&quot;). It is only at this point that the responder accepts and responds with the second part of the adjacency pair, telling the coder &quot;Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D&quot;. The coder does not respond to this statement, and therefore accepts the responder&#39;s answer to their question, grounding the information that neither is sure of whether they had spoken before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder now responds to the responder&#39;s concern about the method not working, assuming that they understand what it is the responder is saying (&quot;yeah, that&#39;s true. if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order&quot;).</p>\r\n','<div class=\"well well-lg\">\r\n<p>A) <strong>Transcript</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Responder</em>: Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks to see if the two strings are anagrams of each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings are notequal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Coder</em>: Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just checks that if that index of word1 is in word2. If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>: Very good and clever!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: Thanks, now are you the same person I was talking to before?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>:&nbsp; Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sorry word1 and word2 reversed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: yeah, that&#39;s true. if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>R</em>: right, but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>C</em>: yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B) <strong>First Analysis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder and responder first start with some initial common ground. Both know the end goal of the code, to compare two words and see if they are anagrams of each other, and they both have a background in Java, and therefore supposedly know the available methods, primitives, and structures of the languages. There is also an assumption that the coder has actually tried to solve this problem in their code, another piece of common ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case, the initial contribution was given by the coder, who wrote their code using variable and method names that would hopefully allow for easier understanding for the responder. The responder then read the code to the best of their ability and provided evidence that they understood the goal of the coder (&quot;Logic looks good; user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks to see if the two strings are anagrams of each other&quot;). The responder followed this by asking a question in attempt to clarify a part of the code that they found confusing (&quot;Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings are notequal?&quot;). The coder accepts the response and believes that they understand the question the responder is asking, and that the responder understood their goal correctly. The coder therefore responds &quot;Yeah, the for loop just runs through each letter of word1 and word2.contains() just checks that if that index of word1 is in word2.&quot; Their use of &quot;Yeah&quot; indicates agreement with the responder&#39;s assesment of the code. The coder continues on to say &quot;If it&#39;s not, then they aren&#39;t anagrams, but if it makes it to the end of the loop without returning false, they are&quot;, giving additional explanation to make sure that the responder correctly understands what is happening in the code. The coder&#39;s lack of response to the first statement made by the responder, commenting on the main goal of the program, is verification and grounding of that piece of information. The responder then acknowledges the answer given by the coder and accepts it by saying &quot;Very good and clever!&quot;, grounding the information up to this point, as well as implying that the answer to the problem that the coder gave was sufficient to solve the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder then starts a new adjacency pair, trying to establish if they are communicating with the same person as previously. At this point, the responder initiates a repair to their previous statement (&quot;Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?&quot;). The &quot;actually&quot; indicates that they are returning to a previous statement, in this case where they had accepted the solution as correct. The responder then starts a second repair on this statement, as they had accidentally mixed up the variable names (&quot;sorry word1 and word2 reversed&quot;). It is only at this point that the responder accepts and responds with the second part of the adjacency pair, telling the coder &quot;Not sure if you were the same person I was talking to :D&quot;. The coder does not respond to this statement, and therefore accepts the responder&#39;s answer to their question, grounding the information that neither is sure of whether they had spoken before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coder now responds to the responder&#39;s concern about the method not working, assuming that they understand what it is the responder is saying (&quot;yeah, that&#39;s true. if both words have the same characters then it will say that it&#39;s an anagram even though they&#39;re in a different order&quot;). The responder acknowledges the coder&#39;s response and begins their next statement with &quot;right.&quot; However, the responder then continues on the say &quot;but they may not be anagrams because if word one is bbbb and word two is abba, the words won&#39;t be anagrams, but word two will contain b for all bs.&quot; Here, the responder is accepting the coder&#39;s explanation, and grounding the fact that the described fact is true in some situations, but the rest of their response indicates that the coder misunderstood. The responder is therefore initiating a repair here. Finally, the coder accepts the responder&#39;s explanation, and grounds the fact that the code has a bug (&quot;yeah, that&#39;s true! overlooked those cases&quot;). The lack of contiued conversation indicates that the responder accepted the coder&#39;s response and moved on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C) <strong>Access Framework Analysis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge - The knowlege standpoint of the framework is fairly constrained. The coder and responder had no access to books, the internet, or other tools they generally have access to. They were therefore both only working off of their own personal knowledge when working alone, and then each others knowledge once they were allowed to converse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation - Again with representation, the participants were fairly restricted, as they were unable to use anything external other than the text editor they were given. The coder was able to use their own mental representation of the problem, and then the text editor to represent the problem externally. The color coding in the editor is part of the aid it provided, representing different data types and commands in different colors. The responder was given the code in the text editor as a representation of the coder&#39;s thoughts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retrieval - Retrieval is similar, in that both the coder and responder were limited to their own memory and later each other&#39;s memory. The responder is given the coder&#39;s code, which may have triggered certain memories that they would not have come up with on their own. In return, the responder may have mentioned fixes and suggestions that would have reminded the coder of things they forgot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction - All of these aspects together allow the coder to write a working algorithm. The text editor itself also helps in the construction of the code, with it&#39;s automatic production of second brackets and automatic color coding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D) <strong>Joint Problem Space</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is indeed a joint problem space in this situation. The coder and responder have a fairly large amount of shared knowledge about the problem. This includes their end goal, the current state that the solution is in once their conversation starts, and likely the steps necessary to achieve the goal. Throughout their interaction, the students are both constantly updating each other on their thoughts and checking in on the other&#39;s understanding. Repeatedly, one will initiate a check, usually asking a question, such as &quot;I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings ar notequal?&quot; and &quot;Actually what if word 1 has ababab and word two is bbbbbb. Wouldn&#39;t the method fail to work?&quot; The other will then make an attempt to answer the question and display their understanding of the situation. Responsibility then falls back to the one that asked the question to confirm whether or not both have the same understanding. If the person does not believe that this is the case, then they will present a repair in an attempt to get back to a shared understanding of the problem. The quote &quot;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration&quot; is therefore very relevant to this transcript. For example, the initial display of code is an introduction of the coder&#39;s solution to the problem. The responder then accepts this knowledge by replying on the code, saying that the &quot;logic looks good.&quot; As mentioned before, there is a constant check for divergences in meaning. Every time a question is asked. One particularly good example is when the responder says &quot;user inputs two strings and isAnagram procedure checks to see if the two strings are anagrams of each other. Within the isAnagram method I assume that word2.contains just checks to see if a given substring of word1 is in words 2 and if not says strings ar notequal?&quot; The responder asks this question in order to check if their interpretation is correct, providing the coder with an opening to repair any misunderstanding, and get the two to a consistent understanding of the problem space. Repairs for these divergences are then made in the discourse. In the given example, the repair is made by the coder confirming the responder&#39;s interpretation as correct.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reflection</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The comments I received on my analysis gave me an idea of what I did well and what I should expand upon. It helped to indicate the points where my analysis was lacking or confusing and required more explanation. Reviewing the other analyses was, however, much more helpful. It allowed me to look at my own analysis in comparison with those of the other people in my group. I believe I did decently in comparison, which did boost my confidence a certain amount, as I do not feel like I am missing something large that everyone else understood. It also gave me an idea of how other people approached the analysis and what they saw in their own transcripts. By using these examples, I was able to expand my own analysis, and gain a better understanding of what to watch out for. It also clarified some of the concepts that I did not understand as well as I wanted to, by giving an example of how the concept applies to a real situation.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n',21,2,8,0,1,'2016-03-09 03:16:50','2016-03-15 02:30:39'),(44,'','<p>Note: For convenience I would refer to the conversation in white boxes person A, and the green person B. Grounding Grounding is that the participants in the joint activities accumulate mutual knowledge, or beliefs. The two participants in the transcript share the initial common ground that both had been given the same problem, knowing what the problem it is for them to solve together. The first two lines by person A, &ldquo;LOL&rdquo; and &ldquo;-___-&ldquo;, would not mean much to someone who did not know what was going on. But because person B shared that common ground, knowing at least what A is trying to do here, B said, &ldquo;haha yeah it did seem like you had 2 different systems going on&rdquo;, showing that he/she understood what the emotion or feeling that is underneath (most likely due to solving this problem) presented by A. &ldquo;But it was too much lol&rdquo;, A went on to explain more of what he/she thinks of her solutions, and how he/she end up with two systems. Person B was trying to understand A&rsquo;s thinking process by confirming with A like this, &ldquo;Oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&rdquo; This is grounding because A and B is trying to achieve a common understanding of A&rsquo;s thinking process and solution, to help with the general problem solving. Adjacency pairs As person B said that he/she could tell that A had 2 systems going on, A confirmed by saying, &ldquo;yeah I think I put Mr. Red and Mr. Yellow in a different order.&rdquo; According to the definition of adjacency pair, A&rsquo;s response was according to B&rsquo;s comment. In this case it was not responding to a question, but these two utterances were ordered, the latter depending on the former. Later B asked &ldquo;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&rdquo; To B&rsquo;s question, which basically asked whether A meant putting Mr. Red and Mr. Yellow in a different order from that they were introduced in the question, A answered &ldquo;I put the Mr&rsquo;s out of order&rdquo;. As A answers depending on B&rsquo;s question, this part of the chat is an adjacency pair. Contribution A and B&rsquo;s individually adding to their common ground are contributions to their conversation. As previously mentioned in the Grounding section, A explained why his/her solution appeared to have 2 systems and that he/she was confused during the thinking process. In fact, their contribution is everywhere in the conversation. B said, &ldquo;I found the count really useful as well&rdquo;, and &ldquo;yours seemed to be organized pretty similarly, with 