o; and &ldquo;- -&gt;&rdquo;. Because they were chatting through the computer, that was the only way they could communicate on this platform. They could not put up a chart or draw anything for better representations, but only the computer in front of them as the surround. Nevertheless, the computer still provides short-term and long-term memory for them to combine both understanding to solve the problem together. Executive function The whole process of problem solving in the transcript suggests that there is a distribution of executive function. Because that the representation was explicit and clear, and the retrieval was pretty successful as the person showed the understanding of the other, and both achieved an agreement to some extent, according to their conversation that A said B&rsquo;s solution was more organized, and B agreed. Situated activity In this transcript, the arena would be participants sitting in front of laptops and following the instruction of the exercise. They were given the problem on the screen to think about, told to type their thoughts on the screen, required to see other&rsquo;s typed thoughts, and to chat with one another, etc. The context/setting would be that as they were asked by the instructions to interact with the other participant, and given the other&rsquo;s code/solution, and respond to it. It is depended on the the given situation where the other person showed an understanding the problem itself, and also how the two would interact with each other, for every person would not react in the same way. The setting is also dialectically related to the activity. For example, because B was not sure if A meant, so B asked A whether A meant putting the order differently from the way it was introduced. Then they could focus on this issue, and to make sure they were on the same page in terms of understanding. Gap-closing As B was asking, &ldquo;oh you mean the order that the gardeners are introduced?&rdquo;, he/she was reassuring that they we