\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 600px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(For the sake of distinction, I will refer to Green with feminine pronouns and White with masculine pronouns)</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Summary/initial analysis</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>This transcript is interesting in that it does not directly focus directly on finding a solution to the logic puzzle. Instead, the participants are trying to figure out how Green formatted her response. Green worries that White is not able to understand the where the final answers are because they ran out of time and did not make them very &ldquo;user-friendly&rdquo;, but this is repaired when White is able to understand Green&rsquo;s thought process anyway and considers the layout to be &ldquo;very user-friendly.&rdquo; White contributes that the problem would be easier to solve if there was a was a side-by-side comparison to help him remember his answers, which Green accepts with &ldquo;lol yeah.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Access Framework</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge &ndash; the knowledge here is primarily in White and Green&rsquo;s long term memories, drawing from experiences with similar problems. Even if neither has completed this logic puzzle (or any logic puzzle), prior knowledge from solving a written problem was applied by both in order to solve this. The instructions to the puzzle also presumably provide some knowledge specific to this context.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representation &ndash; Green has created a system for representing her answers and guesses by organizing each person on their own line and putting guesses/solutions next to each one. While there is no official explanation for the meaning behind this organization, White indicates that he understands (&ldquo;It made sense to me!!&rdquo;) and is able to guess the meaning from seeing Green&rsquo;s work and working through the problem himself. This facilitated the transfer of knowledge because Green picked up the information from the problem and applied her own thoughts, which is how it was transferred into the system. She recoded it using the described system, which White was able decode for himself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Retrieval &ndash; in order to assist with retrieval, Green is able to separate each guess onto a separate line. Additionally, she separates the sections of her notes with extra line breaks to make them organized into relevant &ldquo;chunks&rdquo;. This also assists White in following her thought process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Construction &ndash; Using the instructions, prior knowledge, and system of note taking; Green is in the beginning stages of constructing an answer. It appears as though she is preparing to give a definite answer on line 9. She also indicates this in the chat when she indicates that she &ldquo;wasn&rsquo;t done&rdquo; and &ldquo;a few more minutes would have helped.&rdquo; She constructed a new knowledge structure which acted as a new piece of information for White.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because of the presence of the access framework, there is distributed cognition present in this exchange. The platform itself is the surround and the representation left by Green and the exchange between Green and White make up the residue left by thinking. Despite the fact that White and Green are no longer present, we can follow their thought processes both in solving the logic puzzle and communicating over Green&rsquo;s method of displaying her thoughts, which means that there is distributed cognition.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Joint Problem Space</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>In this problem space, Green had to adapt to the code editor by finding some way to transfer her thoughts about the logic puzzle. This was both to help her externalize to solve the problem and eventually to collaborate with White to come to an answer. The initial state of this problem is not knowing which person matches with which colors in the logic puzzle. The goal state is to have a definite list of colors for each person. The intermediate states are seen on lines 4-7, where Green is still working between the two states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The problem space becomes joint because the two partners share the goals of solving the logic puzzle and figuring out each other&rsquo;s thought process in doing so. White and Green describe the current problem state between &ldquo;I wasn&rsquo;t done&rdquo; and &ldquo;I hope so&rdquo; by discussing the way in which Green laid out her intermediate states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The knowledge is introduced into the JPS in some earlier portion of the problem-solving process when each partner receives the instructions for the problem. Green is concerned that the organization is not &ldquo;user-friendly&rdquo; which could lead to a divergence in meaning, but White reassures her that &ldquo;it made sense to [him].&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Reflection</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, I got a better idea of the things to look for in my analysis of the transcript by looking at my classmates&rsquo; posts. I wasn&rsquo;t sure initially how to do this, because the discussion was mostly based off of the way Green formatted the page rather than the actual logic puzzle. But as I dug deeper and read through my classmates&rsquo; posts, I realized there was more going on than I thought. I feel more confident now than I did with the initial draft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n',4,2,5,0,1,'2016-03-10 16:54:09','2016-03-15 06:49:37'),(47,'','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As we can see on the left side of the image where the logical analysis were being done, the required information from the problem were collected and noted down for next approach. The objects are identified and grouped properly for the further analysis according to the problem. On the code section, we can see that there are 12 lines among which the first two lines are telling the analyst about the number or roses and their colors and the number of appearances of each color which is two times. From the fourth line the analyst stared to write down the names of the persons and the possibility of color of roses individually. If we keep reading further then we can guess the memoing is unfinished.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now if we look at the right side which is the chat session among the participants who were involved solving the logic problem, there are two types of representation of the session. It is unclear in the first few lines that the participants are posting their comments one after another and also it needs to be analyzed internally by recognizing the pattern that which statement is written by the other participant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Grounding:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In terms of grounding, both participants of this logic problem solving situation, knew that they need to solve the same problem however the procedure could be different. The acknowledgement of solving the problem put them in a common ground. Here, participant 1 knows that the participant 2 is solving the same problem which s/he&rsquo;s solving and the participant 2 knows the same thing about participant 1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Adjacency pair:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We can notice the adjacency pair in the second part where the conversation between two participants is represented with two different colors and by the definition of the adjacency, the two participants were exchanging their ideas/thoughts one after another. In this conversation, we can see the complement pair in the line &ldquo;and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such&rdquo; which was replied with the acceptance by other participant. We can also notice that in the following pair, one was complementing about the interface by rating it &ldquo;A+&rdquo; where it was replied back with a refusal with the line &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Acceptance:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the chat, the acceptance can be noticed in the line where one of the participant says &ldquo;agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers&rdquo; when it comes to the part of explaining and discussing the complexity of the system/ user friendliness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Virtual co-presence:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both of the participants are virtually co-present during the chat session as well as during the problem solving session although they were solving the same problem individually but after that problem-solving session, both discussed their experience, problems and ideas about the problem solving structure and the system virtually. This activity resembles the STDP (same time different place) however at the end of the chat session, one of the participant stopped replying which might let us think that they were no more virtually present.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>c. Access framework</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Knowledge:</strong> While solving the problem, the participants have the procedural knowledge, strategies to solve the problem. This can be seen by looking at one participant&rsquo;s arrangement of the codes and the other participant&rsquo;s statement of expressing the similarities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Representation: </strong>Both of the participants represented their knowledge in a manner so that they can solve the problem following that. The representation of their acquired knowledge of flowers and gardeners made it easy for them to proceed on to solve the problem easily. Although we can notice that some of the representations are different from one another while we see one participant&rsquo;s statement on chat &ldquo;The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning&rdquo;, which might lead us to think that the one who wrote this represented his knowledge on the code area in different manner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Retrieval:</strong> Participants represented their knowledge in a way so that the required information to solve the problem can be retrieved easily. Again if we look at the chat, one participant wrote &ldquo; it is interesting that these rules for arrangements are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts and less like&hellip;&rdquo; which means the one who was writing that code, arranged in a manner so that the retrieval of the information gets easy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Construction:</strong> From the code, individual pieces of information were assembled together which can be retrieved into new knowledge structure. Also from the chat section, the construction of the flow of communication might be helpful for the participants to gather knowledge about other participant&rsquo;s way of solving the problem or the structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Distribution of executive function:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the perkin&rsquo;s paper, the executive function of a person-plus during thinking and learning can be distributed in several ways. In this case of logical problem solving, both of the participants were solving individually without aiding each other. There was no computer aided instruction either hence we see that there was no implicit set of executive decisions. The participants were only guided by themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>d. i)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this case of problem solving, I don&rsquo;t see any joint problem space since both of the participants were solving the problem individually on their own machines. After logging into the system, both participants got the same logical problem to solve within same amount of time. They had the same time and problem but had to solve that individually using their own methods. It is not quite surprising that some of their method of solving the problem matched which they revealed on the chat. But to solve that problem, they were not working together on the same computer or inside the same space. They were not guiding themselves each other. To share their knowledge, participants used the chat section where they were able to see each other&rsquo;s approach and get the idea. They were also able to talk to each other through the chat section, shared their thoughts on the other&rsquo;s approach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this way, the participants introduced their knowledge of solving that specific problem to other and also accepts the others way of solving the problem as well through the chat section. Since they were communicating with each other in same time in same virtual space, in my opinion, that chat section could be an example of JPS where the problem could be their confusion about some particular item which could be discussed and solved in that space.</p>\r\n','<p><strong>Transcript:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: I hope so</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 2: and I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your final answer were and such</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: lol YES</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 2: A+</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 2: very user friendly</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 2: it made sense to me!!</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly lol</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: im glad you could figure out my thought process and method of keeping track of things</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: lol yeah</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 2: agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answer haha</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: which you pointed out</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: there was a similar method in place though</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: I wasn&rsquo;t done lol</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: L</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: a few more minutes would have been helped</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: I know we had the same answer for mr. blue</li>\r\n	<li>Participant 1: I think I was 