 section, the construction of the flow of communication might be helpful for the participants to gather knowledge about other participant&rsquo;s way of solving the problem or the structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Distribution of executive function:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the Perkin&rsquo;s paper, the executive function of a person-plus during thinking and learning can be distributed in several ways. In this case of logical problem solving, both of the participants were solving individually without aiding each other. There was no computer aided instruction either hence we see that there was no implicit set of executive decisions. The participants were only guided by themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>d. i)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joint problem space was present while both of the participants were solving the problem individually on their own machine, observing the changes are being made by the other participants live, sharing each other experiences and one&rsquo;s action is affecting the situation. After logging into the system, both participants got the same logical problem to solve within same amount of time. They had the same time and problem but had to solve that individually using their own methods. It is not quite surprising that some of their method of solving the problem matched which they revealed on the chat. But to solve that problem, they were not working together on the same computer or inside the same space. They were not guiding themselves each other. To share their knowledge, participants used the chat section where they were able to see each other&rsquo;s approach and get the idea. They were also able to talk to each other through the chat section, shared their thoughts on the other&rsquo;s approach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also if I consider the statement &ldquo;The joint problem space is not a mental model, but a shared set of experiences and references that grows as a group explores a problem. It has strong ties to external inscriptions, such as the shared whiteboard, which provide continuing visual support for cognition and create experiences shared by the group.&rdquo; from the paper &ldquo;essays in computer supported collaborative learning&rdquo; by Gary Stahl; in this case, the participants were using a shared space which is chat window to share their ideas, knowledge and experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this way, the participants introduced their knowledge of solving that specific problem to other and also accepts the others way of solving the problem as well through the chat section. Since they were communicating with each other in same time in same virtual space, in my opinion, that chat section could be an example of JPS where the problem could be their confusion about some particular item which could be discussed and solved in that space.</p>\r\n',14,2,7,0,1,'2016-03-10 19:10:17','2016-03-14 21:16:32'),(48,'','<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">I didn&rsquo;t paste a copy of the transcript all at once; instead, I am responding to each part of the conversation as it comes up. I thought this made a lot of looking back and forth not needed. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Part B: Analyze the chat in your transcript in terms of grounding, adjacency pairs, contribution and acceptance phases, repairs, and &ldquo;virtual&rdquo; copresence. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Original Poster: From lines 4-8 I had a similar way of representing my thoughts externally, through listing the four gardeners and identifying the colors I knew they had, and the colors I knew that they could have. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Grounding: The OP introduces an important piece of common ground here. They list one of the rules that they used to sort the roses to the gardeners. The commenter now has this piece of information available to them to interpret the data. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Adjacency Pair: This first comment by the OP is not part of an adjacency pair. It is simply a statement. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Commenter: The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning I am assuming that the colors before the parentheses are concrete answers, the ones in parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Grounding: Continuing from before we see that the commenter has indeed put to use this piece of common ground declared by the OP. They have performed some construction internally. They had to take the not complete rule that the OP had posted and infer some of what the color placement meant, deciding that colors before parentheses are concrete answers, while the ones in the parentheses are under consideration, and the colors after it are the current guesses. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Adjacency Pair(Assessment/Agree): The first statement by the commenter in this section forms an adjacency pair with an answer by the OP far down the thread of comments. The commenter here has used construction to try to understand exactly how the OP was trying to solve the problem. They then pose their assessment of the situation so that the OP can agree/disagree and a repair can occur or this piece of knowledge can be accepted into the common ground of the situation. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Repair: This assessment is an attempt at repair. The commenter assumes that there was a straightforward logic in the presentation of the transcript that would allow them to understand the OP&rsquo;s answer; they then post their assessment to the OP so that they OP can review this assessment and compare it to their internal representation of how they went through listing the information in the joint problem space(abbreviation JPS, Here it is the two participants, the transcript that is posted, the chat window that the participants are typing in, and even the keyboards that they are typing with. ), so that they can then repair the gaps between these two. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Commenter: Why is Mr. Yellow repeated? </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Grounding: The OP has included information below the organizational structure that has been referenced above. The commenter is asking here for clarification of what the purpose of that information is, trying to establish more common ground. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Adjacency Pair(Question/Answer Type): Here the commenter asks a direct question for the OP to answer. In the line that follows below they make a comment that the repetition of Mr. Yellow might just be some type of visual organization. The OP later answers that this was correct and that this was some type of sporadic organizational issue saying a couple times that they needed more time and agreeing that with this time it would have been very explicit where the final answers were. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Repair: This question/answer AP is another attempt at repair. The commenter doesn&rsquo;t know why Mr. Yellow is repeated towards the bottom of the transcript, so they ask the OP to clarify. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Commenter: It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: I hope so </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Acceptance Phrase: Here the OP has accepted the commenter&rsquo;s analysis that the bottom part of the transcript was simply a visual organization of thoughts. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">C: And I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: LOL YES. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">C: A+ Very User Friendly. It made sense to me. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Grounding: Here the OP and commenter comment on ways that they could have made the task easier, deciding that they needed a little more time, and that if they could do a side by side comparison talking about the problem would become easier. They might use this knowledge to alter their JPS next time by including extra visualizations. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly lol. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: Im glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Acceptance Phrase: This acceptance phrase is paired with the commenter&rsquo;s first interpretation of how the OP was posting their answers. It is the first explicit recognition that the commenter interpreted the whole logic to the posting of the answers. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: lol yeah</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">C: Agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: Which you pointed out. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: There was a similar method in place though.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: I wasn&rsquo;t done lol.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: :(</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: A few more minutes would have helped. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: I know we had the same answer for mr. blue. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: I think I was stopped as I was changing my answer for mr. green. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">OP: WHICH ONE IS IT</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Virtual Co-Presence: Almost the entirety of this discussion is focused around the fact that the two participants are not in the same place. If they were they could have simply pointed to the different parts of the transcripts and said this part does this yes or no. The fact that this JPS is occurring over the computer is a limiting factor in the discussion of the two pairs, because understanding the transcript is the first step in discussing if it was a good way to do it or not. To understand the different parts of the transcript requires that there is a question formed about them, which requires that they are identified, which requires that they are referred to, and the fastest way to do this is to point in person. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Part C: Analyze the transcript in terms of the access framework</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Knowledge: The blocks of knowledge that are important units in this transcript are as follows. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">The OP says that they listed the colors they knew the gardeners had and that they could have. </b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">(The Assessment AP phrase by the commenter, later agreed to by the OP)The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning I am assuming that the colors before the parentheses are concrete answers, the ones in parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses. </b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">(The one yielded by the Question/Answer AP about Mr. Yellow) Mr. Yellow is repeated at the bottom because it is part of a visual organization of thoughts.</b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">(The one yielded by the other Question/Answer AP)Both parties agree more time and better organizational methods would be important.</b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Representation: This knowledge is stored in a few locations. From the perspective of each individual, relevant information in the JPS is stored in the other person. The JPS also contains the transcript that holds information about how the OP originally tried to solve the problem. The chat log contains constructions of new knowledge structures from the OP and commenter. A limiting factor here is that the OP may have engaged in methods of problem solving that don&rsquo;t lend themselves very well to being expressed in English, as is true of much of math. The participants at one point agree that they would like more data available to them in the form of side by side comparisons. They are here being limited by the representation as well. They claim they are spending a large part of their time trying to recall things that could just be displayed for them. They comment that changing the representation to include this information that they are trying to remember would reduce the work in remembering that they have to do and that this would allow them to spend more mental energy making comparisons. This is where distributed cognition begins to come in. All the data that is given in the transcript is stuff that the participants don&rsquo;t have to remember at the time, which allows them to process other information. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Retrieval: The OP and commenter can access the other person by commenting in the chat. They access the chat by reading it. The limitation here is that they have to make jumps in interpreting what the other person means by their comments. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Construction: The OP and Commenter take the information that they have retrieved from each other and use this information to alter the common ground in the situation. The commenter knows piece of information number 1. They combine this piece of information with their prior knowledge about how people organize things. It is common convention to list options together in a set of parentheses as the OP did. (Yellow/Green/Red). The commenter, knowing that they should look for something that could be the representation of the information that the OP is talking about, recognizes the parentheses motif in their prior knowledge and at this point constructs the new piece of knowledge that this particular parentheses structure here is a representation of a concept that the OP is now talking about. The commenter appropriately leaves a residue of new knowledge in the situation, which is this construction they have just made above. It is now in the representation of the JPS. It is then retrieved by The OP who confirms through another representation in the JPS that the Knowledge that the Commenter has constructed is valid. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">More Distributed Cognition in the JPS: If the situation is viewed as one in which each participant has the goal of figuring out what the best approach was to this problem and problems of this type then each person has the other person to consider as a form of distributed cognition in this JPS. The way that this is being done here is that the OP has tried a problem and the commenter is evaluating the way in which the OP has done this, trying to say if it is best. In order to do this, they need the piece of knowledge: how did the OP try to do the problem? When the commenter asks the OP about the parentheses enclosed information being provisional they are retrieving information from the representation that is stored in the other person that is part of the JPS. The fact that the chat log stays up and contains a record of all that has been said is also a piece of distributed cognition that is performed for the participants. They don&rsquo;t have to remember what they have said to each other and can at all points access this bank readily. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Part D: Analyzing in terms of a joint problem space</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Is there a joint problem space?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">The JPS has already been talked about in depth here. Each person has the goal of understanding how to do this problem best. The OP also has the goal of specifically understanding the Commenter and providing relevant information to them and the Commenter has the analogous goals of asking good questions and understanding information provided by the OP. For each person the other person is part of the JPS. The other person is part of the representation of information that the other must access. The JPS also consists of the transcript the OP created and the chat dialogue that is going on between the OP and commenter. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">What work is done to maintain the infrastructure as the students work together, creating and sharing knowledge? </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">The OP posts some of their logic about how to read their answers. They then read the commenter&rsquo;s assessment of this and respond in agreement. The infrastructure of the JPS(of the OP) is changed such that the commenter now has this piece of knowledge that was originally only with the OP. The commenter in this section also has their JPS modified in a meta way in that the commenter knows that the OP thinks that the commenter knows basically how they are constructing their answers. It seems simple but treating the two as information processing machines it seems necessary to say since the commenter would not be able to interact correctly with the OP and move on if their JPS was not modified as stated.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">&ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration. Explain how that quote is relevant to your transcript.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS: </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">Here there are two methods of introduction. The OP uses the transcript to introduce their attempt at solving the problem into the JPS. Both parties use their keyboards to introduce their current thoughts into the chat log and to the other person. It may also be of worth to note that the other person has tried this challenge as well and this knowledge is in them as part of the JPS from the perspective of the OP. The acceptance of knowledge comes in the form of modifying parts of the JPS. Since the JPS is in part the other person for each person the way to accept knowledge into the JPS is directly through the acceptance of the other person. The Keyboard also counts as a method of introduction into the chat log. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">This occurs at a couple stages. Both parties do this when they are considering the responses of the other. Here it consists of interpreting the other&rsquo;s understanding and comparing it to one&rsquo;s own understanding, so that they can rectify the differences. The commenter also does this when they are reading the transcript of the OP. The only difference there is they are reading this info and not asking for it from the OP. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-18071540-6662-9274-6225-583570042f1b\">This occurs when the two are trying to bridge the differences that they might have in understanding the model the OP is using in the transcript to display information. When the OP makes the acceptance phrase to the commenter that confirms the commenter&rsquo;s assessment of the model of the OP that is the point at which the divergence in their knowledge has been repaired. When the OP makes the acceptance phrase that yes the bottom is just a visual organization of thoughts that is a point at which divergence is repaired. The divergence being that the OP knows some information was not relevant to the answer, while the commenter did not know this. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n','<p><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><meta charset=\"utf-8\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">What I changed: My teammates unanimously told me that organization was my main problem, and no one said anything wrong about any of my analysis or concepts, so I decided to overhaul the organizational structure. I thought that mixing the transcript with the text would make it more readable because it would minimize back and forth, but I am able to admit when I am wrong and this was a comment made by 3 people. I listed the whole transcript at the front now. I also put in line numbers where needed to follow as the other comments were that as a result of my chosen organizational scheme and my lack of line numbers some things got a little too vague. I suppose I have learned not to buck common organizational trends, because they are probably pleasing because they are common and taking away the expectedness of the data presentation, even if the form could be better in an idealistic &ldquo;people as machines&rdquo; vision. Regardless of whether or not that could even be true here, it doesn&rsquo;t play out. Commenting on other people&rsquo;s posts I was surprised the depth of analysis that could come out of analyzing only a few lines in someone else&rsquo;s and I may try to go for a more in depth approach next time in a much more narrow scope and really really try to get in good to a particular phenomena. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Part A:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">1. Original Poster: From lines 4-8 I had a similar way of representing my thoughts externally, through listing the four gardeners and identifying the colors I knew they had, and the colors I knew that they could have. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">2. Commenter: The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning I am assuming that the colors before the parentheses are concrete answers, the ones in parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">3. Commenter: Why is Mr. Yellow repeated? </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">4. Commenter: It is interesting that these rules for arrangement are placed at the bottom. It seems more like visually organizing thoughts.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">5. OP: I hope so </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">6. C: And I think if you had the time to finish it would have been very explicit where your final answers were and such. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">7. OP: LOL YES. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">8. C: A+ Very User Friendly. It made sense to me. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">9. OP: I forgot that we were going to be able to look at each others things, and I didn&rsquo;t make it user friendly lol. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">10. OP: Im glad you could figure out my thought process though and method of keeping track of things</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">11. OP: lol yeah</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">12. C: Agreed, I would also like to see a side by side because I can&rsquo;t remember my answers haha. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">13. OP: Which you pointed out. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">14. OP: There was a similar method in place though.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">15. OP: I wasn&rsquo;t done lol.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">16. OP: :(</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">17. OP: A few more minutes would have helped. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">18. OP: I know we had the same answer for mr. blue. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">19. OP: I think I was stopped as I was changing my answer for mr. green. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">20. OP: WHICH ONE IS IT</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Part B: </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Grounding: The OP introduces an important piece of common ground here(line 1) &nbsp;They list one of the rules that they used to sort the roses to the gardeners. The commenter now has this piece of information available to them to interpret the data. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Adjacency Pair: This first comment by the OP is not part of an adjacency pair. It is simply a statement. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Grounding: Continuing from before we see that the commenter has indeed put to use this piece of common ground declared by the OP(Line 2). They have performed some construction internally. They had to take the not complete rule that the OP had posted and infer some of what the color placement meant, deciding that colors before parentheses are concrete answers, while the ones in the parentheses are under consideration, and the colors after it are the current guesses. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Grounding: Here(Lines 12, 17) the OP and commenter comment on ways that they could have made the task easier, deciding that they needed a little more time, and that if they could do a side by side comparison talking about the problem would become easier. They might use this knowledge to alter their JPS next time by including extra visualizations. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Grounding: (12,17) The OP has included information below the organizational structure that has been referenced above. The commenter is asking here for clarification of what the purpose of that information is, trying to establish more common ground. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Acceptance Phrase: Here the OP has accepted the commenter&rsquo;s analysis that the bottom part of the transcript was simply a visual organization of thoughts. (Line 5)</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Acceptance Phrase: This acceptance phrase is paired with the commenter&rsquo;s first interpretation of how the OP was posting their answers. It is the first explicit recognition that the commenter interpreted the whole logic to the posting of the answers. (Line 10)</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Adjacency Pair(Assessment/Agree): The first statement by the commenter in this section forms an adjacency pair with an answer by the OP far down the thread of comments. The commenter here has used construction to try to understand exactly how the OP was trying to solve the problem. They then pose their assessment of the situation so that the OP can agree/disagree and a repair can occur or this piece of knowledge can be accepted into the common ground of the situation. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Adjacency Pair(Question/Answer Type): Here(lines 3-5) the commenter asks a direct question for the OP to answer. In the line that follows below they make a comment that the repetition of Mr. Yellow might just be some type of visual organization. The OP later answers that this was correct and that this was some type of sporadic organizational issue saying a couple times that they needed more time and agreeing that with this time it would have been very explicit where the final answers were. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Repair: This question/answer AP is another attempt at repair. The commenter doesn&rsquo;t know why Mr. Yellow is repeated towards the bottom of the transcript, so they ask the OP to clarify. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Repair: (lines 2,4)This assessment is an attempt at repair. The commenter assumes that there was a straightforward logic in the presentation of the transcript that would allow them to understand the OP&rsquo;s answer; they then post their assessment to the OP so that they can review this assessment and compare it to their internal representation of how they went through listing the information in the joint problem space( Here it is the two participants, the transcript that is posted, the chat window that the participants are typing in, and even the keyboards that they are typing with. ), so that they can then repair the gaps between these two. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Virtual Co-Presence: Almost the entirety of this discussion is focused around the fact that the two participants are not in the same place. If they were they could have simply pointed to the different parts of the transcripts and said this part does this yes or no. The fact that this JPS is occurring over the computer is a limiting factor in the discussion of the two pairs, because understanding the transcript is the first step in discussing if it was a good way to do it or not. To understand the different parts of the transcript requires that there is a question formed about them, which requires that they are identified, which requires that they are referred to, and the fastest way to do this is to point in person. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Part C: Analyze the transcript in terms of the access framework</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Knowledge: The blocks of knowledge that are important units in this transcript are as follows. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">The OP says that they listed the colors they knew the gardeners had and that they could have. </b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">(The Assessment AP phrase by the commenter, later agreed to by the OP)The placement of some colors before/after the options in parentheses seems like it has meaning I am assuming that the colors before the parentheses are concrete answers, the ones in parentheses are the options she is considering, and the colors after are her current guesses. </b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">(The one yielded by the Question/Answer AP about Mr. Yellow) Mr. Yellow is repeated at the bottom because it is part of a visual organization of thoughts.</b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n	<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">(The one yielded by the other Question/Answer AP)Both parties agree more time and better organizational methods would be important.</b></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Representation: This knowledge is stored in a few locations. From the perspective of each individual, relevant information in the JPS is stored in the other person. The JPS also contains the transcript that holds information about how the OP originally tried to solve the problem. The chat log contains constructions of new knowledge structures from the OP and commenter. A limiting factor here is that the OP may have engaged in methods of problem solving that don&rsquo;t lend themselves very well to being expressed in English, as is true of much of math. The participants at one point agree that they would like more data available to them in the form of side by side comparisons. They are here being limited by the representation as well. They claim they are spending a large part of their time trying to recall things that could just be displayed for them. They comment that changing the representation to include this information that they are trying to remember would reduce the work in remembering that they have to do and that this would allow them to spend more mental energy making comparisons. This is where distributed cognition begins to come in. All the data that is given in the transcript is stuff that the participants don&rsquo;t have to remember at the time, which allows them to process other information. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Retrieval: The OP and commenter can access the other person by commenting in the chat. They access the chat by reading it. The limitation here is that they have to make jumps in interpreting what the other person means by their comments. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Construction: The OP and Commenter take the information that they have retrieved from each other and use this information to alter the common ground in the situation. The commenter knows piece of information number 1. They combine this piece of information with their prior knowledge about how people organize things. It is common convention to list options together in a set of parentheses as the OP did. (Yellow/Green/Red). The commenter, knowing that they should look for something that could be the representation of the information that the OP is talking about, recognizes the parentheses motif in their prior knowledge and at this point constructs the new piece of knowledge that this particular parentheses structure here is a representation of a concept that the OP is now talking about. The commenter appropriately leaves a residue of new knowledge in the situation, which is this construction they have just made above. It is now in the representation of the JPS. It is then retrieved by The OP who confirms through another representation in the JPS that the Knowledge that the Commenter has constructed is valid. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">More Distributed Cognition in the JPS: If the situation is viewed as one in which each participant has the goal of figuring out what the best approach was to this problem and problems of this type then each person has the other person to consider as a form of distributed cognition in this JPS. The way that this is being done here is that the OP has tried a problem and the commenter is evaluating the way in which the OP has done this, trying to say if it is best. In order to do this, they need the piece of knowledge: how did the OP try to do the problem? When the commenter asks the OP about the parentheses enclosed information being provisional they are retrieving information from the representation that is stored in the other person that is part of the JPS. The fact that the chat log stays up and contains a record of all that has been said is also a piece of distributed cognition that is performed for the participants. They don&rsquo;t have to remember what they have said to each other and can at all points access this bank readily. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Part D: Analyzing in terms of a joint problem space</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Is there a joint problem space?</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">The JPS has already been talked about in depth here. Each person has the goal of understanding how to do this problem best. The OP also has the goal of specifically understanding the Commenter and providing relevant information to them and the Commenter has the analogous goals of asking good questions and understanding information provided by the OP. For each person the other person is part of the JPS. The other person is part of the representation of information that the other must access. The JPS also consists of the transcript the OP created and the chat dialogue that is going on between the OP and commenter. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">What work is done to maintain the infrastructure as the students work together, creating and sharing knowledge? </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">The OP posts some of their logic about how to read their answers. They then read the commenter&rsquo;s assessment of this and respond in agreement. The infrastructure of the JPS(of the OP) is changed such that the commenter now has this piece of knowledge that was originally only with the OP. The commenter in this section also has their JPS modified in a meta way in that the commenter knows that the OP thinks that the commenter knows basically how they are constructing their answers. It seems simple but treating the two as information processing machines it seems necessary to say since the commenter would not be able to interact correctly with the OP and move on if their JPS was not modified as stated.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">&ldquo;collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS; monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning; repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration. Explain how that quote is relevant to your transcript.</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">collaborators must have ways of: introducing and accepting knowledge into the JPS: </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">Here there are two methods of introduction. The OP uses the transcript to introduce their attempt at solving the problem into the JPS. Both parties use their keyboards to introduce their current thoughts into the chat log and to the other person. It may also be of worth to note that the other person has tried this challenge as well and this knowledge is in them as part of the JPS from the perspective of the OP. The acceptance of knowledge comes in the form of modifying parts of the JPS. Since the JPS is in part the other person for each person the way to accept knowledge into the JPS is directly through the acceptance of the other person. The Keyboard also counts as a method of introduction into the chat log. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">monitoring on-going activity for evidence of divergences in meaning</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">This occurs at a couple stages. Both parties do this when they are considering the responses of the other. Here it consists of interpreting the other&rsquo;s understanding and comparing it to one&rsquo;s own understanding, so that they can rectify the differences. The commenter also does this when they are reading the transcript of the OP. The only difference there is they are reading this info and not asking for it from the OP. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">repairing divergences that impede the progress of the collaboration</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-f792ed21-7834-b11d-34c3-b19e78015c1a\">This occurs when the two are trying to bridge the differences that they might have in understanding the model the OP is using in the transcript to display information. When the OP makes the acceptance phrase to the commenter that confirms the commenter&rsquo;s assessment of the model of the OP that is the point at which the divergence in their knowledge has been repaired. When the OP makes the acceptance phrase that yes the bottom is just a visual organization of thoughts that is a point at which divergence is repaired. The divergence being that the OP knows some information was not relevant to the answer, while the commenter did not know this. </b></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n',30,2,8,0,1,'2016-03-11 15:54:18','2016-03-15 02:59:04');
